north carolina democrats pick 82 pledged national convention delegates through a ``bonus delegate'' primary system
the presidential candidate receiving the most votes in a congressional district in the march 8 primary will receive one delegate from that district, and the remainder of the pledged delegates from that district will be allocated among the presidential candidates in proportion to the results of the primary
north carolina's remaining 29 pledged national convention delegates will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to the results of the primary
method: primary
date: tuesday, march 8
candidates filed: george bush, bob dole, jack kemp, pat robertson, pete du pont, alexander haig
delegates: 54
delegates allocated: tuesday, march 8
selection of delegates: friday, april 1 and saturday, june 4
all of north carolina's 54 republican national convention delegates are allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to the results of the march 8 primary
a presidential candidate must receive at least 10 percent of the vote statewide to qualify for any national convention delegates
thirty-three people to serve as delegates from congressional districts are chosen at district conventions held during april
the remaining 21 delegates at-large are picked at the state convention june 3-4
the delegates are not required to pledge their support to a presidential candidate
while the state's delegation is required to vote in line with the primary results, this obligation applies only to the first ballot, and the actual preferences of individual delegates may differ from the way the delegation as a whole must vote
