texas has a peculiar two-track system for picking its pledged delegates to the democratic national convention
allocation among presidential candidates of the state's 119 pledged delegates from congressional districts will be in proportion to the results of the march 8 primary
however, also on march 8, the state party begins a three-step system of caucuses and conventions that will govern allocation of the state's remaining 64 pledged national convention delegates
the precinct caucuses begin at 7:15 p.m. on march 8 and only those who voted in the primary are eligible to participate. allocation of the 64 pledged delegates at-large will be in proportion to presidential preference expressed at sign-in by delegates to the state convention on june 18
method: primary
date: tuesday, march 8
candidates filed: george bush, bob dole, jack kemp, pat robertson, pete du pont, alexander haig
delegates: 111
delegates allocated: tuesday, march 8
selection of delegates: wednesday, june 15
results of the republican primary in texas will govern allocation of the state's national convention delegates among presidential candidates
a candidate receiving more than 50 percent of a vote in a congressional district is entitled to all three of that district's delegates. if no candidate receives a majority in a district, the one receiving the most votes will get two delegates and the second-place finisher will get one
all 30 of the delegates at large will be awarded to the candidate receiving at least 50 percent of the vote statewide. if no candidate gains a majority, the delegates will be distributed proportionally among the candidates receiving at least 20 percent of the vote
