virginia republicans pick their national convention delegates through a three-step process of caucuses and conventions beginning with city and county caucuses on march 1
the caucuses pick delegates to the congressional district and state conventions
virginia's 10 congressional district conventions will be held between may 14 and june 14, and each will choose three national convention delegates. the state's remaining 20 national convention delegates will be chosen at the state convention on june 10
delegates are not required to declare their support for a presidential candidate
virginia also is holding its first-ever presidential primary on march 8, the results of which are not binding on the republican party
here, at a glance, are the methods for picking delegates from washington to attend the 1988 democratic and republican national conventions this summer
method: caucus
date: tuesday, march 8
presidential filing deadline: none
pledged delegates: 65
super delegates: 8
total: 73
delegates allocated: tuesday, march 8
selection of delegates: saturday, june 4 and sunday, june 12
washington democrats pick pledged national convention delegates through a three-step system of caucuses and conventions beginning with precinct caucuses on march 8
allocation among presidential candidates of the state's 43 pledged delegates from congressional districts will be in proportion to presidential preference expressed by participants at the congressional district caucuses on june 4. the pledged national convention delegates from the congressional delegates will assemble on june 12 to pick the rest of the state's 22 pledged national convention delegates
method: caucus
date: tuesday, march 8
presidential filing deadline: none
delegates: 41
delegates allocated: friday, july 15
selection of delegates: friday, july 15
washington republicans use a three-step process of caucuses and conventions to pick their national convention delegates, beginning with precinct caucuses on march 8
the precinct caucuses elect delegates to the county or legislative district conventions to be held between april and june. those conventions choose delegates to the state convention july 15-16, when all of the national convention delegates will be chosen
the government has decided to standardize the spelling of a common name in malaysia
current variations on the name include mohamed, mohamad, mohamat, muhamat and muhammad
to simplify matters for the bureaucracy, the national registration department recently issued an order standardizing the spelling to muhammad
this does not mean that prime minister mahathir mohamad and information minister mohamed rahmat will have to change the spelling of their names
a spokesman for the department said tuesday the directive only applies to names recorded on birth certificates after the order was issued
china has 20 million surplus workers, although there are substantial manpower shortages in jobs requiring heavy labor, the official china daily said today
the newspaper said surplus workers in the work force of 132 million are costing the state billions of dollars and are a heavy burden to enterprises
it quoted the director of a boiler factory as saying his operation would be more efficient if the current staff of 10,000 was reduced by 4,000
but it said workers in overstaffed plants and unemployed youths are reluctant to volunteer for jobs in repair businesses or those requiring heavy labor. such jobs are filled mainly by surplus agricultural workers, it said. families</head>
an attorney for five relatives of challenger astronauts says that other families who settled with the government and with rocket maker morton thiokol for $7.7 million were shortchanged
that settlement is woefully inadequate,'' said ronald d. krist, a houston attorney who represented astronauts' survivors from the apollo spacecraft fire in 1967 as well as three families from the 1986 space shuttle disaster
krist said the four challenger families in the government-company settlement should have and ``would have netted more money'' if they had hired lawyers
the cost of the four-family settlement, which came in cash and annuities, was disclosed in government documents released monday
the documents show that morton thiokol, which produced the faulty booster rocket blamed for the jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the space shuttle challenger, paid $4,641,000, or 60 percent. the government's share of the settlements was $3,094,000, or 40 percent
the documents were released by the justice department to settle a civil suit brought under the freedom of information act by the associated press and six other news organizations
in court papers, the government acknowledged that the four settling families did not hire lawyers, relying instead on informal advice from leo b. lind, jr., executor of the estate of christa mcauliffe, a 37-year-old concord, n.h., public high school teacher killed in the explosion. lind is the law partner of mcauliffe's husband, steven
michael d. oldak, an attorney and ex-husband of mission specialist judith a. resnik, represented her father, marvin, in settlement talks with the justice department
i think it was a big mistake'' for the four settling families not to hire lawyers, oldak said monday. ``i think if i hadn't been involved, they probably may have coerced the resniks into accepting their original offer. these are people in the midst of their grief.''
oldak said the original government-company offer was ``a few hundred thousand,'' and ``i told them nicely what they could do with it.'' he rebuffed them again when ``nearly a year later, they doubled the offer.''
instead, marvin resnik settled with morton thiokol last month for an amount he put at between $2 million and $3.5 million. the government refused to contribute to the settlement
the government's treatment of the four families was viewed differently by betty grissom, whose husband gus died in the apollo fire
mrs. grissom said she received only $350,000, and had to sue north american rockwell on her own for that
i never heard from the justice department,'' she said. ``i thought we got an injustice done to us. they act like they care now, but they didn't back then
it kinda hurts,'' she added. ``it stings that ... we never got treated like that. it hurts when i think that they're getting that much money.''
the settlements were reached dec. 29, 1986, with the immediate survivors of spacecraft commander dick scobee, 46, a retired air force officer employed by the national aeronautics and space administration; mission specialist ellison s. onizuka, 39, an air force lieutenant colonel; payload specialist gregory jarvis, 41, an employee of hughes aircraft co.; and mcauliffe
the surviving four spouses and six children will receive more than $7,735,000, because each was given an annuity, which pays benefits larger than its cost but over a period of many years
the total dollar amounts they will receive over time and the breakdown by family were not released
among the disclosures:
_the justice department did all the negotiating for morton thiokol as well as the government. the families never spoke to company officials
_the rocket maker tried to have the settlements cover any property damage morton thiokol might have caused, such as destruction of the orbiter and payload, but the government refused
_although the justice department claims it cannot legally be sued by the families of military or federal civilian employees who die on duty, it contributed 40 percent to each of the settlements. only the jarvis and mcauliffe relatives had a right to sue the government directly; all the astronaut families could sue the company
morton thiokol attorney john w. adler said the government was being unfair to the parents of resnik, a 36-year-old civilian nasa employee, because of ``the government's refusal to participate to any degree at all'' in a settlement the company considered acceptable
resnik's mother, sarah resnik belfer, and jarvis' father, bruce, settled with morton, thiokol but the government did not contribute. so did cheryl mcnair, wife of mission specialist ronald e. mcnair, 35, a civilian nasa employee who had two infant children. all five were represented by krist
jane smith, wife of pilot michael j. smith, 40, a navy commander, has a suit pending in federal court against the company. the government last month got itself dismissed as a defendant, because military personnel may not sue the government for wrongful death
justice spokeswoman amy brown said the government made settlement offers to attorneys for the resniks, smiths and mcnairs based on the same formula used for the other families, but they were rejected. she said the government would not offer them settlements which exceeded the guidelines used for the other families or which were separate from settlements with morton thiokol. base</head>
leonore sarabia, clutching her sweater against the morning chill, awaited jesse jackson's arrival at the mirasol housing project, a heavily hispanic neighborhood where the presidential hopeful was searching out votes for today's election
she had come ``to check him out,'' she said, even though she already knew she would vote for him. she didn't really know anything about the other five democratic contenders, but jackson ``is more for the people,'' she explained as the candidate emerged from a limousine
two days earlier, it was tom trantham's dairy farm in the south carolina county where jackson grew up. there, he talked farm policy and shared a breakfast of grits and eggs with trantham and a few neighbors as cameras and reporters jostled around the table
the white farmers said they were grateful for jackson's support during the 1986 drought, when he helped unload trucked-in hay. but they were noncommittal about whether they would vote for him
i haven't made a decision,'' said bertha tinsley. her husband doug tinsley, fetching coffee refills for the jackson group, said he was a republican and would probably vote gop
the two campaign stops illustrate the challenge and the success jackson has had as he tries to expand his base beyond his core of black supporters
in the south, voters today are deciding if he can overcome what he describes as an ``ancient cultural barrier,'' and pull white support here as he did in five northern states with fractional black populations
today's super tuesday election, with 14 southern states among the 20 where voters are going to the polls, has shaped up as the day when jackson's presidential bid will shine
it is virtually certain he will be picking up more non-black votes than he did in his 1984 race. and he hopes to do well enough to lay to rest the so-called electability question, the notion that he can't be elected because he is black
casual interviews along the campaign trail indicate jackson has engendered considerable respect among southern whites. although some say the racial issue is not as much a factor as it was in 1984, they acknowledge it still remains for many
the older group, they won't change,'' jackson supporter thomas delong, a 57-year-old white student at mississippi state college, said of mississippi voters. he and others interviewed, said that among students, a group the campaign is targeting, jackson has considerable support
jackson's campus rallies are a big draw, and the enthusiastic audiences are sprinkled with whites, including republicans, who seem to come as much out of curiosity as anything
at the university of arkansas, white economics student tony green was impressed by jackson's powerful delivery, commenting, ``wow, quite a speech.''
he said race is not an issue for him but jackson ``is just too liberal.'' he may even vote republican if vice president george bush wins the gop nomination, he said
jackson has touted the endorsements of a handful of prominent white southern politicians including texas agriculture commissioner jim hightower, oklahoma state sen. gene stipe, and tennessean john j. hooker, a former gubernatorial candidate with close ties to former sen. albert gore sr., the father of one of jackson's rivals
in texas, with its large hispanic population, he was joined on the campaign trail by new mexico gov. toney anaya, a prominent hispanic leader
and selma, ala., last week saw a historically dramatic moment. the white mayor who had had dr. martin luther king and other civil rights activist arrested more than two decades ago welcomed jackson, a king protege and longtime civil rights activist, giving him the key to the city
mayor joe smitherman then joined jackson for a stroll through streets that saw some of the most tense moments of the civil rights struggle
the mayor said he was wrong to oppose the civil rights movement and while he's not officially endorsing jackson, he supports his message. the message, powerfully hammered home in jackson's stump speech, is:
_that ``the new south'' is one of equal civil rights but economic inequity
_that greater efforts are needed to fight the drug influx, the no. 1 national security threat
_that multinational corporations are to blame for loss of u.s. jobs because they take their business to cheap labor markets overseas
_that corporate agribusiness is to blame for squeezing the family farm
_that the minimum wage should be increased, and health care and day care programs are needed for the poor
_that overall hemispheric cooperation is needed to help ease latin nations' debts, increase u.s. exports and make peace with cuba and nicaragua
this is a referendum on economic violence,'' jackson says. ``people who are unemployed are rebelling. people who have jobs are insecure. people feel abandoned by the government.''
there also is considerable evidence that jackson is benefiting from being a celebrity in a contest where the other five candidates are a blur in many voters' minds
the other democrats have made multimillion-dollar media buys, compared to jackson's paltry $100,000 worth of ads in mostly non-major markets
jackson relies on the free media attention that follows him on his 18-hour campaign days, filled with tv-oriented events and photo opportunities
campaign manager gerald austin says the chartered dc-9 that carries the candidate and traveling press corps is jackson's media expenditure
it's always easy to spot a presidential contender going down the tubes in a primary election. he's the one noisily protesting that the other guy can't possibly get enough votes to win the white house
that's why sen. bob dole says vice president george bush can't win a national election for the republicans. and that's why aides to rep. richard gephardt and sen. albert gore jr. are beginning to whisper that michael dukakis would lead the democratic party to a resounding defeat in the fall
electablity is looming larger as the issue,'' dole said monday as he tried to stir up doubts about the vice president in alabama _ one of several super tuesday states where he looks like a landslide loser. ``we ought to nominate a winner instead of a loser.''
the unspoken message is that dole fears he is about to be swept under by a bush tide of ferocious proportions by the time the votes _ and the delegates _ are counted in the super tuesday contests
there will be more talk of that type in the days ahead. dole and his campaign aides are likely to produce polls, charts, graphs, senators, and an academician or two to explain why bush can't possibly win the presidential race in the fall
whether that will stem bush's surge in the nominating war now unfolding will have to wait for the decision of voters of illinois, ohio, pennsylvania and elsewhere
but curiously enough, the same play is being made against dukakis in the democratic race
gore's aide have begun to speak of a ``very real electability problem'' with dukakis, saying he has been unable to attract swing voters in the south who will be critical to democratic chances in the fall election
gephardt's advisers, even less charitable, have started to whisper alarmingly to reporters about a 50-state sweep next fall by the republicans if dukakis is the democratic nominee
such talk is designed to mask the prospect of a gore or gephardt failure in super tuesday _ possibly finishing behind not only dukakis, but jesse jackson, as well, and to lay out a rationale for remaining in the race
sen. paul simon's aides are attempting a variation on that theme, claiming that no matter what the outcome on super tuesday, dukakis will be unable to garner enough delegates to be assured of the nomination when the democratic convention opens in atlanta in july
in other words, don't ask simon why he took one look at the south and hustled back home to illinois, passing up even a chance at most of the 1,307 delegates at stake
even before the first curtain is pulled aside to admit a voter to a super tuesday polling booth, one outcome seems certain
super tuesday was conceived as a chance for the south to rise again in democratic politics, a way to mobilize an entire region behind a white, moderate to conservative candidate _ preferably from the south _ and push him firmly along the path to the party's nomination
instead, the two men who most nearly fit that bill, sen. albert gore of tennessee and rep. richard gephardt, find themselves in a struggle for survival in the race
the southern conservative political leaders made their stand in the final days of the super tuesday campaign. in a last bid to salvage something for their work. georgia sen. sam nunn, gov. joe frank harris and virginia gov. charles robb all made 11th-hour endorsements for gore
but the southerners' concern will be relegated to the back pages in a few days
dole will want the headlines to say that bush can't win a national election. dukakis' rivals will want the same thing said about him
unless, of course, the vice president and the massachusetts governor actually win their respective parties' nominations and fight it out for the white house in the fall election
then, the chances are that one of them will win
_
editor's note _ david espo covers the 1988 presidential campaign for the associated press
a spokesman for the rev. jerry falwell, who lost a lawsuit against larry flynt and hustler magazine over a crude satire, says portrayal of the case this week in the comic ``doonesbury'' is fair comment
i don't think anybody puts newspaper cartoons and the ad parody that was before the supreme court in the same ballpark or the same category,'' falwell spokesman mark demoss said from his office here
in a ruling viewed as a major victory for cartoonists who lampoon public figures, the u.s. supreme court last month threw out a $200,000 award a roanoke federal jury granted falwell in 1984 for emotional distress caused by the hustler ad parody, which portrayed falwell as a sexual deviant
in monday's ``doonesbury,'' cartoonist garry trudeau feigns a sigh of relief before cutting to a satire of evangelist jimmy swaggart's alleged sexual misconduct
dr. falwell's wife keeps a scrapbook of cartoons that mention him, so i'll take the scissors and cut this out and it will go into the scrapbook,'' demoss said
the editorial director for universal press syndicate said trudeau is not trying to prove that the court allowed him to sharpen his pen. ``garry's just doing what he's always done anyway,'' lee salem said from his office in kansas city, mo
producer joseph papp, founder and president of the new york shakespeare festival, says a musical opening on the campus of florida state university in june may be broadway bound
betsey brown,'' written by ntozake shange, will bring together papp's new york production team and university faculty and students to create a professional and educational experience, officials said monday
this is an unprecedented relationship. there's nothing like it nationally,'' said gil lazier, dean of the university's theater school
plans call for casting most of the major characters in new york, but some parts in tallahassee, and involving students in the development of sets, costumes and the musical score
papp said the musical may end up on broadway after three weeks in tallahassee beginning june 21 and short stops elsewhere
betsey brown'' tells the story of a young black girl growing up in st. louis in the 1950s
michael jackson and recent grammy winner jody watley led the nominations for the second annual soul train music awards
jackson was nominated monday for best single and album for ``bad'' and for best music video for his hit single, ``the way you make me feel.''
miss watley, the former singer with the group shalamar who won a grammy last week for best new artist, received nominations for best single and album in the female division and will compete against jackson in the music video category for her video, ``looking for a new love.''
others receiving multiple nominations were whitney houston, stevie wonder, natalie cole, prince, janet jackson and earth, wind &amp; fire
the winners will be named during a two-hour telecast march 30
three of the ``test-tube'' quintuplets of raymond and michele l'esperance left the hospital in a white limousine decorated with silver balloons to join the couple's three other children at home
a crowd of doctors, nurses and hospital administrators gathered monday to bid farewell to raymond jr., danielle and erica l'esperance, who have gained about 3 pounds each since their jan. 11 birth. danielle is the biggest at 6 pounds, 6 ounces, said nurse pamela wells of william beaumont hospital
the other two babies, veronica and alexandria, should be able to go home in a few weeks, said dr. daniel batton
we can't wait to have the other two home. we'll just start getting down to being a family,'' said l'esperance, a corrections officer who has built a new, larger home in clarkston
the babies were the first quintuplets born in the united states after being conceived through in-vitro fertilization, which involves fertilizing eggs in the laboratory and implanting the embryos in the womb
nobel laureate james tobin says he plans to retire from teaching this spring after 38 years as an economics professor at yale university
tobin, 69, served on president kennedy's council of economic advisers and won the nobel memorial prize in economic science in 1981 for his work on modern portfolio theory
a disciple of the late english economist john maynard keynes, tobin argues for government involvement in the economy and full employment. he is at odds with the reagan administration in his view that taxes should be increased to reduce the federal deficit
a management shakeup at the national basketball association's sacramento kings moved coach bill russell from the bench to the executive suite
russell, 54, said monday that gregg lukenbill, general managing partner and part owner of the club, suggested replacing him with assistant coach jerry reynolds, 44, to try to turn around the team's 17-41 win-loss record
russell said he agreed it was time for a change, and was looking forward to becoming vice president in charge of basketball operations, a recruiting post
every time we lost a game, it was a real hard kick in the stomach,'' russell said, flanked by reynolds and lukenbill at a news conference. ``i don't sleep after we lose and, you know, i've had a lot of sleepless nights,'' he added, his voice quivering and his eyes appearing moist. ``the losses _ i haven't been able to handle that.''
russell, a former five-time nba most valuable player, was named coach last year with the understanding he would be on the bench for two to four years and then move to the front office
amanda mcbroom, the one-time grammy nominee who has performed ``the rose'' in front of audiences of 60,000, clutched a microphone and stood under a fluorescent light next to an old coffee urn
no, times aren't tough for mcbroom. but they are for the 75 people who listened politely in a drafty soup kitchen on the city's northern border
few have jobs, and fewer have a permanent place to live. entertainment, whether paying to see a movie or a musician, is out of the question, so once a week professional entertainers come to them, singing a song or telling a joke to a poor but grateful crowd
i'm really happy i was here,'' mcbroom as she retrieved her coat after a six-song set. in a few hours, nightclub patrons would pay $10 to hear what the soup kitchen regulars enjoyed free
it's a look at reality,'' mcbroom said. ``you think of the homeless as a faceless group. that's not so. they're the same as me, but they've had bad luck.''
the weekly entertainment at the soup kitchen, which doubles as the storefront good news community church, was the idea of the rev. bob tschannen-moran and his indefatigable volunteer, joyce heitler, who dishes out food each night
by day, she's a teacher and part-time publicist for various professional acts around chicago
we needed something around here that's more than just food,'' she said, dropping on a bench to wipe her hands in an apron. ``some people thought it was frivolous. they said our job was to feed the poor, not entertain them
well they're entitled to something extra once in a while. they've had hard lives,'' she said
besides mcbroom, the soup kitchen has provided a stage for free performances by chicago's famous second city comedy troupe, the lyric opera, magicians and puppeteers
it does my heart good to see people doubled over in laughter, especially when they don't have much to laugh about,'' tschannen-moran said recently. ``we don't pretend that this is solving any problems, but i do think, for a brief time, this program is lifting spirits.''
the soup kitchen, within earshot of the last train stop before evanston, is tucked between a coin laundry and fast eddie's soul food. last year, the kitchen served 20,000 meals five days a week, including 9,000 to people age 18 and younger
a glance around the tables at mealtime finds gap-toothed children sitting beside single mothers. the youngsters' pants are often ripped and their jackets dirty and worn. outside on a recent night the temperature was near zero
we're pretty much regulars,'' said carol barton, 31, pointing to her 10-year-old son, shaun
i'm a single mother on public aid. people on my type of income can't afford entertainment. you have to use your imagination,'' she said. ``this is a bonus in life. it gives you a chance to survive the rest of the week.''
after 30 minutes, mcbroom has taken her bows. there is another evening engagement, but she still has a few minutes to sign autographs and answer questions
bette midler is best known for singing ``the rose'' in the movie of that name, but mcbroom wrote the lyrics. although the listeners couldn't offer her roses, each table in the soup kitchen had a soda pop bottle with water and carnations
how many times have you done `the rose?''' mcbroom was asked
a million times,'' she replied, ``but never to a more grateful bunch. this is a very classy group here. good night.''
the head of the environmental protection agency says restrictions on driving may be necessary to meet clean air standards in large cities, but such limitations shouldn't be determined in washington
i can make decisions at the federal level to establish regulations for certain industries, to establish regulations for each individual car's emission control equipment,'' epa chief lee m. thomas told a meeting of the national association of counties on monday. ``but if we look at smog in our major cities in the future, that's not going to be enough.''
sixty-two cities are on epa's list of non-complying areas for ozone, a key constituent of smog that worsens breathing problems. many will slide into compliance as older, more polluting cars are junked, but the worst cities _ perhaps 20 _ are bound to have serious problems ever meeting the standard, epa officials have said
ozone is formed by the interaction in sunlight of certain hydrocarbon and other compounds with nitrogen oxides, a product of combustion in motor vehicles, factories and power plants. the hydrocarbons can be unburned gasoline from cars, other compounds from industrial sources and even aerosol propellants. to reduce ozone formation in urban areas, scientists believe reductions in hydrocarbons must precede reductions in nitrogen oxides
at the moment the compliance question is in limbo as members of congress wrestle with revisions to the clean air act in back-room negotiations. congress has imposed a moratorium until aug. 1 on penalties against non-complying areas
telling county officials that ``the easy days are over'' in pollution control, thomas said ``in the long term we'll be right back at making the tough choices about how we are going to meet those standards.''
i can't have full responsibility in washington of establishing a uniform system of regulations and controls when in fact i've got such a diverse group of sources, when the smog problem may well need to be dealt with by reducing the number of cars on the street, by telling people they can't drive nearly to the extent they have in the past,'' thomas said
epa made stabs in the early 1970s at reducing auto use in urban areas, notably boston and los angeles, but public and congressional opposition prompted the agency to backpedal
thomas, who has said before that a serious commitment to the current standards might have to mean cutting down driving, evidently expects opposition again
in the smog and other programs, he said, ``the public will demand of all levels of government far more information on what do these sources do in terms of cost, in terms of degradation of the environment or degradation of their health, and on the other hand what do our programs do for them in terms of benefits and is it worth it to go forward with these programs.''
farmland prices nationally are headed up for the first time in six years, but an agriculture department analyst says there still are areas where land values are lagging
we're thinking there are going to be rather strong increases in the corn belt states and in the northeast,'' says roger hexem of the department's economic research service. ``we're less certain what's going to happen in the south and in the west.''
hexem's analysis came in an interview and in a report written for the march issue of agricultural outlook magazine
the department is scheduled to issue its annual farmland value report on april 14, showing average market prices as of feb. 1 for the united states as a whole and for each state
a year ago the feb. 1 values showed u.s. farmland, including buildings, were worth an average of $548 per acre, an 8 percent drop from 1986 to a 19-year low. farmland nationally rose to a peak of $823 per acre in 1982 before starting to slide
when inflation is accounted for, the ``real'' value of farmland declined even longer, from a 1981 peak of $551 per acre to $290 as of feb. 1, 1987
but a lot has changed during the past year, including some brightening of the dreary farm export situation, improved market prices for some commodities and the massive idling of highly erodible land under the government's conservation reserve program, or crp
nationwide, i'm thinking it's going to be up,'' hexem said. ``but i don't know how much.''
there are still ``soft'' areas where land market prices are lagging, he said. some states are gaining faster than others, and it also depends on what kind of agricultural enterprises prevail
within the corn belt, for example, i think that there are some indications that iowa will show a pretty good increase, where another state, like missouri, might not show as strong an increase,'' hexem said
in texas and oklahoma, for example, the economy is ``still kind of soft, so i think that has dampened demand on the part of the non-agricultural purchasers'' of farmland, hexem said. on the other hand, improved cotton prices probably strengthened land values in cotton-producing areas
another factor has been the long-term payments under crp, where farmers can get annual rental payments for planting grass and trees on fragile land. those payments have been averaging around $50 per acre each year for the 10-year life of the contracts
in his report, hexem cited survey results from a number of sources that point to rising farmland values. last november, for example, more than 500 farmland experts, all members of the american society of farm managers and rural appraisers, were surveyed by the university of wisconsin for the usda agency
over one-third of the respondents indicated that land values rose during the august-october (1987) quarter, while over one-half considered values unchanged,'' hexem said. ``less than a tenth indicated lower values.''
those reponses ``point to a strengthening of the market'' since last may, june and july, when only 28 percent thought farmland values had gone up and nearly 18 percent thought they had dropped, he said
for november, december and january, the rural appraisers expected continued increases in farmland values, hexem said. surveys last august, september and october by several federal reserve banks tend to support the national survey by the appraisers
the federal reserve bank of chicago, representing iowa and parts of illinois, indiana, wisconsin and michigan, reported that values for good farmland increased just over 3 percent during the third quarter, compared with a 2 percent gain in the preceding quarter,'' he said
but ``some uncertainties remain'' in the 1988 land market, hexem said. on the up side, demand for farm products is rising, and there are more manageable inventory levels. the crp ``seems to be strengthening prices for lower-quality land in some areas.''
on the down side, farm income is forecast to be down from last year's record level, in which federal payments accounted for 30 percent of the net cash income of farmers. crop target prices and price support loan rates will be down about 3 percent in 1988, and current legislation calls for further reductions in 1989
credit for buying land is available, but interest rates edged slightly upward in late 1987 and could go higher in 1988 if monetary policy is tightened to support the price of the dollar,'' hexem said
average incomes have dropped 25 percent in the countries of black africa during the 1980s, according to the latest figures from the world bank
the seriousness of the short-term economic outlook ... must not be underestimated,'' eugene v.k. jaycox, the bank's vice president for africa, said in a speech monday to the united nations advisory panel on africa
the bank released 1987 figures showing incomes were down by 4 percent from a year earlier. that drop followed a more than 2.7 percent decline reported for 1986 and an average annual decline from 1980-85 of 3.7 percent
exports and imports both declined for the year, but there was a 1.6 percent improvement in prices that africans got for their products, compared with what they had to pay for foreign goods. that was a lot better than 1986, when there was a drop of 25.2 percent
gerard rice, a world bank spokesman, said its economists are looking for a better year in 1988 with the average income holding steady. some countries have had continuous declines since they won independence in the 1960s
the figures cover what the bank calls ``sub-saharan africa,'' which includes the whole continent except for south africa and the northern tier countries algeria, egypt, libya, morocco and egypt
carol lancaster, who deals with africa at the institute for international economics, said the countries in worst shape are those hit by war and drought, such as angola, ethiopia and mozambique. the institute is a private study group financed largely by the west german marshall fund
nigeria, the most populous country on the continent and the one with by far the biggest economy, has been hurt by the drop in the price of oil, its dominant export. the decline in its income has a big effect on the overall figure
the world bank is the single biggest source of loans to improve living standards in the third world. in 1985 treasury secretary james a. baker iii said the bank should take the lead in planning new programs with heavily indebted countries. since then it has been giving more emphasis to broad lending programs, though the majority of its loans are still for individual projects
for the year ending june 30, it is expected to lend africa $5 billion
the international monetary fund, the bank's sister organization, is expected to make another $1.5 billion worth of loans at minimal interest
but the united nations advisory panel on africa said the continent also needs about $1 billion a year in relief from its old debts, most of them to governments, and another $1 billion in new aid
africa's $200 billion dollar debt is less than half latin america's, but its population is poorer, smaller and growing fast. discrimination</head>
the supreme court is beginning another examination of sex discrimination in the american workplace, agreeing to decide how difficult it should be for employers to disprove charges of sexist stereotyping
setting the stage for an important ruling likely to be announced in 1989, the justices on monday said they will hear an appeal by price waterhouse, one of the nation's leading accounting firms
the company is accused of allowing sexism, some of it perhaps unconscious, to play a key role in denying a woman a partnership in the firm
a federal appeals court placed a heavy burden on the firm to disprove the sex bias charges
price waterhouse, one of the nation's so-called ``big eight'' accounting firms, is accused of discriminating unlawfully against ann hopkins. she quit the firm's office here after she was denied promotion to partnership, a move that would have made her a part owner
ms. hopkins joined the firm in 1978 and was nominated for partnership in 1982, the only woman among 88 candidates for partnership that year. at the time, the company had more than 660 partners in 90 offices nationwide
ms. hopkins had been very successful in getting business for the company, winning government contracts worth an estimated $34 million to $44 million
of the 88 candidates in 1978, 47 were invited to become partners; 21 were rejected outright; and 20 including ms. hopkins were placed on hold
the following year she was told she would not become a partner and she resigned in 1984 to set up her own consulting firm
both her critics and supporters at price waterhouse said she sometimes was overly aggressive, too harsh, impatient with her staff and very demanding
one critic suggested she needed to take a ``course at charm school.''
a partner in the firm who urged her promotion told her she would stand a better chance of becoming a partner if she would ``walk more femininely, talk more femininely, dress more femininely, wear makeup, have her hair styled and wear jewelry.''
others said her use of profanity was a black mark against her
ms. hopkins then sued price waterhouse, accusing the company of violating title vii of the 1964 civil rights act prohibiting on-the-job sex discrimination. she said that sex stereotyping, unconscious or otherwise, barred her from being named partner
the supreme court ruled in 1984, in the case of a woman denied partnership in a law firm, that professional partnerships are covered by the 1964 law
a federal judge ruled price waterhouse must prove ``by clear and convincing evidence'' it would not have made her a partner regardless of whether sexual stereotyping played a part in its decision
price waterhouse did not provide such proof
the u.s. circuit court of appeals here last august said there is ``competent evidence that ... the partnership selection process at price waterhouse was impermissibly infected by stereotypical attitudes toward female candidates.''
the appeals court said even if there is evidence that ms. hopkins' personality played a part in her denial of partnership, price waterhouse is unable to prove ``impermissible bias was not the determinative factor.''
the appeals court ordered further hearings to determine what back pay and other remedies the company must provide
in other matters, the court:
_ruled that companies have a heavy burden of proof when defending themselves against investor lawsuits alleging the companies withheld information about merger discussions
_agreed to decide whether states may use anti-racketeering laws to close down adult bookstores accused of selling obscene materials. the court said it will review free-speech challenges to indiana's racketeer influenced and corrupt organizations law, patterned after the much-used federal rico act
_agreed to use a case from canton, ohio, to try again to decide whether cities may be sued successfully by citizens who say their rights were violated by inadequately trained city employees
_ruled that financially troubled farmers may not avoid foreclosure under federal bankruptcy law by promising to pay back debts by using their labor and expertise while continuing to operate their farm
_said it will decide in a case from chicago whether a criminal defendant's right to a jury selected from a cross-section of the community is violated when prosecutors disqualify potential jurors based on their race. murkier</head>
as voters went to the polls today in 20 states, a survey suggested that jesse jackson was leading in seven southern states, albert gore jr. was ahead in three states and michael dukakis was in front in the two states with the biggest delegate prizes, texas and florida
the abc news poll, based on interviews with 8,659 voters last thursday through sunday in all 16 states holding primaries today, also found rep. richard gephardt ahead only in his home state of missouri
in its survey released monday night, abc said dukakis's lead in texas was ``paper-thin'' over jackson and gephardt, who were tied for second in the state. but dukakis had a strong lead in florida, as well as back home in massachusetts and rhode island
on the republican side, abc said the poll indicates today's events look ``like a blow-out for george bush in virtually all states except missouri.''
overall, in the dozen southern states with primaries, bush led bob dole, 60 percent to 20 percent, followed by pat robertson at 12 percent and jack kemp at 4 percent. four percent were undecided
among the democrats in the south, jackson led with 29 percent to dukakis's 25 percent, with gore in third at 21 percent and gephardt fourth with 13 percent. gary hart was fifth at 5 percent, followed by paul simon at 2 percent. four percent were undecided and 1 percent supported other candidates
abc said the southern state results had a margin of error of three percentage points in either direction, but the samples for the non-southern states were too small to generate specific figures for the candidates
it also said the horse-race figures for the entire south were somewhat misleading because the two largest states, texas and florida, make up a large share of the vote. it said jackson led in most of the deep south, with gore, the tennessee senator, running second
it said jackson's strongest leads were in alabama and mississippi, where nearly half the voters polled said they support him. he also led among voters polled in arkansas, georgia, louisiana, north carolina and virginia. jackson was second in tennessee behind gore and second in florida and maryland behind dukakis, and tied for second with gephardt in texas
dukakis led among the voters abc polled in florida, maryland, massachusetts, rhode island and texas. abc said dukakis seemed to be headed for second in virginia behind jackson, while he was in tight battles for second with gore in arkansas, louisiana and north carolina
gore had strong leads in tennessee and kentucky and a thin edge in oklahoma, where abc said gephardt was ``running only slightly behind him.''
gephardt was ahead in the poll only in missouri and second just behind gore in oklahoma and second to gore in kentucky. gephardt and jackson were tied behind dukakis in texas. abc said gephardt was running fourth in most of the other states and was in danger of falling below the 15 percent threshold for delegates in a dozen of the 16 primary states
in an earlier abc news poll completed feb. 28, jackson led dukakis across the south by just 26 to 25 percent, followed by gore with percent, gephardt 13 percent and hart 7 percent. simon had 3 percent, 6 percent were undecided and 1 percent were for others
abc said dukakis has lost a bit of support in the deep south to gore, but gore has not been able to pull off the southern sweep his strategy called for
it said bush's 60-20 lead over dole region-wide is paced by the vice president's strong showings in texas and florida. bush was the choice of about 40 percent of those polled in missouri, and 70 percent in texas. ``in most states he is getting more than 50 percent of the vote against his three rivals,'' abc said
dole averages in the low 20s across the south, while robertson averages 12 percent. kemp averaged only 4 percent in the southern states. kemp's best states in the poll were massachusetts and rhode island, where he was the choice of about 10 percent of those polled. primaries</head>
for the democratic party's most prominent non-candidates, super tuesday marks a milestone _ it's too late to step in and win the presidential nomination through the primaries
by the numbers, it just can't be done
that's not to say that new york gov. mario cuomo, new jersey sen. bill bradley or georgia sen. sam nunn couldn't wind up with the nomination. but as of wednesday, they would have to get it by making political deals with the announced candidates for delegates or by swaying a deadlocked national convention
neither scenario can be ruled out because none of the three has ruled out accepting a draft for the nomination. cuomo has gone so far as to say he would accept such a draft at a deadlocked convention if party leaders made it his ``obligation.''
just last week, former president jimmy carter said there was an even chance that no democrat would clinch the nomination before the july convention in atlanta
there will be 4,160 delegates to the national convention and 2,081 are needed to win the nomination. with the passing of super tuesday there will be 2,279 delegates available from the 31 primaries and caucuses that remain
however, the problem for any late-starting candidate is that most of the filing deadlines to get on the later primary ballots will have passed with super tuesday
a new candidate could get on primary ballots in just five states, participate in caucuses in six other states, in caucuses for democrats in guam and the virgin islands and in a primary for democrats living elsewhere outside the united states
in all, by winning 100 percent of the delegates available in all those post-super tuesday contests qualified for, the candidate would wind up with 628 delegates going into the convention
cuomo, talking about the mathematics of a late start, said: ``number one, you can't do it. number two, it's irrelevant because i wouldn't anyway.''
the major contests still open after super tuesday are the june 7 primaries in new jersey and california. the filing deadlines are march 24 for california and april 13 for new jersey
in california, some democrats are trying to collect enough signatures to get cuomo's name on the ballot. in new jersey, meanwhile, a group of prominent, pro-bradley democrats announced late last month that it would attempt to run an uncommitted slate of delegates in the june 7 primary to give bradley strength at the national convention, if he wanted it
in new york, a group of pro-cuomo democratic county clerks has already qualified an uncommitted slate for the state's april 19 primary even though cuomo asked them not to do it. the new york primary is for 255 delegates
by getting into some of the later primaries, such as california and new jersey, a new candidate could demonstrate strength among the electorate
cuomo says the nomination shouldn't go to someone who hasn't been tested in the primaries. the candidates already in the race share that sentiment
if i lose the nomination, i want to be eliminated by someone who has played in the same league,'' said jesse jackson late last year when asked about a possible cuomo convention draft
nonetheless, nunn said last week that if no clear favorite emerges from super tuesday, the pressure will increase on cuomo and the other prominent non-candidates. also last week, former virginia gov. charles robb said cuomo was the only non-candidate who could possibly capture the nomination at a deadlocked national convention
while robert beckel, democrat walter mondale's 1984 campaign manager, said he thinks the nomination will go to one of the current crop of candidates, he also said ``there's a possibility of chaos.''
you will hear about a cuomo run between now and june 7, i'm convinced of that,'' said beckel. ``whether it will happen or not, i'm much less convinced.''
david garth, the new york-based political consultant and occasional cuomo adviser, said he doesn't expect any immediate move from the new york governor
i think he's going to do nothing until the convention. i think it's going to the convention and at that point he's got some very difficult decisions to make,'' said garth. ``he's going to have a difficult time at the point saying no.''
political organizers for gop presidential hopeful pat robertson have been asking local pastors to use church bulletins to solicit support for their candidate, robertson aides acknowledged monday
i don't think it's out of line,'' said henry hughes, robertson's chief organizer in new york state. ``we are not taking up collections in church like (jesse) jackson's campaign.''
he said pastors should be free to provide political guidance to their congregation as long as it does not actively involve the ``structure'' of the church
but several pastors in this rural upstate community disagreed
i very strongly object to that and i don't support endorsing any political candidate,'' the rev. d. gregory van dussen, pastor of the bergen united methodist church told the batavia daily news
van dussen said he received a letter from the regional committee of americans for robertson based in rochester asking for the use of church bulletins to announce its organizing meetings
he said the letter steered clear of asking for donations or recommendations from the pulpit
mainly it was for behind-the-scenes support,'' he said. ``they were asking us, somewhat diplomatically, to use church sponsorship and organize support for robertson.''
the letter, according to the pastor, said that robertson was a christian candidate presenting the views of christians and that ``christians of like mind would support him.''
robertson, a former baptist minister and television evangelist, scored well in the iowa primary last month, coming in second behind sen. bob dole. but his campaign has since faltered. he predicted a win in south carolina saturday, but came in a distant third behind vice president george bush and dole
van dussen said it was the first time he has ever received a letter asking for the church's political support. he said he has asked his fellow clergymen to refuse to allow the robertson campaign or any other campaign to use the church for political purposes
another pastor, douglas spencer of the first united methodist church in batavia, said, ``i didn't think the church should make that type of decision. the church contains people from various backgrounds. the letter sought institutional support for one candidate.''
al gore's strawberries ... bob dole's generic airliner ... jesse jackson's missing tree ... michael dukakis' hopes for a ``super martes'' ... george bush's return ``home''... richard gephardt's mom goes to bat..
vignettes from the campaign at the end of the long super tuesday trail:
paul simon wrote a book a few years ago called ``the tongue-tied american.'' it deplored americans' ignorance of foreign languages. it was written in english, the only language that simon speaks
by contrast, michael dukakis grew up in a home where both greek and english were spoken. he became fluent in spanish as a college student on visit to mexico and peru
dukakis put his language facility to good use before ``super martes,'' as he called it. he read a lesson in spanish at a televised mass in san antonio, and finished stump speeches across texas with the words: ``poco a poco. paso a paso. mano en mano. juntos. vamos a ganar.'' or, as he translated: ``little by little. step by step. hand in hand. together. we shall succeed.''
near the border with mexico, dukakis did not just sprinkle a few words of spanish into his speech: he delivered a five-minute portion in spanish after his english opening
like his rivals, al gore dashed back and forth across the southeast in the days leading up to today's primaries and caucuses in 20 states. he managed sometimes to touch down in half a dozen states or more in a single day
he traveled in a fleet of four or five lear jets, a curious caravan that made for speedy flying time but sometimes meant the candidate cooled his heels on the tarmac while waiting for his secret service agents and traveling press corps to land
gore's campaign couldn't afford a big jet and couldn't locate a mid-sized jet to accommodate the entourage of candidate, aides, secret service agents, reporters and television crews
gore earlier traveled in a single-prop airplane, a slow but comfortable aircraft not much younger than the 39-year-old candidate. but the campaign eschewed it after repeated mechanical breakdowns _ a couple times in flight
bush, by contrast, had a full-size chartered boeing 727 to carry his press corps _ which sometimes numbered so few the entire lot could sit in the first-class section. and did
that meant comfort and convenience for the travelers _ and sometimes staggering bills for their employers. campaign aides said the cost billed to news organizations was in the thousands of dollars a day for some days of heavy flying
campaign travel for reporters was feast or famine. jesse jackson's campaign press corps took a petition to the candidate to protest ``nutritional violence'' _ they weren't getting fed. he signed too, scrawling, ``let my people go.''
in gore's caravan of lear jets, the problem was too much food
there were platters of fresh strawberries as well as sandwiches, egg rolls, barbecue and chicken. on one day of travel, reporters noted they had faced five platters of food on five separate legs of travel, plus a bag-snack of submarine sandwiches for a midnight-flight snack
somehow, they managed to eat most of it
bob dole's campaign differed from the others in one striking way: no secret service. dole refused the protection, making a visible contrast with bush's almost imperial parade of escorts
dole traveled on the same plane with his troupe of reporters and sometimes wandered along the aisles to chat
his chartered airplane bore the words of its operating airline on one side: ``presidential airways.'' but some of the words were missing on the other side of the boeing 737 aircraft; it said just ``airways.''
this truly was the ``tarmac campaign.'' super tuesday eve sent three republican candidates to tulsa international airport within a four-hour period monday afternoon, but their paths never crossed. the scheduled did keep reporters crisscrossing the windswept tarmac, however
bush touched down in air force ii right on schedule at 12:05 p.m. and made quick work of a rally at an american airlines hangar. he toured the company's tulsa maintenance and engineering facility and talked briefly with reporters before lifting off again about 2 p.m
meanwhile, jack kemp took over a nearby hangar for a 12:30 p.m. news conference, then took off for oklahoma city, where he addressed the oklahoma legislature at 2:30 p.m
dole was taking off from oklahoma city about the same time kemp was speaking at the legislature. he arrived at a private business office at the tulsa airport for a 3:20 p.m. news conference
jesse jackson led his entourage through fieldcrest village, the spartan brick apartment complex in greenville, s.c. where he grew up as a boy
in fact, he said, ``i planted this tree right there.''
not so, the current residents told him. the tree he planted was struck a while back by lightning
in some ways, dukakis' super tuesday campaign has been southern in latitude only
while his democratic rivals were talking about grits and home fries, dukakis cracked jokes monday morning with a largely jewish crowd of senior citizens in north miami beach, fla., where many jews from the north have retired
there's nothing i like better than to walk on a cape cod beach and finish it off with a bowl of clam chowder,'' dukakis told the gathering, many of whom, no doubt, have been to the cape
`of course,'' he added, deferential to his audience, ``i don't have to worry about the dietary laws.''
rep. richard gephardt's longest-standing supporter _ his mother _ led the gephardt campaign in south florida on the eve of super tuesday. she faced rush-hour highway traffic on u.s. 1, posting herself at roadside with a sign: ``support my son.''
the 80-year-old loreen gephardt has stumped for gephardt in iowa, new hampshire, texas, south dakota, louisiana, georgia and alabama
the last four digits in my social security number are 1988. it's a good omen! a good omen!'' she said
vice president george bush, who worried aloud earlier this year that his supporters might be delayed at debutante balls or the country club, picked a prosperous section of houston to await the super tuesday election returns
bush, who long has fought the image of being a new england preppie, decided to hold his party tonight in the posh westin oaks hotel here
both westin oaks and the houstonian, where bush has a condominium he lists as his legal residence, are nestled in an opulent section west of downtown
republican rules in eight of today's super tuesday states could mean the biggest delegate prize for george bush, while bylaws and home-town contests for three of the democratic contenders may prevent an outright winner
bush, who currently has 126 delegates, could pad his lead considerably as the four gop candidates battle for 712 national convention delegates in 16 state contests, including virginia's non-binding primary
while the democrats allot delegates based on a percentage of the vote, republicans in eight super tuesday states _ alabama, florida, georgia, louisiana, maryland, mississippi, oklahoma and texas _ award delegates on a winner-take-all basis in each district and statewide
the vice president, who stands as the front-runner in many of those states, is expected to reap the benefits of the gop process
according to the latest polls, bush leads in 14 states that hold gop primaries or caucuses, including delegate-rich texas with 111, florida with 82, massachusetts with 52 and georgia with 48
the vice president also is ahead in alabama with 38 delegates, louisiana and maryland with 41 each, mississippi with 31, arkansas with 27, kentucky with 38, oklahoma with 36, rhode island with 21 and tennessee with 45
bush is even expected to win in rival pat robertson's home state of virginia, where no delegates are at stake on super tuesday
kansas sen. bob dole is hoping for some success in missouri, which has 47 delegates at stake, and north carolina with 54
according to the associated press survey, dole has 65 delegates heading into the super tuesday events while new york rep. jack kemp has 35 and former television evangelist robertson has 8. twelve delegates remain uncommitted
the democrats will be competing for 1,307 delegates in 21 states or territories. but the party requires that a presidential candidate reach a certain level of support to be eligible for winning delegates _ a system that decreases the chance of a clear-cut super tuesday winner
each candidate must receive at least 15 percent of the vote in any given congressional district or statewide
fueling the possibility of a four-way democratic race are contests in three of the candidates' home states _ michael dukakis' massachusetts, richard gephardt's missouri and albert gore jr.'s tennessee
dukakis, who leads the ap survey of delegates with 69.50, is counting on success in massachusetts with 98 delegates at stake, and possibly a large share of the delegates from florida with 136, maryland with 67, rhode island with 22 and washington with 65
dukakis' chief rival in florida is gephardt, who has obvious high expectations for missouri with 77 delegates, and hopes to do well in oklahoma with 46, and plans to fight it out in texas, which boasts the biggest prize _ 183 delegates
gephardt has 50 delegates so far, while gore has 21.80, jesse jackson 27.55, paul simon 35.50 and 258.65 remain uncommitted
jackson looks to do well in the south, especially in alabama with 56 delegates, georgia with 77, louisiana with 63, mississippi with 40 and perhaps hawaii with 20. jackson enrolled 2,000 new democrats in the island state
gore and gephardt are expected to be locked in a close race in arkansas with 38 delegates. gore is hoping to grab a large portion of delegates in kentucky with 55 at stake, nevada with 16, the obvious _ tennessee _ with 70, and virginia with 75
in north carolina, jackson, gore and dukakis are vying for 82 delegates, while in idaho, dukakis and gore are battling for 18 delegates although state officials would prefer an uncommitted slate
three democratic delegates are at stake in american samoa. service</head>
a federal judge's ruling will allow the regional bell telephone companies to offer consumers new computerized services that do the work telephone answering machines now do
in his decision, u.s. district judge harold greene said the risks that the local phone companies would monopolize the market were outweighed by the benefits this new service and others like it would provide consumers
what has until now been a relatively quiescent market is likely to become a broad, vigorous and competitive one'' that will make the service available to a broad base of consumers, he said in a 66-page decision monday
about 10 percent of american households use answering machines, he said
besides voice messaging, as it is called, the bell companies also could provide electronic mail services, which allow computer-to-computer transfer of messages, greene said
in addition, he outlined a set of computer ``gateway'' functions the companies can provide to guide a computer user to various information services. but he restricted these functions to services like data transmission, billing management and services that enable different computers to ``speak'' to each other
in so doing, he refused to retreat from his september ruling in which he said phone companies could transmit information services but could not generate or manipulate the content of the information
the bell companies generally praised greene's decision as a ``first step'' toward making a wide range of information services available to the public, but they said the judge didn't go far enough
we view this as a start, but only a start. we still are not allowed to provide content for information services,'' a bellsouth statement said
the bell companies have lobbied heavily for full participation in the information services market so they could provide services that would enable consumers with personal computers to bank and shop from home, make travel arrangements and even read newspapers
bell atlantic chairman thomas e. bolger said the company is ``particularly concerned'' that greene is continuing to forbid the bell companies from electronic publishing of yellow page phone directories
though greene's decision lifts the legal barrier to the bell companies' offering of voice messaging and electronic mail, the companies still would need state and federal regulatory approval before they could offer the services to consumers
industry experts and bell company officials say the computer software for these services has been developed and could be offered to consumers in some parts of the country within one to two years
greene, who oversees the antitrust decree that stripped american telephone &amp; telegraph co. of its bell operating companies four years ago, reiterated in his ruling that the baby bells should not be permitted to compete in content-based information services because they continue to control the local phone networks. with this advantage, he maintains, the bells could control the information services market
good morning, vietnam'' remained the top box office hit last weekend despite heavy pressure from ``moving,'' a new movie starring comedian richard pryor
good morning'' earned $5.1 million while ``moving'' earned more than $4 million in its debut weekend
the film stars pryor as a new york engineer forced to relocate his family to boise, idaho, with more than a little trouble along the way
frantic,'' a thriller from roman polanski, earned more than $3.7 million. the movie about an american heart surgeon whose wife disappears during a medical conference in paris stars harrison ford and betty buckley
the romantic comedy ``moonstruck'' was in fourth place with $3.2 million, followed by ``three men and a baby,'' which earned more than $3.1 million in its 14th week, bringing it to a total gross of $144.2 million for disney-touchstone
switching channels,'' a broadcast version of the venerable newsroom comedy ``the front page,'' earned $3.1 million for its debut week
the tri-star movie stars kathleen turner as a network news reporter who keeps trying to quit her job, get away from her ex-husband played by burt reynolds, and marry her new love, a sporting goods company owner played by chistopher reeve
shoot to kill,'' a thriller starring sidney poitier as an fbi agent chasing a maniac in the northwest woods, earned $3.1 million for seventh place. it was followed by ``action jackson'' with $1.8 million
a night in the life of jimmy reardon,'' starring ``stand by me'' star river phoenix, earned $1.4 million for ninth place
the last emperor,'' director bernardo bertolucci's oscar nominated movie about the china's last emperor, pu yi, was in 10th place with $1.3 million
