interest rates on short-term treasury securities rose in the latest auction to the highest level since last month
the treasury department sold $6.4 billion in three-month bills monday at an average discount rate of 5.74 percent, up from 5.62 percent last week. another $6.4 billion was sold in six-month bills at an average discount rate of 5.93 percent, up from 5.86 percent last week
the rates for three-month bills were the highest since feb. 1 when they sold for an identical 5.74 percent. three-month bills sold for 5.85 percent on jan. 25. the rates for six-month bills were the highest since feb. 16 when they averaged 6.03 percent
the new discount rates understate the actual return to investors _ 5.91 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for $9,854.90 and 6.20 percent for a six-month bill selling for $9,700.20
in a separate report, the federal reserve said monday that the average yield for one-year treasury bills, the most popular index for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages held steady at 6.63 percent last week, the same as the rate for the previous week
fresh snow on the trail continued to slow the pace of the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race as mushers slogged their way down from the frosted peaks of the alaska range
on monday, jan masek of anchorage led a tightly grouped caravan of more than 20 mushers to rohn roadhouse, a remote log-cabin checkpoint 271 miles from the start in anchorage
masek arrived at 3:10 p.m., followed eight minutes later by lavon barve of wasilla. defending champion susan butcher arrived at 3:20 p.m., followed closely by jerry austin of st. michael and jacques philip of thomery, france
tim moerlein of kasilof pulled in at 3:31 p.m., trailed four minutes later by four-time iditarod champion rick swenson, in seventh position
by 8:30 p.m., half the 52 mushers in the race had made it to rohn. the rest were spread the 78 miles back to finger lake
racers were slowed by up to 6 inches of new snow as they mushed down to rohn from rainy pass, at 3,400 feet the highest point along the trail
rohn is a favorite point for mushers to take the 24-hour layover required of all mushers sometime during the anchorage-to-nome race. the isolated cabin provides a refuge from spectators and reporters, and the dogs often are tired from crossing the rugged mountains
the race, which started at 9 a.m. saturday, has been slower than last year's record-setting pace, when butcher reached nome after 11 days, 2 hours on the trail
the race is inspired by a 1925 dog sled relay that rushed diphtheria serum to nome during an outbreak of the disease. the top 20 mushers will split a purse of $150,000. the winner will get $30,000. ^an ap extra</head>
panama's strongman, gen. manuel antonio noriega, is emphasizing class and racial distinctions in what appears to be an effort to rally support by polarizing society
the humble, the poor, the blacks, they are the utmost authority of this people,'' noriega, commander of the country's 15,000-strong defense forces, told a crowd friday in the provincial town of carriazo
his regime, under mounting economic pressure from the united states, has tried to characterize domestic opposition as rich and white. in government newspapers and on official radio and tv stations, noriega's opponents are termed ``oligarchs'' and ``sellouts.''
whiteys, to the firing squad,'' says graffiti scrawled on walls in some of this capital's more affluent neighborhoods. the message is signed vt, for victoria torrijista, a populist organization that reveres the late strongman omar torrijos
in speeches, noriega repeatedly invokes torrijos _ killed in a 1981 airplane crash _ as inspiration for his defiance of washington
vt, like all groups supportive of the defense forces' de facto rule, is subsidized by the government, according to former government officials now at odds with noriega
panama, with 2.2 million people, is a racially mixed nation with african, indian and european heritage. as is the case throughout latin america, people of european or predominantly european heritage are generally better off than descendants of those their forefathers conquered or enslaved
compared with the rest of the region, there is a relatively large middle class. but there is also a big gap between rich and poor
the national civic crusade _ an opposition alliance of about 200 business, professional, political and labor groups _ has struggled to overcome the popular perception of it as representative of limited and privileged interests
in the dining room of the opulent marriott hotel, ernesto gonzalez de la lastra, a leader of the crusade, rose in response to a question about the government claim it is ``oligarchic.''
gonzalez de la lastra, in stylish clothes, a rolex watch gleaming on his wrist and gold chain around his neck, escorted foodworkers' union official martin gonzalez, in humbler garb, to the table
i'll let don martin answer that,'' said the president of the association of panamanian executives
oligarchy means government by the few,'' said the union man from a working-class district just outside the capital of panama city. ``so the defense forces and their government is the real oligarchy.''
noriega does not hold pro-government demonstrations at the marriott, and those who attend rallies supporting him are poorer than the drivers of the cars that join the crusade's occasional protest caravans through town. but the opposition has significantly broadened its appeal
noriega tries to represent himself as the standard-bearer of the poor,'' said dedys ramos, saleswoman at a clothing store in the downtown area. ``but it is the poor who suffer more than anyone because of him.''
from a lower-class neighborhood, mrs. ramos earns just above the minimum wage of $150 a month and is an adamant opponent of the regime
referring to the beginnings of hardship _ including the closure of banks last week _ resulting from u.s. economic pressure on panama, she said:
he (noriega) is not going to go without. he has food and a roof. but what about those abuelitos (little grandfathers) who can't cash their paltry pension checks? that's why you can see me out there waving my white hankie with the civilistas (civic crusade backers).''
supporters of the civic crusade, which has spearheaded opposition to noriega since its formation in june, wave white handkerchiefs at their demonstrations
a gallup poll taken in august indicated that nearly 75 percent of panamanians would like to see noriega out
a power struggle earlier this month between noriega and ousted president eric arturo delvalle sparked the current crisis
noriega loyalists in the national assembly dismissed delvalle feb. 26, a day after delvalle had tried to fire noriega
noriega was indicted last month in florida on federal drug trafficking charges. he has denied those accusations
the nikkei stock average closed at 25,465.73 points, down 150.85 points, on the tokyo stock exchange on tuesday
cosi fan tutte'' may be difficult to sing, but one wouldn't have known that from the performance given monday night as the mozart opera was heard at the metropolitan opera for the first time in three years
because all the singers paid such rapt attention to their vocal lines, instead of tossing them off, the opera in which two men, on a dare, disguise themselves as foreigners and woo each other's sweetheart, was more serious than it sometimes is. and it was sung glowingly!
one felt the women's real attempts not to fall for the new men _ and the men's pain when they did. in contrast to what happened in the 1984-85 season, this time the couples paired up as they began. last time, they stayed as they had switched around
the cast of six principals provided a gem of an evening as james levine conducted
dame kiri te kanawa, from gisborne, new zealand, sang fiordiligi
susan quittmeyer of new york impressed as one who should be heard again when she made her met debut earlier this season in ``the tales of hoffmann.'' that impression was correct. as dorabella, she held her own beside dame kiri. they made a splendid pair and blended beautifully
also splendid were the suitors, baritone hakan hagegard of karlstad, sweden, engaged to fiodiligi, and tenor david rendall of london engaged to dorabella
it was good to have hagegard's fine voice back at the met; he last was heard here as wolfram in ``tannhauser'' four years ago. rendall is a veteran in ``cosi'' at the met and sounds even better in it than before. his voice abosolutely floated
carlos feller, from tarnopol, poland, made his met debut as don alfonso, who bets the two men that their sweethearts won't stay true to them. the bass has been a member of the cologne opera since 1969. his tones are round and open and he seemed right at home. he has sung the part at the glyndbourne festival and the washington opera and recorded it
dawn upshaw, from nashville, was another delight, as the maid. she was singing instead of hei-kyung hong, who was originally announced
set designer hayden griffin solved the problem of an opera with six principal singers on a huge stage by setting action inside a large wooden frame on the met stage. simply and effectively, side panels were turned for indoor or outdoor scenes
the evening had a minor problem with hats. in the first scene, dame kiri had difficulty taking hers off, then it fell to the floor. then the easel on which miss quittmeyer's hat rested clattered over. later, hagegard's fur busby fell off. but nobody missed a beat. shipyard workers' participation in caucuses</head>
washington state has filed suit in federal court to challenge a navy claim that its civilian shipyard employees are barred by the federal hatch act from participating in today's presidential precinct caucuses
u.s. district judge jack tanner promised a ruling this morning
the state's suit contends that prohibiting federal workers from speaking at their party caucuses unconstitutionally violates their right to free speech, said david bryant, a spokesman for the washington secretary of state's office
bryant said the suit asks tanner to clarify the intent of the hatch act by interpreting ``conflicting sections'' of the regulations
a bill to revise the hatch act and allow workers to participate in partisan political activities on their own time overwhelmingly passed the u.s. house of representatives last year. it is still pending in the senate
the hatch act regulates political activities of federal workers
officials at the puget sound naval shipyard in bremerton told workers recently they can attend the political caucuses scheduled in neighborhoods across washington state tonight, but cannot discuss candidates
in washington, the precinct caucuses are the first step in the months-long process leading up to a selection of delegates to the national presidential nominating conventions this summer. at stake ultimately: 73 democratic national convention delegates and 41 gop delegates
the caucuses provide the only opportunity for most washington voters to express a preference for a presidential candidate
obviously, addressing the caucus is part of the activity,'' said james sommerhauser, representing professional and technical engineers local 12 in bremerton, but ``most federal employees are so intimidated by the hatch act they're afraid to participate.''
sommerhauser said his union represents 1,800 federal workers at the yard and elsewhere in kitsap county. the yard employs 11,600 people
rep. norm dicks, d-wash., whose district includes the shipyard, said over the weekend that the navy's ``outrageous'' claim that its civilian shipyard employees can't participate in the caucuses is one more good reason to change the hatch act
dicks commented after leaders of both major political parties said they thought the navy order violated free speech guarantees
shipyard spokesman bruce andrae earlier defended the order on the basis of the hatch act
that law includes one provision allowing a government employee to ``express his opinion as an individual privately and publicly on political subjects and candidates.''
but another provision cited by the navy forbids ``addressing a convention, caucus, rally or similar gathering of a political party in support of or in opposition to a partisan candidate for public office.''
yard workers learned of the issue when they read a page 1 article in the feb. 25 edition of the base newspaper that said: ``when the caucus discussion in favor of one candidate or another is held, you may not participate.''
laura baumgaertner, a spokeswoman for the washington, d.c., office of the merit system protection board, which enforces the law, agreed the law bars government workers from speaking up at caucuses
the soviet union's surprise call for security council condemnation of the iran-iraq ``war of the cities'' was greeted by western skepticism and renewed u.s. calls for an arms embargo against iran
iraq said the u.n. body should stick to its cease-fire resolution, while iran supported the soviet proposal and called again for condemnation of iraq
under the circumstances, the security council has to do something in order to eliminate the damage of the further escalation of the military conflict between iran and iraq,'' soviet ambassador alexander m. belonogov told reporters monday after closed-door security council consultation
but when asked whether the soviet union would approve an arms embargo, he did not reply directly and said more diplomatic efforts were needed
iran and iraq, fighting a 7{-year-old war, have fired dozens of missiles at each other's cities since last tuesday, killing hundreds of civilans
u.s. ambassador herbert okun told reporters after council consultations that a soviet resolution on the ``war of the cities'' should not ``undercut or erode'' security council resolution 598 of july 20 which demanded an immediate cease-fire and provided for sanctions against the belligerents
we don't need a new resolution. we need observance of the resolution which is already in front of us,'' he said
the united states has been pushing for an arms embargo against iran, and the 15-member security council is working on an embargo, but it has not been approved
iran on monday again called on the security council to condemn iraq for escalating the latest round of missile bombardment of tehran and baghdad
iraq is trying to spoil the atmosphere for a political settlement by escalating the current conflict,'' said iran's acting ambassador, mohammad ja'afar mahallati
the iraqi ambassador, ismat kittani, told reporters after the council session that his government will insist the council act within resolution 598 and that other action sought by the soviet union be secondary
moscow has been under international pressure to agree to punitive action against iran, or both belligerents. it has been wooing iran and is reluctant to impose an embargo against the tehran government
western diplomats said the new soviet proposal might be intended to deflect world criticism, delay an arms embargo resolution by the council and portray moscow in a positive light as an initiator of a strong peace proposal
some of the missiles used by both iran and iraq have been made in the soviet union, according to experts. but the soviet union denies that iraq is using soviet-made missiles in its bombardment of tehran
the soviet ambassador said he expected a meeting on the soviet request today or wednesday, but none was scheduled
jerry burns, editor of the san francisco chronicle's editorial page and a respected newsman at the paper for more than 20 years, has died of cancer at age 51
burns, who first sought care for his illness in august, died early monday at his home here with his family by his side
burns held several important positions during his career at the chronicle, including city hall reporter, chief political correspondent and city editor
former mayor dianne feinstein remembered burns' ``wonderful sense of humor, twinkling eyes and sharp wit.''
he was really concerned about what happened to the city,'' said feinstein, whose career burns covered. ``if his byline was on a story, it was reported fairly and squarely.''
chronicle editor and publisher richard t. thieriot said burns was ``universally beloved'' at the paper
as a journalist, jerry always saw both sides of complex issues fairly and objectively, and he maintained a solid intellectural integrity in the editorial pages,'' thieriot said
burns, who was born in hollywood on nov. 28, 1936, graduated in 1958 from the university of southern california. he later received a master's degree in journalism from university of california, los angeles
after working for the santa monica evening outlook, he was hired at the chronicle in 1964 as a night police reporter
three years later, burns was given the city hall beat, and in 1976, he was promoted to chief political correspondent. in 1979, he became city editor and in 1984 editorial page editor
survivors include his wife, marilyn burns, a son and daughter
a memorial service will be held thursday at temple emanu-el in san francisco
with a soviet deadline drawing closer, pressure is mounting on negotiators seeking a settlement to end the 9-year-old war in afghanistan
it remained uncertain monday whether pakistan, which is representing the afghan guerrillas and does not recognize the soviet-backed afghan government, will drop its demand for a broad-based transitional government to replace the existing regime after soviet troops withdraw
the transitional government could ensure the safe return of more than 5 million refugees from pakistan and iran because guerrillas vow to fight on if the soviet-backed government remains in power
sources close to the talks, which continue today, said the afghan government has shown some flexibility, giving hope that a compromise could be worked out, perhaps with pakistan signing the pact in return for assurances that an interim government would be formed within weeks
soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev says moscow will begin withdrawing its estimated 115,000 soldiers in mid-may if the accord is signed by mid-march
pakistani president zia ul-haq was quoted monday as saying an afghan peace accord must and will be signed soon
there is no question of the accord not going through,'' zia was quoted as telling the gulf news, a united arab emirates newspaper. ``allowing it to be dropped is no option.''
pakistan's chief representative in the peace talks, acting foreign minister zain noorani, said islamabad hopes for soviet cooperation, even though his country wants an interim government to replace the soviet-backed regime
it is in their interest, too, to see that there is peace and calm after they leave,'' said noorani after talks resumed monday after a weekend recess
a representative of the largest group in the seven-party alliance of moslem guerrillas reiterated on monday that the resistance is determined to fight on if a peace deal is struck on ``moscow's terms.''
speaking at a news conference, professor abdul kadir kariab said signing the settlement ``in the present shape will be a historic treason to the afghan people'' which he said was mourning 1.3 million dead
sources close to the u.n.-sponsored talks, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said negotiators seemed to remain cautiously optimistic that a peace package can be tied up by next week
they said the slow pace _ with monday meetings only during the morning _ did not indicate a deadlock
the talks moved speedily last week with agreement announced friday on the timetable and logistics of the proposed soviet troop withdrawal from afghanistan. this had been, according to u.n. mediator diego cordovez, the last major ``difference of substance.'' lithuanian-american</head>
the state department has confirmed that the soviet union is not allowing lithuanian-american povilas peciulaitis to emigrate despite a statement last december that he would be free to leave, according to rep. edward feighan
feighan, d-ohio, urged secretary of state george p. shultz to quickly intervene and monday requested a meeting with soviet ambassador yuri dubinin. he also sent a letter to soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev asking that the matter be resolved quickly
they have the audacity to tell us now that it was a mistake,'' feighan said of the soviets. ``if the soviets think i'm going to stand by and meekly accept this broken promise, they had better think again.''
peciulaitis, 64, was born in lithuania and exiled to siberia for 22 years, but his parents were naturalized american citizens
feighan said he fears for peciulaitis' personal safety, adding that verbal attacks against the man have recently appeared in newspapers and on television in lithuania
the justice department's nazi-hunting unit has identified 9,800 people as former concentration camp guards and says it will have them placed on the immigration watch list of individuals to be barred from the united states
the office of special investigations compiled the names with the assistance of a sophisticated new computer database
names of suspected criminals and nazi persecutors are systematically checked against immigration records to determine if they are in the united states
the names of individuals not found to be in this country are included in the watch list to prevent them from entering
a provision of a federal law, known as the holtzman amendment, was invoked when austrian president kurt waldheim was placed on the watch list last year following a decision by attorney general edwin meese iii
osi has listed thousands of such people in the past few years. but the 9,800 now to be placed on the watch list of the u.s. immigration and naturalization service ``for serving as concentration and death camp guards is probably the greatest number'' to be added at one time, said the office's chief, neal sher
the united states would welcome participation by north korean athletes in the seoul olympics, according to a senior u.s. diplomat
the olympics would be better off if north korea chooses to participate,'' said assistant secretary of state edward derwinski. ``but time is running out.''
he added that ``we have nothing but a positive attitude'' toward participation by pyongyang
derwinski said monday the united states will have ``some additional naval units'' in the region at the time of the september olympic games. speaking at the u.s. information agency's foreign press center, he said the additional naval presence was ``a very timely, practical coincidence.''
other u.s. officials have said the additional presence probably will consist of one or two aircraft carriers
derwinski warned that any attempt by the north koreans to disrupt the games ``would make them a total pariah.'' north korea is one of only a handful of countries, including cuba, which is boycotting the games
an airport in gambia will become an emergency landing site for the space shuttle under a new agreement between the united states and the african nation
gambia, africa's smallest nation, is a narrow strip of mango grove swamps, no more than 30 miles wide and 200 miles long, that snakes in from the atlantic ocean on the western coast of africa. it is surrounded by senegal
under the agreement, signed monday by ambassador herbert horowitz for the united states and m.c. cham, minister of works and communications for the government of gambia, the national aeronautics and space administration will locate specialized navigational aids at banjul airport
the landing strip would be used if a failure or poor performance of rockets causes the shuttle to fall short of the speed needed to get into orbit
banjul airport is almost directly below the normal flight path of a shuttle launched into a standard orbit
interested in a staple gun that joins broken bones? how about a ceramic sushi knife that leaves no trace of that unpleasant metallic aftertaste? or maybe a robot caddy for golfing?
these and other innovations are on display at this year's national design and engineering show, intended to give engineers a vision of ``products of the future,'' said jim greif, a show spokesman
the theme of the maze of exhibits at the mccormick place exposition center is ``the impact of product design on global competitiveness,'' greif said
although our exports have gone up since the dollar's decline, they haven't gone up nearly as much as people had predicted,'' greif said. ``most american companies are not geared for selling abroad.''
take refrigerator exports, for example
the american refrigerator market was basically killed off'' because an 18-cubic-foot fridge won't fit in a typical kitchen in developing countries, said another show spokesman, dave dasgupta
if you send these bulky things abroad, you don't have a market for it,'' he said. by contrast, when the japanese began selling cars in the united states, they totally redesigned the interiors to suit americans' larger physiques and longer legs
the four-day show, which began monday and is sponsored by the american society of mechanical engineers, features exhibits by 763 companies from 40 states, japan, canada, austria and britain
among the more unusual products featured is the japanese-made ceramic knife
developed by kyocera corp. of kyoto, the knife is used by restaurants in japan but has not been marketed to consumers in this country, said joe lewis, a district sales manager for kyocera's american subsidiary
the $35 knife is made of zirconia, a ceramic material that is tougher than ordinary ceramics, lighter than steel, sharp enough to slice flesh and cuts a smoother, less jagged line than ordinary knives, lewis said
the staplizer surgical staple gun, introduced about a year ago, is being used by scores of hospitals in the united states and abroad, said design engineer edward p. skwor, who developed it for the orthopedic products division of 3m in st. paul, minn
with the press of a trigger, the hand-held gun punches office-sized staples into a broken bone, helping it heal in place, skwor said. the staples aren't removed
staples allow the surgeon to do his job quicker and easier,'' skwor said. when those patients are back on their feet, and if their budgets aren't quite depleted, they might find use for the $2,350 robot golf caddy, a remote-controlled device resembling a grown-up tricycle
the golfer simply attaches a small electronic transmitter to his waistband, and the caddy follows him around the course, carrying golf clubs, balls and even highballs while keeping a proper 3{ feet to 4 feet behind, said bill reilly, chief electronic engineer at gettig engineering in spring mills, pa
lawyers for a youth accused of bludgeoning a classmate to death for a thrill rested their case after psychiatrists gave conflicting testimony about whether the defendant had a chronic psychotic disorder
closing arguments were expected to be delivered this afternoon
rod matthews, 15, of canton, has admitted killing 14-year-old shaun ouillette, but defense attorneys contend matthews was unable to control himself because of a mental disorder aggravated by his use of a drug prescribed to hyperactive youths
prosecutors say matthews, who is on trial as an adult, clubbed ouillette to death with a baseball bat for a thrill
classmates have testified that matthews took them to view the body in a wooded area where it remained for three weeks after the november 1986 killing
dr. kenneth holbert, director of the state's gaebler children's center in waltham, testified that while matthews has had a long-term mental illness that may have contributed to his behavior, he should have been able to control his actions the day he killed ouillette
i don't believe he was suffering from a chronic psychotic disorder,'' holbert said. ``he could have used his cognitive strengths to behave in another manner.''
but dr. bernard yudowitz of belmont's mclean hospital said matthews ``was suffering from an atypical psychosis which in every manner impaired his ability to conform his conduct to the standards of law.''
matthews first decided to kill someone after viewing the videotape faces of death, which shows animal and human killings and tortures, said yudowitz. he said matthews' use of the drug ritalin may have made it harder for him to control himself
matthews did not kill for reasons of vengeance but ``to get rid of the urge to kill,'' said yudowitz, a former director of bridgewater state hospital
yudowitz said he knows of hundreds of cases in which children and adults are misdiagnosed as hyperactive and given ritalin
there is no way of knowing what the exact effect ritalin had'' on matthews, said yudowitz. ``there was a distinct possibility'' it contributed to a loss of impulse control, he said
assistant norfolk county district attorney peter casey questioned the methodical manner with which matthews approached the killing of ouillette and the cover-up of the killing
yudowitz said that the methodical nature of the act ``in no way contradicts the fact that rod matthews is an extremely sick individual. it's consistent with this boy having a disturbed mind.''
former friends have said matthews told them he wanted to see what it was like to kill someone. they said he named several potential victims before settling on ouillette
the teen-agers testified last week about viewing ouillette's body only hours after a pre-thanksgiving pep rally, then bicycling with matthews to a shopping mall pizza parlor for a snack. detail of new law, opposition leaders vowing to fight it. pickup 12th graf pvs ``differences on...''</note>
the governing democratic justice party declared its new set of election laws passed early tuesday despite attempts by members of the opposition to disrupt the national assembly session
the bill was passed in less than a minute after a plenary session was called at 2:10 a.m
deputy speaker chang sung-man declared it passed when members of the governing party on the floor said, ``no objection.''
opposition lawmakers had tried to stop passage by occupying the speaker's platform since the previous night. a pushing-and-shoving contest began when some governing party memebrs tried to remove them
chang had to use a back door to reach the podium
the governing party has 160 of the 276 seats in the national assembly, more than the simple majority required to pass the bill. assembly officials said they could not say immediately how many governing party lawmakers were present when the bill was declared passed, but most were believed to be there
opposition lawmakers protested the passage, but the spokesman for the governing party said it was unavoidable because the new constitution requires legislative elections to be held by april 28
the trouble was caused by a last-minute opposition demand to change some parts of the bill, including the the total number of lawmakers, poll watching in barracks and campaign methods
a new system of electing one lawmaker in each constituency instead of two is at the heart of the proposed changes. that would handicap the governing party in big cities and the opposition in rural areas, where there are far more election districts
the new bills would increase membership in the national assembly to 299
under the proposals, 224 members would be chosen by direct popular vote and 75 under a proportional system based on each party's total vote. the opposition wants to increase the number of lawmakers to more than 330
the new legislation also limits the number of campaign rallies in any district to three joint meetings including all candidates. it bans any rallies by individual parties, prohibits street campaigning with loudspeakers and would exclude appearances by national political leaders
opposition leaders said they would fight to overturn the sections of the law that limit campaigning, but it was unclear how they could succeed
differences on election laws have caused friction between the two main opposition parties. they hope to merge in time for the legislative election to avoid the defeat they suffered in december's presidential ballot by running rival candidates
they agreed on the new election formula last week, but a dispute over future leadership created a new split
kim young-sam's reunification democratic party said rival kim dae-jung must take a back seat in a new party, but kim dae-jung's party for peace and democracy described the demand as ``meddling in private matters.''
dr. william masters and virginia johnson have created a stir in the medical community with their latest book, but that's nothing new after more than 30 years of pioneering research into human sexuality
criticism of the couple's new book, ``crisis: heterosexual behavior in the age of aids,'' focused monday on its claim that the epidemic is ``running rampant in the heterosexual community.''
the authors acknowledged using a relatively small and unscientifically chosen sample of sexually active heterosexuals, but said they had enough information to sound an alarm about a group that may not realize how much it is at risk
their first landmark book, ``human sexual responses,'' is said to have radically changed the way sex is viewed
research for that book began in 1957 with an unprecedented seven-year study of sexual response, research that included the observation of volunteers and prostitutes engaged in intercourse or masturbation
many credit their research with helping spur the so-called sexual revolution and opening up human sexuality as a topic for mainstream newspapers and magazines
in 1970, masters and johnson's book ``human sexual inadequacy'' was a best seller. it carried the authors' assertion that 79 percent of their female patients treated for inability to reach a climax had responded successfully to therapy originated by masters and johnson
the book brought great attention to the masters and johnson institute of st. louis, a non-profit clinic where couples receive therapy for sexual dysfunction
in the early 1980s, two pyschologists from berkeley, calif., bernie zilbergeld and michael evans, challenged the masters and johnson claims of treatment success rates of nearly 80 percent. the critics said the couple had failed to disclose the criteria used for evaluating success
other therapists said they were unable to duplicate the masters and johnson success record even when using the couple's techniques
evans and zilbergeld made their first assault in psychology today in august 1980, accusing masters and johnson of ``research so flawed by methodological errors and slipshod reporting that it fails to meet customary standards _ even their own _ for evaluation research.''
zilbergeld claimed that in 1982, he and evans met masters at a professional conference and that masters spelled out his success criteria for treatment of sexual dysfunction in women: the woman should reach climax at least once during the two-week intensive therapy period and at least once again during a five-year follow-up period
masters has since denied making any such statement. he also has lashed out at critics and defended his research
in a field plagued by real and troubling problems which deserve the best effort of the best minds, it is indeed unfortunate that we must devote any energy to absurd allegations,'' masters said, as he defended his research before a scientific forum in washington, d.c., a few years ago
masters graduated from the university of rochester medical school and did his residency in 1943 at maternity hospital in st. louis. he then joined the faculty of the washington university medical school in st. louis
masters met johnson when the school's placement office sent her to interview for a job in the obstetrics and gynecology department
they began working together jan. 2, 1957, and married jan. 7, 1971. both had been married before
johnson, who once described herself as ``a perpetual student,'' said she pursued an advanced degree in social anthropology until about age 50, when she gave up
just when i got things going academically, he would start something spectacular and he would suggest that i might be on hand for it.''
the dollar fell sharply in tokyo today following declines on overseas markets, and stock prices fell too
the dollar closed at 127.80 yen, down 1.07 yen from monday. it opened today's trading at 127.75 yen, and ranged between 127.70 yen and 127.95 yen
on the tokyo stock exchange, the 225-share nikkei stock average, which fell 10.99 points monday, lost another 150.85 points, or 0.59 percent, ending the day at 25,465.73. volume was 800 million shares, light compared with last friday's turnover of 1.3 billion
dealers said the dollar's lower opening reflected its decline monday on overseas markets, where traders sold dollars to buy british pounds because of higher interest rates in britain
the u.s. currency rose slightly during tokyo trading because of profit-taking and covering of dollar-short positions by traders, they added
a lack of follow-up selling from corporate players including japanese exporters is prompting traders to cover short positions,'' said masaharu takenaka, a senior currency trader for the bank of tokyo
the weaker dollar dragged down prices on the stock exchange, where traders stayed on the sidelines waiting for a market adjustment following recent sharp gains
the market is clearly very tired,'' said ron napier, a vice president at salomon brothers. he said rising interest rates also have dampened buying sentiment in tokyo. ``we've seen a very dull market, and that's the way it's going to be for a while,'' he said. test scores</head>
a 12-state study found that advanced math and science courses and family income were more important factors than ethnicity in how hispanic high school students scored on college entrance tests
the study of 1,928 hispanic and non-hispanic white students, presented monday to the national association of secondary school principals, also found that scores of both groups increased with the size of schools they attended
george a. chambers, professor of educational administration at the university of iowa, and researcher phyllis s. peterson studied 1987 scores on the american college test, the predominant college admission test in 28 states
the purpose of the study was to compare how hispanic students and caucasian students score when the two groups are similarly situated,'' chambers said
students in the study were from arizona, california, colorado, florida, illinois, kansas, louisiana, nevada, new mexico, oklahoma, texas and utah
the students were divided equally among two groups identified as caucasian and hispanic, which included two subdivisions of mexican-americans and puerto ricans, cubans and others
the study created 964 pairs of one hispanic and one non-hispanic white student matched on the basis of 13 common attributes: high school, family income range, mathematics courses (algebra 1, algebra 2, geometry, trigonometry, calculus), science courses (general science, biology, chemistry, physics), gender and number of siblings
according to the study, the u.s. average composite act score is 15.2 for mexican-americans, 16.6 for the puerto-rican-cuban group, and 19.6 for non-hispanic whites. the act is scored on a scale of one to 36 and is taken annually by more than 1 million students
when matched, or ``similarly situated,'' the non-hispanics had a mean score of 18.7 compared with 16.7 for the mexican-american group, a difference of just two points instead of the national difference of 4.4 points
the non-hispanics scored 19.8 and puerto rican-cuban students scored 18.9 when similarly situated, a difference in composite score points of just 0.9 rather than the three points in the u.s. average
in addition, chambers said, the statistical analysis found that course work is more important than the level of income in determining scores
he said, however, that the higher the income level, the greater the tendency for a student to take advanced courses. that is probably because of factors such as the expectations of parents who have college educations, he said
it's not income necessarily in and of itself that makes the difference. rather, it's the things that result from income,'' chambers said
so we need to find a way to raise the expectations. we must overcome this force of income.''
the study also found that when schools were grouped into five categories according to the size of the graduating class, ranging from less than 200 to 900 or more, hispanic and non-hispanic scores went up with size, possibly because the larger schools have an expanded curriculum. each recorded an overall gain of two points
while many believe big is bad, if you look at the data here, it suggests big is better,'' chambers said
the principals' association, which was meeting here this week, represents 38,000 educators in middle, junior high and high schools nationwide. ^washington wire: gop vents fury on order to arrest absent senators</note>
fuming and sputtering, the senate is writing a new chapter in the long and tumultuous history of the legislative filibuster
actually the chapter is written, but the fuming and sputtering about it continue unabated
the other side needs to vent itself from time to time, and this is one of those occasions,'' said sen. alan simpson, r-wyo., the senate's acting minority leader, as senate republicans engaged in four hours of complaint about it last week
crybaby stuff!'' exclaimed senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., who initiated the order to the senate sergeant-at-arms to compel the attendance of absent senators
the facts:
on feb. 23, after midnight, as the senate was deep into an old-fashioned, all-night, republican-led filibuster against a congressional campaign financing bill sought by majority democrats, an arrest warrant was issued for gop senators whose flight from the senate chamber prevented the quorum needed to do business
such a warrant was issued on sen. bob packwood, r-ore., who had locked himself in his senate office. packwood was carried onto the senate floor, feet first, and the quorum was established
keystone cops,'' republican senators cried
a low comedy about a legislature in a banana republic,'' steamed new york republican sen. alfonse d'amato
i am afraid we are playing a giant game of `gotcha,' to see who can get the other side,'' said sen. daniel evans, r-wash
under this arrest warrant for senators does the sergeant-at-arms have the right to enter my home?'' evans asked. ``does he have the right to seize me from my bed, for heavens' sake, in order to return me to the senate floor?''
the rules permit us to delay things for endless periods of time and to stay here all night and to arrest each other, and if all we do is to exhaust what is permitted under the rules then we create real havoc,'' said sen. john c. danforth, r-mo
why should a u.s. senator be arrested for less cause than a common criminal?'' asked sen. arlen specter, r-pa
hold on, said sen. george mitchell, d-maine, a former federal judge. the warrant was issued only to compel packwood's attendance on the senate floor, ``that is, do that which the senator was elected to do.''
there was nothing criminal about it, mitchell said
the rule in question is based on the provision in the constitution establishing a simple majority of the house and the senate as the number needed to establish a quorum to do business and authorizing a smaller number ``to compel the presence of absent members, in such manner, and under such penalties as each house may provide.''
each house has so provided, and when virtually all republican senators disappeared, the sergeant-at-arms was authorized to compel their presence. hence the packwood arrest
led by specter, several republican senators demanded the rules be changed to bar the arrest of senators between the hours of 11 p.m. and 8 a.m., among other things
byrd said that would ``cement in stone the ability of senators to stop any action simply by hiding in their offices.''
the senate arrest was not a game,'' byrd said. ``it was not a laughing matter
imagine senators, who are supposed to be grown-up people, adults, elected by the people to serve here _ and most senators would have given their right arm to serve here _ imagine seeing them run down the hall, run when they see the sergeant-at-arms. they made a calculated decision to run and hide, barricade their offices, put chairs against the doors.''
now they want to cry about it,'' byrd said. ``it was not the arrest that caused us to look bad. it was the spectacle of senators running to avoid coming to the senate floor. ... we are not elected to play games like children.''
the complaints and the counter complaints rolled on and finally there was a final complaint
the arrest warrants that were written but not served had been destroyed
many republican members said they wanted copies as mementos
never in my 63 years have i had an arrest warrant issued,'' evans told the senate
because it was unique i asked if i could have a copy so that i could put it in my scrapbook and have it available to show my children and my grandchildren,'' he said
now i find they are, somehow, not available.'' destroy it</head>
a woman who built an 80-ton wooden ark from salvaged timber is dismantling part of the vessel in an effort to beat a court deadline ordering it off a church's property
but kea tawana, who calls the ark her ``life's sweat and blood,'' says she needs more time to move the 86-foot-long craft, which has been termed a work of art by the american museum of folk art but an eyesore by the city
it's consumed 20 years of my life. short of a miracle ... the ark is doomed,'' tawana said
tawana had been working under a march 31 court deadline to move the ark from the parking lot of the humanity baptist church to newark bay, three-quarters of a mile away. superior court judge harry a. margolis recently extended the deadline until april 15
but tawana, who says she built the ark from oak, hemlock and pine to live in, not for religious reasons, says she needs more time to dismantle part of it for the move and obtain coast guard approval of the ship's seaworthiness
bad weather this winter prevented work on the ship from continuing,'' tawana said, adding that she will ask margolis at a march 22 hearing for a 90-day extension. ``april 15 does not give me enough time to render the ship floatable.''
tawana said she plans to sail the ark to the great lakes region and live there, although she did not say where
newark officials have long wanted the ark torn down. the city went to court over the issue, saying it was an eyesore and health hazard and violated zoning laws
however, margolis last spring prohibited the city from destroying it after the american museum of folk art in new york city wrote to mayor sharpe james and gov. thomas h. kean, urging them to preserve the structure
the ark is a very important and very rare example of urban folk art expression,'' said didi barrett, the museum's director of publications
the humanity baptist church had allowed tawana to live on the property as a caretaker in a ramshackle house next to the ark until last year, when it ended the relationship, saying that the court battle over the ark cost too much
the city wants to drive me out and turn this over to developers for condominiums,'' tawana said
but audrey davidson, assistant corporate counsel for newark, said zoning laws are the issue
i have no idea whether the city is trying to build something there. all i know is that the structure there is illegal,'' ms. davidson said
tawana said she will cut 4 feet off beams in the ark to reduce the vessel's height to 17 feet from 21 feet so it will not get snagged on cables running over streets on the trip to newark bay
the governing party rammed an election law that limits campaigning through the legislature today over the objection of opposition lawmakers who seized the podium and started a scuffle
leaders of the governing democratic justice party, protected by guards, ended hours of furious arguments and scuffling by suddenly calling for a vote and declaring the bill passed before the opposition could react
the governing party, which has a strong majority in the national assembly, passed the bill by a voice vote in a few seconds
opposition lawmakers rushed to the podium to try to drag down vice speaker chang sung-man and halt the vote but were blocked by assembly guards
outraged opposition representatives screamed insults at democratic justice party leaders after they were caught by surprise
the new law revises the assembly's constituency system to one lawmaker per district instead of two and clears the way for elections expected to be held in late april. the number of seats will increase from 276 to 299
the new law also limits the number of campaign rallies in any district to three joint meetings including all candidates. it bans any rallies by individual parties, prohibits street campaigning with loudspeakers and excludes appearances by national political leaders
opposition leaders said they would fight to overturn the sections of the law that limit campaigning, but it was unclear how they could succeed
opposition lawmakers occupied the podium for almost three hours to prevent passage of the bill after dragging the vice speaker from his chair and scuffling with government legislators
the government broke the deadlock when chang surrounded by guards suddenly took to the podium, called for a voice vote and passed the bill
kim tae-ryong, spokesman of the opposition reunification democratic party, said the government's actions proved it did not support democracy
the bill contains various malicious clauses designed to steal votes,'' he said after the bill was passed
the government, which had favored retention of the existing two member system, changed its position after the opposition repeatedly blocked attempts in the assembly to pass a new election law. the law had to be passed to hold elections scheduled to be held by april
opposition leaders said the bill would place excessive restrictions on campaigning
the opposition also wanted open counting of absentee ballots, charging that the government has used absentee ballots in the past to rig elections
the dispute, which lasted for almost two months, reflected the opposition's refusal to work with the government and deep divisions between the two sides
opposition leaders continue to insist that president roh tae-woo and the governing party won presidential elections in december through massive fraud. some top opposition leaders have refused to recognize roh's election
roh won with less than 50 percent of the vote because two opposition leaders split the opposition vote
the new law is expected to diminish the government's electoral chances in urban areas where it lacks sufficient strength to win majorities. the governing party had counted on coming in second in urban areas in the past to gain seats
but the governing party is also expected to gain in rural areas under the new system since it is strongest in the countryside. roh has promised broad democratic reforms to end decades of authoritarian rule and has said that elections will be fair and democratic
the bill increases the number of electoral districts from 184 to 224 and provides for one lawmaker per district
the existing system, whereby the winning party gets two-thirds of 92 bonus seats, also was changed so that it gets half of 75 bonus seats with the rest being divided among other parties on the basis of votes
the bonus system is designed to avoid deadlock in the assembly by giving the main party a clear majority
the new york post has officially become the property of real estate developer peter kalikow, who paid $37.6 million for the tabloid that has been losing money and circulation for years
it is my intention to stop the financial losses of the new york post,'' kalikow said monday in a statement after the papers transferring ownership were signed. ``the paper will be a winner financially and editorially.''
kalikow acquired the post after the paper's 10 unions agreed to a $22 million in concessions, which included a last-minute $3 million gift from then-owner rupert murdoch
the rescue of the post is nothing less than an historic moment,'' kalikow said
there was not one person involved in negotiations that did not go the extra mile in an effort to keep this great new york institution from disappearing. i want to thank all of our unions and employees for their heroic efforts.''
union leaders were to sign formal papers today and planned to meet with kalikow on thursday to ``get to know each other,'' said george mcdonald, president of the allied printing trades council, which represents eight of the unions
we're delighted, really delighted, glad it's all over.''
murdoch, who sold the paper to comply with federal regulations barring ownership of two media outlets in one city, claimed he was losing $100,000 a day on the post and lost $150 million in the 12 years he owned it
kalikow has pledged $2 million to promote the newspaper
i am committed to expanding its readership base through millions of dollars in promotion, adding features to the paper, greatly expanding its investigative reporting and strengthening its advertising revenues to make the paper profitable on a long-term basis.''
under murdoch, whom kalikow called ``one of the great contemporary publishers,'' the tabloid had a reputation for sensational coverage, with blaring headlines and plenty of gossip
new publisher peter price said ``my role is to make it work
i think peter kalikow has made an enormous financial commitment and it's my challenge and opportunity to put the pieces together and make a real business out of the post and not just a good newspaper,'' price said
spokesman howard rubenstein declined to say what specific changes kalikow and price would make in the appearance and content of the post, the nation's oldest continuously published daily newspaper, founded in 1801 by alexander hamilton
price, however, noted that ``the big difference between what we are able to do versus what others before us have tried to do is that peter kalikow and i share a sense of the city
we are both single-minded about the new york post. we are both single-minded about making this paper a permanent fixture in the new york city scene.''
hasan ahmed sat near a pile of rust-colored bricks, using a small bar of metal to pound the bricks into gravel
it was election day, declared a national holiday by the government and a nationwide general strike by the political opposition
sixty-year-old ahmed knew nothing about the holiday or strike, but he knew he needed his 50 cents in daily earnings
the turmoil of the parliamentary elections last week, in which 13 people died in clashes, passed by ahmed who still has four children at home. but he and the more than 80 million other bangladeshis who live below the poverty line still are caught up in its results
the election made no immediate headway in ending the stalemate between president hussain muhammad ershad and major opposition parties demanding his ouster
ershad, whose jatiya party won a predictable parliamentary majority, refuses to resign. the opposition vows to keep up its nearly four-month campaign of general strikes that is eroding the already weak economy
economic growth was an expected 5 percent this year, but the strikes and severe floods last summer have reduced the projection to 2 percent
we are in very bad shape,'' said a.s. mahmud, president of the dhaka chamber of commerce and industry. ``the politicians, they don't think of or try to understand the impact on the economy.''
mahmud said the 25 days of general strikes called since november last year were deeply affecting the country's new garment industry and could scare off foreign investment
the country of 105 million people has an estimated 30 percent unemployment and under-employment. more than 80 percent of the people live below the poverty line, defined by the world health organization as not earning enough for a diet of 1,800 calories daily. about 80 percent also are illiterate
while mahmud talked in terms of long-range economic consequences, abdul ghafoor saw more immediate effects of the political turmoil. it means trouble in feeding his family
ghafoor, 45, drives a bicycle rickshaw and has a wife and six children. he averages about $1.65 in earnings daily and says he does not work on a strike day for fear of being attacked by workers for opposition parties
we have no savings. we suffer that day,'' he said
ghafoor said he saw little hope that the election, which ershad called in a move to compromise with the opposition, would lead to such a compromise
how can i think that any of these people care about us?'' he asked. ``no leader has done anything for the poor.''
politicians and diplomats, who talked about the election results on the basis of anonymity, had more sophisticated judgments on the likelihood of a compromise. but they also expressed doubts one could be achieved
ershad, a former general who took power in a bloodless coup in 1982, still has strong backing from the army, meaning another coup soon seems unlikely. in bangladesh, a military takeover is always a possibility since every change in government in the country's 17 years of independence has been achieved by coup
the opposition, which claims ershad's 1986 election as president resulted from vote rigging, has failed to unseat the 58-year-old ershad despite the violent general strikes that led to at least 25 deaths
stepping up the violence could prompt ershad to reimpose the martial law in effect from 1982 to 1986 or could anger the public by devastating the economy
westerners in lhasa today said security forces had withdrawn from around the tibetan capital's main temple, where monks led a violent weekend protest that beijing said left hundreds of police injured
in the fullest official account yet of the rioting against chinese rule, the chinese news service today said more than 300 police were injured in the rioting saturday and sunday in lhasa. previous official reports had said that one policeman was killed and 28 injured in a single day of rioting
the fighting occurred in lhasa at the jokhang, tibet's holiest temple
one westerner in lhasa, a tibetan-speaking traveler, said tibetans told him five tibetans and three chinese police were killed in daylong violence saturday, the last day of a major prayer festival
another traveler, who arrived today chengdu, 750 miles east of lhasa, said officials told him two people were killed _ a chinese policeman who was pushed off a roof and a tibetan. both travelers spoke on condition of anonymity
the china news service said 30 police officers were hospitalized with serious injuries and ``numerous'' civilians were hurt in the violence _ the second nationalist riots in lhasa since october
in an eyewitness report seen in hong kong, the agency claimed the disturbances were plotted by unidentified tibetans who had bags of rocks placed on top of buildings around the central barkhor marketplace. it said buddhist monks on saturday poisoned tea given to officials and journalists, who had to be hospitalized. the report did not elaborate on their condition
during the rioting, local government and communist party officials were forced to slide down ropes from a second-story office in the jokhang to escape enraged monks, said the account by reporter geng jun. he said the officials slid to safety just before the monks broke down the office door
the report said ``some rioters set up barricades in barkhor marketplace on sunday morning and indiscriminately threw stones that injured numerous city residents.''
one monk stood up and started shouting for independence and he was arrested,'' the western traveler in lhasa said by telephone. ``the monks started throwing stones. the crowd just ran.''
he said authorities hustled him and other foreigners to their hotels. but when he left his room a few hours later to get food, he encountered a clash in the square in front of the johkang
i found myself in the middle of a skirmish. some tear gas went off near me. twenty to 30 tibetans were throwing stones at chinese soliders and the chinese soldiers were throwing stones back.''
the traveler said the chinese did not open fire. ``in that sense, the chinese were showing a lot of restraint.''
there have been no official figures given on arrests, but unconfirmed reports have said hundreds were rounded up
westerners in lhasa said johkang remained closed today but police on monday stopped blocking entry to the barkhor market square. they said uniformed police had been replaced by dozens of plainclothes officers who closely followed the few foreign tourists in town and would not allow them to take pictures
william tang, assistant foreign manager at the lhasa hotel, said guests were being told they could go to the square but ``at their own risk.''
the violence was the first in lhasa since oct. 1, when 2,000 tibetans led by monks burned down a police station facing jokhang temple. police opened fire, and at least 14 people were killed in the battle
the dalai lama, tibet's exiled spiritual leader china blames for instigating the riots, issued a statement from his office in new delhi on monday saying ``the courage of the tibetan people in expressing, once again, their dissatisfaction against chinese rule in spite of the obvious risk involved clearly reveal their desperation.''
the dalai lama, who fled following a failed uprising in 1959, also called on tibetans to ``restrain from violence.''
china says tibet has been part of the nation for centuries, and claims it is making amends for past polices that suppressed tibetan customs and religion and destroyed many of their temples
antagonisms remain strong, however, between the tibetans and the hans, china's ethnic majority who hold most of the top government posts in lhasa
the western traveler said tibetans told him police beat two monks to death inside the jokhang. several tibetans later carried the monks' bodies around the square, he said, triggering further clashes
television and movie producers scrambled to hire replacement scriptwriters and urged strikers to cross picket lines today in an effort to keep hollywood game shows and soap operas on the air
but the scriptwriters vowed to wait out the struggle as nearly 2,000 of them marched five abreast in front of 20th century fox studios monday, the first day of a walkout over demands for higher fees and more creative control
hollywood has treated writers like bean-field workers for years,'' said screenwriter and science-fiction author harlan ellison. ``it begins with the dream. without the dream on paper there is nothing.''
the writers guild of america rejected sunday's final offer by the alliance of motion picture and television producers and a strike was ordered for 9,000 members
the wga strike is the fourth since a 17-week walkout in 1973. the longest, in 1981, lasted three months
nick counter, the alliance's president and chief negotiator, predicted the walkout may be a long one. ``it's the same kind of feeling as we had in 1981,'' he said. ``this could go on even longer than that.''
issues include demands by writers for a higher percentage of foreign market distribution fees and more control over scripts, and a producers' demand to scale back syndication fees for one-hour television shows. producers say new shows made for independent stations have dried up the rerun syndication market
for some pickets like james l. brooks, whose writing credits include the films ``broadcast news'' and ``terms of endearment'' and television's ``the mary tyler moore show,'' a key battle was for creative control
if you take creative rights from enough different groups, you end up without a creation, you end up with something else. you end up with an exercise in marketing,'' brooks said
counter said producers may begin hiring temporary replacements for striking writers until a settlement is reached
our companies are encouraging whoever wants to come forward to write these scripts,'' he said, urging union and non-union writers to cross picket lines
counter said non-guild writers were being sought to avoid having soap operas and game shows go to reruns. the union said talk shows also would be among the first to suffer from the walkout
however, spokespersons for cbs and nbc said soap operas such as ``days of our lives,'' ``as the world turns,'' and ``the young and the restless'' shouldn't be affected soon because of stockpiled scripts
it's business as usual. we're prepared,'' cbs spokeswoman janet storm said
nbc's ``late night with david letterman'' and ``saturday night live,'' already were on scheduled breaks this week. ``the tonight show with johnny carson'' on monday featured guest host jay leno, who used material prepared before the strike
the guild's contract expired feb. 29. the median annual income for writers is $40,000, but about half of the wga's members are unemployed at any given time
israelis who spent nearly an hour on a bus with three armed guerrillas said they tried to stay calm, even offering one captor some milk, but finally became convinced ``we're not getting out of this alive.''
one wrote a final note to her three children. another laid down and thought: ``that's it, goodbye.''
three israelis _ two women and a man _ were killed monday during the incident in southern israel along with the three plo guerrillas
the bus' other eight passengers, workers on the way to their jobs at the dimona nuclear plant, were all injured during the ordeal
the palestine liberation organization claimed responsibility for the attack. the army said the guerrillas infiltrated from egypt
while israeli officials were negotiating with the three guerrillas to try to end the standoff, ``we tried to create a calm atmosphere,'' stella bechar, 46, who was hospitalized with multiple shrapnel and gunshot wounds, told the daily jerusalem post. ``each one had a gun, a kalashnikov, ready to shoot.''
some of the israelis aboard the bus spoke some arabic
i asked one (of the guerrillas) if he wanted some milk because he said he was thirsty,'' mrs. bechar said. ``we even tried to joke with each other, and we told each other that there is a god and we would get out of this alive.''
as negotiations continued, said fellow hostage daisy sorek, ``the terrorists were getting more and more impatient'' and threatened to kill a hostage every half hour if a red cross negotiator was not summoned
at one point he (one of the guerrillas) got a megaphone and became very, very agitated. he said, over and over in arabic, ``every half-hour, one,'' mrs. sorek said
the leader of the gang then called one passenger, victor ram, and ordered him to stand at the front of the bus, sorek told the post
then they shot him in the chest and he just fell, immediately. and then we knew: we're not getting out of this alive,'' she said. ``they seemed very confused. after they shot ram, the commander's gun didn't work anymore. something was wrong with it.''
i told them `it's such a shame, you're so young. you don't have to do this,''' rachel matza, who was recovering from surgery to remove shrapnel, told the post. ``but they said `no, we're going to die and we're going to blow you up with us.' ... we felt we were dead women.''
mrs. bechar remembers little of the rescue operation except laying down next to a pile of purses that the guerrillas had searched through
i remembered that on television they always say it's a good idea to lie down,'' she said. ``then i closed my eyes and i remember thinking, `that's it, goodbye.'''
mrs. sorek said while she was held on the bus she wrote a note to her three children. ``i wrote to them to ask the government to speed matters along between jews and arabs, to do something,'' she said
only with a peace agreement are we going to get anywhere.''
masters and johnson may have expertise in sexuality, but they have no credentials to justify their recommendations concerning aids public health policy _ recommendations that will surely alarm the public.'' _ mathilde krim, chairwoman of the american foundation for aids research, commenting on claims by the famed sex researchers that aids is spreading widely among heterosexuals
imagine senators, who are supposed to be grown-up people, adults, elected by the people to serve here _ and most senators would have given their right arm to serve here _ imagine seeing them run down the hall, run when they see the sergeant-at-arms.'' _ senate majority leader robert c. byrd, d-w.va., defending his decision to order the arrests of republican senators who left the chamber to prevent a quorum
it stings that ... we never got treated like that. it hurts when i think that they're getting that much money.'' _ betty grissom, who received $350,000 for the death of her astronaut husband, gus, in the 1967 apollo spacecraft fire, on the $7.7 million settlement reached by the families of four victims of the challenger explosion
specially trained u.s. drug agents are venturing into the bolivian jungle with local forces in a program that targets drug trafficking and may soon be expanded to other countries, a federal official said
the program, which began last year, is reportedly the first putting u.s. drug enforcement administration agents alongside local forces in south american countryside. the agents work in an advisory capacity, the san diego union reported today
the assistance was requested by bolivia and will be expanded into five other south american countries that have also requested the service, dea chief john lawn told the newspaper. he refused to identify the other countries
this is a significant step for dea because we have countries seeking the kind of assistance that we want to provide,'' lawn said. ``we believe this operation will have an impact in the u.s. and european cocaine market.''
u.s. drug agents previously have concentrated their anti-drug efforts in the region's urban areas, but agents sometimes worked in undercover at a host country's request, lawn said
under the program, volunteer u.s. drug agents undergo a three-month training program that includes a weapons course at the marine training base at quantico, va., a language program, and a jungle survival school led by the u.s. army special forces in panama, he said
the first graduates were sent to bolivia last fall
some u.s. agents trained in the program were involved in the tracking down of two major bolivian cocaine labs two months ago, lawn said. twelve suspects were indicted on drug trafficking conspiracy charges as a result of that investigation
in addition, bolivian pilots are using u.s. helicopters to find and disrupt the drying of coca leaves
mercedes-benz of north america has announced its fourth price increase since march 1987 because of the continuing weakness of the dollar against the west german mark
mercedes said monday prices on nine of its 13 models will increase an average 1.6 percent on cars delivered to dealers starting april 18
the three least expensive mercedes models, the 190es, will not be affected by the increases, which will boost the price of the next model, the 260 e sedan, to $37,845 from $37,250
at the other extreme, the price of 560sec will jump to $77,065 from $75,850, said mercedes spokesman a.b. shuman
iran and iraq today fired more missiles at each other's capitals, and iran accused the united states and france of helping iraq refit soviet-designed missiles to give them enough range to hit tehran
the charge was made by iranian parliament speaker hashemi rafsanjani
before the latest round of the so-called ``war of the cities'' began feb. 29, iraq had been unable to hit tehran with surface-to-surface missiles because the city is nearly 300 miles from the iraqi border
iran's official islamic republic news agency reported that an iraqi missile crashed into a residential neighborhood of tehran early today, killing or wounding ``several'' civilians and damaging a church
state-run baghdad radio reported that iraqi gunners fired the missile into tehran, a city of 6 million people, less than an hour after iran claimed it had lobbed a projectile into baghdad
iraq's news agency confirmed the latest iranian missile strike on a residential area in baghdad, saying civilians, including women, children and eldery people, were killed. no figures were given
irna also said revolutionary guards today shot a missile at a ``military center'' at amarah, an iraqi town close to the border and halfway between baghdad and the southern port city of basra
iraqi statements made no mention of the amarah strike
the reports were monitored in nicosia
iraq said it fired three missiles into tehran on monday, and iran reported its revolutionary guards blasted baghdad with four missiles and launched a fifth at the northern city of mosul for the first time
iraq confirmed only two missiles crashed monday in baghdad, a city of 5 million, killing or wounding ``many civilians, including women and children.''
iraq says it has fired 42 projectiles into tehran since the missile duel began when iran sent two missiles crashing into baghdad in retaliation for an earlier iraqi air raid on the tehran oil refinery
iraq also has fired three missiles at the holy city of qom, seat of ayatollah ruhollah khomeini's religious hierarchy
the iranians have reported more than 30 missiles have hit tehran. they said revolutionary guards fired 25 long-range missiles on iraq during that period, 23 of them on baghdad. the iraqis have only acknowledged 19 hits on the capital and one on mosul
both sides reported air raids on each other's cities and artillery bombardment of border towns on monday
irna said 30 civilians were killed and more than 100 people wounded in monday's iraqi missile attacks on tehran's residential areas. it reported one missile demolished a clinic, a school and several houses
iran has listed at least 122 civilians killed and more than 300 wounded in the iraqi missile blitz, with more than 100 killed and more than 500 wounded in air raids over the last week. the iraqis have reported heavy civilian casualties, but gave no exact figures
rafsanjani, khomeini's representative on the supreme defense council which directs war policy, said iranian experts who examined several unexploded missiles confirmed the projectiles were soviet scud-bs, tehran radio reported
it became clear that although the missile is made in russia, most of the eastern (bloc) countries manufacture or assemble this missile today, and iraq can obtain it from other sources,'' he said in an interview on the radio
iran last week accused moscow of supplying iraq with the missiles, triggering several violent protests outside the soviet embassy in tehran and the consulate-general in the central city of isfahan. the soviet union who, along with france, is main arms supplier of iraq, denied the charge
iraq said the missile used, named ``al hussein'' after a 7th century shiite moslem saint, was of its own design and production
however, western military analysts believe the missiles were scud-bs, fitted with the help of north korean experts with strap-on boosters to give the projectile enough range to reach tehran
but rafsanjani said the missiles fired at tehran were scud-bs that ``have been clumsily tampered with'' in order to increase their range. the scud normally has a range of 190 miles
of course, not the iraqis themselves, for the iraqis are incapable of even tampering with these missiles. no doubt, the major powers did this. such powers as the americans and france,'' he said
investigators searching for the cattle rustlers who stole 25 cows from a western illinois farm know they aren't dealing with amateurs
of the 80 cows at two rivers farm, the thieves took only the ones that were pregnant
all had been bred and were ready to calve, some of them within 24 hours,'' state police sgt. mike ernst said monday
it would have had to have been somebody familiar with cattle.''
the cows were stolen late saturday or early sunday from a holding barn 2 miles north of kingston, ernst said
it's in a pretty secluded area,'' he said. ``there's no house and no house in sight. the nearest house is a half mile away.''
the mixed-breed cows, which two rivers was feeding and housing for their owners, are more valuable because they are pregnant, ernst said
a calf would be worth at least $150 by itself,'' he said
investigators have few leads, ernst said. there are indications that a truck was used to haul the cows away, police said
the thieves also took a motorcycle, a welder, a saddle, tools and several bags of orchard grass and clover seed, police said. the loss of the animals and equipment was valued at $30,000, ernst said. ^by michael west</byline>
panamanian embassy workers and private security men used a land rover to smash into and seize the panamanian consulate, whose top diplomat had remained loyal to deposed president eric arturo delvalle
police said they believed the six assailants, including two representatives of panamanian ambassador guillermo vega, entered the building monday night after using the jeep to break through its reinforced plate glass door
the consul, eduardo arango, had refused to give up his post despite being fired for still recognizing delvalle
the british broadcasting corp. said the consulate staff had also remained loyal to delvalle, who was ousted feb. 26 after trying to dismiss gen. manuel antonio noriega, panama's military leader and de facto ruler
control of panama's embassy in washington is also in dispute
the reagan administration has been trying to force noriega to step down since the general was indicted on federal drug trafficking charges in florida last month
the land rover, driven by one of the british security men, mounted the sidewalk, smashed through the door into the lobby of the consulate, which is about a mile from the panamanian embassy
shortly after this several people left the building, including three women believed to be secretaries, and a number of security staff. one glass-paneled front door was damaged. no one was injured,'' police said in a statement
arango was at his london home at the time and was told about it by one of the consulate staff
one consular official who was forced out, tourism commissioner rolando domingo, 24, said: ``we were just working in there and then suddenly we heard a crash.'' he said the jeep came through the glass door and then a group of men entered the building carrying large hammers
they threatened us with hammers and one tried to hit my face. they took my passport and documents. then they pushed me down the stairs and out of the building,'' domingo said
police sealed off the area around the consulate in tudor street in the city, london's financial district
police said they entered the consulate after negotiations with panamanian government representatives they did not identify, and left the building in the control of the ambassador and his security staff
arango, in a bbc interview, condemned the forced entry as ``a thuggish way of behaving and an unbelievable way of doing things in a civilized country.''
he was quoted by the british domestic news agency press association as saying he was prevented from entering the consulate after the seizure and that one of the men involved told him they were working for vega and carrying out orders from panama
the agency also quoted arango as saying he had received letters from panama saying he was dismissed but ignored them. british government officials said they were told on friday that arango was being fired as consul
the bbc said arango was in panama at the time of delvalle's ouster and has said he helped smuggle delvalle from his residence to a hiding place in the central american country
arango said he would protest to the british foreign office and said the british driver of the land rover ought to be prosecuted
the security guards involved work for gb security, a private company based at sutton in south london
a spokesman at the british foreign office, who in accordance with british practice declined to be named, said it was too early to say what action, if any, foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe might take over the incident
poufs, ruffles, frills and furbelows are banished from the fashion scene, say the cream of italy's designers showing their fall-winter collections in milan
coming on strong is a cool, calm and collected look that is both elongated and elegant. pants play a major role in preference to last season's mini skirts
the new, haughty look is one which is right up gianfranco ferre's alley. he has always designed with a high-stepping female in mind rather than a romantic heroine
in his show monday, the dramatic shirts that are his signature had important, stiffly up-standing collars that jutted forward into crumb-catcher folds
actress ali mcgraw, who was a guest at the show, said: ``i love them.''
slim pants in smooth wools or crushed velvet provided the perfect accompaniment to these important shirts
ferre's color choice, in scarlet, black and white, was as forceful as his fashion statement. he even dyed beaver fur scarlet for blouses and detachable cuff collars that trimmed coats and jackets
but one red touch he could have done without was the scarlet eyeshadow daubed on the models' eyelids
big winter coats were cut slim and straight and almost brushed the ankles. jackets that were neat and short and minus collars were wrapped up in matching wool stoles
and he had lots of little foxes running down the runway in a variety of guises, spiralling round sleeves, forming skirts and curling round necks and hemlines
evenings were largely based on black, looking good on long-length smartly tailored redingotes that flared into fullness from a lowered waistline. white lace kerchiefs _ another mcgraw favorite _ spilling from collars and cuffs gave a dandified look
earlier on monday, leather fashions specialist, mario valentino, was another pants fan but with a difference. he cut them newly wide-legged and floppy, stemming from a high waistline, in supple suede
accompanying jackets were also loose and boxy. he took the padding out of shoulders on a handsome coat in calf that flared out to its near floor-length hemline
and he struck a blow for the return to the straight and narrow with his super-slender suit comprising a trim little jacket and pencil-slim, calf-length skirt in glossy leather. aviators' jackets and top coats in dark chocolatae brown were treated to fur linings
with ferre and versace now both creating couture fashions in addition to their lines of deluxe ready-made styles, there is news that the fashion house of andre laug, which showed in milan sunday, has also reversed its decision to no longer make clothes for private clients
this house, famed for its superb sartorial skills, suspended the custom-made side of the business for a brief period but now intends to reinstate it
couture provides a fashion house with allure and gives invaluable promotional power that can aid other activities belonging to the same establishment
milan shows swing into their third day today. highlights are to include the fabulous furs of the famed fendi family
everywhere evan l. mecham goes, people ask him about his political and legal problems. he tells them he has none
evan l. mecham is not the governor of arizona. he is not facing impeachment, a recall election or a trial in superior court
he lives in denver, owns a liquor distributorship, and in his travels around the country is constantly telling people, ``no, no, no, i'm not that evan mecham.''
when he first heard that arizona's mecham had been elected governor in november 1986, colorado's mecham said he was encouraged
well, you would hope some good would come of it,'' said mecham, 38. ``i'd hate to run for public office now. my political aspirations would have to be put on the back burner.''
to say that he takes the notoriety in stride is an understatement. a call to his home phone gets the recorded voice of his daughter, tiffany, 11
if you're trying to reach governor evan mecham, you have the wrong number,'' the recording says. ``however, if you have a campaign contribution of $300,000 or more and wish to keep it confidential, please leave your name and number and we'll get back to you. thank you for your support.''
playing in the background is the battle hymn of the republic
the demolition of the 16-story travelers insurance building provided some surprises for its downtown neighbors. one was a phenomenon little seen by city dwellers: sunlight
a restaurant manager directly across from the rubble-filled site in boston's financial district jokingly complained monday that light now beats through his floor-to-ceiling windows without the skyscraper to block it out
they should start issuing sunglasses to the employees,'' said manager frank strangie, manager of sandwich expressions
but others in the area weren't amused by the dusty windows, dirty floors and shattered glass resulting from sunday's demolition
there was a little bit more broken glass than we had expected,'' said bill ramsey of control demolitions inc., which conducted the blast that caused the building to implode, or collapse inward
up to two dozen windows at strangie's building were shattered, said its manager, david ham
the whole building is filthy, we have to have it washed down,'' strangie said
the demolition company has agreed to pay for the cost of replacing the panes but plans to look at clean-up costs on a case-by-case basis, ramsey said
the weather seemed springlike across much of the nation early today, with mild temperatures and rainshowers common
but on monday, a severe thunderstorm struck north-central texas, producing hail an inch in diameter in some places. lightning sparked numerous grass fires
milder, springlike thunderstorms developed across parts of northern texas and oklahoma, while showers extended across western missouri, western iowa, parts of kansas, northwest oklahoma, the texas panhandle, western louisiana and southeast texas. light rain covered much of southern minnesota, wisconsin and parts of lower michigan
rain mixed with sleet and wet snow fell in northern wisconsin, while snowfall in the northern plains diminished late monday. some light snow extended from western nebraska across parts of the dakotas to northern minnesota. an inch of wet snow was reported at duluth, minn., early today
windy conditions covered portions of the northern and central high plains. winds gusted to between 40 and 50 mph throughout monday evening and early today at rapid city, s.d
other than scattered light rain in western washington, the western third of the nation was dry, as was the east coast and much of the southeast
mild temperatures prevailed over much of the nation, and even the colder air in the rockies and northern plains lacked a wintry punch
the high for the nation monday was 88 at thermal, calif
the forecast for today called for showers and thunderstorms from southern and eastern texas across eastern oklahoma to the lower and middle mississippi valley; scattered showers from lower michigan to alabama late in the day; rain or snow from northeast new mexico and northwest texas to upper michigan, with snow likely over minnesota and the eastern dakotas; sunny skies over the atlantic coast states and west of the rockies, except for light rain spreading into western washington state; strong winds over south texas and the northern high plains
much the nation is expected to have highs in the 50s or 60s. highs will be in the 30s and 40s from the central rockies across the central and northern plains, from the upper mississippi valley to upper michigan, and from upstate new york to northern and central new england; 40s from northern new mexico to central oklahoma; and 70s and lower 80s in california, the desert southwest and from southern texas to the southern atlantic coast
