a bus plunged 260 feet into a ravine in central china, killing 39 people and injuring the other 17 on board, the official xinhua news agency reported
the chinese-built bus was making a turn at the bottom of a hill in henan province on monday when it swung off the road and fell, the agency said. the crash immediately killed 33 people and six others died later in the hospital, said the report, monitored in tokyo
all the survivors were injured, but the report did not say how seriously
police were investigating how the accident occurred, xinhua said
several bus and train accidents have been reported in china in recent weeks, with more than 100 people reported killed
the murder trial of a jobless handyman accused of killing seven women in his apartment and leaving their bodies to rot moved quickly into testimony after the defendant waived his right to a jury trial
the defense and prosecution also declined to give opening statements monday in the case of harrison ``marty'' graham
graham, 28, waived a trial by jury as a panel waited to be interviewed, then pleaded innocent to seven counts each of murder, involuntary manslaughter and abuse of a corpse
he and his mother agreed that a judge would be more objective than a jury,'' graham's attorney, joel moldovsky, said after the court session. the move is also expected to shorten a trial that had been expected to last up to three months
assistant district attorney roger king moved for admission of all testimony and documents from a monthlong pretrial suppression hearing, including a confession graham made to police in which he admitted strangling the seven women during sex. common pleas judge robert latrone granted the request
during the pretrial hearing, moldovsky, contending his client is mentally incompetent, sought unsuccessfully to suppress the confession
moldovsky said the confession was made in violation of his client's constitutional rights and after graham allegedly was beaten by police during 17 hours of interrogation. latrone ruled last week the confession was voluntary and that graham was competent to stand trial
the first witness called by the prosecution, acting city medical examiner robert catherman, testified that all seven deaths were homicides. however, the cause of death, due to the condition of the bodies, was undetermined, he said
graham turned himself in a week after police discovered rotting bodies in his bedroom and leg and foot bones on the roof of the house in a philadelphia neighborhood notorious for drug dealing
in the confession graham told police the bodies began piling up in his bedroom, and he began having problems with maggots. he also told of difficulty sleeping during the day because of big black birds on the roof outside his apartment eating the woman's body there
i had to stay high all the time,'' the confession said
moldovsky has indicated that his defense will be insanity
ten-year-old kristin segal wanted to solve a universal problem, so she decided to make the glue on stamps taste better by rubbing a banana across the back
robbie cadle, 10, hates carrying out the garbage so much that he has set out a project for himself: motorized garbage cans that he can drive out to the street and back
seth swanson, 11, wants to make sure he can locate his dog at night, and he is designing a nighttime dog collar with a light on it
these and other ideas were developed by the fifth-graders at dommerich elementary school as part of the invent america program, which seeks to boost the level of creativity and innovation in this country
it may not be possible to teach creativity, but the program believes that it can certainly be nurtured in schools
the privately funded u.s. patent model foundation in washington began invent america a little more than a year ago as part of an effort to boost the share of inventions patented in this country by americans
the proportion of patents issued by the u.s. patent office to americans has dropped from 89 percent in 1966 to 53 percent in 1987. the remainder go to foreign-born inventors who want to protect their creations in this country
the invent america class is taught at dommerich one day a week to each of five classes of gifted students in different grades by gil rowe
he came here from ocoee elementary school, where he started the program and had great success. ocoee won four of invent america's nine state awards last year, the most of any school in the country
we've just kind of forgotten to teach the children the old american ingenuity,'' says rowe, 44
eleven-year-old seth is certain that the creativity class works
like when you grow up, if you become a scientist, you'll be a little bit better at it than someone who never had this before,'' he said
besides opening up the innovative process, rowe says, the program enhances students' self-esteem. one ocoee second-grader who was emotionally and mentally disturbed and had no friends invented a device that earned him his classmates' admiration
suddenly he became a famous inventor. he just became a totally different individual,'' rowe said
only two orange county schools took part in the program last year, but two dozen are involved this year, as are others around the state
four million pupils in kindergarten through eighth grade participated nationwide in 1987 _ about 13 percent of all students in those grades, the foundation reported
other inventions have ranged from a self-cleaning bathtub to salt dyed red so that people can know how much they use
a judge froze the remainder of a half million dollars donated to save liver-transplant patient ronnie desillers after officials complained that his mother squandered money on a luxury waterfront apartment, clothes and jewelry
immediate and irreparable injury will result to assets of the estate of ronald desillers jr. if maria desillers is permitted to withdraw the funds deposited in the account,'' dade circuit judge francis j. christie wrote in his order monday
when ronnie died at children's hospital of pittsburgh last april 29 at age 7, an account in his name had accumulated $509,913, state officials said. the account balance on feb. 17 was $239,288, said fred kerstein, assistant dade county state attorney
our concern was that the remaining assets would be wasted,'' kerstein said. ``we wanted to safeguard those assets and let the court determine how they'll be distributed.''
as recently as jan. 19, $25,000 was withdrawn from the fund, said a court document filed by state attorney general bob butterworth and state attorney janet reno of miami
the state accusation said bank records indicated ms. desillers spent at least $47,000 on jewelry, clothing, furniture, housing expenses, an automobile and auto expenses
ronnie, who died last year while awaiting a fourth transplant, attracted donations from around the country, including $1,000 from president reagan, after news reports that money raised by his classmates had been stolen
ms. desillers, who created a foundation to assist other children in need of organ transplants after her son's death, denied squandering any of the donations
why do they not say that money went to charity?'' ms. desillers told the associated press on monday night. ``why do they not say that some of that money was assigned to me personally? ... how come they don't say how much of that money went to kids?''
she said she would straighten out the status of the frozen money in probate court and use the funds to provide organ transplants for two children
there are two children that have less than six months to live, and that's what i want to do with the money,'' she said
ms. desillers' lawyer, harry robbins, said his client maintains she never asked the public to donate money and thus was not legally a charity. she also has said she was entitled to the money as ronnie's sole heir
ms. desillers' finances came under question when it was learned she lived in a luxury apartment building on biscayne bay and was driving a 1985 bmw equipped with a telephone. she contends the car was second-hand and bought with a loan, that the car telephone was a gift and the apartment doubled as her office
ms. desillers is being sued by children's hospital for failing to pay $261,189 of ronnie's $424,302 bill. she has charged the hospital with giving poor care to her son. first sentence. picks up 2nd graf pvs ``foreign minister...''</head>
syria, the strongest critic of u.s. middle east policy, has found ``positive elements'' in american efforts to reactivate the stalled process but remains suspicious of the initiative's goals, sources say
syria's leaders are consulting with jordan and studying proposals handed last week to president hafez assad by secretary of state george p. shultz
foreign minister farouk al-sharaa is expected to fly to amman this week to discuss the plan after weekend contacts between assad and king hussein, said the knowledgeable syrian sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity
but they question whether the united states is serious about finding a comprehensive settlement to the arab-israeli conflict or is simply trying to end palestinian rioting in israeli-occupied lands through promises of peace
like all arab governments, damascus supports the palestinian rebellion in the west bank and gaza strip, unprecedented in the 40-year-old conflict, that threatens washington's middle east ally with a prolonged civil war
more than 80 palestinians have been killed in the violence that has plagued the occupied territories since dec. 8 in what arabs hail as the ``intafada,'' or uprising. there have been no israel fatalities in the rioting
syria, moscow's main arab ally and a key player in the middle east, remains suspicious of attempts to isolate issues involved in the quest for a settlement into separate negotiations, a strategy it believes favors israel
syria believes it has a better chance of regaining the strategic golan heights, captured by israel in 1967, through a comprehensive settlement. unlike the other occupied territories, israel annexed the heights in 1981
charles snow, a veteran middle east analyst, wrote in the respected middle east economic survey: ``there is one major problem which clearly has the potential to derail the entire process _ the golan heights
syria has always been deeply suspicious that attempts to separate the issues in the arab-israeli conflict are merely camouflage for a partial settlement which will leave israel in ... possession of the golan.''
the u.s. plan would convene an international conference within a few weeks. by may 1, israel and a joint delegation of jordanians and palestinians would discuss limited self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinians in the west bank and gaza for an interim three-year period. later in the year, a wider international conference would bring in other parties to debate the ultimate future of the occupied arab land captured by israel in the 1967 war
a syrian source said the main question is how much pressure washington is prepared to exert on israel to accept a ``land for peace'' exchange
the arabs, including syria, spearhead of arab radicalism, have accepted this principle. but israeli hardliners reject withdrawal from lands it seized in 1967 and are at odds with moderates over the way to go. arabs fear the israeli impasse could block any progress
some syrian officials question the sincerity of an initiative launched by the reagan administration, which they say has done little to rein in israel
since reagan was elected in 1980, israel attacked iraq's nuclear plant in 1981, annexed the golan heights later that year, invaded lebanon in 1982, bombed the plo's headquarters in tunisia in 1984 and continued to build settlements in the occupied territories
israel also has defied a series of u.n. resolutions condemning its repeated air raids on palestinian bases in lebanon
furthermore, arab officials stress, the reagan adminstration has made no effort to pressure israel to honor commitments under the camp david accords which called for palestinian self-rule
the accords, signed by egypt and israel in 1978 under the sponsorship of former president carter, has been dormant since reagan took office
syria, like other arab governments, denounced the accord as violating arab summit resolutions that banned seperate peace treaties with israel outside a comprehensive settlement
but, with u.s. presidential elections only a few months away, the syrians are wondering what guarantees shultz can offer that any accord reached under reagan would be honored by israel after the change of adminstration
a commentary by state-run damascus radio said that although the exact details of the u.s. proposal have not been made public, arab leaders felt it was an american effort to monopolize the peace initiative, outside the framework of the united nations, and to keep out the soviet union
but the commentary, the first official reaction to shultz's plan, welcomed washington's renewed interest in resolving the conflict and its support for an international peace conference as a step in the right direction
mona ziade has covered middle east affairs for the associated press in beirut and nicosa, cyprus, since 1983
mikhail gorbachev's chief economic adviser has cut short his visit to silicon valley because of his mother's death in the soviet union
abel aganbegyan had planned a three-day tour that included visits to sun microsystems and acuson, both in mountain view. sun microsystems makes desktop workstations while acuson produces medical imaging equipment
aganbegyan held a brief news conference at san francisco international airport on monday
american citizens know very little about joint ventures with the soviet union,'' he said
the soviet official said the united states is ``putting up obstacles in the way of technology transfers. other countries, such as japan, do not.''
aganbegyan is an architect of ''perestroika,'' gorbachev's wholesale restructuring of the stagnant economy
the visit to santa clara county was to have been the final part of an 18-day trip through six american cities to increase interest among u.s. companies in joint ventures with the soviets. light</head>
a man parachuted off a downtown building, landing on a car that was stopped at a red light, then jumped into another car and fled, police said today
officer thomas karczewski said police had no suspects but were checking a license plate number provided by musiliu alagbala, whose car was hit by the parachutist monday afternoon
karczewski said today he didn't think the parachutist was injured
witnesses told police the parachutist jumped off a building that was under construction and landed on the hood of alagbala's car
alagbala, 38, ``was waiting at the light when he saw a man roll off the hood with a parachute on,'' patrolman charles weyer said monday
he folded up his parachute, went running across the street and jumped into a car,'' said bonnie panagakis, 39, of palatine, who saw the incident
mrs. panagakis said she saw a man flying ``higher than the light poles'' above the chicago river
i think he saw he was about to go into the river, and he had to get himself righted,'' she said
she said that he maneuvered his parachute back toward the street but that the parachute was torn by a lamppost. ``that's when he landed on the guy's hood,'' she said
alagbala said the man caused between $300 and $500 damage to the car
more than 500 elementary school children and whale watchers stared in horror as a container ship hit a 35-foot gray whale as it swam four miles off shore, witnesses said
the 30-ton mother whale, which was escorting its calf along with another cow and calf pair, was hit saturday while migrating north toward the arctic
the children were just devastated. one little boy wanted to swim out and help the whale,'' said nancy pavlich, a first grade teacher at deer canyon elementary school in suburban alta loma
robert yoshitomi, a lawyer for nippon yusen kaisha (nyk), japanese owners of the container ship hakusan ii, said company officials were looking into the case
we're still checking,'' he said. ``we're sorry for any difficulty that was caused. as far as we know, it was unintentional.''
pavlich said many of the children were still somber about the incident monday morning and some students are writing letters about the whales and sending them to the coast guard
the whale slid along the side of the ship, broke free from the ship's current, swam helplessly for a minute than made a final blow of air before sinking, witnesses said
kids were screaming and crying as they were watching this,'' said bill samaras, a marine biology teacher at carson high school who was aboard the children's boat
we had been following the whales for about 15 minutes when we noticed the container ship coming from the southwest. it then very drastically turned and crossed our path
i thought, `they're going to hit the whales,' and we tried to contact the ship on the emergency radio but i guess they weren't monitoring the line.''
at this point we can't confirm its death, but there is a good chance that it died, we just can't say for sure,'' said tom lewis, biologist at the los angeles county museum of natural history and president of the american cetacean society
the hakusan ii, 209 feet long and with a dead weight of 20,934 tons, arrived at the port of los angeles on saturday and left sunday evening headed to taiwan, officials said
samaras, a research associate with the county museum, said he was certain the ship's navigators didn't see the swimming mammals
to them it was like a road kill,'' he said. ``like killing a chipmunk with your car,'' he said. ``i'm sure it was nothing intentional. they didn't know they hit it.''
samaras said he plans to file a complaint with the coast guard about the ship, which he said changed course and came about 150 yards in front of the whale watching charters
typhoon bola pounded the east coast of new zealand's north island today, killing at least one person and forcing the evacuation of 2,500 people
the high winds also fanned a bush fire on south island that consumed nearly 1,000 acres before it was brought under control
four towns and portions of gisborne were evacuated during widespread flooding, civil defense spokesman doug bent said. authorities declared a state of emergency
residents were ordered out of low-lying areas as a precaution against rising rivers. at least four people were lost in the floodwaters and one body was recovered, officials said
insurance companies estimated damage at hundreds of millions of dollars. the most serious damage was on the east coast of north island, where homes were heavily damaged as far north as auckland
in new plymouth on the west side of the island, winds damaged more than 300 homes and several high-rise buildings. bola was expected to pass over the north island later tuesday
winds of up to 93 mph began pounding the region late sunday as bola moved southwest across the pacific ocean after leaving more than 100 people homeless on the small island nation of vanuatu
a state of emergency was declared around gisborne and in wairoa after that town's main bridge collapsed
a man who killed one worshipper and wounded four others in a church shooting spree had been spurned by a former member of the congregation and talked about her after he was captured, parishioners said
cheun-phon ji, 29, a native of taiwan who earned a master's degree from emporia state university in december 1984, was charged monday with one count of first-degree murder and six counts of attempted first-degree murder. bond was set at $1 million and a preliminary hearing was scheduled for march 31
one person was killed and four wounded in the sunday morning shooting spree at calvary baptist church. parishioners wrestled the gunman to the ground after a church trustee chased him outside and struck him with a hymnal
as he was being brought to the courthouse monday past a crowd of journalists, ji was asked why the shootings occurred. he shouted, ``justice, revenge.''
church members said monday that ji had attended a church service or bible study with a woman named georgia ann mejia several years ago. he apparently was rejected by the woman when he asked her to marry him, they said
allen bush, a church trustee, said he and three other men surrounded ji outside the church after the shooting
he said, `don't you remember? don't you remember?''' bush said. ``we said, `remember what?' he said, `georgia.' more than one of us said, `georgia who?' at that point he answered, `georgia mejia.'''
mejia, 27, was married nov. 4, 1985 and her name is now georgia ann johnson, according to court records. she transferred to another baptist church about four years ago, her mother said
police detained nine journalists, assaulted a television soundman and confiscated their film during an anti-apartheid demonstration this morning by about 100 black women
riot and security police arrived outside the chamber of mines about 10 minutes after the peaceful protest began and the crowd began to disperse
police began taking journalists into custody, including crew members of the american network, cbs, and london-based world television news, and taking film out of photographers' cameras
soundman prince msuthu of world television news said police punched him with fists and poked him in the stomach with their batons. he said he had bruises on his arms and intended to file charges
other journalists saw police dragging him toward the vehicle and holding him in a wrist-lock
they were manhandling me, pushing me around up to the point where the recorder on my shoulder fell on the ground,'' he said. ``they put me into the truck and as i was getting into the truck one of them assaulted me, using the baton
they kept on punching me, saying that i am `cheeky,' '' msuthu said after he was released from police custody and his recorded cassette confiscated
police spokesman col. frans malherbe said police took nine journalists to police headquarters and confiscated their film. but he denied they were detained or arrested. he said they could face charges ``if they have done something wrong.''
we arrived on the scene and had to deal with the news people somehow. ... so we took them to an office at john vorster square,'' he said, adding that emergency regulations prohibit members of the news media from being at the scene of unrest
however, journalists at the scene disputed malherbe's statement that police gave notice the gathering was illegal
the protesters, members of the federation of transvaal women, called on the nation's largest mining houses and biggest foreign currency earners to take a tougher line against government restrictions on anti-apartheid organizations
the women sang ``god bless africa,'' and unfurled posters addressed to the chamber saying: ``your silence is conspiracy,'' ``bannings protect mine profits,'' ``unban democracy,'' and ``chamber of mines speak.''
the women's federation is an affiliate of the united democratic front, one of 18 organizations the government banned on feb. 24 from any political activity
the congress of south african trade unions, whose biggest affiliate is the 300,000-member black national union of mineworkers, was also banned from any political activity
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services. to panama</head>
a federal judge has tacked an additional 10 days onto a restraining order preventing two american banks from transferring an estimated $50 million to the national bank of panama
on monday, u.s. district judge lloyd f. macmahon extended the order he had issued thursday that prevented three banks from transacting any business with or transferring funds to the banco nacional de panama
he also said he would sign a stipulation dropping irving trust as the third bank in the suit, which was filed on behalf of the republic of panama at federal court in manhattan
ousted panamanian president eric arturo delvalle is still recognized by the u.s. government as the legitimate head of panama, and the order effectively prevents the funds from being transferred to the regime of gen. manuel antonio noriega, panama's military leader
assistant u.s. attorney kenneth handal told the court that irving trust had agreed to a permanent injunction against transferring funds until the situation in panama has been resolved
lawyers for marine midland and bankers trust told the court that the situation in panama remained unclear and said they would respect the court's wishes
criminal attorney barry slotnick asked to intervene on behalf of banco nacional de panama because of what he said was panama's urgent need for cash. banks in panama remained closed for a fifth day monday, sparking a demonstration by thousands of retired people unable to cash their pension checks
last wednesday another bank, republic national bank of new york, agreed to transfer $10 million to the federal reserve bank
two u.s. grand juries in florida indicted noriega on drug charges feb. 4. delvalle sought to dismiss noriega feb. 25, but was ousted the next day by noriega supporters and went into hiding
last tuesday, delvalle froze all panamanian assets outside the country
coleridge, 44, middle east coordinator of the british oxfam relief agency, and traboulsi, 31, the agency's representative in lebanon, were kidnapped at sidon's ein el-hilweh palestinian refugee camp on thursday
saad said representatives of fatah-revolutionary council, the radical faction headed by abu nidal, turned the two captives over to him at his house in sidon at 3:50 p.m
the rapides parish sheriff's office, trying to find local satanists, has ordered the library here to turn over a list of people who have checked out books on the occult in the last year
assistant district attorney dexter ryland said he has advised rapides parish library officials to withhold the information until his office can determine if the order is an invasion of privacy
we are working on it. we haven't formulated our final legal opinion on it,'' ryland said monday. ``it struck me when it was called to my attention that it could possibly violate the privacy of individuals.''
chief deputy tommy hollingsworth said his office is ``simply trying to get some intelligence'' on serious followers of satanic beliefs because ``a lot of times it is connected with narcotics.''
lynn dunn, who works in the sheriff's narcotics office, said the names and addresses were subpoenaed ``to weed out the curious from the serious'' followers of satanism
it is not an invasion of the readers' privacy ``because no one is going to be contacted or anything like that,'' she said
hollingsworth said his office is not investigating any specific incidents involving devil worshippers. the sheriff's office is simply updating files it has kept for the last 15 years, he said
library director stephen rogge said it is his policy not to release such information simply on a request, but he could be forced to comply because of the court order
rogge said he would consider the sheriff's request an invasion of privacy ``unless there is a good reason for it.'' if the district attorney's office determines there are not sufficient grounds to turn over the list, rogge said he won't do it
rapides chief of detectives william earl hilton said there may be some satanic activity in the parish, but so far it has not been linked to any crime. with car</head>
a south african diplomat has been charged with assault after his car hit a protester and a police officer outside a radio station where he had been interviewed
south burlington police chief john race said south african vice consul duke kent brown was arrested by south burlington police monday about a quarter-mile from the scene of the incident
brown was charged with simple assault, released on his own recognizance and ordered to appear in court in april. race said the charge carries up to a year in prison and a fine of $1,000
police said brown left the burlington area following his release and failed to make three other scheduled appearances
jim condon, news director at radio station wjoy-wqcr and a witness to the incident, said the protester who was struck, laurie larson of richmond, suffered minor bruises
race identified the injured officer as todd shepard and said he had suffered bruises on his leg
race said police had called the state department in washington to ask if brown was covered by diplomatic immunity and were told ``to treat this case like any other.''
a spokesman in the south african embassy in washington, third secretary heyn van rooyen, said brown is connected with the south african consulate in new york
van rooyen said, ``there are different degrees of diplomatic immunity,'' and he was not sure that consular officials are given the same degree of protection as those connected with embassies
race said he hoped police could proceed with the case. ``politics don't enter into the justice system, as far as i'm concerned.''
condon said about 30 members of the vermont committee on southern africa had gathered outside the station to protest brown's participation in a talk show, ``viewpoint,'' which was broadcast beginning at 9 a.m
he said brown left the station under police escort and made his way to a car in a nearby parking lot. brown got into the car and a few of the protesters sat on the hood, condon said
protesters were climbing off the hood of the car without any resistance, condon said, when brown ``hit the accelerator'' and the incident occurred
philip fiermonte, one of the leaders of the protest, said brown ``shows disregard for humanity, as (south africa's) apartheid policies have.''
harry d. williams, a yurok indian who served as stanford university's mascot for 21 years until protests arose against the school's indian symbol, died on sunday. he was 64
williams, who was ``prince lighfoot'' from 1951 to 1972, died of injuries suffered in an automobile accident
williams, a graduate of the university of san francisco, first performed an indian dance at a stanford rally when he was 27
he was such a favorite he was asked to lead the university band onto the football field, which he did until 1972. in that year, the school dropped the nickname indians after complaints of racism, changing it to cardinal
williams was active in indian affairs and served as chairman of the california rural indian health board. exchanges, soviet call for u.n. comdemnation; edits throughout; no pickup.</note>
iraq said its warplanes hit a ``very big naval target'' in the persian gulf today, breaking a three-week lull in attacks on iran's oil shipping
the two nations also kept up their brutal barrage of missile attacks, firing surface-to-surface rockets into each other's capital cities. iran accused the united states and france of helping iraq refit soviet-designed missiles to give them enough range to reach tehran
the official iraqi news agency said iraqi jets struck ``accurately and effectively'' at the naval target off the iran coast and returned safely to base
it was the first raid on a ``large naval target'' _ iraq's term for an iranian tanker _ since feb. 16. the last independently confirmed attack by iranian warplanes was on feb. 12
the last time that iran is known to have attacked a ship, in retaliation for iraq's air raids on its own shipping, was on feb. 11
since then, the two belligerents, at war for 7{ years, have battered each other's capitals with long-range missiles and struck other population centers with artillery and bombs
hundreds of civilian casualties are believed to have resulted from the bombardments
also today, iranian parliament speaker hashemi rafsanjani accused the united states and france of helping iraq modify soviet-made missiles to reach longer-range targets in iran. tehran is 290 miles from the iraqi border
iran's official islamic republic news agency reported that an iraqi missile crashed into a residential neighborhood of tehran about midnight, killing or wounding several civilians
state-run baghdad radio reported that iraqi gunners fired the missile into tehran, a city of 6 million, early today less than an hour after iran claimed it lobbed a projectile into baghdad
tehran radio said president ali khamenei, who visited a bombed tehran neighborhood, said ``our nation will never forget those who have assisted the criminal in perpetrating its crime.'' unlike rafsanjani, khamenei did not refer to any specific country
iraq's news agency confirmed the an iranian missile strike on a residential area in baghdad, saying civilians, including women, children and eldery people, were killed. no figures were given
iran's news agency said revolutionary guards today shot a missile at a ``military center'' at amarah, an iraqi town close to the border and halfway between baghdad and the southern port city of basra
the reports were monitored in nicosia
iraq said it fired three missiles into tehran on monday, and iran reported its revolutionary guards blasted baghdad with four missiles and launched a fifth at the northern city of mosul for the first time
iraq confirmed only two missiles crashed monday in baghdad, a city of 5 million, killing or wounding ``many civilians, including women and children.''
iraq says it has fired 42 projectiles into tehran since the missile duel began
the iranians have reported more than 30 missiles have hit tehran. they said revolutionary guards fired 25 long-range missiles on iraq during that period, 23 of them on baghdad. the iraqis have only acknowledged 19 hits on the capital and one on mosul
both sides reported air raids on each other's cities and artillery bombardment of border towns on monday
irna said 30 civilians were killed and more than 100 people wounded in monday's iraqi missile attacks on tehran's residential areas. it reported one missile demolished a clinic, a school and several houses
iran has listed at least 122 civilians killed and more than 300 wounded in the iraqi missile blitz, with more than 100 killed and more than 500 wounded in air raids over the last week. the iraqis have reported heavy civilian casualties, but gave no exact figures
iran last week accused moscow of supplying iraq with the missiles, triggering several violent protests outside the soviet embassy in tehran and the consulate-general in the central city of isfahan. the soviet union who, along with france, is main arms supplier of iraq, denied the charge
the soviet union, meanwhile, called for security council condemnation monday of the war
under the circumstances, the security council has to do something in order to eliminate the damage of the further escalation of the military conflict between iran and iraq,'' soviet ambassador alexander m. belonogov told reporters. graf pvs, ``they hurt; also subs 8th graf pvs, dukakis plans</note>
massachusetts gov. michael s. dukakis cast his democratic primary vote today at his hometown precinct in brookline, where he was greeted by neighbors who applauded his arrival
it's good to be in this precinct where a great deal of my political career and my life, really, has been shaped by a lot of great friends who are here,'' said dukakis, who was accompanied by his wife, kitty, and their daughter, kara
dukakis had closed his super tuesday campaign monday night, worrying about the last-minute impact of negative campaign ads aired by tennessee sen. albert gore in texas and north carolina
they hurt, there's no question about it,'' dukakis said as his campaign plane headed for boston on monday night after a day of campaigning in the south. ``by the time you find out what they're doing it's too late.''
dukakis said of the latest gore ad, ``it's a piece of garbage.''
the comments were a final note of concern following an otherwise upbeat weekend of campaigning that saw large crowds, extensive media coverage and a few key endorsements
dukakis planned to spend the day at his statehouse office and then fly to chicago to begin campaigning in the next battleground _ illinois, which holds its primary a week from today
in his final stop in the raleigh-durham area monday night, dukakis once again rejected the notion that he is the most liberal of the democratic candidates, saying he preferred the label ``progressive.''
among the positions that have helped pin the label liberal on dukakis are his opposition to aid to nicaraguan contra rebels, his opposition to any cuts in social spending, his opposition to a space-based missile defense system and the midgetman missile and his support of closer relations with soviet leader mikhail s. gorbachev
but dukakis insisted that he has also cut taxes in massachusetts _ even though some of those tax cuts occurred over his initial objections. he said he has balanced nine consecutive budgets and has cut crime in massachusetts. in his work with other governors, he said the most consistently progressive are those from the southern states
in addition to stops in miami, plant city, fla., and raleigh-durham, dukakis squeezed 21 television interviews into his schedule monday
still, he said, ``don't let them tell you this is a television campaign. this is a grass-roots campaign and if we're successful, it will be because of our organization.''
the dukakis organization is recognized as the best-funded and most extensive in texas, florida and washington state, among the 20 super tuesday states holding presidential primaries and caucuses today. in north carolina, though, campaign organizers predicted dukakis would finish third there behind jesse jackson and gore
dukakis kicked off the day of campaigning in perhaps his most solid base of support in the south: miami
at a senior citizens rally, dukakis picked up the coveted endorsement of 70-year-old annie ackerman, not a household name, but someone with a reputation in miami for being able to get out the vote
the woman who was a ward organizer for chicago mayor richard daley spurned other democratic suitors and endorsed the massachusetts governor at a morning rally attended by about 500 senior citizens
a man who went without sleep for a week in order to watch over his wife, who reportedly suffered from alzheimer's disease, apparently shot her to death and then killed himself, officials said
the bodies of douglas and clodene schofield, both 67, were found monday morning at their home in a trailer park, said butler county coroner pete tutchtone
she had gotten to where she was straying away from the trailer,'' tutchtone said. ``i guess she had alzheimer's disease.''
tutchtone said schofield realized he needed help in caring for his wife, but he could not bear to part with her. ``he didn't want to put her in a nursing home,'' he said
the coroner said neighbors contacted authorities last week after mrs. schofield strayed. ``she walked out of the trailer and got locked out and neighbors called the sheriff to get her back in,'' he said
neighbors said schofield had not slept for the week so he could watch her and keep her from wandering again
alzheimer's disease is a progressive, irreversible neurological disorder that results in gradual memory loss, impairment of judgment, disorientation and loss of language skills
tutchtone said schofield used a .38-caliber handgun to kill his wife and then himself. suspected collaborator; picks up 3rd graf pvs: elsewhere in...</note>
palestinians stabbed to death an arab policeman suspected of aiding israel and wrapped his body in a palestinian flag, and another arab was killed today by israeli gunfire, hospital officials and witnesses said
the suspected collaborator was slain in a refugee camp near jericho, the reports said, the second killing of a suspected collaborator in the occupied territories since palestinian unrest began dec. 8
the army confirmed that the body of nabil juma farah, 30, had been found in the aqbat jaber refugee camp, but said it was investigating the cause of his death
according to u.n. figures, 83 arabs have been killed by israelis since the riots began in the lands israel captured during the 1967 middle east war
elsewhere in the west bank, doctors said three male protesters were wounded today by israeli gunfire and arab women heeded underground calls to demonstrate
also today, the military said four army officers who were unarmed when three plo guerrillas commandeered their car and went on to hijack a bus monday were sentenced to 35 days in jail for not carrying weapons
the major and three lieutenants were on their way to an army sporting event and were in track suits. the four fled when the guerrillas opened fire on their car, the army reported
prime minister yitzhak shamir said the bus hijacking in which the guerrillas and three israeli hostages were killed was initiated by the same element that is behind three months of arab rioting in the occupied lands
these are the same people who incite violence in the territories,'' shamir said on israel radio after the attack in southern israel. ``we shall not tire fighting them.''
also today in the west bank village of mazraa sharqiya, 10 miles northwest of ramallah, family members and the arab-owned palestine press service blamed jewish settlers for the shooting death of khader mohammed hamideh
hamideh, a 45-year-old coffee shop owner, died of a gunshot wound to the heart, said dr. yasser obeid, director of ramallah hospital
a man who identified himself as hamideh's nephew and spoke on condition of anonymity said israeli settlers entered the village today and shot his uncle without provocation as he stood outside his home
hospital officials in jericho said the arab police officer, of the nearby aqbat jaber refugee camp died monday night of three stab wounds to the chest and stomach. the army said it was investigating
local residents, who demanded anonymity, said farah's body was wrapped in the outlawed palestinian flag and dropped at his mother's doorstep inside the refugee camp, where 2,600 palestinians live
they said the army detained seven camp residents in connection with the slaying. an associated press reporter saw five army jeeps parked in front of the camp and dozens of soldiers questioning residents
in the west bank city of nablus, officials at al ittihad hospital said they treated three palestinians shot today by israeli troops, including a 19-year-old from the balata refugee camp who was in serious condition after being shot in the groin
another arab from balata was shot in the right ear and a third from nablus was wounded in the right leg, the officials said. the army said it was investigating the shootings
the plo, in a leaflet distributed last week, called on palestinians to take revenge against collaborators. the leaflet also called on palestinian women to demonstrate today. hundreds of women in east jerusalem and ramallah heeded the call
police used tear gas to break up two protests by women in east jerusalem, said police spokesman rafi levy. police arrested seven women and two were hospitalized with tear gas poisoning after they threw stones at a police patrol car and briefly blocked one street, levy said
on monday night, the army bulldozed the homes of two palestinians who allegedly killed an arab they suspected of collaborating with israel
israeli troops demolished the homes of the two residents of bidou, near ramallah, the army reported. the army suspects the two of taking part in the killing four months ago of adnan saadi, an alleged collaborator with israel
some assemblies of god members have left the fold or are seeking counseling because of the rev. jimmy swaggart's alleged sexual misconduct, says a minister who has talked to the television evangelist
i hope to god there aren't any more'' sex scandals, added glyn lowery, pastor of pace assembly of god in this pensacola suburb. ``i don't know how we'll stand many more scandals in the assemblies of god. it has shaken our movement tremendously.''
another assemblies of god television evanglist, jim bakker, was the subject of earlier reports that he had sex with a church secretary
lowery was one of about a half-dozen ministers called to baton rouge, la., to counsel swaggart in the wake of reports he had been photographed with a prostitute in new orleans
he is a broken man,'' lowery said sunday. ``as he told me, `glyn, nobody could exact any punishment on me greater than that which i put upon my own self for what i done.' ''
church officials have proposed to relieve swaggart of his ministry for three months
some preachers feel like he needs a year out of the pulpit; others don't,'' lowery said. ``for him to stay out of the pulpit for a year would be a death sentence to his ministry ... but that's something he should have thought about when he went to new orleans.''  ambassador. picks up 5th graf, `jana said ...'</note>
libya's official news agency said today 130 foreigners, including one american, have been released from prison in libya
the jana news agency report, monitored in rome, carried expressions of gratitude from prisoners from west germany, italy and the united states
jana mentioned a ``u.s. prisoner'' and quoted him as expressing his happiness and gratitude
the belgian ambassador, camille reynens, reached by telephone from rome, said the american was staying at his residence but declined to give his name or any details about the case
belgium represents u.s. interests in libya
jana said the prisoners were released monday in a ceremony attended by diplomats from embassies in tripoli representing the various prisoners
the report did not say what the freed prisoners had been charged with, but the italian foreign ministry in rome said three italians released were businessmen accused by libya of defaulting on contracts
the jana dispatch quoted a libyan foreign ministry official as telling the diplomats that the prisoner release was an expression of the ``freedom and liberty'' brought by libya's 1969 revolution and evidence of its ``humanitarian aspect.''
last week, libyan leader col. moammar gadhafi, driving a bulldozer, knocked down a wall of a tripoli prison to release prisoners as part of an amnesty he declared. jana said 400 prisoners were freed
gadhafi announced he was releasing all libyan prisoners except those accused of plotting with foreign countries
a former independent record promoter pleaded innocent to charges he paid more than $200,000 to radio station program directors to get his records on the air
william craig, 42, of scottsdale, ariz., also is accused of deducting the alleged payments from his corporate income taxes
trial was set for may 3
also monday, ralph and valerie tashjian were ordered to enter pleas next week on similar payola charges
ralph tashjian is accused of giving cash and cocaine to radio program directors in fresno and el paso, texas. he and his wife are charged with evading taxes on $300,000 in corporate income between 1983-85
craig, who is free on $50,000 bail, the tashjians and a former los angeles radio station vice president and general manager, george wilson crowell, also known as george wilson, were named in a feb. 26 indictment that culminated a two-year grand jury probe into payola allegations
