a kuwaiti held his two wives and 13 sons at gunpoint for more than two days and fired randomly at police, injuring one man, before surrendering, the interior ministry said today
nasser farraj al-rukeibi released his family members unharmed and gave up late monday, a ministry spokesman said. one of the women was eight months pregnant and the eldest of the sons was less than 7 years old
police were interrogating al-rukeibi to determine his motives but they did not think the 58-hour standoff was related to his polygamous marriage, sources said. al-rukeibi, a moslem, is permittted by islamic law to have up to four wives
one neighbor was slightly injured by a stray bullet when al-rukeibi began firing in response to police attempts to talk him into releasing the hostages
police and special forces staked out the family home and used bullhorns to negotiate with al-rukeibi. authorities said he threatened to kill his wives and sons if the house was stormed
the sources, who could not be named under police regulations, said the standoff began saturday morning when al-rukeibi clashed with his personnel manager at the ministry of communications where he is employed
al-rukeibi pulled out a revolver and opened fire, but no injuries were reported. he then rushed to his car and drove to his home at firdous, a suburb 10 miles north of the city center, where took his wives and sons hostage
the brother of an american being held hostage in lebanon said today he thinks the hostages should be an issue discussed by the u.s. presidential candidates
they have never mentioned a word,'' said anthony cicippio, whose brother, joseph, has been held for 18 months
i think they're treating it like a hot potato. they're just laying off of it,'' he said on abc-tv's ``good morning america.''
he also chided members of congress for what he said was a lack of concern for the hostages
we sent 300 letters to the congressmen and senators over the last six months and, through that time, we've only received 13 replies,'' he said. one of them, whom he did not identify, asked for a campaign contribution, said cicippio, of norristown, pa
i live on hope,'' said peggy say, who joined cicippio on the program. her brother, terry anderson, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, was abducted march 16, 1985. he has been held longer than any of the nine americans in captivity
mrs. say said increased activity involving the search for lt. col. william higgins, who was kidnapped three weeks ago, gives her some hope. but she said the hostage families should not ``have to wait for a time when we could attach ourselves to a larger issue.''
i think the (reagan) administration is consistently saying this is too complicated and that quiet diplomacy is the answer. none of these things are acceptable any more,'' said mrs. say, of batavia, n.y
she noted that a ceremony will be held in washington march 16 to mark the third anniversary of her brother's abduction. the event, sponsored by no greater love, a humanitarian organization, and the journalists' committee to free terry anderson, is to be duplicated in other areas across the country and is indicative of a growing grass-roots movement to gain the hostages' freedom, she said
