a bus carrying american tourists from israel to egypt today skidded on a wet highway east of the occupied gaza strip and flipped over, injuring all 56 people on board, hospital officials and radio reports said
the bus was taking members of the united methodist church, west virginia conference, on a tour of the middle east, said a church spokeswoman in charleston, w.va
debbie mcgraw, a church secretary, said the accident injured 55 tour members and the bus driver
the bus was carrying lay people and clergy from various parts of west virginia as well as relatives from virginia and possibly other states, mcgraw said
the u.s. embassy initially said all the passengers were from west virginia. it refused to identify any of the tourists
most of the americans suffered fractured limbs, including broken hands, wrists and shoulder bones, or cuts requiring stitches, said a surgeon in the emergency room of barzilai hospital in ashkelon, 40 miles southeast of jerusalem
five of the americans suffered more serious fractures that would require orthopedic therapy, but none were in critical condition, said the surgeon, who spoke on condition of anonymity in a telephone interview
police commander ezra menashe told army radio the accident occurred when the bus from the east jerusalem tourism co. went out of control on a curve on the road between miflasim and kfar azza, two kibbutzim or collective farms located about three miles east of the gaza strip
the radio said the driver lost control of the bus which careened onto a field adjacent to the highway and overturned
there was heavy rain and suddenly the bus overturned and everyone started screaming,'' passenger rick farley, of dunbar, w.va., told the itim news agency. ``people in passing cars provided some first aid and then the ambulances came.''
the bus, which departed from the northern city of tiberias, was headed for the egyptian border crossing at rafah, on the southern tip of the gaza strip, army radio said
a hospital spokesman denied a request by the associated press to speak with them
an appearance by two members of the ku klux klan at a free speech forum turned into a massive demonstration at the university of kansas as protesters waved signs and shouted slogans
an estimated 3,000 people, some shouting ``kkk not today'' and ``don't go in,'' protested outside monday night as about 2,000 people gathered inside hoch auditorium
no serious violence was reported, but several windows were broken as protesters tried to push their way into the auditorium. police wearing riot gear guarded the entrances to the building, breaking up one shouting match and ejecting another person
the forum was delayed for about 20 minutes when eight black ministers from lawrence and kansas city stood up and began singing spirituals. the audience joined in and gave the ministers two standing ovations before the forum began
the ministers continued singing throughout most of the evening before marching out a side door in protest
one of the klan members, thom robb, of harrison, ark., accused the ministers of stifling free speech
these people are so filled with hatred and bigotry they refuse to let you hear us,'' said robb, national chaplain of the knights of the ku klux klan. he was accompanied by j. allen moran, exalted cyclops of the missouri knights of the ku klux klan
allan hanson, a professor of anthropology participating in the forum, told the students to listen to the klan members and make up their own minds
if you find the ideas here are ugly or twisted, use your own judgment and freedom of expression to tell other people that,'' hanson said
another participant, journalism professor ted frederickson, said he wanted to stand up for free speech, even though the klan had denied that right to people working for civil rights in the south
those people were met with bombs and guns and fists and violence,'' he said. ``but i believe in free expression, even for the klan.''
michael foubert, a graduate student and head of the group that sponsored the forum, said he invited the kkk members to the campus as a way of examining whether a university should support free speech for all viewpoints
foubert, director of ``slightly older americans for freedom,'' organized the forum after faculty members last month canceled a planned visit to campus by two klan members. the two had been scheduled to speak to a journalism class for an exercise on reporting on extremist groups and participate in a student radio talk show
black ministers in the lawrence area and the black student union had opposed the visit
david ambler, ku vice chancellor for student affairs, said the university did not interfere with the forum because it was sponsored by a student organization
students have a right to explore ideas. we're obligated to protect that right,'' ambler said. ``i hope a lot of learning goes on tonight.''
mia crawford, a black student from kansas city, kan., said she wasn't concerned that the klan would recruit any students
i'm against the kkk but they do have a right to speak,'' she said. ``i think a lot of people are here just out of curiosity.''
ninety-one junior high school students were sent to hospitals after a mysterious irritant caused rashes, blisters and breathing difficulties during physical education classes, authorities said today
chemicals were ruled out after a grounds check at rincon junior high school on monday and experts were concentrating on water contamination as a possible cause, said diane ho, a spokeswoman for the rowland unified school district
it is a mystery,'' said anastacio medina, chief of the county health department's hazardous materials control program
all but one of the seventh- and eighth-grade students were treated and released from hospitals by mid-afternoon, authorities said. one student, who was not identified, was kept overnight for observation of an asthmatic condition at inter-community medical center in covina, a nursing supervisor said today
paramedics accompanied students in ambulances and school buses to the hospitals after the first symptoms were reported monday morning, said west covina police lt. clint collins
the 700-student campus is part of the rowland unified school district in west covina, about 30 miles east of los angeles
experts from the san gabriel valley fire authority, the public health department, the department of agriculture and the walnut water district were called in to find the problem after the students started reporting swollen eyes, rashes, blisters or stomach cramps, ms. ho said
all of the youths had participated in one of three periods of physical education classes
we found no chemicals on the playgrounds,'' ms. ho said, adding that a couple of fleas were found in a grassy field area but none was known to cause such an intense reaction
none of the school's teachers or other adult employees experienced any symptoms, she said
the playgrounds were closed to all students after the outbreak was initially reported, but the rest of the school remained open
cbs inc. chairman william paley, who underwent emergency gall bladder surgery last month, was released from a hospital today after making a remarkable recovery, a spokeswoman said
paley, 86, was in critical condition following his feb. 11 surgery at new york hospital-cornell medical center
hospital spokeswoman myrna manners said paley had ``remarkably improved after one month in the hospital,'' and the network's founder was sent home this morning
paley bought the columbia broadcasting system, a fledgling radio network, in 1928. he controlled it for more than half a century, turning over the reins in 1983
when cbs's biggest stockholder, loew's corp., became unhappy with his successor's policies, paley teamed with loew's chairman lawrence tisch to retake control in 1986.   
the federal aviation administration, worried about a rash of commuter airline accidents that claimed 56 lives over a recent five-month period, today announced a year-long inspection of the commuter industry
faa administrator allan mcartor said the inspection will cover 173 commuter airlines. agency inspectors are planning to focus on about 20 percent of those carriers
mcartor said faa officials already are reviewing ``major problem areas'' in the industry, which last year carried 30 million passengers,
and plan within 60 days to begin inspections
teams of faa inspectors will focus on such areas as airline management, training programs, record keeping and aircraft condition
mcartor said the commuter airlines' safety record in recent months has sharply reversed from the trends seen in recent years. the faa cited seven commuter accidents from november through february in which 56 people were killed
the worst accident was that of a ryan air commuter nov. 13 near homer, alaska, in which 18 people died
commuter airlines have played an increasingly important role in the nation's aviation system because they often are used as feeder airlines for the major jet carriers at large airports around the country. last year the commuters carried nearly 30 million passengers, according to the regional airline association, and that number is expected to continue to climb
we want a return to the 1986 environment when commuters had the safest year in their history,'' mcartor told a news conference. in 1986, commuter airlines had just two fatal accidents in which four people were killed
faa officials said they expect the initial inspection phase of the commuters to be completed by the end of september. the agency then will prepare a final report on the findings, which would be used by inspectors responsible for the individual airlines in having corrective action taken
eliminate bc-compubug, c1067, which was a month-old column moved inadvertently on friday, march. 4. a sub column moved today on datastream as c0191. impersonator, rather than transvestite, picking up 3rd graf pvs</note>
divine, the outrageous 300-pound female impersonator who starred in such cult classics as ``pink flamingos'' and ``lust in the dust,'' died at age 42 on the verge of acceptance as a legitimate character actor, his manager said
divine, whose real name was harris glenn milstead, was a garishly made up, loud and foul-mouthed character who was introduced in 1972's ``pink flamingos'' as ``the filthiest person alive.'' milstead made the same campy character suitable for a wider audience in the current movie ``hairspray.''
he was finally getting respect within the industry,'' said manager bernard jay. ``he was getting the legitimate screen and television offers that showed the industry had finally accepted him as the very good character actor he always knew he was.''
milstead, found in his bed at the hollywood regency plaza hotel on monday, apparently died of asphyxiation in his sleep, said publicist john west of pmk
the los angeles county coroner's office said it was investigating the cause of death
last friday, a doctor declared milstead in excellent health, other than his weight, ``which has been a constant problem throughout his life,'' said jay
milstead said in a 1985 interview he grew up fat and was taunted by classmates in the baltimore suburb of lutherville. milstead told an interviewer he had a fantasy life revolving around female movie stars and dreams of becoming a celebrity
milstead was made a celebrity, at least among fans of after-midnight art films, by one of his few friends from high school, director john waters
waters cast milstead in trashy and bizarre roles as the female-impersonating star of ``pink flamingos,'' ``lust in the dust,'' ``polyester'' and ``female trouble.''
i'd see him waiting for the school bus, wearing different color hair every morning,'' waters said in a recent interview with the los angeles times
i remembered my father would just flip out. he'd get so excited. so i thought _ wow! if divine can make my father that crazy, think of how great he'd be in a movie.''
despite his dressing in drag for acting roles, milstead wasn't a transvestite at heart, waters wrote in his book, ``shock value.'' ``he says he sometimes dreads getting into drag but realizes these flamboyant outfits are his `work clothes,''' waters wrote
with each film, waters and milstead found a wider audience. the waters-directed ``hairspray,'' a spoof of the 1960s, was rated no. 16 last weekend in the box office, earning $577,258 at 79 theaters
west said milstead was in los angeles to appear in an episode of the fox television network series ``married ... with children.''
milstead was to have appeared in that series dressed as a man, as he did playing a sydney greenstreet-type character in the 1985 film ``trouble in mind.''
in ``hairspray,'' milstead played dual roles. in men's clothing, he was a television station operator determined to keep black and white youngsters from appearing together on a dance show. as divine, he starred as the stage mother of a chubby, teen-age dance show contestant
the character is a real person,'' milstead once said of divine. ``sometimes she's just too bold, but she has socially redeeming qualities, no matter what she does. she's her own person and a lot of people like that. the camp element is something out of the ordinary, this big man playing a sexy woman.''
besides film roles, milstead also used the divine persona in a nightclub act
milstead is survived by his mother and father, frances and harris milstead, of florida, west said. funeral arrangements were pending. picks up 8th graf, `howe said ...'</note>
militant roman catholics rioted through the night and into the early morning over the killing of three unarmed irish guerrillas in gibraltar. the irish government said it was ``gravely perturbed'' at the shootings
youths in belfast pelted police with gasoline bombs and set ablaze several dozen automobiles in rioting that lasted into early today, police said. no injuries were reported
it was one of the worst nights of violence in the british-ruled province since last summer, and was touched off by the shooting of two men and a woman sunday in britain's fortress colony on spain's southern coast
foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe said monday that a ``dreadful terrorist act has been averted'' by the slayings
the three people killed were actively involved in the planning and attempted execution of that act,'' he told the house of commons in london
police in gibraltar said the three were believed to be involved in an irish republican army plan to detonate a car bomb at the governor's residence during a ceremonial changing of the guard today
fifty members of the royal anglian regiment, just transferred from duty in northern ireland, took part in the ceremony which occurred without incident
security was heavy as gibraltar police and british troops with dogs patrolled the fringes of a crowd of about 300 tourists and residents who watched the colorful ceremony in front of the convent, official residence of governor sir peter terry
the ira, which is fighting a guerrilla war to drive the british from northern ireland, acknowledged that the three guerrillas were on a mission but accused the british government of needlessly killing them
in dublin, prime minister charles haughey's government said it recognized the need for security forces ``to take all reasonable measures to combat terrorism.''
the government is, however, gravely perturbed that three unarmed irish people should have been shot dead ... when it appears from reports that they could have been arrested by the security forces,'' the government said
ireland is already embroiled in a series of disputes with britain over security forces in northern ireland, including britain's unwillingness to prosecute police officers who allegedly carried out a shoot-to-kill policy in the province
howe said the soldiers opened fire after the guerrillas parked a renault-5 with spanish license plates near the governor's residence and headed on foot for the spanish border 800 yards away
howe said the three guerrillas ``made movements which led security personnel to believe their lives were in danger.''
police searched gibraltar and adjacent spanish territory on monday for another car believed connected with the three. the theory is the renault-5 was reserving a space for a car bomb
howe said spanish police tipped off the british after a fourth ira guerrilla they were watching crossed into gibraltar, apparently to carry out ``reconnaissance for an act of terrorism.''
the london newspaper the daily mail said spanish police believe the fourth suspect may be evelyn glenholmes, who has been linked with several ira attacks in past years. it quoted them as saying a women of her description was seen visiting the other three at an apartment in malaga, two hours' drive from gibraltar
howe said a car for which the three slain guerrillas had keys was found parked on the spanish side of the gate separating this 2.25-square-mile limestone rock from the spanish mainland. he said it contained keys to a third car, three false passports and equipment including an alarm clock, insulating tape and wire that could be used to detonate a bomb
howe did not identify the british unit involved, but there was speculation they were from the elite special air services regiment, whose movements are secret. witnesses said they wore jeans
the outlawed ira, in a statement from belfast, identified the dead as: mairead farrell, 31, who had served 10 years jail for blowing up a hotel, sean savage, 24, and daniel mccann, 30, both of whom have been arrested on explosive charges
all three were from catholic west belfast, where the rioting broke out after howe's statement
in belfast, police fired plastic bullets to disperse gangs of youths who hurled gasoline bombs and set fire to 30 vehicles including buses, vans and trucks. gunmen launched at least two sniper attacks on police and troops, police said
the mainly catholic ira seeks to drive the british from northern ireland and unite the predominantly protestant province with the overwhelmingly catholic irish republic under socialist rule
the mayor has announced his resignation amid a criminal probe into the handling of client funds in his private law practice
the town council will decide on march 21 whether to appoint a replacement for richard kennett or call a special election. kennett also resigned his position as a council member
please accept my deepest and most sincere apology for any embarrassment and adverse publicity which in any way reflects poorly on our town, its staff or council,'' kennett said in a resignation letter dated friday
the letter did not mention a contra costa county district attorney's investigation into kennett's practice, officials said. kennett has said his attorney has advised him not to comment on the probe
district attorney gary yancey also refused comment because the case involved an ``ongoing investigation.''
kennett's attorney, william gagen, said at least part of the investigation stems from checks sent to debbie peterson of spokane, wash
peterson had hired kennett to settle her deceased mother's estate; the investigation involves checks that allegedly bounced
the state bar of california has ruled in a separate case that kennett failed to represent a client in divorce proceedings in a timely manner, had neglected the case of another client, and had failed to respond to inquiries from the state bar about these complaints
that ruling is going to the state bar's review panel for a recommendation on disciplinary action
kennett, 49, was elected to the danville town council in november 1985 and was named by fellow council members to a one-year mayor's term last december. danville is a suburban town of 7,000 about 20 miles east of san francisco. at his, etc.</note>
a confident george bush cast his ballot in the texas primary today, saying ``i'm encouraged'' about his prospects in the super tuesday republican presidential contests
i'm not making any predictions,'' bush told reporters as he prepared to go into a hotel polling place west of the downtown area
standing with his wife, barbara, beside his limousine under threatening skies, bush said, ``if we exceed our expectations or live up to them, i think we'll be in good shape.''
top campaign aides had said earlier that they thought bush stood a good chance of winning at least 12 or 13 state contests today
as bush prepared to await the returns here and in 16 other states, his aides were getting ready for a series of campaign strategy sessions wednesday
a principal focus of those sessions will be how to continue the vote-getting momentum as the competition moves to illinois and other states in the midwest
asked today if he had gained ``big mo'' over his opponents, bush replied, ``i never use that expression since 1980. i've learned since then.''
after upsetting ronald reagan in the 1980 iowa caucuses bush claimed he had achieved ``big mo.'' but then he went on to lose to reagan in new hampshire and subsequently pulled out of the race
i'm encouraged,'' bush said today when asked how well he would do. ``but regardless of what happens here, the battle goes right on to illinois.''
at his last public appearance on monday, in rogers, ark., bush said he was ``optimistic but not overconfident.''
asked what he'd do if he didn't win today, he replied: ``i'll have to do what i did when i got kicked in iowa _ get up off the canvas, go out and fight hard.'' after his third-place finish in iowa, bush went on to a solid win in the new hampshire primary eight days later
after a day of campaigning in arkansas, missouri and oklahoma, bush flew to his adopted hometown to vote in the texas primary and await the results
but his top campaign aides and leading southern strategists said they wouldn't be surprised if the vice president captured some 600 of the roughly 700 delegates at stake
such a scenario, said campaign manager lee atwater, could present republican presidential rival bob dole with a must-win scenario in next week's illinois primary
i don't know what dole does if he doesn't win illinois,'' atwater said. a dole campaign source agreed that the kansas senator has to win illinois and said the campaign is prepared to spend $500,000 on advertising there
bush seemed tired, but upbeat, as he toured an american airlines maintenance facility at tulsa's airport
the person that clearly wins super tuesday is going to be the nominee of the party and, i think, the next president,'' he said. ``it's critical.''
but bush brushed aside talk of a sweep. ``you always wish for that, but i certainly would never predict that. it's too much for anyone to expect.''
atwater said he expected bush to win 12 or 13 of the 17 gop events, and deputy campaign manager rich bond said the campaign is prepared to spend ``whatever it takes'' to win illinois
bush returned to houston almost five months from the day he declared his presidential candidacy here, saying ``i mean to run hard and i mean to win.''
bush is a native of massachusetts and was raised in connecticut, but he moved here with his wife, barbara, in 1948, to learn the oil business. he became a successful oilman before venturing into politics as a county republican chairman
i'm guardedly optimistic'' about bush's chances in texas, state campaign political kevin moomaw said. ``bob dole's campaign in texas is non-existent. the competition in this state has been pat robertson.''
moomaw said not even the forecast of heavy rains through much of texas would put a damper on bush's prospects
we are warning everybody to go out and vote,'' he said. ``there is a potential for a turnout of 750,000.''
ken wright, bush's florida campaign director, said ``we're looking good. i'd like to see us come out with 70 of the 82 delegates. i think we're going to do very, very well.''
bush got a lift with his lopsided victory in south carolina's primary on saturday. he had stumbled out of the starting gate, finishing behind dole and robertson in iowa. but bush bounced back to win by a comfortable margin in new hampshire, and has done well since, although he did not compete in minnesota and withdrew from south dakota a week before losing that contest to dole
two former leaders of a strict religious group have surrendered their passports and agreed to stay in the united states pending trial on charges involving the death of a 10-year-old diabetic boy
doug kleber and jeffrey siegel, both of champaign, ill., posted $2,500 bond after being charged with second-degree criminal mistreatment and were released from the spokane county jail monday, officials said
kleber, former national leader of the so-called ``no name fellowship,'' and siegel, former head elder of the spokane branch, are among seven people being investigated in the dec. 20 death of aaron norman. an autopsy determined the boy died from untreated juvenile diabetes
at issue is whether the normans and church leaders knew the boy was seriously ill but withheld medical care because of their religious beliefs. leaders have said the church believes in the power of prayer, and former members say the church distrusts doctors and institutionalized medicine
the boy's parents, bob and judith norman, are being investigated for homicide by abuse, said county deputy prosecutor clark colwell
the normans did not seek medical help prior to the child's death, but contacted church leaders after trying unsuccessfully to revive the boy using cardiopulmonary resuscitation, according to sheriff's deputies
the boy was disciplined by spanking on the advice of church leaders the day before he died, authorities say. a pathologist determined the spanking did not contribute to the boy's death but said bruises were found on his buttocks and legs
kleber has said that neither he nor the normans knew the boy was seriously ill and that they would have taken him to a doctor if they had known
the normans have been members of the spokane fellowship since it started in in 1981, but the branch announced last weekend it had disbanded
since the boy's death, the normans' youngest son, 8-year-old david, has been put in foster care by state officials
three others charged with criminal mistreatment are mark roloff, 33, the head elder of the former spokane branch, and church members john johnson, 37, and steve arden of spokane, colwell said
arraignment for all defendants will be scheduled in the next several weeks in superior court, officials said
the church said it has about 200 members in spokane; champaign; plano, texas; and passaic, n.j. it was formed in the 1970s in illinois primarily as a bible-study group for athletes. giving more details</note>
supreme court justice sandra day o'connor had her appendix removed at bethesda naval hospital on monday night and was reported in good condition today
court spokeswoman toni house said o'connor, 57, was feeling ``exceedingly well'' but gave few other details
o'connor arrived at the hospital in mid-afternoon monday, and was operated on about 8 p.m., house said
a hospital spokesman said all details of o'connor's medical treatment would have to come from house's office
o'connor had been scheduled to testify, along with justice antonin scalia, before a house appropriations subcommittee today about the supreme court's budgetary requests for fiscal year 1989
an opposition spokesman said riot police clashed today with hundreds of student protesters in krakow, while at warsaw university thousands of students demonstrated peacefully to demand greater academic freedom
about 70 to 100 people were detained in krakow, but police began releasing them by early afternoon, opposition activist zygmunt lenyk said. he said at least three people were severely beaten by police
the demonstrations coincided with the anniversary of march 8, 1968, student protests at warsaw university against censorship and political repression, which were brutally broken up by police and communist party worker activists
this year's protests reflected a renewed campaign by student activists urging communist authorities to legalize the independent students union, known as nzs, which was outlawed following the december 1981 martial law crackdown on the independent labor federation solidarity
at krakow's jagiellonian university, about 700 students tried to march to the main square in the city's old town following a noon campus rally organized by the nzs, but found the street cordoned off by police, lenyk said
lenyk, quoting eyewitness accounts, said police attacked the crowd with clubs, but some demonstrators pushed their way through police lines to reach the square, where they were detained
he said most of the students returned to campus and tried twice more to march to the square, about 500 yards away, but each time were attacked by police
a government spokesman, asked about the reported clash and violence, said he had no information and promised to look into the matter
at warsaw university, police did not intervene as more than 2,000 students peacefully demonstrated without leaving campus
students and university workers, carrying dozens of banners demanding legalization of the nzs and solidarity free trade union, marched to a campus carrying a plaque commemorating the 1968 protests
the plaque was put up in march 1981 when both solidarity and the nzs functioned legally
university authorities allowed the rally, but the campus' main gates were locked and security guards kept non-university personnel from entering
after students and faculty members laid wreaths under the plaque, campus nzs leaders stood on top of a wall to take turns speaking to the crowd through a bullhorn. cited</head>
a judge had refused to allow the release of fbi surveillance records tracking the political activities of late beatle john lennon because their disclosure could compromise national security
the request for release of lennon's fbi dossier was made by university of california, irvine, professor jon wiener under the freedom of information act. wiener said he will appeal the ruling by u.s. district judge robert takasugi
the decision came in response to a 1983 lawsuit filed by wiener when the fbi released only part of lennon's file, which contains documents about the musician's anti-war activities in the 1970s
they claimed some of these documents would damage national security,'' wiener said. ``to me, it sounds like a ridiculous thing to say about 18-year-old documents about the political activities of a dead rock star.''
lennon was murdered outside his new york city apartment in 1980
the ruling came last week after a closed-doors meeting between takasugi and government attorneys. to 1904, sted 1908</note>
actor robert livingston, who rode the range in dozens of movies and was the only lone ranger to remove his mask, has died. he was 83
livingston, who died at his tarzana home monday, had been battling emphysema, and was seriously ill for the last eight months, said his publicist, samuel m. sherman
when livingston appeared in the 1939 movie ``the lone ranger rides again,'' republic pictures had him remove the mask briefly so that he would be associated in the public's mind as the lone ranger, said livingston's son addison randall
actor clayton moore played the lone ranger on radio and television
born robert e. randall in 1904, in quincy, ill., livingston chose a stage name rather than compete with his younger brother addison ``jack'' randall, who later was killed in a screen accident
as stoney brooke, one of the ``three mesquiteers,'' livingston rode the range with two cowboy pals through 29 of the republic pictures films. when he left for other roles, his replacement was a then little known actor named john wayne, said sherman
his other films included ``the bold caballero,'' 1937; ``mutiny on the bounty,'' with clark gable, 1935; ``pistol packin' mama,'' 1943; ``daredevils of the clouds,'' his last picture for republic, 1948; ``once upon a horse,'' 1958, and ``blazing steweardesses, 1975
funeral services will be private
contra leader adolfo calero said today that the rebels would not attend cease-fire negotiations the sandinista government had scheduled to begin wednesday in nicaragua
calero said in a telephone interview from miami that government officials talked to the rebel leaders on monday ``at the last minute'' to tell them ``that they were ready for a meeting.''
apparently what the sandinista government wants is a unilateral show...,'' he said. ``we are not willing to attend a unilateral meeting set up by the sandinistas.''
three days of talks were to be held at the frontier post of sapoa, about 90 miles from the capital of managua along the southern border with costa rica
calero said the rebels may agree to hold talks at a later date in sapoa
he complained the government had not responded to a statement the rebels issued last week calling for cardinal miguel obando y bravo to continue participating in the talks as a witness and for the talks to center on wider issues than just arrangements for a cease-fire between the warring sides
president daniel ortega proposed the talks last week. he also said obando y bravo, head of the roman catholic church in nicaragua, would no longer serve as a mediator as he had in previous discussions
ortega said the government delegation to the talks would be headed by his brother, humberto ortega, the defense minister and one of nine members on the ruling national directorate
the contras named calero to head their delegation, but insisted that the cardinal be a witness at the meeting
late monday, the government said obando y bravo and joao baena soares, secretary general of the organization of american states, had agreed to serve as witnesses
the government maintains the talks should focus on the laying down of arms as outlined in the regional peace plan signed last august by the presidents of nicaragua, el salvador, guatemala, costa rica and honduras
the rebels want the discussions to be expanded to include a proposal put forth last month in guatemala city by the cardinal
obando y bravo's agenda called for the government to grant total amnesty to political prisoners, review a mandatory military draft law, allow full press freedom and renew a dialogue with its internal opposition. in return for the concessions, the contras were to accept a 30-day cease-fire
the u.s.-backed rebels have been fighting against the sandinista government since november 1981
the hermit of chestnut hill,'' who lived in makeshift huts on government land for nearly two decades and resisted well-publicized efforts to relocate him, died the way he would have wanted, says a friend
he died free, so to speak,'' said clyde raymond. ``he had his own drummer and stuck with it.''
bill britt, 52, had been dead for several months when he was found monday by two of his three childen, ingrid boughner of belmont and britton steven boughner of medford, boston police spokesman scott gillis
his body, dressed in multiple layers of clothing, was almost skeletal because of decomposition and animals, gillis said
dr. stanton kessler of the suffolk county medical examiner's office said today that autopsy results showed britt died of hypothermia. he said identification of the body was ``presumptive,'' because rats had eaten away most of britt's face and other exposed areas
kessler said britt's feet were found dug into the ground, as if to gain some warmth
born britton william boughner in wealthy chestnut hill, britt had lived on nearby land controlled by the metropolitan district commission since 1969. his hut was about 30 feet inside the fence surrounding evergreen cemetery, in the area of a large reservoir on the boston-brookline border
in his case, he felt that this was where he wanted to live, this was his estate,'' said raymond
in 1985, officials started trying to move britt, who was legally blind and lived on money from collecting cans and bottles for the deposits. when he refused welfare and several attempts to relocate him to public or subsidized housing, the news media dubbed him ``the hermit on chestnut hill.''
in may, britt's plastic and wood wigwam was destroyed in a fire. he was in new york city at the time appearing on the ``late night with david letterman'' television show because of the publicity his case attracted
state appeals court judge edith fine issued a stay preventing authorities from removing britt from the property. but when the appeals court order expired in july, officials removed his rebuilt wigwam and his belongings
britt rebuilt it again despite deteriorating health. an opthalmologist testified at a housing court hearing a year ago that britt had ulcers and he needed a corneal transplant. also, britt was nearly toothless
last year, he said he was writing a ``hermit's cookbook,'' but the manuscript and other papers relating to his legal battles were lost in the may fire. graf pvs, the assistant.</note>
a justice department official today proposed raising congressional salaries to as much as $175,000 in exchange for dropping the ``double standard'' that exempts congress from federal ethics laws
i personally am attracted by the idea of raising the salary of all members of congress to a level around somewhere between $150,000 and $175,000 a year,'' assistant attorney general william weld said in a speech attacking public corruption
this would enable you to do some other things like prohibit honoraria,'' added weld, who is in charge of the department's criminal division. ``it would be very, very expensive, and ... worth every penny.''
members of the executive branch and independent agencies are prohibited from supplementing salaries with fees and honoraria for job-related activities. violators are subject to up to a year in prison
congressional salaries are now $89,500 a year, which senators may supplement with honoraria in an amount not to exceed 40 percent of their salaries. the percentage for house members is 30 percent
weld said the payment of $2,000 fees to members of congress who visited a business establishment over which their committee had jurisdiction ``would be a laydown criminal case if performed by somebody in the executive branch.''
you have the double standard (of) criminal acts by one branch of government'' being legal in another ``and that really is neither logical nor is it consonant with the notion of fair play,'' weld said in remarks at the national press club
he said raising congressional salaries and applying the ban on outside payments would end ``any risk that these fees or honoraria would be influencing a legislator's sense of how to spend his time, much less his vote.'' higher salaries might attract talented people who otherwise would be unable to afford being in congress
in response to questions, he rejected the suggestion that his comments were an attempt to overshadow the fact that a number of reagan administration officials are under criminal investigation or have been convicted of crimes
my remarks today are the same as remarks i've been giving ... since 1978,'' said weld, a former u.s. attorney in boston and a former candidate for state attorney general in massachusetts
weld's boss, attorney general edwin meese iii, is under investigation in the wedtech scandal and in connection with a $1 billion proposed iraqi pipeline project that may have involved planned payoffs to the israeli labor party
weld also criticized congress for excluding itself from coverage of conflict-of-interest laws, which former white house political director lyn nofziger was convicted last month of violating on behalf of scandal-plagued wedtech corp. and two other clients
the assistant attorney general noted the lack of restrictions on lobbying by former congressmen
the day after a congressman leaves office, he is free to lobby his former colleagues on behalf of himself or his friends or clients, while continuing to enjoy full access to the house and senate floors,'' said weld. ``as recent events have made abundantly clear, such behavior by a former member of the executive branch would land one in jail.''
nofziger, under the 1978 ethics in government act, was found guilty of lobbying his former agency within one year after he left the government on matters in which the agency had been substantially involved
the matters pertained to a federal contract for wedtech, the continued production of a10 anti-tank aircraft and civilian manning of navy ships
nofziger faces sentencing later this month. 0989</first> comment from gay men's health crisis</note>
aids experts have sharply criticized a book by the sex experts dr. william masters and virginia johnson that claims to find wide spread of aids among heterosexuals
they have not done even the most rudimentary things to establish any representativeness of their results,'' says dr. june osborn, a virologist, pediatrician and dean of the school of public health at the university of michigan
in the book, released monday and titled ``crisis: heterosexual behavior in the age of aids,'' masters and johnson reported finding a 5 percent aids infection rate in men who said they had at least six sexual partners a year for five years, and a 7 percent infection rate in similarly active women
by comparison, federal figures released in february that cover the period from 1985 to sept. 30 show that 5,890 of 3.96 million military recruits tested positive, a rate of 1.5 cases of aids infection for every 1,000 people tested
based on their study of 800 people, masters and johnson concluded: ``the aids virus has certainly established a beachhead in the ranks of heterosexuals, and ... the odds are that the rate of spread among heterosexuals will now begin to escalate at a frightening pace.''
osborn contended that no such conclusion can be reached because the 800, including some people recruited with sign-up sheets on bulletin boards, were not chosen to be representative of the u.s. population
lori behrman, spokeswoman for the manhattan-based gay men's health crisis, today called the findings unscientific and expressed concern that they would harm anti-discrimination efforts
they have squandered their credibity to exploit a public health issue,'' said behrman. ``they have succeeded in alarming the public and have undone the good work that public officials have done around the country. you don't raise false alarms around an issue so potentially explosive as aids.''
late monday on abc-tv's ``nightline,'' masters defended the unscientific sample as a preliminary step, ``raising an alarm'' about the possibility there are heterosexuals outside the known risk groups who are in danger from the aids epidemic
what we haven't realized is that there is another group of those heterosexuals who have a very multiplicity-of-partners type of sex life, and that is all that the experiments demonstrated,'' masters said
masters denied that at a morning news conference the authors had backed off the book's claim that aids was ``running rampant'' among heterosexuals
we think that it is spreading very rapidly in the heterosexual population. we used the word rampant advisedly, because we think that we are facing a situation where there is tremendous danger.''
dr. peter fischinger, aids coordinator for the public health service, disagreed earlier monday, saying, ``we don't see an explosion into the heterosexual community.''
he noted that nationwide screening of blood donors has found that only about one in 40,000 shows evidence of infection with the aids virus. but he added, ``this does not mean we can be complacent about it.''
mathilde krim, chairwoman of the american foundation for aids research, said, ``masters and johnson may have expertise in sexuality, but they have no credentials to justify their recommendations concerning aids public health policy _ recommendations that will surely alarm the public.''
masters and johnson and their co-author, dr. robert kolodny, a director of the masters &amp; johnson institute in st. louis, also resurrected the nearly universally discarded notion that aids can be spread by casual contact
it does a disservice to the public to suggest once again that you can get this from kissing,'' said dr. stephen joseph, new york city's public health commissioner. the authors also called for widespread mandatory testing for aids, a recommendation that has been opposed by most public health authorities
i don't see anything in their own data that would lead one to make the sweeping statements about casual transmission and mandatory testing that i think they've made,'' said joseph
at their news conference, masters, johnson and kolodny appeared to disavow some of the claims they made in the book. kolodny acknowledged writing that kissing could spread aids, but said under harsh questioning from reporters that it was only a very small theoretical possibility
kolodny said today on abc's ``good morning america'' that the authors had ``carefully worded'' their statements ``to say, for instance, of the restaurant situation, as a practical matter, there's no risk.''
but should we be, as scientists, dishonest with the public and say there's no risk at all, none, when the history of this epidemic has been that every year new revelations come forth?'' he added
joseph, on cbs' ``this morning,'' said that he feared a backlash against ``alarmist and unsupported numbers.''
there is a real threat from heterosexual transmission, it's a major part of the epidemic, but blowing it out of proportion, as masters and johnson have done, i think will hurt the credibility of the issue in the end
with aids its not who you are, its what you do. anyone who engages in high-risk behavior, any heterosexual person who is a partner of someone who is in a primary risk group, a bisexual man or a man who uses iv drugs, is at risk,'' joseph said
asked at monday's news conference to back up the book's statement that ``the aids virus is now running rampant in the heterosexual community,'' masters said, ``i simply believe this.'' johnson said, ``i'm not sure we chose the word `rampant' ourselves.''
osborn criticized the authors for being secretive about their findings. she said masters and johnson attended an aids workshop at the kinsey institute in bloomington, ind., in december and ``they didn't give any clue that three months later this would come out.''
it does, to me, shake my confidence in their scientific purpose,'' she said
two former executives of a firm subcontracted to work on the b-1 bomber pleaded guilty to charges involving a fraudulent check-cashing scheme and illegal overbilling for time spent working on the military jet
robert f. butler, former owner of butler industries and purkey co. inc., and steven wooten, former general manager of butler industries, entered their pleas monday before u.s. district judge stephen v. wilson
the pleas were part of a deal in which the defendants acknowledged the government's case against them but claimed they never intended to violate the law, said butler's attorney, gerson s. horn. the arrangement allows them to present their defense in any civil litigation arising from the case
it would have taken a tremendous amount of money to fight this case,'' horn said. ``the government threatened to indict more'' unless the plea bargain was accepted
one of the three federal grand jury indictments accused both butler and wooten of overbilling rockwell inc., the aerospace contractor on the u.s. air force's b-1 bomber, for time spent changing orders on parts for the bomber
rockwell was billed for 495 hours of work on the subcontract, 445 more than were actually involved, said assistant u.s. attorney j. stephen czuleger. the billing amounted to $200,000 in erroneous charges, government officials said
horn said, however, that several company employees could present testimony to show that the amount of time devoted to the change orders was not overestimated
the other indictment charged butler, 54, and wooten, 30, with cashing company checks valued at more than $144,000 made out to fictitious payees over a two-year period. the checks were then illegally deducted on corporate tax returns as a cost of goods sold, czuleger said
butler was indicted in another bogus check-cashing scam of more than $259,000 involving purkey co. inc
horn said the two men claim they were writing the phony checks to obtain cash for real business expenses. the company was habitually overdrawn and would otherwise have been unable to get the money, he said
butler, who pleaded guilty to charges of conspiracy, presenting false claims to the united states, subscribing to a false corporate income tax return and assisting in the preparation of a false tax return, faces a maximum two years in prison and $240,000 in fines. he will be sentenced june 20
wooten, who pleaded guilty to similar charges in two of the indictments, faces one year and fines of $130,000. he will be sentenced april 25
u.s. coast guard vessels have stopped almost 500 haitians attempting to enter the united states illegally in the past three days, a spokesman said today
since saturday three cutters have intercepted four sailing vessels crammed with haitians off the bahamas, said service spokesman luis diaz
the figures in the past three days have almost doubled the number of haitians stopped this year, he said, adding the weather alone could not explain the sudden surge in interdictions
the seas are calm at the moment, but it definitely has to be the economic situation in their country,'' said diaz
on saturday a sailing vessel with 192 people was stopped off great inagua, and since then three other ships have been stopped near crooked island, said diaz
one intercepted today had 90 aboard ``and still counting,'' said diaz
the 1,186 total since jan. 1 is running well ahead of last year's total of 3,556 people caught and returned to haiti, he said. graf pvs ``today's release.. ''</note>
a british relief worker and his syrian aide were freed today, five days after being taken captive in south lebanon, a sunni moslem leader said
the briton, peter coleridge, told reporters in the southern port city of sidon that there had been ``no kidnapping'' and that he and omar traboulsi were detained because they took photographs without authorization
mustafa saad, the sunni leader whose militia controls sidon, said palestinian guerrillas freed coleridge, the 44-year-old middle east coordinator of the british oxfam relief agency, and traboulsi, a 31-year-old syrian who is the agency's representative in lebanon. they were taken captive thursday at sidon's ein el-hilweh palestinian refugee camp
saad said by telephone that representatives of fatah-revolutionary council, the radical faction headed by abu nidal, turned the two captives over to him at his house in sidon at 3:50 p.m
the release of coleridge and traboulsi leaves 22 foreigners missing and presumed kidnapped in lebanon. they are nine americans, four frenchmen, three britons, one irishman, one italian, one west german, one indian, and two unidentified men. the longest held is terry a. anderson, 40, chief middle east correspondent for the associated press, who was kidnapped march 16, 1985
lebanese security sources have said abu nidal's guerrillas seized coleride and traboulsi when they saw coleridge taking pictures of parts of ein el-hilweh
i made a mistake by not asking for a permission (to shoot pictures) from the authority in ein el-hilweh,'' coleridge told reporters at saad's home
i know and respect the people who took us. there has been no kidnapping. it was clear from the beginning that i made a mistake. they were only applying security procedures,'' he said
coleridge, clean-shaven and dressed in dark blue trousers and a beige jacket, said he ``didn't lose hope'' during his captivity
we were well treated. we were held at around 4 p.m. thursday near the place we photographed in ein el-hilweh. three hours later they moved us blindfolded to another place. omar and i were in separate rooms all the time,'' he added
traboulsi did not talk to reporters
today's release came one week after two u.n. relief workers were freed in southern lebanon
jan stening of sweden and william jorgensen of norway had been abducted near the south lebanon's provincial capital of sidon feb. 5. they were freed march 1
their employer, the u.n. relief and works agency, said today it would consider resuming some of its activities in the war-torn country
but unrwa, in a statement released in vienna, austria, said it would not resume full operations in lebanon without minimum guarantees of security for its foreign workers there
unrwa cares for palestinian refugees in the middle east
the health ministry declared a meningitis epidemic tuesday, saying 20 people have died of the disease in recent days and 600 are hospitalized
meningitis normally strikes in sudan every summer, but this year it began a month earlier than usual early because of unseasonably early high temperatures. the temperature tuesday was 111 degrees fahrenheit
the health ministry said khartoum has been declared an ``epidemic-hit area'' and added the government was using all its capabilities to deal with the situation
it said another 148 cases have been reported from other regions in sudan
the statement said the disease was widely spread within overcrowded shanty towns around the capital, where an estimated 750,000 people from southern sudan are seeking refuge from famine and civil war in the south
trophy hunters killed a rare indian antelope at an animal park with a crossbow, then beheaded it, police said
it was the second such incident since 1983 at the symbio animal gardens at stanwell park south of sydney, police said monday
i suppose they will stick the head on a wall and boast about it,'' said park owner bob grover. ``they probably wanted it because of its long, spiraling horns.''
the antelope, named rajah, was beloved by the thousands of children who visited each year. the park staff said its mate, rajeesh, was pining for its companion
police said the poachers also skinned the animal after shooting it at close range
thieves tunneled into a jewelry store through the floor of an adjacent hotel, silenced its alarms and stole $1.6 million in gems, according to a news report
burglars using a blowtorch cut open a safe in the furst jewelry store and took out keys that opened a second safe where the jewels were kept, the italian news agency ansa reported monday
the thieves entered the store by cutting a hole in the floor of the hotel majestic that was closed for renovation and silenced the alarms by cutting telephone lines and pulling one alarm out of the wall, ansa said
store owner manlio bertucci, 36, said someone tried to break into the downtown store several years ago by throwing hand grenades through the front window. he said metal blinds kept the thieves from getting into the store
china has successfully launched into orbit its 22nd satellite, a synchronous communications satellite, it was reported tuesday
the nationally televised evening news showed a long march 3 rocket blasting off monday night from a launch site in xichuang, sichuan province
acting premier li peng, who was shown with military leaders watching the launch of the telecommunications satellite, later congratulated scientists and technicians on its success
the long march 3 is china's most sophisticated rocket
reports have said the three-stage rocket's launch capabilities were nearly doubled last year, and it can now put a payload of 2{ tons into geosynchronous orbit 22,320 miles above earth
china launched its first satellite in 1970 and has recovered all 10 of the retrievable satellites it put into space
it began offering launch services for foreign countries last year. two u.s. companies have contracted with china to launch communications satellites this year. china also is to put a norwegian satellite into orbit in 1991
deng yingchao, widow of premier chou en-lai and one of china's most respected women, will resign as head of a prestigious advisory body, it was reported tuesday
deng, 84, will be among 600 people who will give up their seats on the national committee of the china people's political consultative conference, which will hold its annual session from march 24, the official xinhua news agency said
she told a meeting of the conference's standing committee the resignations will revitalize the advisory body, which is made up of prominent members from the communist party, non-communist groups and mass organizations
the standing committee approved a list of 2,081 for the new national committee, xinhua said
at the age of 21, deng joined the party and married chou. she was one of only about 50 women to complete the 7,750-mile long march in 1934-35
after chou's death in 1976, she began to play a more prominent role in politics, gaining a seat on the policy-making politburo in 1978
often referred to as china's ``elder sister,'' she and chou adopted about 10 war orphans, including acting premier li peng
the report did not say who would succeed her
west german prosecutors are investigating more than 1,100 cases of suspected nazi war crimes, the country's chief nazi hunter said tuesday
there are still formal investigations of 1,164 persons,'' said prosecutor alfred streim, chief of west germany's office for nazi war crimes investigations
streim's office in the southern city of ludwigsburg also has checked out 18,000 names on a list of possible war crimes suspects received from the united nations war crimes commission archives in 1986, the statement said
in january, streim said he had added 10 prosecutors to his staff to help with the increased workload in investigating 4,500 war crimes suspects from the u.n. list. the rest of the suspects had either died, or had been cleared or convicted in previous trials
according to federal statistics, 91,481 people have been investigated by west german officials since the end of world war ii, with 6,482 ending in convictions. of those, 12 were sentenced to death, 160 to life imprisonment, and the rest to lesser punishment, the statement said
former mayor dianne feinstein would stand a good chance of winning the democratic nomination for governor in 1990, according to a california poll released tuesday
the poll showed feinstein leading attorney general john van de kamp, state schools superintendent bill honig and controller gary davis among registered democrats questioned
none of the democrats has announced plans for 1990, and gov. george deukmejian, a republican, has not said if he will seek a third term
feinstein had the support of 47 percent of democrats in northern california and 25 percent in southern california. she was the first pick of 34 percent statewide
van de kamp was the favorite of 34 percent of southern california democrats, 13 percent in the north and 26 percent statewide. honig was picked by 12 percent statewide and davis by 10 percent
the poll found that feinstein was the choice of 42 percent of all registered voters while deukmejian was favored by 48 percent. ten percent of those questioned were undecided
the survey of 769 registered voters was conducted feb. 17-21 and has a margin of error of plus or minus 3.6 percent. the democratic gubernatorial preference of 356 registered democrats had an error margin of plus or minus 5.2 percent
president roh tae-woo's ruling party rammed its version of a new election law through the national assembly on tuesday with an impromptu voice vote, clearing the way for crucial legislative elections
after the law was passed during an unruly assembly session that drew shouts of outrage from opposition lawmakers, officials of the ruling democratic justice party said national assembly elections would be held about april 20
the two sides squabbled over the legislation for hours when vice national assembly speaker chang sung-man, protected by guards, went to the podium, called for a voice vote and quickly declared the bill passed
opposition lawmakers tried to block the move but were caught off guard. some rushed the podium but were stopped by guards. a brief scuffle broke out between ruling and opposition lawmakers, but nobody was hurt
it is regrettable that the assembly could not proceed smoothly, although we made concessions up until the last minute,'' said democratic justice party spokesman you kyung-hyun
you said his party had to pass the bill before the current assembly session ended tuesday in order to hold the general elections by april 28, the legal deadline. he said at least 35 days are needed to prepare
