weeping armenians gathered in a snowy cemetery in moscow on tuesday to exchange tales of brutal beatings and deaths in a southern city torn by ethnic mob violence
their accounts, which often elicited cries of anger from the 300 listeners, could not be verified independently, but were typical of stories that have been circulating in armenian communities since the feb. 28 rioting in the city of sumgait in the republic of azerbaijan
the unrest in sumgait was triggered by protests in the republic of armenia demanding that a region given to neighboring azerbaijan in 1923 be shifted to armenian control. the population of the nagorno-karabakh district is more than three-quarters armenian
tass, the official soviet news agency, has said that 31 people were killed in sumgait, which has an armenian minority. soviet officials have refused to elaborate on what happened and moscow-based journalists have been barred from traveling to the caucasus region
there have been many reports by armenian activists of high death tolls and brutality against armenians by azeris, members of the dominant ethnic group in azerbaijan. the azeris are predominantly shiite moslem, while the armenians are predominantly christian
the tearful crowd gathered in front of a brick church in the armenian section of moscow's vagankovskoye cemetery. plainclothes police watched but did not try to break up the meeting, which lasted two hours
one distraught man said he saw a pregnant woman and her unborn baby slain and mutilated in sumgait. at the local communist party headquarters, he said, he saw people who were covered with knife wounds and who had their ears cut off
the gray-haired man left without giving his name
the meeting began with a moment of silence for women slain in sumgait. a priest clad in black asked members of the crowd who had witnessed anti-armenian violence to come forward to speak
a resident of a village near sumgait said bands of azeris had roved through his settlement, looking under beds for armenian children and raping armenian women. another armenian said young children had been thrown from windows
ambartsum galestyan, deputy chairman of the committee that organized last month's protests in yerevan, armenia's capital, said 33 people had been killed in the sumgait rioting
they included two azeris, galestyan said. he said the azeris had been killed by military units brought in to restore order, and that eight soldiers had been killed. he said 100 to 150 people were seriously injured
galestyan said 4- and 5-year-old children had been thrown out of fifth-floor windows by mobs in sumgait, an industrial city of more than 160,000 people. the yerevan resident did not say how he had learned of the attacks on the children or whether they had been killed, and it was not clear whether he had been in sumgait
a villager who lives near sumgait said four people in his settlement were slain. the villager, who did not give his name, said he did not know where his family or sister were. ``i fear for their safety,'' he told the meeting
some speakers were angry at soviet state-run press and television, which blamed ``extremists'' for the dispute over nagorno-karabakh and never clearly linked the violence in sumgait to antagonisms between armenians and azeris
how can the soviet media today be silent, under conditions of openness and restructuring?'' asked robert aryanpetyan, a specialist in history who lives in moscow. ``shame on the central television.''
john zaccaro jr., who was arrested on drug charges about a year after his mother's vice presidential bid, says working with runaways has shown him that everyone deserves a second chance
i've learned that everyone deserves a second chance, or a third and fourth chance, however many it may take,'' zaccaro, son of geraldine ferraro, wrote in the march 29 issue of woman's day magazine about his volunteer work with covenant house
my problems are nothing compared to the kids i see on the streets; when i ran into trouble, my family was there,'' said zaccaro, 23, who was arrested for sale and possession of drugs in february 1984, while a student at middlebury college in vermont. the case is still pending
zaccaro said two other colleges refused to admit him because of the drug charge and he couldn't get a job
my mom, who had helped so many college kids get jobs, was devastated by her inability to help me. `they don't want the notoriety of john zaccaro working for them,' she told me.'''
so he volunteered at covenant house, riding around in a van all night to offer food, emotional support and other help to teen-age runaways, many of them involved in drugs and prostitution
i'm just john, a friendly face in a blue van. many of these kids pick up newspapers out of the trash cans. if they read the stories about me and my family, they don't make the connection. and i'm glad of that,'' he wrote
i'm proud of my family _ my mom for taking on a tough fight and my dad, well, for going through a lot of grief in a gentle way that gives me a lot to imitate.''
when james l. galliher was called for jury duty, he had an excuse that was hard to refuse
he is in jail, serving three years for grand theft auto and check forgery
circuit court clerk raymond winters said an old voter registration list was used to choose potential jurors
a navy effort to upgrade future los angeles-class attack submarines has generated delays at production shipyards and contract overruns totaling $1.3 billion, the service said tuesday
the estimated $1.3 billion overrun covers 23 of the attack subs scheduled for delivery into the 1990s and amounts to roughly a 5.9 percent increase over the negotiated target price for each submarine, the navy said
the navy's target price for each of the attack submarines currently is between $750 million and $760 million. of the 23 submarines covered by the latest overrun estimate, 11 are being built by general dynamics corp. and 12 by newport news shipbuilding &amp; drydock co
under the production contracts covering the vessels, the overrun will be split 50-50 with each of two shipyards building the subs, meaning the navy will have to pay out roughly $650 million beyond the target price of the 23 submarines
the navy said it already had the funds on hand to pay the overrun, however, because it had anticipated there might be some delays associated with improving the los angeles-class of subs
the navy has retained funds to cover all improvements, and there are no plans to seek additional funds from congress to cover these improvements,'' the service added
the delivery delays vary by shipyard, but range from seven months to 18 months, the navy said
the los angeles class, also known as the 688 class, is the navy's primary attack sub. the nuclear-powered vessel is designed to hunt and destroy soviet submarines and is built at general dynamics' electric boat division in groton, conn., and at the newport news shipyard in newport news, va
the navy is now in the midst of research and development work on a new attack submarine, designated the ssn-21 seawolf, but doesn't anticipate that vessel materializing before 1994 at the earliest
in the interim, the navy set out to improve the 688-class submarine with such things as a stronger hull to allow arctic operations; better electronic and sensor systems; a series of noise-reduction modifications; and installation of launching boxes for tomahawk cruise missiles
the service said tuesday some of the improvements had required extensive modification of the original design, leading to delays that were not totally unexpected
in this case, the navy and contractors have at least agreed up front on how cost overruns will be handled and thus should avoid the type of legal wrangling that erupted after cost overruns skyrocketed on the same submarine in the 1970s, said assistant navy secretary everett pyatt
i'm not going through that again,'' pyatt added
four newport news boats are now expected to be delivered from 14 months to 18 months late, while seven general dynamics' submarines will be delivered from seven months to nine months late
we want the deliveries on as timely a basis as possible, but we have to acknowledge the fact that the modifications which we asked for were a contributing factor,'' dan howard, the pentagon's chief spokesman, said tuesday
jed christensen, director of the office of surface mining, will leave the job march 20 for a county job in california, the office said today
chistensen, who worked in local government in utah, nevada, california and arizona before joining the interior department in 1981, will become deputy chief executive of fresno county
he has been director or acting director of the federal government's chief regulatory body for strip mines since april 1985, longer than anyone else in the history of the 10-year-old agency
during his tenure, the office returned to state jurisdiction parts of the oklahoma regulatory program it had taken over in 1984, installed a computer system to match applicants for mining permits against operators with outstanding violations and won congressional abolition of an exemption from regulation of mines covering less than two acres. voting; dole comment and turnout information from arkansas; pick up pvs bgng ``the person...</note>
republican george bush and democrat michael dukakis, favored in the busiest primary day ever, cast their ballots today in super tuesday elections designed to give a southern cast to the presidential race. with strong support throughout dixie, democrat jesse jackson made a last-minute appeal to minority voters
it was the biggest day in the history of presidential primaries, one that could virtually settle the republican race and give a clearer focus to the crowded democratic contest
five candidates were among the voters
if we exceed our expectations of live up to them, i think we'll be in good shape,'' said bush as he arrived at his polling place in houston
gop rival bob dole told reporters in missouri that ``it's going to be a little tougher as we go along, but i've been in tough fights before.''
dukakis voted in the brookline section of boston and denounced as ``garbage'' television ads run this weekend by sen. albert gore jr. of tennessee. the ads said he let massachusetts lose manufacturing jobs at a rate eight times the national average and that his foreign policy views had been described as ``mushy.''
jackson made one last pitch to black voters in alabama and hispanic voters in texas in his bid to translate dixie appeal into delegates
republican pat robertson was carrying david and goliath dolls when he arrived to vote in virginia beach, va., and said they symbolized his contest against bush
i am the conservative candidate and i will be the conservative candidate all the way to new orleans,'' he said, referring to the site of the republican national convention
gore and his wife, tipper, voted in carthage, tenn., and the candidate said, ``i think we've got the momentum. i think we're going to have a good day.''
rep. richard gephardt of missouri voted by absentee ballot
voters began to make their choices in 14 southern and border states and in seven other locales as far afield as hawaii and american samoa. early reports on voter turnout ranged from light to moderate in many southern states to projections of a record turnout in texas. ``it's just a steady stream,'' said vernon tigner, the democratic judge at cross creek 22 in north carolina
it was raining in arkansas and elections officials reported a light turnout except in black areas where it was heavy
we are having a pretty heavy turnout,'' said janice mcclelland, a worker at a predominantly black precinct in crittenden county
bush sounded confident of a solid delegate boost toward the republican nomination. dole had already returned to the midwest, flying to illinois which holds its primary next tuesday
the person that clearly wins super tuesday is going to be the nominee of the party and i think the next president,'' bush told reporters in tulsa on monday
dole also was in oklahoma and while conceding bush was likely to carry most super tuesday states, said, ``we don't want to lose the white house by nominating the wrong person.''
an abc news poll of voters in super tuesday states said bush was leading in 16 of the 17 states holding republican contests. dole was ahead only in missouri
abc news said it interviewed a total of 8,659 voters across the region between march 3 and 6 for the survey, but cautioned that its samples in the non-southern states were too small to produce specific numbers for the candidates. it said the margin of error for the southern results was 3 percentage points either way
the survey indicated that not only that bush was leading throughout the south, but that his strongest leads were in the two biggest states _ texas with 111 delegates and florida with 82
among the democrats, dukakis had a lock on his home state of massachusetts and rhode island and was leading in florida, maryland and by a narrow margin in texas
jackson was the leader in deep south states such as alabama, georgia, mississippi and louisiana, as well as arkansas, north carolina and virginia where blacks comprise up to 30 percent of the democratic electorate
hands that once picked cotton tomorrow morning will pick a president,'' jackson told an exuberant crowd at a rally in birmingham, ala. on monday night
gore, banking on his southern heritage and longest time spent capaigning the region, was leading in kentucky, oklahoma and tennessee, according to the survey
gephardt, counting on winning support with a populist appeal, was said to be leading only in his home state
a new poll published today in the atlanta journal-constitution also gave bush a wide lead in the south, finding him favored by 56 percent of republicans surveyed in 12 states in the region. on the democratic side, jackson led with 29 percent support, followed by dukakis and gore with 20 percent each
for robertson, the southern primaries amounted to his last, best chance to demonstrate that he could mount a serious challenge to the establishment candidates. despite a strong following among evangelical christians, the former television preacher has yet to win a gop primary and was a disappointing third in south carolina on saturday, a state he once boasted he would win ecisively
bush has me four to one,'' robertson said monday in charlotte, n.c. ``i'm like david up against goliath. but we will do very well in the south.''
rep. jack kemp of new york was given no chance of carrying a super tuesday state and planned to meet with advisers on wednesday and was presumed to be ready to drop out of the race
on the democratic side, sen. paul simon of illinois made no effort in the super tuesday states and planned to resume his candidacy in his home state
gary hart trudged on, attracting little notice and even less support
holding republican and democratic primaries were alabama, arkansas, florida, georgia, kentucky, louisiana, maryland, massachusetts, mississippi, missouri, north carolina, oklahoma, rhode island, tennessee, texas and virginia. in addition, democrats in american samoa, hawaii, idaho and nevada were holding caucuses as were both parties in washington
democrats in minnesota, constrained by national party rules from allocating delegates from their caucuses held two weeks ago, were doing so tonight
dukakis was the big winner in minnesota, but jackson and simon also were expected to pick up delegates
the states holding republican primaries were selecting 712 delegates, more than two-thirds of the 1,139 needed for a convention majority
on the democratic side, the prize was 1,307 delegates. a total of 2,082 were needed for the nomination
the latest associated press delegate count gave bush 126, dole 65, kemp 35 and robertson 8. for the democrats the count was dukakis 69, gephardt 50, gore 21, jackson 27, simon 35, hart 0, and uncommitted 258
during a campaign flight in missouri, bush told reporters he wouldn't predict a sweep. ``it's too much for anyone to expect,'' he said. caucuses</head>
a federal judge today refused to issue a restraining order that would have allowed civilian workers at a navy shipyard to participate in washington's presidential precinct caucuses tonight
the navy earlier had said that the federal hatch act prevented 11,600 workers at the puget sound naval shipyard in bremerton from speaking out on which candidates they preferred
u.s. district judge jack tanner's brief order said the state of washington, which had asked for the restraining order, failed to show irreparable injury would result if the navy's position were allowed to stand and ``failed to establish the balance of hardships tip in their favor.''
tanner's ruling came in a hastily filed state suit, which contended that prohibiting federal workers from speaking at the party caucuses unconstitutionally violated their right to free speech
the suit, filed monday, asked tanner to clarify the intent of the hatch act by interpreting ``conflicting sections'' of the regulations, said david bryant, a spokesman for the washington secretary of state's office
secretary of state ralph munro was miffed at the ruling and said the state may pursue the case for future years
i'm disappointed he didn't provide federal workers more protection,'' he said. ``i can't believe in the long run that this is constitutional.''
he said the state's abortive attempt at gaining an injunction did succeed in clarifying that federal workers may attend their caucuses and participate in most respects
it sends a clear signal they can go to the caucuses and do everything but speak out on the canidates,'' munro said. ``it's absurd. a guy can say `what america needs is a senator from kansas who was wounded and was a war hero,' but he can't say, `what america needs is bob dole.'''
a bill to revise the hatch act and allow workers to participate in partisan political activities on their own time overwhelmingly passed the u.s. house last year. it is pending in the senate
officials at the bremerton shipyard had told workers they could attend the political caucuses scheduled in 12,000 washington neighborhoods, but could not discuss candidates
the caucuses are the first step in the months-long process leading up to a selection of delegates from washington to the national presidential nominating conventions this summer. at stake ultimately are 73 democratic national convention delegates and 41 republican delegates
the hatch act states that federal employees may not use their official authority or influence to interfere with an election
obviously, addressing the caucus is part of the activity,'' said james sommerhauser, representing professional and technical engineers local 12 in bremerton, but ``most federal employees are so intimidated by the hatch act they're afraid to participate.''
sommerhauser said his union represents 1,800 federal workers at the yard and elsewhere in the county
water, food and bugs were not to blame for a mysterious outbreak that sent 91 students to hospitals, officials said tuesday
ninety of the 91 students from rincon junior high school were back in school tuesday, a day after they were treated for rashes, swollen eyes, blisters, stomach cramps or breathing difficulties following physical education classes, said diane ho, a spokeswoman for the rowland unified school district
soil samples were to be taken tuesday, and physicians were to interview the students, ms. ho said. ``hopefully we will find out something and solve this mystery.''
school district officials believe the students came in contact with the contaminant on the playground monday morning. but experts called in by the district have ruled out water, herbicides, bugs, grass and school-prepared food, ms. ho said
no adults experienced any symptoms, ms. ho said. one student, who has asthma, remained overnight in a hospital, she said. but some students were given medication. e principe</head>
a lisbon radio station said today authorities in the west african island nation of sao tome e principe crushed a coup attempt, killing two people
a correspondent reporting from the former portuguese colony for lisbon's radio commercial said 40 armed men landed by canoe before dawn today and tried to seize the police headquarters near the capital of sao tome
the report said forces loyal to the government of president manuel pinto da costa killed two of the attackers and captured the others
the radio correspondent, jaime marques de almeida, said the government blamed the coup attempt on the national resistence front of sao tome e principe that has its headquarters in libreville, gabon. he said the government was expected to make an official statement on the reported coup attempt later
the lisbon-based secretary-general of the national resistence front, quintiliano loures amado, denied the group was responsible
fundamentalist moslem students attacked a group of scouts with knives, stones and bicycle chains, then opened fire on security forces as they came to the scouts' aid, authorities said tuesday
two policemen and two extremists were wounded slightly, said a police spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity
he said officers arrested about 50 students after the monday night incident and another 20 on tuesday. many had been arrested after a demonstration late last year
the fundamentalists apparently attacked the male and female scouts because of their belief that the sexes should not mix
police said the fundamentalist students were found with two empty pistols, iron rods, knives and daggers. about 25 shell casings from rounds used against security forces were found at the stadium on the assiut university campus where the violence occurred
on tuesday, police clamped tight security on the downtown courthouse where the suspects were housed. on campus, about 500 fundamentalists tried to demonstrate for the release of their classmates but were stopped by university guards, security officials said
street demonstrations are banned in egypt under an emergency law enacted after moslem extremists assassinated president anwar sadat in october 1981
for several years, the university campus has been a hotbed of moslem fundamentalist agitation in assiut, a southern nile town 235 miles south of cairo
monday night's trouble began during a meeting and parade of the rovers, the equivalent of the explorers in the american boy scout program
university officials said militants attacked the parade
university guards were unable to contain the fight and called for help from outside security police, normally banned from the campus
four people were hurt in the melee that followed, but the rovers escaped unhurt by climbing out stadium windows and clambering down fire escapes, security officials said
in a telephone call to the associated press in cairo, a man claiming to speak for assiut's fundamentalists blamed security police for the trouble. he said his group demonstrated because the university administration had ``organized a dancing and singing party,'' and security police broke up the demonstration with tear gas and batons
security officials said the suspects were charged with firearms and other weapons offenses and destroying musical instruments
the fundamentalists appear to have been angered because they believe the sexes should be forbidden from mixing in parties, picnics or other social events
sen. albert gore jr.'s southern strategy faced a do-or-die test on super tuesday. democratic rivals michael dukakis and jesse jackson were favored overall in the battle for 1,307 party delegates and richard gephardt fought for survival
jackson, a black man born and educated in the south, relied on his wide support among that region's large black population and figured to be among the delegate leaders in the super tuesday voting
gov. dukakis of massachusetts was virtually conceded the support of his home state, and he sought to win on both sides of dixie with strong bids in texas and florida
gore of tennessee and gephardt of missouri were heavily favored to win their home states. they battled among themselves for what was left of the white vote. theirs was a struggle for survival, with each reduced to a strategy aimed at emerging as the white alternative to dukakis when the campaign moves elsewhere
two other candidates were on the ballot but weren't factors: sen. paul simon of illinois and gary hart, the former senator from colorado
twenty states and american samoa were holding democratic contests in what was the closest thing to a national primary ever held
most were in the south, where every state save south carolina had a primary. south carolina democrats select delegates saturday
outside the south, there were primaries in massachusetts, rhode island, washington state, idaho and nevada
at stake were 1,307 delegates _ more than half the number needed to win the nomination. a candidate had to receive at least 15 percent of the vote in a congressional district or statewide to win delegates
jackson is from the only southern state not voting, south carolina. but he had a strong appeal to blacks, who make up a quarter of the democratic vote in the south _ and as much as half in alabama and mississippi
with so many white candidates fragmenting the vote, jackson hoped to score well in other southern states, too
after wins in new hampshire, maine and vermont, dukakis hoped to demonstrate an appeal to democrats outside new england, and he concentrated heavily on texas and florida. he had wide appeal among jewish voters in south florida and hispanics in texas
gore followed a southern strategy that ignored the earliest contests, even while insisting he was a national candidate. but he faced a severe battle even to emerge as his own region's candidate
gephardt entered the southern campaign with little money to mount the heavy television campaign that succeeded for him in the earlier states. he and gore sought the moderate and conservative vote
simon, running as the clear liberal, was reeling and broke from third-place finishes in iowa and new hampshire. he sat out the super tuesday campaign and awaited the next stop, his home state of illinois where he planned a low-budget campaign to get back in the race
hart, a year ago the odds-on favorite, acknowledged before super tuesday that he didn't expect to be the nominee but was pressing his candidacy in an effort to steer the campaign debate
hart had re-entered the race in december but couldn't regain the support he had before dropping out seven months earlier amid disclosures about his relationship with model donna rice
seven women have been attacked in the last month by the ``center city stalker,'' who forces them into secluded areas of downtown buildings, robs them, ties them up and sometimes rapes them, police said
the stalker strikes day or night, with the latest attack at 8 a.m. monday in the lobby of a downtown building, say police, who speculate he may be a security guard because he showed a badge to one victim
police commissioner kevin tucker has formed a special 24-hour task force
my dad will pick me up from work every day this week until they catch that animal,'' said diane mills, a federal express employee said
police have distributed composite drawings to office buildings and businesses, and federal express couriers dropped off copies of a police sketch as they made deliveries tuesday
monday night, police swarmed the streets after the latest victim gave a description that matched ones from victims in four of the other six cases
the 20-year-old woman was on her way to a class near city hall when she was grabbed near an elevator, police said. the man dragged her at gunpoint into a secluded spot, robbed her of two gold chains and a diamond-studded gold watch
one man has been arrested and charged with robbery and attempted rape in another case. but none of the seven stalker victims could identify him in a lineup, police said
the reagan administration on tuesday joined a group of senators in urging the south african government to release zwalakhe sisulu, a prominent black journalist detained for the past 14 months without trial
we see no justification for mr. sisulu's detention,'' state department spokesman charles redman said. ``he has been a leader in efforts to resolve south africa's political problems peacefully.''
he's the type of black leader the south african government should be talking to, not repressing,'' redman added
redman said u.s. ambassador edward j. perkins made a personal appeal to the south african authorities for sisulu's release and ``we will continue to urge'' his freedom
a group of 52 senators has written south african president p.w. botha on sisulu's behalf. the letter was made public monday
a bus carrying american tourists on a trip through the holy land skidded on a rain-slick highway east of the occupied gaza strip and flipped over tuesday, injuring all 56 people on board, officials said
three of the 55 americans were in serious condition and the bus driver also was hurt. the passengers, en route from israel to egypt, crawled from the overturned bus through shattered windows
i was climbing over bodies. blood was just running all over,'' said dora bowling, a retired secretary from fairmont, w.va
the americans were participating in an extensive tour of the holy land sponsored by the united methodist church's west virginia conference
tour coordinator wendall eskew identified the three seriously injured passengers as margaret glass of dunbar, w.va.; mary lou moore, of charleston, w.va.; and donna light of wheeling, w.va
he said glass and moore are in their 70s and light is in her 50s
five other people were in moderate condition at barzilai hospital in ashkelon, 15 suffered minor injuries and the others were treated and released, said ilana zeev, a spokeswoman for the facility, 40 miles southeast of jerusalem
we were going around a curve and it was raining and slick and the bus seemed to hydroplane,'' said bonny eskew, a piano and organ teacher from charleston, w.va
we were heading for a ditch, then we swerved back to the right, lost control and turned over,'' said mrs. eskew, 59, who had a badly bruised right eye. ``it happened so fast we didn't have time to do anything.''
passengers spoke at jerusalem's hyatt hotel, where they returned after being treated at the ashkelon hospital
many of the americans suffered fractured limbs, including broken hands, wrists and shoulder bones, or cuts requiring stitches, said an emergency room surgeon who spoke on condition of anonymity
police commander ezra menashe told israel army radio the accident involved a bus from the east jerusalem tourism co. and occurred on the road between miflasim and kfar azza, two collective farms located about three miles east of the gaza strip
the tourists were headed from jerusalem to cairo via the egyptian border crossing at rafah on the southern tip of the gaza strip. the bus departed from the northern city of tiberias
debbie mcgraw, a church secretary in charleston, said the bus was carrying lay people and clergy from various parts of the state, as well as relatives from virginia and possibly other states, mcgraw said
she said the bus passengers were part of a larger tour and had opted to extend the tour and visit egypt. she said tour members on the bus were scheduled to return friday and saturday
those on the bus had ``successfully completed a holy land pilgrimage and were on the way to egypt for a three-day tour extension,'' said richard ridgeway, vice president of educational opportunities inc. of lakeland, fla., the tour operator
china's foreign minister told president reagan today his government is very concerned about the iran-iraq war and supports an arms embargo against the tehran regime, a white house spokesman said
president spokesman marlin fitzwater said the administration also accepts china's declaration that it no longer is selling silkworm missiles to iran, although it remains a supplier of conventional arms
reagan met for nearly 40 minutes in the oval office with wu xueqian, who was making his first visit to the united states in four years. posing for photographers, reagan said, ``we have a very cordial relationship between our two countries and we want to continue it.''
briefing reporters on the meeting, fitzwater said wu offered support for a u.n. cease-fire resolution in the iran-iraq war, and also endorsed an arms embargo to back it up ``if the overwhelming majority of the (u.n.) security council believed it should be adopted.''
fitzwater said the administration did not believe that wu was trying to qualify or limit his endorsement
it was our reaction, the president's reaction, that this was a very positive sign, a very strong expression of support and one, frankly, one we hope the soviet union would emulate,'' fitzwater said
in the talks, reagan did not bring up the subject of the silkworm missiles, although it was discussed in wu's earlier meetings with secretary of state george p. shultz, fitzwater said
the united states protested to china last fall about its sale of silkworms to iran. ``to the best of our information, they have not delivered any missiles since then,'' fitzwater said
while noting that china still remains a major supplier of conventional arms, he said, ``we think the fact that we have not detected any new missile shipments and their general attitude toward the iran-iraq war and the u.n. resolution _ that those are very hopeful signs.''
wu met monday with shultz and with defense secretary frank c. carlucci
during toasts following a state department luncheon on monday, shultz and wu hailed the progress in bilateal relations and made almost no reference to issues dividing them
chief among those issues is china's reported sales of military weaponry to iran in defiance of u.s. efforts at the united nations to win support for a worldwide arms embargo against iran
the administration has been seeking assurances from china that it will not veto an embargo resolution
last october, the united states retaliated against china for selling silkworm anti-ship missiles to iran by suspending the process under which china had been given increasing access to u.s. products with advanced technology
since then, china has said it has stopped selling silkworms to iran
shultz made no reference in his remarks to recent anti-chinese rioting in tibet. state department spokesman charles redman said between three and nine people are believed to have been killed, and he expressed deep concern over the human rights situation in tibet
a 9-year-old boy on monday accidentally fired a .38-caliber handgun into a seat on a school bus carrying about 45 children, bruising a child's knee, authorities said
the 9-year-old boy was suspended pending investigation, and the 7-year-old boy who was bruised did not require medical attention, authorities said
we believe that the child didn't know what he was doing _ it was just a prank,'' said sandra lindsay, assistant superintendent for instruction
the bus was about a mile from knightsville elementary school, which both children attended, when the gun discharged as the boy was trying to unload it, mrs. lindsay said. she said he got the gun from his parents' home
the bullet went through the bus seat, ricocheted and bounced off the knee of a boy two seats behind. mrs. lindsay said the bullet didn't pierce the boy's pants, but caused a small bruise
the children on the bus were being counseled by school nurses, guidance counselors and principals, and none appeared extremely upset, said bob flowers, transportation director. ``milstead, 49 ...'' ^laserphoto pn1</note>
arizona's ranking lawman said today he decided to cooperate in an investigation of an alleged death threat but didn't tell evan mecham because the governor was so angry about the probe he ``was not to be reasoned with.''
department of public safety director ralph milstead, in his second day of testimony at mecham's impeachment trial, continued to insist that mecham had obstructed justice by ordering milstead not to cooperate
during his five hours of testimony monday, milstead had portrayed mecham as a frightened, angry leader who told him: ``i don't want you to help the attorney general hang me. don't tell him anything.''
the first-term republican governor is accused of trying to thwart an investigation into whether an associate, lee watkins, threatened last nov. 12 to send former top mecham aide donna carlson on ``a long boat ride'' if she testified before a grand jury investigating mecham's campaign finances. watkins has denied threatening ms. carlson
during continued cross-examination today by defense attorney fred craft, milstead testified that mecham was fully informed about the alleged threat and the involvement of the attorney general's office when he told mecham the attorney general wanted information from dps officers about the matter
milstead said today he did not tell mecham during their telephone conversation that he intended to cooperate with the attorney general despite the governor's order not to
i was in shock from his anger that was directed toward the attorney general,'' milstead said. ``he was not to be reasoned with.''
milstead testified monday that he considered the alleged threat serious because watkins had a criminal record. watkins resigned as state prison construction chief after a past assault conviction was disclosed
milstead, 49, said he phoned mecham on nov. 15 to alert him to the possible death threat. ``i think my words to the governor were, `i don't want you to be blindsided,'' said milstead
milstead said when mecham told him not to cooperate with the attorney general, ``i was in shock over what he was saying, taken aback, speechless.''
craft asked milstead why he had not included his own part of the conversation in a report he wrote on his talk with mecham
because i'm not committing a crime,'' said milstead. ``i'm not obstructing justice.''
when did you conclude that the governor's words constituted a crime?'' asked craft
as i'm hearing them and reflecting on them,'' said milstead, adding it took him ``about two seconds'' after hanging up the phone
craft asked if milstead was surprised that his staff didn't tell him the governor had assigned cabinet member max hawkins, then-head of the department of administration, to investigate the death threat allegation
no, it didn't surprise me,'' said milstead. ``max hawkins is not a law enforcement officer. he's not competent to investigate it. lee watkins works for him, and max hawkins wouldn't be taken seriously anywhere on earth that i know of.''
the senators decided monday to forego hearing from watkins because it meant granting him immunity from prosecution. watkins invoked fifth amendment protection against self incrimination
senators also expressed impatience with craft's long interrogation, which minority leader alan stephens, a democrat, called wearing and repetitious
if that's what they do in a court of law,'' said stephens, ``i'm glad i'm not a lawyer.''
mecham, 63, the first u.s. governor to be impeached in six decades, is not attending his trial and did not comment on milstead's testimony. in january, he testified before a house impeachment committee that he may have told milstead not to cooperate with the attorney general's investigation but that he was not fully informed about the seriousness of the situation
mecham also is charged with concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 in a state funds by loaning it to his car dealership
he faces a a may 17 recall election and a march 22 criminal trial on the campaign loan disclosure allegation. a prosecutor in that case, however, sought monday to have it delayed until april 21 on the ground that pretrial defense maneuvers have left the prosecution too little time to prepare
defense lawyers monday filed a series of motions, including one asking for a dismissal of the charges
judge michael ryan of maricopa county superior court said he would rule wednesday or thursday on the prosecution request but did not indicate when he would rule on the defense motions. democrats</head>
pat robertson's fervent band of supporters waged political warfare against republican regulars in presidential caucuses tuesday, while massachusetts gov. michael dukakis was favored over his democratic rivals
none of the state's 41 gop delegates were directly at stake in the caucus voting, but the former television evangelist hoped to embarrass vice president george bush and kansas sen. bob dole
robertson was given a good shot at winning the state where evangelicals have controlled the party for most of a decade, ramming through anti-abortion, ultraconservative platforms at carefully orchestrated conventions
we're stomping the daylights out of them!'' robertson's state organizer, bruce hawkins, said with a delighted chuckle a few days ago
bush and dole forces, waging conventional campaigns, admitted to high anxiety over the robertson factor, but held out hope the party regulars would get worried enough to go to their neighborhood caucuses
the caucus voting was basically a straw poll, since delegates elected to go on to district-level caucuses are not bound to any candidate
on the democratic side, with 65 delegates at stake, dukakis benefited from endorsements by gov. booth gardner, sen. brock adams, seattle mayor charles royer and other party leaders
jesse jackson and illinois sen. paul simon were fighting it out for second- and third-place finishes and a sizable number of caucus-goers were expected to vote for uncommitted delegates, said state democratic chairwoman karen marchioro
a 48-year-old man who held his 11-month-old daughter at gunpoint for more than five hours was arrested today when police officers crept into his apartment and found him asleep, police said
warren dean brown was arrested without incident after the five-hour standoff, during which police evacuated other residents of brown's apartment building, some of them going down ladders from second-floor windows, said helena police chief bill ware
brown is charged with felony assault and was scheduled for arraignment later today in helena justice court, ware said
brown was arrested about 1 a.m. when police entered the family's apartment. they found brown asleep in the master bedroom with his young daughter, crystal, and a loaded .22-caliber pistol, ware said
the incident began at monday night when police received a call from another resident of the building
ware said brown's wife, 26-year-old kathy brown, had escaped with another daughter, 3-year-old amber, after brown pistol-whipped his wife with the handgun, striking her on the face
the area was secured and the wife ... indicated mr. brown stated he was going to kill the family,'' ware said
mrs. brown was taken by ambulance to st. peter's community hospital, where she was treated and released
police evacuated seven people from two other apartments in the building
of the 35 officers in the helena police department, 20 were at the apartment complex while lewis and clark county sheriff's deputies assisted with other calls in the city
there was no phone in the brown apartment and brown did not respond to a hostage negotiator who spoke through a bullhorn, ware said
police aimed a directional microphone at the apartment, heard no movement inside, and at 1 a.m. sent in three members of the department's ``quick response team,'' who found brown and the child in a bedroom, along with the loaded pistol, the chief said
no shots were fired during the incident and brown offered no resistance when arrested, ware said
he said crystal was returned to her mother, who along with her two daughters is now staying with friends
scott b. chambers, editor of the new castle courier-times for 50 years, has died. he was 80
chambers, who died monday in the henry county memorial hospital, was part owner of the courier-times until the chambers family sold it to nixon newspapers inc. in 1986
scott was a major force for both freedom of the press and in the development and welfare of new castle,'' said wes rowe, publisher of the courier-times
chambers was graduated from indiana university in 1930 and became managing editor of the paper when the chambers family purchased the courier and consolidated it with the times, which the family already owned
when chambers' father, walter s. chambers sr., became ill in the late 1940s, scott chambers became both editor and publisher of the courier-times. delegates</head> add will stand as background throughout the cycle.</note>
george bush bid to take command of the republican presidential race in southern-dominated super tuesday elections that offered a third of all nominating delegates. michael dukakis hoped to show nationwide appeal and emerge as the front-runner in a bruising democratic race
jesse jackson, drawing upon his black political base in dixie, looked to win several states and hundreds of democratic delegates. sen. albert gore jr. tested his southern strategy in a battle with rep. richard gephardt to emerge as the moderate contender in the industrial states to come
pre-election surveys indicated bush could hope for a sweep of the gop contests, with sen. bob dole contesting in just a handful of states. pat robertson and jack kemp seemed out of the running almost everywhere
the campaign was notable for its accusatory tv commercials. the number of convention delegates at stake _ 712 in 17 republican contests and 1,307 in 21 democratic primaries and caucuses _ made super tuesday the busiest day of this or any other presidential nomination campaign
as the day dawned, bush and dukakis were the leaders in the hunt for national convention delegates. democratic delegates from minnesota's feb 23 caucuses were being allocated with most to dukakis, followed by jackson
beforehand, dukakis had 70 delegates, gephardt 50, simon 36, jackson 28 and gore 22. it takes 2,082 delegates to win the democratic nomination
among the republicans, it was bush with 126, dole with 65, kemp with 35 and robertson with 8. it takes 1,139 delegates to win the gop nomination
democratic surveys suggested that dukakis and jackson would each carry at least a handful of states. dukakis had his home state of massachusetts in his pocket, but gore countered with his tennessee and gephardt with missouri
dukakis, having won several new england contests, hoped to demonstrate a broader appeal than any of his rivals with victories in texas, florida, washington, maryland, rhode island and hawaii. jackson was strong all across dixie and gore's hopes seemed to rest on the strength of second-place finishes
dukakis targeted his campaign at ethnic voters, liberals and union workers in pockets across the south, aiming his appeal as well at the huge elderly population in florida
dukakis hoped to use his superior finances and organization to pick up dozens of delegates in states where he didn't expect to win outright. his rivals made the same effort on a smaller scale, knowing they could earn at least one delegate in any congressional district where they received 15 percent of the vote
jackson, who has run well in some states without a large number of black voters, was drawing on his core constituency for the first time this year and hoped to win in georgia, virginia, mississippi, louisiana and alabama, as well as one or two other states
sen. paul simon of illinois bypassed the super tuesday elections to concentrate on the primary next week in his home state. gary hart, the long-ago front-runner, was the invisible man politically
the republican picture was entirely different. bush, whose campaign was in jeopardy before new hampshire voted three weeks ago, was comfortably ahead in pre-election polls in nearly every super tuesday state. he aimed to pile up enough delegates to make his nomination seem inevitable, while dole hoped to snare enough to carry him credibly to next week's primary fight in illinois
robertson, the former television evangelist, bid for second place in a few states and a win in the washington caucuses. kemp, who had dreamed of emerging as a conservative alternative in the race, faced a 17-state shutout and seemed likely to withdraw later in the week
gore was banking everything on a strong showing in his native region. he began with his base in tennessee and hoped to pick up a few hundred delegates even if he finished behind jackson across dixie
gephardt, who won the kick-off iowa caucuses exactly one month ago and followed it up in south dakota, counted on a home state win in missouri
_
a radical sikh priest freed from jail just three days ago was elected tuesday as chief priest for the golden temple, a post that makes him spokesman and spiritual leader for 25 million sikhs
the council responsible for sikh shrines unanimously picked jasbir singh rode to be the new head of the akal takht, or eternal throne, the seat of sikh authority, united news of india reported
the sprawling golden temple complex in amritsar is sikhism's holiest shrine. the council, the shiromani gurudwara prabandhak committee, met in chandigarh, the capital of punjab state about 150 miles north of new delhi
rode, 34, replaces darshan singh, a moderate who resigned last year
rode was released from jail saturday. he has been in custody since 1985 on federal charges of sedition but was never brought to trial
his release, and that of other sikh priests and militants, is believed linked to a government move to include militants in the political process in punjab, which has been wracked by a sikh separatist insurrection since 1982
on sunday, the government dissolved the punjab state legislature. the legislature had been suspended since may 1987 after an escalation of separatist violence. since then, punjab has been ruled by the federal government
new elections will have to be held in the state, possibly drawing participation by the militants
sikhs form just 2 percent of india's 800 million people but are in a majority in punjab
rode is the nephew of sikh militant leader jarnail singh bhindranwale, who was killed in an army attack on the golden temple in 1984
ten people were killed in punjab on tuesday and monday in violence blamed on sikh militants, police said. this year, more than 400 people have been killed in punjab in attacks blamed on sikh extremists. most of the victims have been hindus or moderate sikhs
both races were marked by accusatory campaign commercials on a scope that was unprecedented for a presidential campaign
dukakis aired a commercial featuring an acrobat doing somersaults as he tried to depict gephardt as a man who flip-flops on the issues. dole ran commercials saying bush had approved arms-for-hostages swaps during the iran-contra affair
thus ended what amounted to a southern regional primary campaign, an idea hatched by democratic officials who wanted to give a moderate-to-conservative contender a boost toward the party's 1988 nomination
the idea was to help nominate a democrat who could run strongly across the south in the general election campaign in the fall _ and bolster the prospects of democratic candidates in local elections
but whatever the theory, the result was a struggle carried out largely through costly television commercials with no particular southern cast. the candidates, trying to campaign in an impossible number of areas simultaneously, often were reduced to staging appearances at airports so they could leave as quickly as possible for the next stop
but the commercials were eye-catching, particularly on the democratic side. voters who didn't see the ads would read about them in the paper or see clips on the television news
gephardt attacked dukakis for raising taxes while governor of massachusetts and mocked dukakis for once suggesting that farmers diversify their crops by growing belgian endive. he also aired a spot seeking to portray dukakis' campaign as guilty of a string of dirty tricks
dukakis returned fire with ads featuring an acrobat doing somersaults, while the announcer attacked gephardt as flipflopping on critical issues
gore retooled his message in mid-campaign with a populist appeal designed to siphon off some of gephardt's support. his final flurry of ads attacked gephardt and dukakis. in one commercial he even added a mild jab at jackson
as much as anything, super tuesday was a test of gore's southern strategy for gaining the nomination. alone among the contenders, he ignored the iowa caucuses and spent months collecting endorsements and campaigning in his native region in hopes of jump-starting his campaign at home after others had left the field. however, among the original democratic candidates, only bruce babbitt was gone by super tuesday
the democratic idea for a regional primary suited the bush forces fine. the vice president's aides quickly spread the word that they had erected a ``southern fire wall'' that would contain any damage resulting from defeats in earlier contests. and when bush finished a poor third in the feb 8 iowa caucuses, it looked like the theory would get a test
but then came bush's victory in new hampshire's primary, followed by his convincing triumph in the south carolina primary on saturday
and instead of merely hoping to hold his own, the vice president spent the last two days campaigning and advertising heavily in dole's strongest state in missouri in hopes of pulling off a sweep
dole suffered through a difficult period as his campaign manager fired two senior aides in an internal struggle for control
even as the polls opened on super tuesday, the contenders were looking ahead to the next round in the nominating wars
dole had begun airing television commercials in illinois, a contest his aides said he had to win to sustain his candidacy
the average college administrator got a 3.3 percent pay increase this year, down from 5.3 percent a year ago, the college and university personnel association said tuesday
the 3.3 percent increase for 1987-88 was less than the 3.7 percent increase in consumer prices during the same period, and the first time since 1982-83 that the college salaries trailed the rise in the consumer price index
the association derived the figures from its 11th annual survey of how much colleges pay their presidents, deans and other administrators
college tuitions have been rising faster than consumer prices for most of the 1980s, and campuses have come under increasing pressure from secretary of education william j. bennett and other critics to hold down costs
an air force transport plane crashed shortly after takeoff tuesday, killing 12 people, five of them on the ground, a news agency reported
the plane, which was not further identified, crashed over a four-square-mile area near cuttack, in eastern orissa state, the united news of india reported
in addition to the five villagers killed by debris from the crash, eight others were injured and more than 40 homes and stores were damaged, the news agency said
the plane was bound for new delhi. the air force is investigating the cause of the crash
a senior tibetan communist party official tuesday condemned the ``savage actions'' of his tibetan countrymen who sparked two days of anti-chinese riots in the capital of lhasa last week
sabotage'' of the monk-led rioters ``went completely against the people's wish for a normal democratic life.'' tibet's party deputy secretary raidi was quoted as saying by the official xinhua news agency
xinhua also claimed in a report from lhasa that no policemen carried arms while on duty saturday. western sources have said that five tibetans and three policemen were killed in the rioting, while chinese officials say the only death was that of a policeman
another chinese official report said the riots, which started saturday, stretched into sunday. previous reports said there was no unrest sunday
that report, by the china news agency, also said tibetan monks tried to poison the tea of chinese officials and journalists attending ceremonies to mark the end of a major buddhist festival
xinhua said 309 policemen were injured, 29 seriously, by tibetans attacking with stones, clubs and iron bars. the china news service, monitored in hong kong, put the number of hospitalized police officers at more than 30
there have been unconfirmed reports that some rioters were shot, and western travelers in lhasa, contacted by telephone, have reported seeing large contingents of armed police
travelers said police on tuesday withdrew their blockade from around the jokhang temple, lhasa's main temple and the scene of the violent protest against chinese rule
william tang, assistant foreign manager at the lhasa hotel, said guests were told they could go to the temple's market square but ``at their own risk.''
most tibetans detest and oppose the savage actions of the handful of splittists,'' raidi, a tibetan, told xinhua
splittists is a termed coined by the chinese to describe those who seek independence for regions in china
the weekend violence followed a similar outbreak of pro-independence unrest in early october during which at least 14 people died
chinese troops entered tibet in 1950 after beating nationalist chinese forces in a civil war. nine years later, tibet's spiritual and temporal leader, the dalai lama, fled into exile after an abortive uprising
many tibetans continue to be bitter about china's suppression of local customs and religion and its destruction of temples
china news service accused the monks of being the ringleaders saturday, the final day of a major 10-day festival known as the great prayer festival
the report said monks saturday attacked the vans of chinese tv crews photographing the 500-year-old prayer festival and dropped a 22-pound boulder from a rooftop
seven cars from tibet's local tv station and a camera were smashed, the report said. two cars were turned over and another set afire as the rampaging monks shouted, ``smash anything that is communist!''
a western traveler said tibetans told him police beat two monks to death inside the jokhang temple
several tibetans later carried the monks' bodies around the square, he said, triggering further clashes
the dalai lama, in a statement from his office in new delhi, monday said the violence clearly revealed the ``desperation'' of the tibetan people. he called on tibetans to ``restrain from violence in spite of repressive measures that the chinese may take.''
negotiators on tuesday reported progress in their work on the fine print of an emerging afghan settlement in talks to end nine years of fighting
u.n. mediator diego cordovez told reporters that negotiations were focusing on ``sensitive technicalities'' of the four documents that are to make up the peace package and govern the withdrawal of an estimated 115,000 soviet troops backing kabul's communist government
asked if there was substantive progress, he said ``yes'' but did not elaborate. ``even if the two sides wanted to sign the accords now they cannot do so before the agreements are ready,'' he said
cordovez's optimistic comments came as an afghan resistance group quit the seven member anti-soviet alliance because it said the interim government in afghanistan could be dominated by moslem extremists
the abrupt departure of the afghan national liberation front reduces to two the number of moderate parties in the alliance
pakistan is going to bring in a fundamentalist government. it is not good for afghanistan. it will destroy afghanistan,'' said the front's leader, sibghatullah mojaddedi
it was not clear how mojaddedi's move might affect negotiations
cordovez and other sources close to the talks made it clear that nothing spectacular was likely to emerge in the next few days from the indirect negotiations between pakistan and afghanistan
you should go sightseeing for three days,'' he counseled journalists
still, there was considerable behind-the-scenes activity
cordovez and delegates reportedly kept close touch with deputy u.s. secretary of state robert peck and another visitor, ambassador nicolai kozyrev, described as a soviet specialist on afghan affairs
pakistan's chief representative, acting foreign minister zain noorani, was eager to dispel any notions of a standstill
things are moving forward,'' he said. ``don't you see that i am coming here every day?''
a diplomatic source who insisted on anonymity said prospects for a settlement continued to look good in the current round, which started march 2. the source said that no substantive discussions had taken place on the question of an interim government. pakistan wants the formation of a broad-based transitional kabul government to move on a ``second track'' parallel to the implementation of troop withdrawal
it argues that only a generally acceptable government can ensure the safe return of more than five million refugees and prevent more bloodshed in the country already mourning more than one million dead
the kabul delegation has publicly rejected pakistan's request as an attempt to introduce an extraneous issue that could undermine the talks. but pakistan is reported to be still hoping for a compromise, perhaps by agreeing to sign the settlement with the present leadership _ which it does not recognize _ in return for assurances that an interim government will be formed soon afterward
pakistani president muhammad zia ul-haq, in dubai for inauguration of the emirates golf club, said tuesday an interim government was a necessary ingredient in any settlement
we do not want to go over just pages of an agreement. out of the geneva process we want to take a comprehensive settlement. and for that settlement, an interim government is one of the most essential instruments,'' zia said
an afghan resistance group on tuesday quit an anti-soviet alliance because of fears that the interim government in afghanistan will be dominated by moslem extremists
sibghatullah mojaddedi, leader of the moderate afghan national liberation front, also resigned as party chief
the front's abrupt departure reduces to two the number of moderate parties in the alliance
hamed karzai, the party's information director, said mojaddedi's move was to protest plans for a future afghan government worked out by the alliance's moslem extremist members
for us it's is finished,'' karzai said of the alliance
at a news conference, mojaddedi said the ``most important decision about afghanistan'' had been made by seven people _ the leaders of the seven-party alliance
nobody has looked to the 15 million people of afghanistan,'' he said, adding that the three million shiite moslems had particularly been ignored
mojaddedi said the proposal for an interim government announced late last month was too hardline
pakistan is going to bring in a fundamentalist government. it is not good for afghanistan. it will destroy afghanistan,'' mojaddedi said
he said the best alternative was to convene a grand national council, whose membership of about 1,000 would include commanders, scholars, tribal and religious leaders, refugees and afghans living abroad
the council, he said, would decide the future government
moslem extremists in the alliance apparently oppose that plan
the alliance, under pressure from pakistan, announced in late february plans to form a future afghan government headed by an all-guerrilla executive council and 28 ministers, possibly including non-communist officials from the communist government in kabul
while pakistan cautiously endorsed the plan, rumors soon circulated in peshawar that the alliance leaders were split over which parties should wield the most power
pakistan, which is negotating with the kabul government over a withdrawal of soviet forces from afghanistan, has insisted that the formation of a broad-based interim afghan government is crucial for the safe return of about 5 million afghan refugees from pakistan and iran
meanwhile, the remaining six guerrilla leaders called an emergency meeting to discuss the development. none of them would comment on mojaddedi's move
although mojaddedi personally has considerable political influence, his party, comprised of traditional pathan tribal militias with few outside sources of military or financial support, is not strong
the split comes at a sensitive time for pakistan, which speaks for the guerrillas at u.n.-sponsored peace talks in geneva. race</head>
sen. paul simon, silent in the south, lies in wait for democratic rivals jesse jackson and michael dukakis as the presidential campaign turns north to illinois where sen. bob dole is readying a republican last stand against george bush
jackson hopes to reap delegates and votes in chicago, where he lives, while simon seeks strength from state democratic leaders who encouraged him to keep afloat his fading campaign effort
the home-state candidates face a strong challenge from dukakis, whose well-heeled and well-organized staff has scoured the state since last fall and has slates in all districts. dukakis will likely hammer away at economic themes in a state struggling with plant closings and job losses
rep. richard gephardt is not expected to mount a major campaign in the state. he sees no hope of success, given simon and jackson's built-in strengths and dukakis' substantial effort
i think with muddled results (from super tuesday) and a strong favorite son in paul simon, we're going to look at the state beyond that, and that's michigan,'' said spokesman mark johnson
sen. albert gore jr. of near-neighbor tennessee plans to spend part of the week in illinois, as does former sen. gary hart of colorado,
on the republican side, sen. dole, a kansan who has done well in the midwest and calls illinois ``friendly territory,'' has another shot at farm votes
however, vice president bush is backed by gov. james thompson, 93 of 102 county leaders and other influential state leaders
there are no areas we consider ourselves weak in,'' said ed murnane, deputy campaign director
dole also has a strong state operation, with coordinators in all counties and well-known delegate candidates, said campaign director mark schroeder. dole's organization began shifting forces to illinois even before super tuesday
rep. jack kemp of new york and former television evangelist pat robertson were not expected to be major factors
illinois is a diverse state, with numerous ethnic groups, industrial centers, farms, big cities, small towns, professionals and blue-collar workers
illinois is a microcosm of the nation,'' said samuel gove, a political scientist and director emeritus at the university of illinois' institute of government. ``a candidate who can do well here can do well nationally.''
more than 5.9 million residents are registered to vote in tuesday's primary _ the lowest number for any statewide election since 1982. the race is divided into a non-binding presidential preference, dubbed the ``beauty contest,'' and the selection of delegates pledged to a candidate or uncommitted
because of heavy emphasis on earlier races, the candidates have devoted little time to illinois, where 113 democratic and 82 gop delegates will be chosen tuesday. the remaining 85 will be selected at party meetings
during the next six days, however, candidates will crisscross illinois and burn up the airwaves with their messages. dukakis aides, for example, have said they expect to spend about $500,000 on tv advertising
simon, however, a first-term senator who has served as congressman, state lawmaker and lieutenant governor, doesn't plan any tv advertising here
he shouldn't have to. he's run here his whole life,'' said jerry sinclair, simon's illinois political director. ``we're short of dollars.''
both simon and jackson have made strong showings in recent state polls
simon, who is supported by many party leaders, has denied speculation he stayed in the race so illinois delegates committed to him can attend the national convention
the plan is to concentrate on illinois and then the midwest industrial states, to keep accumulating delegates,'' sinclair said. ``the way it looks now, no one is going to get this thing on the first ballot. if it becomes more and more ... fragmented, why should paul drop out?''
but jack van der slik, political studies professor at sangamon state university in springfield, said, ``his votes are going to be lower than before he bowed out of super tuesday. he's going to look weak. that's going to be the coup de grace.''
jackson, though, expects to do better than his 1984 showing of 21 percent of illinois' vote, said spokesman frank watkins
watkins said jackson has delegate slates in 21 of 22 congressional districts, compared with four in 1984. he said jackson will fare well in chicago, where 56 percent of the voters are black or hispanic, and will expand his white base, as he has in vermont and minnesota
van der slik, however, said, ``i think jesse is much more vulnerable in this state. people have made up their minds about him. he was much more of a fresh face in a lot of those other situations.''
city supervisors have agreed to ban the sale of realistic toy guns following the recent fatal shooting of a retarded boy who drew a toy pistol on police officers
the measure was proposed by supervisor wendy nelder, daughter of a former police chief, who said some toy stores already have removed toy weapons from their shelves
nobody wants to be responsible for a little kid's death, or a police officer's death, or anybody else's,'' she said in an interview
on feb. 17, two police officers killed silivelio ``tony'' grohse, 13, when he pointed a toy gun, which the officers thought was real, at them during a confrontation
the district attorney's office cleared the officers of wrongdoing, saying they had a ``well-founded fear for their lives.''
in another incident on dec. 21, 1986, a police officer shot a 15-year-old burglary suspect to death after the youth held up a toy gun
toy guns already are banned in los angeles and neighboring burbank and santa monica
nelder's plan won unanimous tentative approval late monday night. final adoption usually is a rubber-stamping procedure taking place within 30 days
under the plan, possession of a toy gun would still be legal. otherwise, she notes, it would be possible for a police officer to arrest people in one house for having toy guns, but impossible to arrest a neighbor with real weapons that were otherwise legal
it also will be legal to sell toy guns that were obviously toys. but, nelder said, ``they'd have to be about four feet long and made of pink plastic, because that's about all nowadays that makes something a toy gun.''
many toymakers already are changing designs as the result of pressure from retailers like toys r us, which has urged manufacturers to come up with ways to keep toy guns from being mistaken for authentic guns, said douglas thomsom, president of the new york-based trade group toys manufacturers of america
to celebrate his 50th birthday march 17, rudolf nureyev will dance the romantic role of albert in the classic ballet ``giselle.''
the paris opera ballet said tuesday that nureyev, director of the paris company, was invited to dance in three performances with the american ballet theatre during its tour to los angeles. the invitation was made by abt director and ballet star mikhail baryshnikov, who, like nureyev, defected from the soviet union
most dancers in nureyev's troupe retire at age 45, but while he makes only rare stage appearances, the elder statesman of classical dance has yet to hang up his slippers
mayor bernie simon said he was delighted with a caricature of himself that is the new ``face on the barroom floor'' at the omaha press club
i'm flabbergasted. i thought i'd look like hell,'' said simon, who has been undergoing radiation therapy for brain tumors. about 125 people attended the unveiling of his portrait monday
the drawing by jim horan shows simon placing toy building blocks along the city's riverfront, where conagra inc. is planning to build a multimillion-dollar headquarters and research center
simon's picture will be displayed in a frame on press club floor for about three months and then will hang in the club's gallery of more than 30 politicians, athletes and business people
cbs inc. founder and chairman william paley made a remarkable recovery from emergency gall bladder surgery and went home tuesday, a spokeswoman said
paley, 86, was in critical condition following his feb. 11 surgery at new york hospital-cornell medical center
hospital spokeswoman myrna manners said paley had ``remarkably improved after one month in the hospital.''
paley bought the columbia broadcasting system, a fledgling radio network, in 1928. he turned over the reins in 1983. but when cbs's biggest stockholder, loew's corp., became unhappy with his successor's policies, paley teamed with loew chairman lawrence tisch to retake control in 1986
tami erin, the 13-year-old star of ``pippi longstocking,'' says she was very excited to see the premiere of her movie accompanied by a japanese princess
it was so weird seeing myself on the big screen,'' miss erin said tuesday after the world premiere of the film based on the popular tomboy of astrid lindgren's novels. ``it was great and i was very excited.''
japan's princess nori, the 18-year-old granddaughter of emperor hirohito, joined miss erin for the first showing of the film, directed by ken annakin
the princess ``was a very sweet girl and very friendly,'' miss erin said. ``she loved it (the movie) a lot.''
the eighth-grader from shark river island, n.j., who began performing in commercials in 1983, was chosen from 9,000 aspirants to play pippi, whose stories have been translated into 44 languages
the movie will be released in the united states in july
two british weeklies have accused prince andrew's wife, the former sarah ferguson, of brash and vulgar behavior during the couple's recent visit to california
london's sunday times said that after seeing the duke and duchess of york, americans will likely ``retreat to their more refined dinner parties, there to cap each other with anecdotes about the awful vulgarities of the british.''
the observer, a liberal weekly, in a profile of the 28-year-old duchess, said: ``something appears to have gone awry with the royal fairy story.''
the newspapers were particularly critical of the duchess' quip, ``i'll see you later,'' to a man who yelled out, ``i love you,'' breaking a fake bottle over her husband's head and what they saw as generally failed attempts at humor
the sunday times, in an article by sketch writer craig brown, criticized british daily newspapers for using headlines such as ``hollywood bows to a touch of british class'' and ``royal one-liners woo u.s. hosts.''
of a black-tie dinner at which the duchess wore a red-and-black gown, brown wrote:
while the stars of hollywood dressed in discreet black and stayed in the shadows, down the stairs walloped someone who looked as if she'd just won third prize for her carmen miranda impersonation in an end of pier show at some forgotten resort.''
the observer asked, ``has the duchess of york gone too far?'' and added, ``even in this day and age it is easily possible for noblesse to be too obliging.''
a continental airlines airliner that crashed and left 28 people dead waited 24 minutes in a snowstorm between de-icing and takeoff while other aircraft were taking off only 15 minutes after de-icing, officials said today
robert benzon, heading a national transportation safety board investigation team, said possible ice buildup on continental flight 1713 would be among the ``items of interest'' to be considered as four days of hearings into the november crash began
the dc-9, powered by two pratt &amp; whitney jt8d-7 engines, had just lifted off when it rolled over and broke into three pieces as it slid down a snow-covered runway. twenty-eight people were killed and 54 others were injured
other possible crash causes being considered included the inexperience of the pilots and a wingtip vortex from a plane landing on an adjacent runway, benzon said in an opening statement
flight attendant kelly englehart testified today that she had been so worried about the weather and the co-pilot's inexperience that she asked the pilot who would be landing the plane in the snowstorm when the flight returned to denver
it as snowing outside, and the weather was pretty bad. it was the second officer's second trip, and i just wanted to know,'' said englehart, adding that capt. frank zvonek told her he would land the plane
benzon noted that said that zvonek, 43, who had 198 hours on a dc-9 with only the previous 33 hours as captain, and first officver lee bruecher, 26, never had flown together before. both were killed
benzon said the ntsb investigation showed the temperature was 28 degrees fahrenheit and the wind was blowing at 10 knots, gusting to 17 knots, when the plane was being prepared for takeoff
the tower personnel (the control tower) could not see the de-icing pad or the end of the runway because of low visibility,'' he said
he said 24 minutes elapsed between the time the plane was de-iced and the time the plane took off
other aircraft on the ramp during this time frame were spending approximately 15 minutes between de-icing and takeoff,'' he said
the reasons for flight 1713's 24-minute delay and the possible effects of snow or ice buildup on the wings and tail surfaces of the airplane during this delay are items of interest during this hearing,'' benzon said
englehart, the first of 29 scheduled witnesses, then testified that she closed her eyes and prepared to die as the plane slid down a snow-covered runway at denver's airport last nov. 15
she the dc-9 had just lifted off the runway at stapleton international airport when it rocked first to the left and then sharply to the right, finally turning over and coming to a stop
a six-week-old baby in my section started screaming and everybody was so glad to hear that baby cry. they knew the baby was all right,'' she said
about 30 minutes of recorded cockpit conversation showed that the crew used the appropriate checklist before taking off, said benzon
the wreckage also showed the landing gear was down and locked and the flaps were at an appropriate takeoff setting upon impact, he said
ntsb spokesman ted lopatkiewicz said monday that engine failure will not be discussed because there has been no evidence that the engines failed
the chairman of the board of inquiry is ntsb board member joseph t. nall, assisted by three other ntsb staff members. ``a final report is still many months down the road,'' said lopatkiewicz
the federal aviation administration, meanwhile, announced plans monday for ``white-glove inspections'' of continental airlines, possibly as early as this summer
the continental inspection is part of a continuing effort by the faa to take a regularly scheduled, full-scale look at the operations of big domestic airlines, said faa spokesman fred farrar
the world health organization's chief aids investigator said tuesday that sex experts william masters and virginia johnson were ``irresponsible'' for suggesting aids can be transmitted by casual social contact
dr. jonathan mann, the american director of who's global program on aids, challenged the noted sex researchers to produce scientific evidence or admit they were indulging in ``idle speculation.''
if it's just theorizing, then i think they have done us all a grave disservice,'' mann told reporters at the first international conference on the global impact of aids
about 1,100 specialists from 20 countries attended the start of the three-day meeting at london's barbican center
in a new book, masters and johnson claim u.s. health officials have understated the extent of aids among heterosexuals to avoid public panic. they also say that aids might be transmitted by casual contact such as from a toilet seat or a waiter's bleeding finger
they wrote in their book: ``the aids virus is now running rampant in the heterosexual community.'' when that assertion came under fire at a news conference in new york on monday, masters said, ``i simply believe this.'' johnson, asked the same question, said ``i'm not sure we chose the word `rampant' ourselves.''
mann suggested the authors' assertion that aids might be more prevalent among heterosexuals than health officials believe was a matter for debate and might be useful if it strengthened awareness that the disease can be transmitted both heterosexually and homosexually
but if they're talking about putting their prestige behind the idea that you can catch this from a toilet seat, i think that's irresponsible unless there are data.''
mann said he strongly objected to the authors' implication ``without data, without information, that the virus spreads in other ways than we know it spreads.''
mann and most other experts believe aids spreads mainly by sexual contact, through the sharing of needles and from pregnant mothers to their babies
the who official suggested that masters and johnson were trying to promote their book with headline-grabbing findings, saying ``publicity about this will undoubtedly sell more books.''
he also expressed doubt about the authors' scientific qualifications regarding aids
they know a lot about sex. i don't know how much they know about aids,'' said mann, who added that he had not read the book and was responding to news reports about its content
asked again about the masters and johnson study at a later news conference, mann said: ``it would be very unfortunate if their credibility in sex was used by people to give credence to their theorizing rather than to the facts that have been collected about aids in the last seven years from all over the world
during the aids conference, dr. gary noble, deputy director of the centers for disease control in atlanta and head of the federal agency's aids program, also refuted the masters and johnson study without mentioning it by name
he said separate u.s. studies confirmed that aids is not spread through casual social contact. one study showed that infected people did not pass aids to members of their family except through sexual contact. another study showed that insects cannot transmit the virus
noble said that the incidence of aids among heterosexuals in the united states had increased from 1.1 percent of all cases in 1982 to 2.3 percent in 1986. he said health officials expected that proportion to increase to 4 to 5 percent by 1991
in his conference speech, mann said aids sufferers face the danger of discrimination and proposed an international system for monitoring human rights violations in combating the disease
he did not explain how the system would work but said, ``we need to know when and how discrimination occurs.''
we know that in aids, isolation and exclusion create danger and that inclusion creates safety,'' he said
mann said the world health organization had recorded 81,433 aids cases from a total of 133 countries as of march 1
as of feb. 29, the centers for disease control in atlanta had received reports of 54,723 americans with aids, 30,715 of whom had died
the geneva-based u.n. agency is co-sponsoring the conference with the london school of hygiene and tropical medicine
acquired immune deficiency syndrome cripples the body's natural immune system, making its victims vulnerable to a variety of infections and cancers. it is invariably fatal and there is no known vaccine or cure
ted turner's cable entertainment network could start oct. 3, now that turner broadcasting system's board approved it
the board monday unanimously approved the proposed turner network television, or tnt, which turner said will compete directly with the three major networks
with tnt, we are offering the cable industry the programming vehicle to drive penetration past the 60 and 70 percent marks,'' turner said in a statement
at present, about half the homes in the country with televisions subscribe to cable television
turner broadcasting is prepared to invest up to $30 million in tnt through the end of 1990. plans call for the network to be offered free to cable operators in 1988, but they will be charged 15 cents per subscriber in 1989, with the fee rising to 20 cents in 1990 and 25 cents in 1991
the new network is envisioned as an alternative to cbs, nbc and abc that will eventually offer first-run programming, major sporting events and awards shows. turner has said the company's contract with the national basketball association could allow a shift of games from superstation tbs to tnt once the latter reaches 30 million homes
we will begin immediately to solicit subscriber commitments, and preliminary indications from cable operators show strong and substantial support,'' turner said
prime cable in atlanta has agreed to become the first cable system to carry tnt, said allan barnes, vice president and general manager of prime cable
tnt will provide us with the kind of breakthrough programming we need to draw new subscribers,'' barnes said
tnt would become turner's fourth cable network, joining cable news network, cnn headline news and superstation tbs
police today found what appears to be the painting by french impressionist claude monet that was stolen from the fisher community center nearly a year ago
we're extremely pleased,'' said rex ryden, head of the fisher foundation. ``obviously, it's going to be something that will be of value as far as the entire art world is concerned.''
lt. darrell templeton said the department recovered the painting in a mail drop box in legrand, about nine miles east of marshalltown
the painting, ``the fishing boats in front of the cliffs at d'etretat,'' is to be examined to see if it is the original. ryden said the painting was rolled up when found and that templeton unrolled it just far enough to determine that it may be the monet
ryden said officials will not bend nor otherwise tamper with the painting for fear that it might be damaged in the process
the painting, valued at up to $300,000, was stolen march 19, 1987. authorities soon after called in the fbi and the international police agency interpol to help locate it
the painting was stolen by a man who rushed into the center at night, carved the 23-by-32 inch canvas from its frame and vanished on foot
ryden said the foundation's insurance carrier paid $175,000 for its loss. ``i'm not sure who owns that painting now, since the insurance company paid us for it,'' he said. pvs, rep. stephen.</note>
the reagan administration said today it intends to keep holding the threat of sanctions over panama's gen. manuel antonio noriega, but said no decisions have been made on possible actions
the threat's still out there. we're still considering it. the situation is changing rapidly and we're still monitoring it. but we don't want to act precipitously,'' white house spokesman marlin fitzwater told reporters
he made the comments to clarify statements he'd made earlier indicating the administration might be withholding a decision on possible economic and trade sanctions
earlier in the day, the house foreign affairs committee voted unanimously to endorse reagan's course of action against the military regime and to urge him to consider further economic sanctions
the administration has called for noriega's removal since he was indicted on federal drug trafficking charges in florida last month
the sanctions are being considered as a means of bringing pressure against noriega's military regime and to promote a return to civilian rule under president eric arturo delvalle
let me back you away from the inevitability of these kinds of decisions,'' the spokesman had said initially, adding, ``it's been our feeling from the very beginning that change should come from within in panama and we should watch it carefully and if that is the process, that is preferable to our taking actions.''
but fitzwater later returned to the briefing room to say, ``we want to keep the threat of sanctions still out there.''
he said the options were still before the administration, but that no decisions had yet been made. he said such decisions depended upon ``a very complicated set of criteria.''
he cited the impact the sanctions might have on the status of the noriega government, u.s. interests in terms of the canal, the panamanian military and u.s. investment in that country
fitzwater also offered support for statements issued by delvalle and opposition parties that have called for the establishment of a ``government of national reconciliation.''
we welcome those statements,'' the spokesman said. he also issued a statement saying the u.s. government supports the goal of ``restoring democratic government and civilian constitutional order. once this goal has been achieved, we will work cooperatively with the government of panama toward the recovery of panama's financial and economic health.''
the house foreign affairs committee resolution, which will be voted on by the house later this week, also reaffirmed congressional support for the full implementation of the panama canal treaties which require the united states to hand the canal over to panama at the end of the century
rep. stephen j. solarz, d-n.y., noted that panama's military ruler, gen. manuel antonio noriega, has said that the criticism from the united states aimed at his alleged involvement in drug trafficking and other acts of corruption is actually a smoke screen
noriega is contending the real reason is to create the groundwork for an ultimate american decision to renege on the commitment to turn over the panama canal'' in the year 2000, solarz said
this resolution shows that we fully intend to live up to our commitments under the panama canal treaties,'' solarz said
the senate foreign relations committee already has adopted a resolution calling for a total trade embargo against panama, but several members of the house panel said they thought that approach was premature
several members said their resolution is more in tune with reagan administration measured strategy and is essentially an endorsement of a targeted approach designed to put pressure on noriega while not harming the panamanian people as a whole. says</head>
cheating on federal income taxes has declined by as much as 20 percent, mainly because of tax law changes and tougher federal policing, internal revenue service commissioner lawrence b. gibbs said tuesday
gibbs told a house appropriations subcommittee an irs study indicates the much-publicized ``tax gap'' _ the difference between taxes owed and taxes paid _ has dropped to between $80 billion and $90 billion in 1987. the agency's last report on the annual gap estimated it would rise to more than $100 billion in 1987
gibbs attributed the decline to campaigns by congress and the irs to force stricter compliance, through tougher penalties and the computer-matching of tax returns with income reports, and to the numerous changes brought about by the 1986 tax law revision
the commissioner announced also that the irs has temporarily suspended efforts to collect back taxes from students who were paid stipends for teaching or research work at their universities
we've put the word out (to irs offices) to hold up on any'' of the students' cases that are pending until the agency adopts a consistent policy on how such income should be treated, gibbs said
he said cases affecting students who receive stipends developed from a computer matching of employer reports with students' tax returns _ not from any irs initiative to ``go after the graduate students.''
in dispute are stipends paid in 1984, 1985 and 1986. the 1986 tax revision declared all such stipends to be taxable income
irs officials said they had no estimate how many students are involved in the controversy, although the washington post on tuesday quoted unofficial estimates of up to 17,000 cases
apparently there are some inconsistencies in the way the examination of students' returns are being conducted,'' irs spokesman steve pyrek said. there is a wide variety of stipends paid by colleges and universities, he noted, and some irs field offices are following court decisions on the issue while others abide by a 1975 ruling by the agency itself
in looking at the cases, case law is a lot harsher (toward students) than our rules,'' gibbs told the subcommittee
the students' troubles began when their colleges sent the irs copies of w-2 wage statements indicating they were paid taxable wages. when the students filed their tax returns, the computer indicated those wages were not reported as income
gibbs said the irs hopes to announce within a month new guidelines on treatment of such stipends from the three earlier tax years
also within a short time, the commissioner said, he hopes to be able to report on the new estimate of the tax gap. he declined to provide any details of the new findings but told the subcommittee: ``the amount of the tax gap has diminished since the last time we did a study.''
the last irs study of the tax gap was published in 1983 and was based on 1981 information. it estimated that individuals and corporations dodged $81.5 billion in taxes on legal income that year, by understating income and overstating deductions
the agency estimated that another $9 billion in taxes was lost on three types of illegal income: drugs, prostitution and gambling. the new report will not even attempt to estimate the tax loss from illegal income that is never reporte
since the last tax-gap study was published, irs researchers have reported evidence that taxpayers may be cheating less. in may 1986, the agency released a report indicating that a 20-year trend of declining compliance with the tax laws might have been reversed
that study estimated that voluntary compliance rose to 91.8 percent in 1982, from 91.0 percent in 1979. compliance had declined steadily from 94.3 percent in 1965
the vatican newspaper on tuesday criticized attempts by the families and friends of the accused to discredit a 30-year-old woman raped by three men
the woman walking to her car early sunday was beaten and raped repeatedly by three men near the piazza navona in central rome. a police patrol came on the scene of the attack and arrested the men
digging into the private life of the victim, the three `good boys' _ as they were defined by family and friends _ are trying to appear to be the victims, wrapping the only true victim of the incident in a halo of allusions, of accusations that are not even well veiled,'' the vatican newspaper osservatore romano said in an editorial
it criticized the parents of the defendants, saying they expressed ``wonder that a woman should walk around alone at that hour, rather than being upset and expressing pain for the crime committed by their sons.''
even if the assaulted woman was the last of the outcast, if she was addicted to drugs or alcohol _ as some have suggested _ the responsibility of the aggressors not only would not diminish, it would increase.''
the editorial came tuesday as italy celebrated women's day with feminist speeches and calls for stronger measures to combat rape
christian democratic senator rosa russo jervolino, minister for special affairs and the only woman in the cabinet, also criticized the defendants and their families
the behavior (of the three men and their families) shows a distorted mentality which has completely lost sight of the value of personal freedom,'' she said, ``we have a great job to do of cultural restructuring.'' chairman</head>
the comptroller of the currency has dismissed proposed civil penalties against a former michigan bank chairman accused of misusing bank funds
the ruling monday by comptroller robert l. clarke overturned an administrative law judge's recommendation that stanford stoddard, former chairman of michigan national corp., be fined $146,000 for allegedly misusing $167,385 in bank resources for private purposes, including wedding receptions, maintenance of home and vacation properties and renovation of mormon churches
although mr. stoddard flagrantly misused bank funds, the bank's expenditures ... do not constitute extensions of credit,'' clarke said in his ruling. ``accordingly, the civil money penalty shall not be assessed.''
stoddard, 57, was removed as chairman of the bank holding company in 1984 after the comptroller began investigating his activities
the son of the bank's founder, stoddard had run the company since 1972
stoddard's attorney, richard roberts, said, ``our position ... has always been that he did not (misuse funds), that the funds were expended properly for him, either as ... charitable contributions in the instance of the church properties, reimbursement or proper expenditure on his behalf for entertainment, and other permissible expenditures by a corporation on behalf of its chief executive officer.''
the comptroller's ruling said stoddard used bank funds for four purposes: renovation of buildings that were or were to become mormon churches; improvements to his residence, vacation home and florida condominium; payment of bills for a wedding reception for his children and friends; and extensive personal secretarial and errand services
the money was spent on salaries for bank employees assigned to work on the projects, payment of bills for supplies, use of bank supplies, and direct payments to contractors, the comptroller's ruling said
roberts said stoddard had paid the bank about $280,000 as reimbursement
in a separate statement, clarke said his decision was not intended to condone ``mr. stoddard's blatant misapplication of bank funds.''
congress may wish to consider amending the appropriate statutes to make it possible to asssess civil money penalties in similar circumstances in the future,'' clarke said
higher stamp prices won't take effect until next month, postal officials said tuesday after postponing a final decision on the effective date of the new rates
the board of governors of the u.s. postal service will hold a special meeting march 22 to discuss putting the new rates into effect
although no definite decision on an effective date for rates has been scheduled, the board has set april 3 as the target date to give mailers advance notice to plan for the new rates,'' the agency said in a statement issued following its meeting tuesday
under the law, the agency has to give 10 days notice once it votes to impose new rates, so a vote on march 22 could get the new prices in force by april 3, which is also easter this year
the new prices, recommended by the independent postal rate commission last friday following 10 months of deliberation, call for a sweeping series of increases averaging more than 17 percent. included would be a 25-cent first-class rate
at tuesday's meeting, new postmaster general anthony frank said he would like to restore some of the recently cut postal services when higher stamp prices take effect, but he was concerned about the costs involved
post office window openings and sorting hours were cut in january in an effort to comply with congressional spending limits
the higher postage rates are not connected to those cuts, having been proposed nearly a year ago to help compensate for the agency's overall budgetary problems
but, frank admitted, explaining to the public the reasons for reduced services at the same time rates are rising ``is a very difficult message to get out.''
frank said expanded window hours at some offices are being considered, at least to help out during the changeover from one set of rates to another
in addition, he said many offices will stay open until midnight april 15 to accept last-minute tax forms
the postal service, meanwhile, announced that it is offering telephone sales of stamps nationwide during the transition to the new rates
callers will be able to use visa and mastercard credit cards to order the new undenominated ``e'' stamps, with the stamps to be mailed out once the final decision is made on the new rate
customers who want to order the non-denominated stamps can do so, 24 hours a day, by calling 1-800-stamp24. the minimum order will be $12.50 plus a $2 service charge
sales of stamps by telephone have been tested in eight cities since last fall, with total sales now of more than $2 million
in addition to the new ``e'' stamps, which can be used only for letters within the united states, some post offices still have supplies of 25-cent stamps featuring a portrait of writer jack london
in addition, consumers with supplies of 22-cent stamps will be able to purchase stamps to make up the difference between those and the new rates
a new 3-cent stamp showing a conestoga wagon was released feb. 29, and some supplies of the 3-cent stamp showing dr. paul dudley white may also be available. post offices also should have 2-cent stamps featuring mary lyon and 1-cent stamps with the likeness of margaret mitchell
speed-the-plow,'' the new david mamet play starring madonna and produced by the lincoln center theater, will bypass that cultural complex altogether and open directly on broadway, a spokesman said tuesday
the play was to have been performed at the small, 299-seat mitzi newhouse theater in lincoln center before moving to broadway's royale theater in late april, said merle debuskey
now it will begin preview performances april 9 at the royale for a may opening, possibly may 3, debuskey said. he said ``boys' life,'' the current tenant at the newhouse, will extend its run there until june 5. the play, written by howard korder, was to have closed march 13
the lincoln center theater, run by gregory mosher and bernard gersten, has has experienced a booking jam at its two theaters. ``anything goes'' has been a solid hit at the larger vivian beaumont theater where it opened in october. debuskey said the vintage cole porter musical would remain until july 31 and then transfer to broadway
the lincoln center theater opened its fall season at the mitzi newhouse with ``sarafina!'', a south african musical which has moved to broadway. following ``boys' life'' at the newhouse will be ``road,'' by english playwright jim cartwright. it will open june 29
debuskey also confirmed that ``waiting for godot,'' starring steve martin, robin williams, f. murray abraham and bill irwin, would be on the company's fall schedule. it will begin performances oct. 25 at the newhouse, he said
the soviet union, accused of foot-dragging by reagan administration officials, has presented drafts of two key provisions of a treaty to sharply reduce u.s. and soviet strategic nuclear weapons
one of the documents submitted to american negotiators in geneva deals with ways to guard against cheating and the other with procedures for eliminating the weapons
a u.s. official, speaking tuesday only on condition of anonymity, said there were ``big areas of disagreement'' with the american positions in some respects and accord in others
he said the soviet drafts, which were submitted monday, were being translated from russian, and a full appraisal by the u.s. side was not complete
the aim is to have the treaty ready for president reagan and soviet general secretary mikhail s. gorbachev to sign at their next superpower summit meeting. it will be held in moscow in late may or early june
the treaty would reduce the total arsenals of u.s. and soviet long-range bombers, missiles and nuclear submarines by 30 percent to 50 percent
charles e. redman, the state department spokesman, said ``it's encouraging we have the drafts on the table.'' but, redman said, the ``real proof of the pudding'' will be whether the soviet proposals can be meshed with u.s. drafts
still to come from moscow is a memorandum of understanding outlining the numbers and locations of soviet strategic weapons. the u.s. memorandum was offered last week
secretary of state george p. shultz and soviet foreign minister eduard a. shevardnadze decided feb. 22 in moscow to give the negotiators a month to agree on the three treaty protocols. the idea is to have them ready for review by shultz and shevardnadze when they meet in washington on march 22-24
last friday, a u.s. official, also speaking on condition of anonymity, said american negotiator s. read hanmer had complained ``very forcefully'' that moscow had failed to submit its verification and other proposals
at the same time, phyllis oakley, the state department's deputy spokeswoman, publicly criticized the soviets for not presenting their drafts. she said the complex issues required time for thorough study
the negotiators face a number of obstacles in trying to get the treaty ready. ways to verify compliance with a cutback agreement is only one problem
another is the u.s. strategic defense initiative, which the soviets want to restrict. president reagan has vowed not to give ground, however, in the u.s. search for a space-based shield against soviet ballistic missiles
another roadblock is the extreme difficulty in monitoring mobile missiles and some of the other weapons that may be covered by the treaty
five italian sisters showed their latest furry creations at fall-winter shows tuesday alongside the real skins, and they dared the audience to guess which was which
women who still yearn to wear the big cats can now choose the fendi sisters' version consisting of ocelot markings printed on synthetic fur fabric coats with the added bonus of cuffs in real sable
karl lagerfeld, who designs the fendi collection, is never short on witty ideas and when he wasn't making fabric look like fur, he was reversing the process to make furs imitate fabrics. his long winter coats in shaved weasel worked to look like corduroy velvet were a case in point
there were plenty of other surprises, such as the big muffs in chinchilla or sable which, at a flick of the models' wrists, became complete fur coats
but although lagerfeld had his fun with the fakes, he also indulged in the real thing, showing styles in sumptuous mink, sable, ermine and mongolian lamb so lavish that that they could retail for as much as $100,000
favored shapes included high-waisted, oval-skirted coats that harked back to the fashions in vogue in the early 1920s. shoulders were soft and natural with padding sent into retirement
there were spectacular capes such as the circular version in black-dyed mole threaded intricately into lace, and shapely coats in black ermine worked to look like shiny and matte-striped silk velvet
a princess-line coat, fitted and flared, came in woven gray wool and had an extra layer of warmth in its luxury lining of sumptuous chinchilla. monuments</head>
a house subcommittee tuesday approved prime national park sites in washington for two new monuments honoring korean war veterans and the 5,000 black patriots who supported the american revolution
interior secretary donald hodel's designation of both proposed monuments as being of ``pre-eminent historical and lasting significance to the nation'' was endorsed by the house interior subcommittee on national parks and public lands by voice vote
under a 1986 law, congressional approval of such a designation authorizes construction of new monuments on choice parkland in washington that includes the capitol grounds, the mall, the ellipse, west potomac park and constitution gardens
the exact sites for the korean war veterans memorial and the black revolutionary war patriots memorial will be determined later. congress already had authorized construction of the two monuments, and the senate recently approved building both on preferred land
rep. nancy l. johnson, r-conn., said at a subcommittee hearing tuesday that there is only one monument in the capital that honors a black american, a memorial to mary mcleod bethune in a remote city park
both monuments will be built with private funds and maintained by the national park service
a haitian sailing vessel with 60 people aboard was intercepted monday about 300 miles southeast of miami, a u.s. coast guard spokesman said
a ship holding 190 haitians without legal entry papers was found saturday by the coast guard, and passengers were being sent back to port-au-prince
monday's interception was made by the cutter vigorous near crooked island in the bahamas chain, said coast guard spokesman luis diaz
the 45 men, 12 women and three children will be taken back to haiti by the vigorous, he said
coast guard vessels were also searching monday for another ship reportedly in the area, said diaz
diaz said there had been a lull in haitian interceptions in recent months, and that the two seizures could signal renewed efforts to enter the country illegally
a judge has denied a motion to reconsider his reduction of a $10.5 million jury award to an 83-year-old woman who was struck in the eye by a 7-up bottle cap
third district court judge kenneth rigtrup on monday let stand his feb. 17 reduction to $375,000 the damages due mae roberts of holladay
rigtrup said the jurors were ``inflamed with passion'' and had awarded damages that were ``disproportionate and unreasonable.''
rigtrup awarded $75,000 in compensatory and $300,000 in punitive damages. the jury had awarded $500,000 in compensatory damages and $10 million in punitive damages
colin king, the plaintiff's attorney, has said the judge's action would nullify the jury's attempt to punish 7-up and to send a message to bottlers that negligence would not be tolerated
roberts was struck in the eye when an aluminum twist-off cap blew off a soda bottle she was opening with a pair of pliers. as a result, the sight in her left eye was impaired
king said roberts is unlikely to seek another trial because of her age
a justice department official said tuesday he favors raising congressional pay to as much as $175,000 in exchange for ending a ``double standard'' exempting senators and representatives from federal ethics laws
assistant attorney general william weld said it is ``neither logical nor ... consonant with the notion of fair play'' to make it a crime for executive branch officials to accept fees or honoraria for job-related activities, while allowing members of congress to do so
in a national press club speech attacking public corruption, weld said he favors ``raising the salary of all members of congress to a level around somewhere between $150,000 and $175,000 a year. this would enable you to do some other things like prohibit honoraria.''
it would very, very expensive, and ... worth every penny,'' said weld, head of the department's criminal division
currently, congressional salaries are $89,500 a year, which senators may supplement with honoraria in an amount not to exceed 40 percent of their salaries. the percentage for house members is 30 percent
at worst'' the payment and acceptance of fees and honoraria ``can degenerate into a case of veiled extortion or a case of veiled gratuity,'' weld said
weld also said congress should apply to itself the federal conflict-of-interest laws under which former white house political director lyn nofziger was convicted of illegal lobbying. congress has exempted itself from those laws
weld noted that while a member of congress is free to lobby his former colleagues the day after he leaves office, ``as recent events have made abundantly clear, such behavior by a former member of the executive branch would land one in jail.''
nofziger was found guilty of lobbying former white house associates within one year after he left the government on matters in which the agency had been substantially involved: a federal contract for wedtech corp.; the continued production of a10 anti-tank aircraft; and civilian manning of navy ships. nofziger faces sentencing later this month
weld rejected the suggestion that he was raising the congressional ethics issue in an election year to overshadow the fact that a number of reagan administration officials are under criminal investigation or have been convicted of crimes
weld's boss, attorney general edwin meese iii, is under criminal investigation by an independent counsel
my remarks today are the same as remarks i've been giving since ... 1978 ... so it's no recently cooked-up farrago,'' weld said. ``i'm speaking about legislation when i talk about double standard, not anybody's performance. i'm not saying one branch has a monopoly on sleaze.''
weld also expressed support for the 1978 ethics in government act under which independent counsels and the office of government ethics police federal ethics laws in the executive branch. the investigation of meese was launched last may 11 under that law
i like the ethics in government act. i think it's a good statute'' and ``i think it deserves to be enforced,'' weld said
a former u.s. attorney in boston, weld said that when he came to washington in 1986, he mistakenly thought a dozen congressmen might have broken the law when they accepted $2,000 fees in a visit to a commercial enterprise over which their committee had jurisdiction
a deputy informed him ``that only members of the wicked and nefarious executive branch and independent agencies are prohibited from supplementing their salaries,'' he recalled. ``that very same action ... would be a lay down criminal case if performed by somebody in the executive branch.''
the congressmen justified taking the fees by saying they expected to be compensated for their time
compensation is the word used in the criminal statute, which ``shows you how deep that double standard runs,'' said weld
rep. barney frank, d-mass., agreed with weld's suggestions, saying his house subcommittee will address the congressional exemptions with proposed legislation
frank is chairman of the house judiciary subcommittee on administrative law and governmental relations
honoraria and fees ``give both the appearance and in some cases the reality of improper influence,'' frank said. regarding conflicts of interest, frank said that when ``a one-time colleague'' leaves congress and ``next month is asking for a favor, personal feeling gets into it that's not legitimate.''
about 4,000 supporters of president joaquin balaguer marched through the capital tuesday on the eve of a 48-hour general strike called by the opposition
to the conspirators, we're going to give hell,'' shouted the balaguer supporters, who ended their afternoon rally at the national palace
a tense calm prevailed in the rest of the city of 1.5 million. police and soldiers were out in force, but the barricades, burning tires and stone-throwing mobs of last week were absent
wednesday's strike was called by the national conference of popular organizations, which claims to represent about 200 groups. the issue is the soaring cost of living in this caribbean nation of 6 million
inflation last year rose 30 percent, according to private economists, who predict that this year it will top 50 percent. the central bank estimates inflation hit 16 percent in 1987
coalition spokesman fabio ruiz said balaguer's pledge to implement price controls on bananas, onions, potatoes, rice and beans, ``don't satisfy our demands.''
the coalition also rejected balaguer's pledge, made last month, to increase the minimum wage by 33 percent to about $75 a month
rising prices for gasoline, meat and other basic commodities have touched off protests in several of the dominican republic's 26 provinces. in the past two weeks, six people have been killed and about 20 injured by gunshots, tear gas or stones. several hundred people have been detained
leftist groups and unions claimed tuesday that police arrested some of their leaders _ including diaz jaquez of the dominican workers party and rafael abreu of the general workers central _ without warrant, and interrogated others
armed forces minister lt. gen. antonio imbert barrera said soldiers will patrol city streets and give ``full support'' to the national police
the strike wednesday is opposed by the main labor unions, the dominican revolutionary party, which is the main opposition party, and the influential roman catholic church. those groups and others have urged that compromises be negotiated to resolve the economic problems
a u.s. official said tuesday he would view as ``unfriendly'' any votes against a proposed united nations inquiry into alleged human rights violations in cuba
vernon walters, the top u.s. representative to the united nations, made the statement at a luncheon for international officials and business leaders as he stepped up pressure on allies to back the u.s.-sponsored proposal
walters also told the 43-member u.n. human rights commission on tuesday that it should examine the alleged human rights violations in cuba or risk becoming ``accomplices of oppression.''
he said a more harshly worded version of the proposal failed to pass last year by one vote for political reasons. the united states has complained of political bias at the commission, which often has condemned human rights violations in israeli-occupied territories, south africa and chile
walters said torture and secret executions continue in cuba and that ``freedom exists only to the extent that (cuban leader) fidel castro decides it can.''
the resolution, which will come before the commission this week, urges the cuban government to permit the international red cross to investigate prison conditions. it also asks the u.n. secretary-general to investigate alleged human rights violations
prime minister margaret thatcher said tuesday that britain's current military exercise to reinforce the falkland islands against possible attack by argentina was ``no one else's business.''
flatly rejecting protests by argentina and other latin american countries, mrs. thatcher told the house of commons that britain had a right and also ``a duty to see that reinforcement proposals could in fact be carried out.''
it is no one else's business except the defense of people's rights in the falkland islands,'' said mrs. thatcher
about 900 troops will travel 8,000 miles next week to the falkland islands from brize norton air base, north of london, as part of the exercise, called fire focus
the exercise began this week with mythical ``intelligence reports'' warning that argentina was preparing again to invade the south atlantic archipelago which it has long claimed. the 1,800 british-descended islanders fiercely reject argentine rule
fire focus is the first major maneuver announced by britain since it recaptured the islands from invading argentine troops in a 74-day war in 1982
britain has said it gave notice last month to argentina of the intended exercise and has since announced that fire focus will involve fewer than 1,000 men
britain maintains a garrison, reportedly of about 2,000 men, on the islands and says it must practice sending in reinforcements in order to avoid keeping more troops there permanently
briefing reporters at brize norton on tuesday, foreign office assistant under secretary robin fearn said fire focus ``threatens no one. it is entirely defensive.''
far from being a cause for concern, it is an integral part of our policy of reducing tension,'' he added
he said the initial post-war garrison had been halved in recent years after the completion of a new runway at the falklands capital, port stanley, which can take wide-bodied jets. cash problem</head>
a $350,000 shortfall is casting a shadow on the largest-ever soviet-u.s. cultural exchange, a three-week festival viewed by the state department as an important symbol of improved relations with moscow, fund-raisers said tuesday
with three days to go before its scheduled opening, ``making music together'' is heavily in the red because of unexpected costs, said harold hestes, president of the greater boston chamber of commerce
hestes declined to detail what drove costs above the estimated budget of $2.4 million, but said revised figures put the price tag for the 80-event festival at about $3.3 million
festival operating co. which is managing the american part of the exchange, last month seriously considered the idea of declaring bankruptcy and canceling the event, said lawyer gabor garai
instead, company directors agreed to try and raise additional funds ``in light of the national and international importance of the event,'' said garai, whose firm, hale and dorr, is providing free legal counsel to organizers
billed by u.s. organizers as the largest cultural exchange ever with the soviet union, the festival, which runs though april 2, will feature 285 soviet musicians, dancers, composers and other artists performing in the boston area
it will continue in moscow in the fall of 1989, where the festival will concentrate on contemporary american music
organizers originally had hoped to cover most costs through ticket sales, a state contribution of $450,000 and private sector pledges of $350,000
the state has promised to provide more grants and loans amounting to $400,000, and businessess and charitable organizations have pledged an additional $150,000, hestes said
of the outstanding $350,000, hestes said, ``we're doing our best to raise it (but) the cash flow situation is extremely tight.''
it would be my hope that that the festival goes on no matter what, as it would be tragedy for the state and the nations if it would fail,'' he said
hestes said he contacted the state department about possible cancellation recently, and ``the clear inference ... (was) that it would be bad for our relations with the soviet union.''
secretary of state george p. shultz expressed his personal support and that of president ronald reagan last year, in a letter to sarah caldwell, a key organizer of the exchange and artistic director of the opera company of boston
i want you to know that both the president and i personally support these exchanges ....,'' he wrote to ms. caldwell. ``these exchanges will continue to be an important element in the u.s.-soviet relationship.''
ms. caldwell provided a copy of the sept. 8 letter to the associated press
in washington, greg guroff, of the government-run u.s. information agency, said he believes the soviet union ``has made a tremendous commitment to this festival.''
guroff, head of the agency's office of u.s.-soviet exchanges and a former cultural attache to the u.s. embassy in moscow, said the soviets would interpret cancellation as a rebuff
because of guaranteed state funding of such events in the soviet union, ``the american concept of fund-raising for most soviets ...(is) not only incomprehensible, but it's not their problem,'' said guroff. ``we have had two or three performing arts exchanges that have fallen through from lack of funding: the fallout was quite considerable in the soviets' minds.''
supreme court justice sandra day o'connor was reported ``in good spirits'' and feeling well tuesday after having her appendix removed
o'connor, 57, underwent the surgery monday night at bethesda naval hospital
court spokeswoman toni house said o'connor was feeling ``exceedingly well'' but gave few other details
justice antonin scalia, asked about o'connor after he testified before a house subcommittee on the supreme court's budget request for next fiscal year, said he had spoken to her by telephone tuesday morning
she sounded in good spirits,'' he said. ``i think she'll be back to work shortly.''
o'connor had been scheduled to testify with scalia but she was taken to the hospital in midafternoon monday, and was operated on about 8 p.m
scalia explained o'connor's absence to the subcommittee members by saying, ``she had a supervening appointment with an appendectomy.''
jed christensen, director of the office of surface mining for the past three years, is leaving his job march 20, the interior department announced tuesday
christensen, who served as the government's chief regulator of strip mining longer than anyone else, will become assistant chief administrative officer of fresno county, calif
his boss will be dan fitzpatrick, with whom he worked previously when chistensen was a budget officer for clark county, nev. ``he called me (just after taking office) and asked if i would be interested ... i will be getting back to my roots.''
he said he was ``not in the least'' pushed out
christensen also has worked in local government in provo, utah; phoenix, ariz and santa anna, calif
he came to the interior department in 1981 and was appointed acting director of the office of surface mining in april 1985, winning nomination as director in december 1985 and confirmation in may 1986
robert h. gentile, an aide to steven griles, assistant secretary for land and minerals management, has been appointed deputy to chistensen for operations, the department said
christensen said it was ``up to the secretary'' to decide on a successor, but other officials, speaking on condition they not be identified, said they expected gentile to be named acting director, perhaps for the remainder of the reagan administration
the office, formed by congress in 1977 after a decade of bitter debate, was subjected to a wrenching reorganization by then-secretary james watt in 1981. when christensen took over, some violation records were still stored in shoeboxes
christensen said most of the $150 million in penalties represented by those boxes would be written off by the end of this fiscal year, with about 15 percent of the amount finally collected, and the records now kept on a computer
his tenure also has seen installation of another computer system to match applicants for mining permits in the states against the list of outstanding violations, and the abolition by congress of the exemption from most regulation for mines under two acres. that exemption had enabled some big companies in virginia and kentucky to break their operations into a ``string of pearls'' _ mines of less than two acres operated by subcontractors
i'm amazed at the things we've accomplished,'' he said, listing among other things better relations with the states and forthcoming proposals for criminal penalties for mining without a permit and for incentives for miners to take coal from and reclaim abandoned mines
thomas galloway, a washington lawyer who has represented environmental groups in several lawsuits against the agency, said christensen's departure was ``not a major move,'' since ``he was not involved in major issues over the past year ... we have been dealing with the assistant secretary's office.''
galloway said he believed the office was ``probably in the worst shape it's been since 1977'' in terms of competence and effectiveness, which he said was ``not entirely the reagan administration's fault.''
i believe abuse is continuing unchecked'' in parts of kentucky, west virginia, virginia and tennessee, largely at the hands of miners operating on a shoestring, galloway said
rep. mike synar, d-okla., who as chairman of the environment subcommittee of the house government operations committee has produced several reports critical of the office, said a change in directors ``will be meaningless, just like all the others have been.'' opponent</head>
off-duty police gathered signatures at polling places tuesday in a drive to abolish a citizens review board, but said they abandoned their efforts at one site after being confronted by a city council member
in at least one of the polling places, we had to leave because (mayor pro tem) diane ragsdale and some of her cohorts started to create problems, so we just decided to leave because it was not worth it,'' said dallas police association president monica smith
ms. ragsdale started an argument, trying to convince people not to sign the petitions, and rather than getting it to escalate, we pulled out,'' said ms. smith
ms. ragsdale, a vocal critic of the police, said there was no confrontation
this gentleman wanted to know from me what to do. he wanted to know about the issue because, you know, many of them _ actually, some of our citizens, seniors _ really don't know,'' she said
they do not realize what they are doing,'' she said. ``they attempted to circumvent their policy makers.''
but one dpa spokesman, larry mcgowan, said ms. ragsdale grabbed one man trying to sign a petition
ms. smith said signatures were being collected citywide by about 1,400 off-duty officers, 200 to 300 firefighters and their families. the campaign to abolish the dallas citizens police review board has drawn opposition from a coalition of black business, community, church and elected leaders
the dpa wants the city to hire more officers and abolish the board, which hears complaints against police. the board was formed in january and has met twice
twenty thousand signatures are needed to force a city charter amendment election
the texas secretary of state had poll monitors at voting places, also observing the police effort
three dallas officers have been shot and killed this year, including john chase, who was shot by a deranged transient as a bus-stop crowd watched the homeless man ignore the officer's pleas to spare his life
four men have also been killed by officers this year, including the transient who killed chase
opponents of the citizens review board, which has limited subpoena powers, say it duplicates existing panels or agencies, including the police internal affairs department and the dallas county grand jury, and calls into question the department's ability to police itself
northwest lawmakers and representatives of the timber industry said tuesday the new u.s.-canada free trade treaty will do little to open canadian markets to american-manufactured plywood, but reagan administration officials said it was a step in the right direction
it's one-way free trade,'' rep. peter defazio, d-ore., said during a house subcommittee hearing. ``the u.s. is being snookered again.''
both defazio and rep. ron wyden, d-ore., said the treaty will allow canadian plywood manufacturers unrestricted access to american markets but only 10 percent of the canadian market, at best, will be opened to u.s. producers
i think a provision like this provides red meat to the protectionists,'' said wyden, adding that congress should draft strong language covering plywood trade when it consider implementing language for the treaty later this year
oregon is the top plywood producing state in the nation and washington state ranks no. 4. other states in the top five include louisiana, texas and arkansas
an arms dealer charged with plotting to sell weapons to argentina, iraq, poland and the soviet union was asked by u.s. intelligence officials to use his contacts in poland to arrange the purchase of two soviet ``super tanks,'' his attorney said tuesday
solomon schwartz, 52, of monsey, was sought out by the cia in 1982 and later had contact with the defense intelligence agency concerning the possible purchase of the soviet t-72 tanks, which the u.s. government wanted to study for intelligence purposes, said attorney lawrence dubin
schwartz negotiated with three polish generals for the tanks but the sale never materialized, dubin said in his opening statement at the trial of schwartz and three co-defendants, who are also arms dealers
the defendants are accused of plotting four illegal weapons deals, including smuggling military equipment to the argentinian government during the falkland islands war and an unsuccessful attempt to ship guns to iraq
they were willing to sell to anyone, no matter whose hands the weapons fell into, if the price was right,'' said assistant u.s. attorney larry krantz
the argentinian deal, the only one that went through, included the shipment of 1,300 night vision goggles and resulted in a profit of $1 million for the defendants, krantz said
the prosecutor charged that schwartz would use the soviet tank deal to ``cover up'' one of the illegal arms deals, a shipment of 500 automatic rifles and ammunition destined for poland but seized by u.s. customs agents at john f. kennedy airport in february 1984
dubin said the weapons were to be shipped to poland but then would be immediately re-shipped to mexico, using a legal export license, by an independent trading company
he said the arms shipment to poland was needed to establish ``a course of routine business'' in poland to facilitate any possible future dealings involving the soviet tanks
schwartz, the owner of texas armament advisors inc., will testify during the trial about the tank deal, dubin said
the other illegal arms shipments alleged in the indictment involved 110 boxes of handguns, shotguns and ammunition destined for iraq but seized by belgian authorities; and 400 night vision devices to the soviet union in a sting operation orchestrated by u.s. customs. all took place between 1982 and 1984
although these weapons are routinely bought and sold in the u.s., the export of these weapons are highly regulated by the government,'' krantz said. ``the defendants were caught red-handed participating in a series of illegal arms transactions.''
the other defendants are h. leonard berg, 52, of the bronx, owner of hlb security electronics ltd. of manhattan; grim depanicis, 44, of mount dora, fla., a vice president of hlb; leon lisbona, 63, of queens, an hlb employee
berg, lisbona and schwartz are charged with racketeering, racketeering conspiracy, wire fraud and violating arms export laws and are accused of participating in all four illegal deals
depanicis is not charged with any of the racketeering counts and is named only in the argentinian and soviet union deals
krantz said the trial was expected to last several weeks and would include secretly recorded conversations
thousands of japanese-americans detained in prison camps during world war ii suffered a ``catastrophic deprivation of civil rights,'' an attorney told a federal appeals court tuesday
but the arguments by the attorney representing 120,000 japanese-americans in a $24 billion class-action suit and by the justice department lawyer fighting the suit were far removed from the gruesome details of what appeals court judge helen nies described as ``a disgrace we all know and lived through.''
instead, the hearing before the u.s. circuit court of appeals for the federal circuit focused mainly on whether the statute of limitations had expired in the case
this is the second time a federal appeals court has heard the case. in 1986, the u.s. circuit court of appeals for the district of columbia ruled that the government must defend itself at trial against the suit, which seeks compensation for property losses suffered by those interned
in doing so, it overturned a 1984 decision by district court judge louis oberdorfer, who had ruled that a six-year statute of limitations on suits against the government had expired
but the supreme court ruled last june that the issue of whether the lawsuit was filed within the legal deadline should have been decided by a different court _ the u.s. circuit court of appeals for the federal circuit
the only time the supreme court has ruled on the internment itself _ authorized by president franklin d. roosevelt in the wake of the 1941 japanese attack on pearl harbor _ was in 1944, when it found it was a constitutionally acceptable military necessity. government documents discovered later indicate no such military necessity existed
this case involves the catastrophic deprivation of civil rights,'' said benjamin zelenko, attorney for william hohri of chicago, the lead plaintiff in the class-action suit
hohri, a san francisco native who lived in southern california when the war began, said tuesday he was interned at manzanar camp east of the sierra nevada shortly after his 15th birthday. he left for the midwest 2{ years later and never returned to california
zelenko argued that the statute of limitations did not come into play until the early 1980s because of ``deliberate concealment and misrepresentation by the government of critical information regarding its claim of `military necessity.'''
the concealment didn't end until the 1980s, zelenko said, when a congressionally appointed commission found that there was no military necessity for the internment. the policy was ``driven by race prejudice, war hysteria and lack of political leadership,'' he told the three-judge panel of giles rich, phillip baldwin and nies
jay bybee, representing the government, told the court, ``there is no dispute that there were great wrongs done to japanese-americans.... but even when mistakes are made, people must file timely claims for redress...
the plaintiffs have known the basis of their claims since the 1940s,'' said bybee, who contended that they didn't file their suit at that time because they believed the government would have been successful in claiming military necessity for its actions. warmth</head> procter, sted proctor. inserts 1 graf after 13th, `both public...' to add information about his contact with his children.</note>
the death of bill britt, whose body was found in his woods shelter alone and partially devoured by animals, symbolized the fate of society's homeless and eccentric people, a housing court official said tuesday
autopsy results tuesday showed that britt, 52, died of hypothermia and was dead two weeks before he was discovered monday by two of his three children in his makeshift wigwam in brookline, according to the suffolk county medical examiner's report
homeless people, people like britt who say they want to be alone, should be protected in this weather,'' said stanton kessler, a senior pathologist in the medical examiner's office. ``he had no food in him. he had no sleeping bag. this type of thing should be prevented.''
kessler said britt was clothed and wrapped in blankets when he died. identification was ``presumptive,'' he said, because rodents had eaten most of his face, hands and fingers. his feet were intact because they had been dug into the ground and covered with dirt, for warmth, kessler said
britt died in the woods near the chestnut hill reservoir, near the affluent community of the same name where he was born and grew up. he had lived in the woods since 1969 and did not attract much attention until 1985, when officials began trying to move him into public or subsidized housing
britt's continual resistance to being moved brought him national attention and his nickname, ``the hermit of chestnut hill.'' at one point, actor mickey rooney planned to buy the rights to his story. last may he appeared on ``late night with david letterman.''
chief housing court justice e. george daher tried to arrange housing and medical aid for britt despite his repeated lack of cooperation
he represents in a microcosm what happens to the homeless, the unfortunates, the eccentrics in this cold society,'' daher said tuesday. ``no one seemed to care about him. he should have been monitored. someone should have checked in on him, rather than have him die a lonely tragic death like this.''
there are more than 3,400 homeless people in the boston area, according to the city emergency shelter commission director, anne maguire. she said about 150 of them are outside much of the time
but britt was unique, she said, adding, ``most people want shelter.''
others also agreed britt did not fit the typical definition of the homeless or mentally ill
a one-time insurance agent who also worked in procter &amp; gamble's marketing division in new york city 30 years ago, britt had been married with a family. many speculated that a reportedly messy divorce in 1969 fueled his change in lifestyle
both public officials and friends said he was a paradox; a loner who loved to chat with boston college students who went to class just yards from his shelter, an eccentric who said he wanted to be left alone but who regularly pitched stories about himself to the media
the britt children recently were in fairly regular contact with him. ingrid boughner, 28, his daughter, who learned last year that her father was the well-known hermit, said she visited him several times over the last few weeks, leaving him sandwiches and notes that were never touched. britt's body was found dead by her and her brother, britton boughner
mary callahan, 27, met britt as a reporter on a local weekly newspaper. she was one of the first to write about him
it seems so sad to me,'' said callahan, now on the editorial staff of boston college's in-house newspaper. ``he was a singular person, a very interesting man. he looked very old but he was so articulate. he talked about writing poetry, about writing books. it's strange that he decided to live there.''
bill blacker, a box clerk at the chestnut hill post office, said britt came in almost daily to check the mail box he paid $11 for every six months
he talked like such an educated man,'' said blacker. ``i sure wouldn't have wanted to live that way but at least he did what he chose to do. i just think something drastic must have happened to him to make him want to live like that.''
sales of u.s. savings bonds increased for the sixth consecutive month in february, rising 2 percent to $658 million, the government reported tuesday
the treasury department said that february sales were $13 million higher than january and were 2 percent above the level of a year ago, when sales were $646 million
with the inclusion of interest earnings, the value of outstanding bonds rose by $1 billion to total $103.24 billion, 10 percent higher than a year ago
since november 1982, savings bonds held five years or longer have earned market-based interest rates. the current rate, in effect until may 1, is 7.17 percent
former interior secretary william clark was hospitalized after erratic winds flipped his plane as it took off from his private airstrip, his wife said tuesday
he had a little mishap with his small plane,'' said joan clark. ``it isn't serious. he will be out in a day or so.''
clark was taken to twin cities hospital in san luis obispo for observation after monday's accident. the hospital referred all calls to the family business, the clark company, which is involved in real estate and other ventures
clark, 56, was alone at the controls of his super cub aircraft when winds jarred the plane at the family ranch, 160 miles northwest of los angeles, mrs. clark said
the plane overturned and didn't get airborne, she said
clark, who said his job as interior secretary was the most satisfying in decades of public service, resigned jan. 1, 1985, and returned to his california ranch, about 50 miles north of reagan's spread in santa barbara
the internal revenue service on tuesday reminded americans of the newest tax they face: a levy on vaccines that protect against childhood diseases
under a law that congress passed and president reagan signed last december, a tax of up to $4.56 was imposed on shots. the tax must be paid to the government by the manufacturer, producer or importer but nothing in the law prohibits it from being passed on to the patient
the irs issued a routine announcement noting that the tax applies to vaccines sold after dec. 31. the money will be used to compensate people who are injured or who die from receiving commonly prescribed vaccines after sept. 30, 1988
the amount paid in claims, which must be filed in u.s. district court, will be limited by the size of the vaccine fund
the tax is $4.56 for a dose of dpt (diphtheria, whooping cough and tetanus) vaccine; 6 cents for diphtheria and tetanus; $4.44 for measles, mumps and rubella, and 29 cents for polio
supreme court justice antonin scalia told a house subcommittee tuesday that trimming the high court's $16.4 budget request could ``cut not fat, not muscle but bone.''
scalia, submitting a budget request for the fiscal year that begins next october, warned that the court cannot withstand an appropriations reduction similar to one imposed for its current budget
we come close to becoming the proverbial turnip'' from which no more blood can be squeezed, scalia said
the court last year requested $16 million for its current, fiscal year 1988 budget but only $15.2 million was appropriated
this has put a very serious strain on the operations of the court during the current fiscal year,'' scalia said
the fiscal year 1989 request includes:
_$100,000 for increased library shelving capacity
_$40,000 to upgrade into legal research databases the word processors the justices and their law clerks use
_$50,000 to celebrate the 200th anniversary of the federal law that created the federal court system
the supreme court's budget is handled separately from the billion-dollar budget of the federal court system but most of the subcommittee's questions, focused on problems facing the federal judiciary generally
rep. joseph d. early, d-mass., asked several questions about what he apparently views as dwindling judicial efficiency
noting that ``there are a lot more laws out there,'' scalia said, ``you simply cannot lay too much additional responsibility upon this institution (the federal courts) without fundamentally changing'' it
responding to a similar question by rep. jim kolbe, r-ariz., scalia said the caseload problem facing federal courts ``originates right here (in congress) and i don't see an answer to it.''
the united states and britain on tuesday vetoed a security council resolution to impose economic sanctions on south africa in an effort to end apartheid
the measure failed by a vote of 10-2, with france, west germany and japan abstaining
the resolution would have imposed mandatory worldwide sanctions, including an oil embargo, for a year
all the speakers deplored south africa's state of emergency and recent restrictions on anti-apartheid groups
in their speeches, the representatives of france and italy condemned pretoria's ban on activities by major anti-apartheid groups and urged dialogue between the white-led government and the black majority. however, the representatives did not endorse mandatory sanctions
the united states and some other western nations have opposed similar measures in the past. the five permanent members of the security council _ the united states, britain, china, france and the soviet union _ have veto power
the resolution proposed a ban on export and sale of oil to south africa, the discontinuation of iron and steel imports from south africa, an end to loans to south africa, a ban on sale of coins minted in south africa and a halt to all military, police or intelligence cooperation with south africa
in johannesburg, foreign minister pik botha said on national television that ``i wrote the words'' used by south africa's u.n. ambassador, leslie manley, last thursday when he told the council, ``do your damnedest.''
either we're strong enough to withstand and resist the onslaught against us or we're not,'' botha said
the draft resolution invoked chapter 7 of the u.n. charter, which provides for economic sanctions and other measures when international peace and security are threatened
last thursday the council opened a debate to condemn south africa's ban feb. 24 on activities by major anti-apartheid groups. it is expected to pass a resolution expressing outrage and condemnation
by law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and health services
four suspects in the killing of a rookie police officer as he sat in a patrol car were indicted tuesday, authorities said
todd scott, 19, scott cobb, 24, philip copeland, 22; and david mcclary, 22, were indicted on charges of second-degree murder and criminal possession of a weapon, said richard piperno, spokesman for the district attorney's office
edward byrne, 22, was shot in the head feb. 26 as he sat in his car guarding the home of a man who had complained about crack dealing in the borough of queens
all four suspects have been held without bail since pleading innocent at arraignments friday and saturday
police commissioner benjamin ward said police believe a major drug dealer ordered the hit. the arrests followed a week-long investigation that included a roundup of 294 suspected dealers in queens
ward said the suspects met in a queens apartment feb. 25 to plan the murder of a police officer. police alleged that copeland was at the planning session, but not the slaying
it was not known who pulled the trigger. mcclary and scott have pointed the finger at each other, police said
he calls himself dee jay, says he is 17 and ran away from new york city. but beyond that, sheriff's deputies say they have no idea who he is or how to help him
this kid has been in limbo for 17 years _ or more. he doesn't know who he is or anything,'' montgomery county chief deputy gary haines said monday
haines appealed for public help to identify dee jay, saying routine missing-person checks and other leads have turned up nothing since the man was arrested outside a bar march 2
dee jay appears to have a severe learning disability, haines said. he also told investigators he may have been involved in pornography films and other abuse, haines said
dee jay was picked up after deputies were called to investigate a car burglar alarm outside a bar, haines said
his explanation is that he heard the alarm go off while he was in the lounge,'' said claudia marlin, the department's victim advocate. she said he was in the lounge because, ``they have free hors d'oeuvres and he was hungry.''
dee jay was not charged and is in the custody of the montgomery county children services board, haines said. he cannot read or use a telephone and can barely write, haines said
he is described as black, 6-foot-2, weighing about 150 pounds, with black hair and brown eyes. he was wearing a black-and-silver sweater and washed jeans, haines said
dee jay told ms. marlin he lived with a man named rick in a three-bedroom apartment in the new york city borough of the bronx. he said he got occasional tutoring and once was treated by a doctor for the flu, she said
he said he hitchhiked from the bronx on a truck, ended up in dayton around christmas and slept in trucks and in doorways, ms. marlin said
the u.n. food and agriculture organization criticized the united states tuesday for its questions about how the agency handles its money and hires employees
fred j. eckert, u.s. ambassador to the agency, sent a letter to fao director-general edouard saouma seeking details of agency spending, hiring practices and saouma's compensation package
these are serious and important questions,'' eckert said tuesday
agency spokesman richard lydiker said: ``the director-general regrets that requests for information have been presented as aspersions on the management and reputation of the fao. as requests for information they are legitimate. but as aspersions they are groundless.''
throughout his entire term of office the director-general has scrupulously observed (the agency's) rules and regulations and this will be demonstrated in his reply to the permanent representative of the united states,'' lydiker said, reading from a statement
he also noted that the united states has not paid its contribution to the agency. lydiker said earlier this year that the united states owes $68 million from its 1986-87 assessment, which amounts to a quarter of the agency's budget
saouma, a lebanese, was elected to a third six-year term in november, defeating an african challenger supported by the united states and other major donor nations
the united states and other nations have called for reforms at the organization, which coordinates agricultural projects in developing countries and is the largest specialized agency in the united nations
last november, a 1988-89 fao budget of $492 million was approved over objections from the united states, britain, australia and canada
in the course of our review, we have become increasingly concerned about reports portraying fao in an extremely unfavorable light. the questions that we shall be putting to you are for the purpose of getting at the truth of these matters,'' eckert said in his letter, dated march 3
the letter also asked for an explanation about travel expenses for delegates to a recent agency conference, the agency's purchase of cars and details of entertainment allowances
it asked how many former ambassadors were on the agency's payroll and whether relatives of current or former ambassadors work for the agency
winter wheat planted last fall for harvest this summer is in ``mostly good to fair'' condition in some of the nation's major production areas, a government report said tuesday
the joint agricultural weather facility said wheat during the week of feb. 29 through march 6 was not quite in such good shape in the northern great plains, delta and rocky mountain states, however
snow cover was virtually nonexistent in the central and northern great plain and rocky mountain states, but mild temperatures kept damage at a minimum,'' the report said. ``snow, preceding freezing temperatures, prevented severe winter damage to small grain (including wheat) in eastern kansas, northern oklahoma, illinois, missouri, indiana and ohio.''
crop development by early march ranged from greening in colorado to jointing of plants in mississippi and oklahoma, and heading in arizona, the report said
the facility is operated by the departments of commerce and agriculture. reports do not forecast actual production of crops, only the condition of fields and plants. organization to national coalition for haitian refugees.</note>
congress was urged by a trio of witnesses tuesday to increase economic and diplomatic pressure on haiti to spur a return to democratic rule
but the latin american director of the center for strategic and international studies, a washington-based conservative think tank, called on the united states to restore aid to haiti
the witness, georges fauriol, said the new government of haitian president leslie manigat ``deserves encouragement and resources _ rather than further sanctions and further hardship for the haitian people.''
barring gross misjudgment and behavior on the part of the new government, the united states, at a minimum, should reinstate the aid package cut off last november,'' fauriol said
but other witnesses disagreed
rep. george w. crockett jr., d-mich., chairman of the house foreign affairs subcommittee on western hemisphere affairs, said washington needs to make clear ``that the united states government will use every diplomatic, political and economic means at our disposal to help accomplish a free and fair election in haiti.''
a haitian journalist, raymond a. joseph, urged manigat to call new elections and order the investigation of politically inspired killings
michael s. hooper, executive director of the national coalition for haitian refugees, said the reagan administration would end the hope for free and fair elections in haiti if it moves to embrace the manigat government, which was installed after haiti's military forces broke up earlier presidential elections
the united states should immediately institute and recommend a complete (international) arms embargo and an end to all assistance that frees up domestic resources allowing the government to sustain the growing army,'' hooper said
patrick bellegarde-smith, an author specializing in haiti and its problems, called on the united states to continue the aid cutoff, to oppose all loans to haiti by international lending institutions, to withdraw haiti's privileges under the caribbean basin initiative, and to insist haiti restore democratic government and end the use of the country as a haven for narcotics trafficking
the congressional appropriations committees have denied a request by the energy department to shift $8 million to pay for evaluation of possible sites for the $4.4 billion super-collider atom smasher, the department said tuesday
we are looking at our options,'' department spokesman jeff sherwood said
the department is seeking $363 million in the fiscal year beginning oct. 1 to begin construction of the collider, a 53-miles-around tunnel that would smash beams of protons into each other
last year it requested $25 million for design and $10 million for early construction work that was not tied to a site, but congress approved only the $25 million
sherwood said the department had not sought site evaluation funds until it knew how many sites it would have to deal with. twenty-five states submitted proposals for 35 sites, a list that was narrowed to seven finalists in december
until recently the department had planned to write an environmental impact statement only for its final choice, expected to be made tentatively in july, but last month secretary john herrington told congress that choice would be delayed until november, and the department said it would assess environmental impacts for all seven sites
there is substantial congressional opposition to the heavy spending required for the project. sen. bennett johnston, d-la., chairman of the energy and natural resources committee and also of the energy and water development subcommittee of the appropriations committee, warned herrington that the department might not get all the money it was seeking in the new fiscal year
the $8 million would have been shifted from general administrative funds of the department for the current fiscal year
sherwood said the department could take evaluation funds from the $25 million, at the cost of slowing down design of the magnets that guide the proton beams, or could delay the evaluations, perhaps at the cost of pushing the site selection decision into the next administration
we would very much like to keep to our planned schedule,'' he said
rising production costs and a weakening dollar overseas are forcing the washington opera to raise ticket prices and reduce the number of performances next season, officials said tuesday. the best orchestra seats will sell for $60, up from $49.50 this year
despite the first major boost in ticket prices since 1981, general director martin feinstein said the opera still must raise $300,000 privately to stage a new production of giacomo puccini's ``tosca'' for its season opener in the kennedy center opera house on nov. 5
tenor placido domingo will star in that production, which will be directed by gian carlo menotti and conducted by rafael fruhbeck de burgos
other season highlights will include peter tchaikovsky's ``pique dame'' (the queen of spades), conducted by mstislav rostropovich and directed by his wife, galina vishnevskaya, and stephen paulus' ``the postman always rings twice,'' a 1982 musical adaptation of james m. cain's depression-era novel
the cheapest seats in washington will sell for $20 in the kennedy center's eisenhower theater, where smaller operas are staged, and standing room remains $10. students and senior citizens can still buy half-price tickets
feinstein blamed the increase on mounting production costs and a 50 percent decline in the value of the dollar abroad in the past three years, which makes it more expensive to hire domingo and other foreign singers
the budget squeeze also forced feinstein to reduce the number of performances from 66 to 48 next season and to present seven instead of the current eight operas
president reagan was asked tuesday to meet with the nation's civil rights leaders, who are trying to prevent a veto of legislation to restore full anti-discrimination protection to women, minorities, the handicapped and the elderly
the request came in a letter from the chairman and executive director of the leadership conference on civil rights, who said that reagan has rarely met with civil rights leaders during his seven years in office
now is the time for reconciliation, not for confrontation,'' said chairman benjamin l. hooks and executive director ralph g. neas, who asked for a meeting ``as soon as possible.''
the leadership conference includes all the major civil rights groups. there was no immediate white house response
reagan has threatened to veto the civil rights restoration act, which passed the house 315-98 and the senate, 75-14 _ margins large enough to override a rejection by the president
the civil rights leaders said the legislation would restore full federal civil rights protections in public and private institutions, and state and local governments receiving federal money. those protections were limited by a 1984 supreme court decision involving grove city college in pennsylvania
reagan, however, said the bill would actually expand federal jurisdiction beyond pre-grove city limits
hooks, head of the national association for the advancement of colored people, and neas, wrote reagan, ``contrary to what some have said, the restoration act is not an expansion of federal power.''
and they added, ``a presidential veto of a bill to end federal funding of discrimination would leave a terrible and lasting stain on your presidency.''
at the pike's landing bar, the regulars have a curious way of telling spring is near _ they wait for the first truck or car to break through the ice of the chena river
gary halmstad earned that dubious distinction monday. his 1979 van broke through 8 inches of ice as he started across an ice bridge used as a winter shortcut by many residents
i hate being this kind of harbinger of spring,'' he said
the ice cracked between the front and back tires, and he summoned a small wrecker to pull him off. instead, the tow truck pulled the front tires off a supporting shelf of ice, and the front of the van plunged into about 5 feet of water. he planned to call a larger wrecker to pull the van out the rest of the way
i'm glad it wasn't in the middle,'' he said. ``i suppose i should giggle. all i have to do is pay money for a tow truck and drain the engine.''
