several california lawmakers are trying not to be spineless as they defend their decision to make the banana slug the official state mollusk
the state governmental orginization committee on tuesday endured slimy jabs about the slug, including comparisons to its garlicky cousin, escargot, before sliding the bill out of committee on a 12-2 vote
the legislation, authored by democratic assemblyman byron sher, now inches onto the assembly floor
sher introduced the bill at the urging of the dynamite blue bird troop of redwood city. six members of the inveterate invertebrate supporters testified before the committee and brought along six banana slugs
the state has several official mascots, such as the california gray whale as the marine mammal and the california dog-faced butterful as the state insect. but it has no mollusk, which is a large phylum of invertebrate animals that includes octopi, abalone, mussels, snails and slugs
blue bird susanna farley said the banana slug should be the state mollusk because ``they're native to the west coast and live in redwood forests, which is the state tree, and also they eat poison oak and that's very helpful.''
can we make escargot out of them?'' inquired assemblyman curtis tucker
i have no inherent objection to the state mollusk being such a useful, slimy, oozy thing,'' said assemblyman nolan frizzelle
assemblyman trice harvey tried unsuccessfully to make the state mollusk the abalone, saying they taste better and are not ``yucky yellow creatures that hide out in the mountains.'' two missiles fired at isfahan. pick up 5th graf: tehran radio...</note>
iran and iraq fired missiles at each other's cities tuesday and the iraqis said their warplanes raided an iranian oil tanker. it was the first reported attack on persian gulf shipping in weeks
iran claimed either the united states or france had helped iraq modify soviet-built missiles so they could reach tehran for the first time since the war began in september 1980
the united states greeted with skepticism a surprise call by the soviet union for the u.n. security council to condemn the ``war of the cities.''
iraq said it fired two surface-to-surface rockets at isfahan in central iran in the first missile attack on that city in the nine-day-old missile duel. it said three missiles were fired into tehran and one at the holy city of qom
tehran radio said 12 civilians were killed when the missiles struck residential areas in the three cities, damaging houses, shops and a medical center
iraq has reported hitting tehran with 43 missiles since feb. 29 and iran says it has fired 23 into baghdad
iran said it fired a missile tuesday into amarah, an iraqi town halfway between baghdad and the southern port of basra, and two at mosul, an important northern oil center. iraq reported casualties but did not specify how many
iran has said 134 people have been killed and more than 300 wounded in the latest round of the ``war of the cities.'' iraq says there have been many civilian casualties, but has not mentioned figures
a dispatch from the official iraqi news agency said warplanes raided a ``very large naval target'' off iran. the phrase usually means an iranian supertanker
maritime sources said they had no information about the raid, which would be the first confirmed attack on a commercial ship in the gulf since feb. 12. more than 400 have been hit in the 7{ years of war
hashemi rafsanjani, speaker of iran's parliament, said the missiles being fired by iraq are soviet-made scud-bs, which previously have been used against iranian border cities
in order to increase the range of the missiles, they have been clumsily tampered with,'' he said. ``there is no doubt that the major powers did this, such as america or france.''
rafsanjani said iranian military experts had examined several unexploded missiles and concluded ``that although such missiles were originally made in russia, most of the eastern bloc countries manufacture or assemble this missile today, and iraq can obtain it from other sources.''
western military experts have said the missiles are scud-bs fitted with strap-on boosters enabling them to reach tehran and qom, which are nearly 300 miles from the border
the missile normally carries a 1,000-pound warhead and has a range of 190 miles. western experts say iran also uses scud-bs, supplied by its arab allies syria and libya, but it does not need boosters because baghdad is only 80 miles from the frontier
at the united nations in new york, soviet ambassador alexander m. belonogov told reporters monday the security council must act to prevent ``further escalation of the military conflict,'' but evaded a question about whether the kremlin would approve an arms embargo
u.s. ambassador herbert okun said a soviet resolution on the ``war of the cities'' should not ``undercut or erode'' council resolution 598 of july 20, which demanded an immediate cease-fire. throughout</note>
gallaudet university students on tuesday boycotted classes to protest the hiring of a hearing woman as the school for the deaf's next president, while a faculty leader said a growing number of instructors favor a deaf leader
the boycott of classes highlighted a second consecutive day of stormy protest over the hiring of elisabeth ann zinser, an administrator with the university of north carolina at greensboro who prevailed over two deaf finalists
at an afternoon rally at the school's football field, students burned effigies of zinser and board of trustees chairwoman jane bassett spilman. more than 1,500 students roared their approval in strong voices and flashing fingers
the rally highlighted a day in which most of the school's 1,800 undergraduate and graduate students skipped classes, and nearly a third of the school's 274 full-time professors did not show up to teach
i'm missing an art history test today, and my grades will probably be hurt,'' said 26-year-old eric spanbauer, a sophomore government major from decatur, ill. ``i'm not going to let my deaf rights get hurt. i've been waiting too long. this is our time.''
psychology professor neil reynolds, who chairs the school's 21-member faculty senate and a larger group that includes all the university's faculty, said a growing number of instructors are advocating a deaf president
there has been in the past week an escalation of overt support from faculty members for a deaf president,'' said reynolds. ``that is definitely a change.''
both the faculty senate and the larger group of instructors will meet wednesday to discuss the ongoing controversy, said reynolds
about 30 percent of gallaudet's professors are deaf, while nearly 22 percent of the school's support staff is deaf, according to university publicist barbara dennis
students took heart from the support from their mentors, and were cheered to know that alumni of the nation's only liberal arts college for the deaf were standing by them
the alumni sympathize with and support the students,'' gerald burstein, president of the school's alumni association, said at an afternoon rally. ``we _ unlike hearing members on the board _ know fully what it is like to be deaf. those members of the board who lack confidence in the abilities of deaf persons ... should resign.''
off-campus groups have also rallied behind the students
fred weiner, a washington spokesman for the national association of the deaf, said state leaders from his 20,000 member organization were planning to meet in washington on friday to discuss ways of helping students gain a deaf president
students say they will not stop their protest until zinser is replaced with a deaf president, spilman is replaced, and the university agrees to make deaf persons a majority on the school's 20-member board of trustees. the board now has just four deaf members
spilman said tuesday that the board will stand by its decision to hire zinser, vice chancellor of academic affairs at greensboro
it was not the intention of the board of trustees to create turmoil on campus,'' spilman said in a telephone interview. ``it was a vote cast in the best interests of the university, and elisabeth ann zinser was selected for one and only one reason _ she was the most qualified person.'' gm comment</note>
three federal appellate judges tuesday upheld a lower court's finding that there was no evidence general motors corp. knowingly sold 1.1 million 1980 x-cars with alleged brake defects
the panel of the u.s. circuit court of appeals in washington affirmed u.s. district judge thomas penfield jackson's 1987 rejection of government claims that the cars had an inherent defect that caused rear brakes to lock up prematurely and spin out of control under certain circumstances
jackson had ruled against the national highway traffic safety administration, which had sought to fine gm $4 million and order a complete recall of the 1.1 million 1980 models of chevrolet citation, pontiac phoenix, buick skylark and oldsmobile omega
the suit was filed in 1983 after the agency received more than 4,000 complaints from drivers that the cars spun out of control after the brakes had locked. without conceding there was a defect, gm had previously agreed to two recalls, which the government said were inadequate to deal with the problem
in its ruling tuesday, the appeals court rejected the government's argument that jackson had improperly rejected the testimony of drivers who said they believed the skidding was caused by defective brakes
we agree with the district court that the drivers were in no position to know if the rear-wheel lockup was, in fact, premature in view of the particular breaking application and driving parameters involved in each incident,'' the panel said in an opinion by circuit judge kenneth starr
drivers cannot assess with reasonable accuracy the external variables that may contribute to a skid, no matter how rich their experience or concentrated their attention may be,'' the court said
gm, in a statement released in detroit, said, ``today's decision more than justifies our determination to stay the course and defend the 1980 x-car through long and costly and highly-publicized litigation.''
the appeals court has given added assurance to the owners of 1980 and later models of the x-car that they may drive those cars with confidence,'' it said
the government did not have any immediate reaction to tuesday's ruling
in his opinion last april, jackson concluded that ``there is simply no engineering evidence of any peculiar property of the x-car generally that renders them in any way exceptional insofar as having a predisposition to yaw (turn).''
the appeals court panel also rejected the government's argument that jackson improperly considered gm test data that was taken after the case was filed
the government contended the test data was based on an insufficient sample of x-cars and ``peer cars'' that had similar brakes. this data demonstrated that x-cars were no more likely to skid than similar vehicles. it also showed that skidding of x-cars was not caused by a brake malfunction
it would have been odd for the district court to have dismissed all this data as irrelevant in assessing the probabilities that the vehicle, rather than other factors, was responsible for the mishaps,'' starr wrote in an opinion that was joined by judges harry t. edwards and douglas h. ginsburg
starr noted that ``over 300 x-cars, including 71 that had been the subject of consumer complaints, and 528 peer cars were run through the testing gauntlet. those impressive numbers stand in rebuke to the government's claim that an insufficient sample was used.'' assets, suit also filed in boston. picks up 7th graf pvs, `the suit...'.</note>
a federal judge temporarily froze panamanian assets in banks here after a suit was filed tuesday to prevent the government of strongman gen. manuel antonio noriega from withdrawing any funds
a similar order was issued last week in new york city, and a suit was filed tuesday in boston as well. a hearing in the boston suit was set for friday
the miami suit lists the republic of panama as the plaintiff and was set in motion by panama's u.s. ambassador juan b. sosa, who has refused to recognize the noriega government
the money at issue is ``a substantial amount,'' said sosa's attorney, mark a. cohen. but he refused to give a figure
u.s. district judge sidney arononvitz issued a temporary restraining issue late tuesday afternoon preventing the defendant banks from turning over any funds to noriega or his government's agencies. the judge scheduled a hearing on the order for 1:30 p.m. wednesday
defendants in the miami suit were the citizens and southern international bank, republic national bank of miami, barnett bank of florida and the boston-based bank of new england's international branch in miami
the suit says noriega, under indictment for drug smuggling in miami and tampa, illegally dismissed panama's legal president eric arturo delvalle on feb. 25
the suit states that delvalle consitutes the ``only lawful government of the republic of panama and that gen. noriega's regime is illegal.''
it said only sosa is authorized to withdraw money from the bank accounts, and seeks an injunction preventing the banks from making payments without his approval. confirmation, new details. corrects spelling of resistance. no pickup</note>
security forces crushed an attempted coup tuesday on sao tome and principe and killed two of the 40 armed raiders who landed in canoes in the marxist-ruled west african nation, a government official said
information ministry official joao carlos said most of the attackers were captured as they tried to seize national police headquarters on the coast of the former portuguese colony
one policeman was wounded and security forces were combing coastal areas for attackers still on the loose, portuguese radio reported from sao tome
carlos, speaking in a telephone interview with portuguese television, said forces loyal to the marxist government of president manuel pinto da costa were securing key facilities, including broadcasting stations and the airport
sao tome and principe lies about 125 miles off the west coast of gabon in the gulf of guinea. the two-island country, with a population of 110,000, has one political party, the sao tome e principe liberation movement
the portuguese radio report said the raiders boarded canoes from a larger craft that anchored offshore
president da costa appealed tuesday night for vigilance against attacks in a two-minute broadcast on national radio after an emergency cabinet meeting, reports said. he said calm was restored within hours of the landings on two beaches between 3 and 4 a.m
da costa blamed the attack on government foes linked to the national resistance front of sao tome and principe. portuguese tv said the raiders were suspected of launching the attack from gabon, where the front is based
the front's lisbon-based secretary-general, quintiliano loures amadao, denied it was responsible
he said the attack may have been carried out by dissidents within the front, or members of the sao tome and pricipe armed forces unhappy over the presence there of angolan troops
the two islands lie on strategic atlantic shipping lanes. news reports in 1984 said about 2,000 soviet and cuban troops ran two radio stations and a submarine facility in the area
rumors of an imminent invasion swept sao tome and principe in 1978 and cuba, angola and guinea-bissau sent troops to help defend the islands
the invasion never materialized, but the country has since strengthened its ties with angola, cuba and the soviet union. an estimated 1,000 angolan troops are stationed in sao tome and principe to support the regular army
the force supposed to be behind the invasion never was clear
the ruling party has not previously faced armed opposition. loures amadao said the resistance front supported peaceful dialogue with the government because it was in no position to engage in an armed struggle for power. plan</head>
secretary of state george shultz told a senior israeli envoy tuesday that he would reject any attempt by prime minister yitzhak shamir to postpone a response to his mideast peace plan, an israeli source said
shultz met for an hour with israel's former ambassador to washington, moshe arens, a close shamir confidante, said the source, who spoke on condition he not be identified by name. the state department confirmed the meeting took place but declined to comment further
arens asked for the meeting following a letter sent last week by 30 senators to shultz urging that shamir cede israeli-occupied lands in return for peace with the arabs
the letter by some of israel's staunchest supporters on capitol hill caused consternation in jerusalem, which is unused to such censure from congress. shamir is expected to face heavy pressure from congress when he comes here for a four-day visit next week
shultz told arens that ``he sees no good reason why shamir cannot come here with an answer'' to the u.s. proposal which calls for negotiations on a three-year period of palestinian self-rule to be followed by talks on a permanent solution for the occupied west bank and gaza strip, said the source
shamir on sunday blocked a cabinet debate on the proposal, which shultz presented during a shuttle diplomacy swing through the region last week, but said he would bring the subject up for a decision after he returns from washington. shultz asked both israel and jordan for an answer within 10 days
israeli news reports say shamir will make shultz a counterproposal which will include self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinians under israeli control but will not address the question of the future of the territories
shamir and his right-wing likud bloc are opposed to a land-for-peace formula
the white house on monday welcomed the senators' call for shamir to give up arab lands, but the state department has not responded publicly. shultz is expected to answer the senators, possibly later this week
shultz told arens that ``israel can't afford to delay,'' especially in view of the growing congressional and public pressure for negotiations to resolve the israeli-palestinian violence which has resulted in the killing of some 80 arabs by israeli troops over the past three months
meanwhile, sen. chic hecht of nevada and several of his fellow republicans were working on a letter or statement in response to last week's letter to shultz. hecht, as well as sens. jesse helms of north carolina and arlen specter of pennsylvania, are opposed to what they view as internal interference in israeli politics
an organization formed to advise president reagan on jewish matters lashed out tuesday at 30 senators who wrote a letter supporting the administration's position that it is time for israel to exchange land for peace
the group, known as the national jewish coalition, said the senators ``operated in haste'' and were ``inserting themselves into the internal politics of israel.''
the group issued its statement after a meeting in the oval office with reagan. however, richard fox, the chairman of the organization, said the president did not discuss the peace process or the violence in the israeli-occupied territories
he said the meeting with reagan lasted only 12 or 13 minutes and the president's comments were ``really more of a ceremonial statement. there was no forum for discussion of the issue.''
the coalition, formed after the 1984 election, comprises jewish republicans
on monday, the white house had said it welcomed the senators' statement, in which they criticized israeli prime minister yitzhak shamir and his likud party, suggesting they may be blocking efforts to reach a peace settlement in the middle east
asked about that letter, fox said, ``our belief is that those distinguished senators _ all of whom are friends of israel _ operated in haste.''
he complained that they based their criticism on a report in the new york times ``rather than direct statements from the prime minister.'' the letter had said the senators were dismayed to read in the newspaper that shamir had opposed giving up any territory, saying, ``this expression of territory for peace is not accepted by me.''
fox said the senators ``are dealing in an area which is very sensitive at this time and essentially inserting themselves into the internal politics of israel
there is obviously a debate going on between the two political parties in israel as to what their position should be and i think the best thing that we who are concerned and interested can do is to hopefully let the israelis develop their own position.''
he also said the organization was supportive of the middle east peace approach taken by secretary of state george p. shultz, but said much of details remain to be defined
construction has begun at an abandoned strategic air command base near ben guerir, morocco, to create an emergency landing site for space shuttles when they begin flying again, the national aeronautics and space administration said tuesday
the former sac base has a 14,000 foot runway, but its surface must be rejuvenated to make it usable by shuttles that for some reason they fail to reach the speeds necessary to get into orbit
the ben guerir base, 40 miles north of marrakech will be the fourth emergency site. nasa announced earlier in the week that another airport site in northwest africa, in the tiny country of the gambia, will be upgraded to accommodate shuttles. the space agency intends to continue using runways at zaragoza air base and moron air base in spain
foundations for shuttle approach and landing aids are being laid at the new sites and other equipment, including 10 personnel vehicles, will be shipped
a cold air mass moving across the nation's midsection produced rain and thunderstorms from michigan to texas on tuesday, while most of the east enjoyed springlike weather
up to an inch of rain was reported across parts of northeast texas, northwestern louisiana and southwestern arkansas. half-inch hail fell at killeen, texas. lake charles, la., got three-quarters of an inch of rain in an hour early tuesday morning
high wind buffeted the high plains and northern rockies, with gusts of 61 mph at brookings, s.d., 53 mph at mitchell, s.d., and 50 mph at cheyenne, wyo
falling snow reduced visibility to a mile or less from northeast minnesota into eastern south dakota
up to four inches of snow was reported across southern and eastern south dakota. huron, s.d., received an inch of new snow the 6 hours ending at 1 p.m. est
rainshowers were scattered across the pacific northwest
heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. est included 1.38 inches at lake charles, la.; 0.97 inch at jonesboro, ark.; 0.96 inch at leesville, la.; 0.94 inch at hot springs, ark.; 0.70 inch at little rock, ark.; 0.61 inch at killeen, texas; 0.51 inch at lafayette, la.; 0.45 inch at alexandria, la.; and 0.41 inch at marquette, mich
springlike weather ruled much of the eastern third of the nation. skies were mostly sunny across the ohio valley and middle-atlantic region into new england
temperatures at 2 p.m. est ranged from 21 degrees at yellowstone park, wyo., to 89 degrees at mcallen, texas. the morning low was 15 degrees below zero at gunnison, colo
wednesday's forecast called for rain showers from central and southern new england through the lower great lakes, the ohio and tennessee valleys into the atlantic coast and in the northern plateau, western washington and northwestern oregon; showers and thunderstorms across much of the south from the lower mississippi valley into the southern atlantic; rain and snow showers across eastern upper michigan, turning to snow late in the day; and gusty winds across the northern rockies
high temperatures were expected to reach the 30s across the northern great lakes; the upper 20s and 30s across northern maine; the 40s from northern washington into western montana and from the eastern dakotas into southern new england; the 70s across southern california and arizona, the central gulf coast and the southern atlantic coast; the low 80s across much of florida and the desert southwest; and the 50s and 60s elsewhere. documents</head>
attorneys for lyndon larouche, six followers and five larouche political groups battled the government tuesday for access to classified fbi information concerning larouche and key players in the iran-contra scandal
several of the defense lawyers sought to dismiss the case after being denied immediate access to the information, but u.s. district judge robert e. keeton deferred ruling on the requests until after questions over access to the fbi files are resolved
defense attorneys, at hearings outside the presence of the jury, have presented evidence in recent weeks of fbi infiltration of larouche organizations
they also have gained access to a one-page memo from retired air force maj. gen. richard secord to marine lt. col. oliver north, the former national security council aide, in which secord reports ``our man here claims lewis has collected info against larouche.'' lewis was not further identified
the memo, found in north's safe after he was fired because of his role in the iran-contra affair, was surrendered to larouche defense lawyers after the special prosecutor investigating the scandal acknowledged its existence
secord, reached tuesday in washington, said he could not recall the memo and said he never had crossed paths with larouche. secord was one of north's principal operatives in his network of private aid to the contras
defense lawyers have said they will prove the reagan administration plotted to ruin larouche because he refused to support reagan's programs to aid nicaragua's contra rebels. they also argue that the government has improperly withheld evidence that could prove their case, which could be grounds for dismissal of the charges
they contend that north directed the fbi to gather information against larouche and infiltrate his organizations as part of a larger fbi surveillance of groups opposed to the administration's central american policies
larouche, the aides and organizations all are charged with conspiring to cover up alleged credit card fraud by larouche supporters during his 1984 presidential campaign. four of the organizations are charged with fraud. larouche is seeking the 1988 democratic presidential nomination, his fourth run for the white house. he faces up to five years in prison if convicted
prosecutors throughout the trial and pretrial hearings denied defense contentions that the government inflitrated larouche's organzations and concocted a credit card fraud and cover-up scheme to destroy larouche and his following
after learning of the may 1986 secord-north memo, defense lawyer michael reilly requested any information the government had about larouche and lewis that might be favorable to defense claims
the prosecutor in the case, assistant u.s. attorney john markham, surrendered documents from fbi files to reilly, but the fbi later told markham that he was not supposed to release the material
other defense attorneys now want copies of the documents, but the fbi opposed the request on grounds the records are classified. reilly, who represents just one of the five larouche organizations that are defendants, has said he cannot give the documents to his fellow defense lawyers because of federal rules on classified information
markham, as the government attorney in the case, normally would argue the fbi's position. but he refused to do so tuesday, saying there was a conflict of interest between the fbi's stance and his role as prosecutor of the case. he did not elaborate, but said the conflict would be resolved before the wednesday hearing on access to the records
keeton also told markham he wants an explanation as to why defense lawyers, through freedom of information act requests, have learned of the existence of thousands of other fbi documents mentioning larouche that were not turned over to defense lawyers before the trial
i've got to have some explanation from the government about how the documents are discoverable through foia requests and not by the prosecution,'' the judge said
after the questions over access to the records are resolved, defense lawyers have said they will renew their motions for dismissal of the case or a mistrial on grounds their opening statements and cross-examination strategies would have been different if they had reviewed the documents prior to trial
the governing christian democratic party on tuesday withdrew the candidacy for the national legislature of a member under investigation for alleged misuse of u.s. aid funds
rodolfo castillo claramount, vice president of the party, appeared before the central elections council to remove luis mejia miranda as a candidate for the national assembly in elections march 20
mejia is going to have support in order to clear up his personal situation, but we don't want the application of justice to be blurred if he is elected and possesses (legislative) immunity,'' castillo told reporters
assembly members have a degree of immunity from prosecution under salvadoran law
castillo called on the public prosecutor's office to conduct a thorough investigation of the allegations against mejia, which were reported sunday by the new york times
the newspaper said mejia is being investigated for allegedly misusing up to $2 million of u.s. aid
it quoted unidentified salvadoran and u.s. officials as saying it could be the largest case of theft of american aid money during the administration of president jose napoleon duarte, who was elected for a five-year term in may 1984
mejia on monday denied the allegations and said, ``can you imagine that if i had ($2 million) i would still be in this country?''
the new york times also said duarte's son alejandro, who is running for mayor of san salvador, was trying to protect mejia
alejandro duarte on monday denied having ties to mejia
according to the new york times, the money allegedly stolen was part of a $10 million program to assist war-ravaged areas and help win the support of salvadorans in the war against leftist rebels
it said mejia resigned three months ago as director of the national commission for the restoration of areas, but president duarte agreed to allow him to become a party candidate for the national assembly on the recommendation of alejandro duarte. involved in consulate assault, none of them embassy workers, britons charged.</note>
britain's foreign office summoned panama's ambassador tuesday after he hired a british security firm to seize the panamanian consulate from diplomats opposed to gen. manuel antonio noriega
the assault, in which seven men from the security firm used a land rover to smash through the glass doors of the consulate monday night, was condemned by prime minister margaret thatcher
differences of opinion should not be fought out on london streets,'' she told parliament
the foreign office said undersecretary tim eggar and panamanian ambassador guillermo vega ``had a full discussion of the incident and the background to it.'' it said foreign secretary sir geoffrey howe ``is now considering what the ambassador said.'' it did not elaborate
police announced tuesday night that the seven security men, all britons, had been charged with offenses against public order
consul eduardo arango and his staff had remained loyal to deposed panamanian president eric delvalle, who was ousted feb. 26 after he tried to fire noriega, the military chief and power behind panama's government
arango, who was not in the consulate at the time of the takeover, had been fired by panama's new government but refused to leave his post, saying delvalle was the legitimate president
it was ``a thuggish way of behaving and an unbelievable way of doing things in a civilized country,'' arango told a british broadcasting corp. television interviewer
vega, loyal to noriega, told reporters that the assailants had his authority and were ordered into the consulate ``because this place was full of outsiders to the panama government.''
police said seven men forced their way into the consulate and that six remained to occupy the offices. they said no one was injured
the seven security employees were questioned by police and after being charged they were released on an undisclosed amount of bail for an april 6 court hearing
police identified them as michael lord, 35, a security officer; james brown, 30, a company executive; robert green, 34, a security consultant; electricians thomas anderson, 34, joseph anderson, 39, and kenneth ford, 38, and construction worker kevin noble, 26. they worked for gb security
noriega was indicted in florida last month on drug trafficking charges and the reagan administration is pressing for his resignation. pickup.</note>
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. and vice president george bush cashed in on endorsements from kentucky politicians to easily win the state's democratic and republican primaries tuesday
gore, running in his neighboring state, defeated massachusetts gov. michael dukakis in the democratic race by 45,593 votes or 39 percent to dukakis' 26,902 votes or 23 percent, with 1,151 of 3,243 precincts or 35 percent reporting
jesse jackson was third with 20,509 votes or 18 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 10,628 votes or 9 percent; former colorado sen. gary hart had 4,363 votes or 4 percent; and illinois sen. paul simon finished with 2,734 votes or 2 percent
in the republican primary, with 1,384 of 3,237 precincts or 43 percent reporting, bush soundly defeated kansas sen. bob dole by 36,887 votes or 58 percent to dole's 14,731 votes or 23 percent
former television evangelist pat robertson was next with 7,287 votes or 11 percent; new york rep. jack kemp had 2,278 votes or 4 percent; and former delaware gov. pete du pont finished with 339 votes or 1 percent
at stake were 55 democratic and 38 gop delegates
gore won a battle with dukakis for the support of gov. wallace wilkinson, who decided to go with a neighboring son of the south
he's one of us,'' wilkinson said
but dukakis wasn't giving up. he began running tv ads on friday and paid his first visit of the year to the state _ in louisville on sunday _ wooing undecided voters
bush had the support of sen. mitch mcconnell, a national campaign co-chairman, and the two gop representatives who endorsed
in a late february poll conducted by the louisville courier-journal, gore was the choice of 28 percent of democrats while dukakis was the favorite of 20 percent. hart was third with 10 percent while gephardt, jackson and simon were all in single digits. undecided voters accounted for 23 percent
the poll found bush preferred by 51 percent of likely gop voters. dole was the choice of 28 percent. undecided voters made up the third largest segment at 11 percent. robertson and kemp split the rest. on motive</head> `made your point,' cuts off further evidence on witness' motive. picks up 3rd graf pvs, `the 63-year-old...'. subs 11th graf pvs, `as craft...', to delete now-redundant first reference to gordon. may stand for ams.</note>
the judge presiding over gov. evan mecham's impeachment trial told mecham's lawyer tuesday that he had showed that the state's top lawman ``had a motive to testify against the governor'' and ordered him to move on to other topics
arizona supreme court justice frank x. gordon, who earlier fielded objections to questions focusing on the witness' sex life, said he would allow no further testimony on the personal life or motives of department of public safety director ralph milstead, a key witness against mecham on an obstruction of justice charge
you have made your point,'' gordon told attorney fred craft as he concluded a two-day cross-examination of milstead
you have established that director milstead had a motive for testifying against the governor,'' said gordon, ``that he had a high-paying job with more than a modicum of influence and with a number of perks.''
he said it was clear that mecham had planned to fire milstead and, ``presumably col. milstead wants to keep his job.''
but he said further evidence on the subject would be cumulative and time-consuming
he noted that the senate impeachment court could overrule his decision. but senators, who protested the slow pace of testimony was costing taxpayers $20,000 a day, went along with gordon
his ruling derailed an announced defense plan to call a parade or witnesses to challenge milstead's crediblity
this witness is the accuser of the governor ...,'' attorney jerris leonard told the senate shortly before gordon's announcement. ``what we are doing is asking questions to lay the foundation for future witnesses to impeach his credibility.''
prosecutor paul eckstein told reporters outside the hearing room that the judge's ruling will bar the defense from calling to the stand a woman who the defense claims was milstead's paramour
craft's questioning drew repeated protests from the prosecutors that he was using innuendo to delve into the sex life of milstead. the subject was ruled off-limits by gordon earlier
the 63-year-old governor, who has not attended any sessions of the impeachment trial since it began last week, is accused of ordering milstead not to help the attorney general investigate an alleged death threat to a grand jury witness by a mecham aide
the governor has acknowledged he may have given such instructions to milstead but says he was not fully informed about the situation. and milstead has said he cooperated with the attorney general's office
craft was interrupted several times by objections from house prosector william french as craft tried to delve into the relationship between milstead and a one-time dps informant christina juell johnston
milstead said they had a professional relationship, adding, ``i counted her as a friend.''
but he denied he escorted her on dates in his state vehicle or paid for her meals out of state funds
craft previously had asked, ``did you ever travel to mrs. christina juell johnston's home in your state vehicle?''
i believe i did, yes,'' said milstead
did you ever stay overnight at mrs. christina juell johnston's home with your state vehicle?'' asked craft. ``no, i did not,'' said milstead
as craft continued to pose questions about the relationship, asking if milstead paid for her meals at restaurants, french arose and addressed gordon
mr. presiding officer, this is cross-examination by innuendo. it's improper,'' said french
gordon noted that he had ruled out questions about milstead's alleged sexual affair as irrelevant. milstead, who is now divorced, was married at the time of the alleged affair, while mrs. johnston was single
but craft insisted he was merely seeking information about possible misuse by milstead of a state vehicle or possible improper listing of meals on his expense account, and gordon permitted the questions to continue
in other questioning tuesday, craft suggested that milstead purposely kept mecham in the dark about the investigation of the alleged death threat
but milstead insisted: ``the relevant information was in his hands
milstead acknowledged he never told mecham he was planning to disobey the governor's orders and take the case to the attorney general
i was in shock from his anger, ... his insistence we not cooperate'' milstead said. ``... he was not to be reasoned with
when his words were, `don't give them any help whatsoever,' i said, `ok' and that was the end of the conversation.''
asked whether mecham might have assumed that milstead was agreeing to obey his order to keep quiet, milstead said, ``he could have construed it that way, yes.''
in addition to obstructing the attorney general's investigation, mecham is accused in the impeachment trial of concealing a $350,000 campaign loan and misusing $80,000 in a state fund by loaning it to his car dealership
mecham, the first u.s. governor to face an impeachment trial in six decades, also faces a criminal trial march 22 on felony charges of concealing the campaign loan and a recall election may 17. with cotugno's version of incident, civil suit.</note>
retired investment banker arthur k. salomon admitted tuesday that he shot a college student after a traffic dispute, saying he was afraid the young man was going to attack him
salomon, 53, pleaded guilty to first-degree assault. he had been indicted on a charge of attempted murder
in return for the plea, state supreme court justice nicholas colabella indicated he would sentence salomon to two to six years in prison on april 27. salomon, grandson of one of the founders of the salomon brothers investment firm, could have received a maximum of five to 15 years in prison
salomon read a brief statement describing what happened june 19 when he shot gianluca cotugno, 19, of larchmont off the hutchinson river parkway in scarsdale, north of new york city
cotugno, who was hospitalized several weeks with a gunshot wound to the stomach, was not in court
salomon said he was heading south on the parkway from his pound ridge home to his manhattan apartment when a white honda began to tailgate him. the driver flashed his lights and ``attempted to run my car off the road,'' salomon said
salomon pulled off at an exit, and stopped his 1977 mercedes-benz. the honda also pulled off, salomon said, and the driver got out of the car
a tall, slim white male was moving rapidly toward my car, waving his arms in a threatening manner and shouting,'' salomon said. ``i believed at that time that this individual was going to attack me.''
the other man was unarmed, salomon said
salomon said he reached for a loaded .38-caliber colt revolver in the car
by then, the man was ``standing adjacent to the passenger door of my car. he was leaning over my car, making threatening motions with his hands. i believe he was going to attack me,'' salomon said. ``knowing that the revolver was loaded, i discharged it in the direction of the individual.''
salomon said that when he realized he had hit the man, ``i panicked and drove away.''
salomon, who had licenses for the colt and another gun, surrendered to authorities several hours later
cotugno told authorities that salomon was traveling slowly in the left lane and, despite his flashing his lights, salomon would not move to the right lane so that he could pass
salomon pulled over, waving for cotugno to do the same, cotugno said
cotugno said that when he approached salomon's car, he spotted the gun and told salomon he was going to get the car's license plate and call police. the shooting occurred after cotugno had started to walk back to his car
a $15 million civil suit cotungo filed against salomon is pending
divine, the bizarre female impersonator who starred in such films as ``pink flamingos'' and ``hairspray,'' was remembered tuesday by john waters, director of the two movies, as ``a kind and gentle man.''
divine is as irreplaceable to me as a member of my own family,'' waters said, reading haltingly from a statment at a baltimore hotel. ``i'll miss him incredibly.''
not only did i respect him as the best actor i've ever worked with, i knew him personally as a kind and gentle man,'' waters said
the 42-year-old actor, whose real name was harris glenn milstead, was found dead in his bed monday at the hollywood regency plaza hotel. waters said he was told divine was found under the covers ``with a smile on his face.''
a preliminary coroner's autopsy failed to pinpoint a cause of death, and a microscopic examination of tissue samples was ordered. preliminary tests showed no signs of trauma or any other factor that would have contributed to the actor's death, los angeles county coroner's spokesman steve stewart said tuesday
publicist john west of pmk said the actor apparently died of asphyxiation during the night. he was in town to appear in an episode of ``married ... with children,'' a fox television network series
divine normally slept upright, propped up because of his weight, said peter haas, a publicist for ``hairspray.''
divine had a long-term weight problem but was found at a medical checkup friday to be otherwise in excellent health, his manager, bernard jay, said tuesday
he was not on drugs at all, and he never drank alcohol,'' jay said. ``i suppose it all comes down to his weight. he was constantly trying to diet, but as soon as he'd take the pounds off, they'd come right back on again.''
waters was one of the actor's few friends in school in lutherville, a baltimore suburb, where milstead said he grew up fat and taunted by classmates
waters' obsession with trashy movies nearly matched milstead's fantasies of celebrity, and waters began casting his friend in bizarre roles
the most famous would be the cult film classics ``pink flamingos,'' ``lust in the dust,'' ``polyester'' and ``female trouble.''
he had been pleased over his role in ``hairspray'' as edna turnblad, the fat mother of a fat teen-age girl
he'd call me in the middle of the night to read me some newspaper interview and say, `isn't it wonderful! they called me divine, the 300-pound actor, not divine, the 300-pound transvestite,''' jay said
as divine, he wore garish makeup and was loud and foul-mouthed. ``she's her own person and a lot of people like that,'' he once said. ``the camp element is something out of the ordinary, this big man playing a sexy woman.''
milstead played a non-transvestite role, that of a sydney greenstreet-type character, in the 1985 film ``trouble in mind.''
besides film roles, milstead used the divine persona in a nightclub act
waters said that the last time he had spoken to divine was two days ago and that he had last seen him at the premiere of ``hairspray'' in new york city
in their last conversations, waters said, ``he was just so happy. he said `can you believe we came this far?''' shamir remarks on peace plan. picks up 7th graf pvs, ``the officers ... with minor editing. restores dropped words in 10th graf, ``in jericho ...</note>
arabs stabbed a man accused of aiding israel and dumped the corpse at his mother's door, and israeli gunfire killed another palestinian on tuesday, hospitals and witnesses reported
hundreds of arab women held demonstrations in the occupied territories, following a call for protests from the palestine liberation organization
hospital officials in nablus said three arab protesters were wounded by israeli gunfire, but the army said a jewish settler shot one of them after the settler's car was stoned in the balata refugee camp
residents of mazraa sharqiya said a settler shot khader mohammed hamideh, a 42-year-old businessman with seven children, outside his home. the army confirmed hamideh's death but said it was investigating the circumstances
according to u.n. figures, at least 83 palestinians have been killed by israelis since arab riots began dec. 8 in the west bank and gaza strip, which israel captured from jordan and egypt in the 1967 middle east war
prime minister yitzhak shamir indicated tuesday on israel television that he intends to debate u.s. peace proposals and to present his own plan when he visits washington next week
the u.s. plan calls for talks on a three-year period of palestinian autonomy in the occupied territories to be followed in december by negotiations on the permanent status of these territories
shamir said, ``this is only a proposal and we can certainly present our own proposals and make our comments.''
asked if he expects pressure in washington, the hardline prime minister replied, ``i don't expect any pressures and if there would be such they would not help.''
shamir opposes the u.s. plan because it calls for an international role in talks and because of its accelerated timetable
the daily hadashot said that shamir's plan calls for talks between u.s. and soviet representatives only. the superpowers would have a symbolic role and talks on a permanent solution would start three years after palestinian autonomy is implemented
in another development tuesday, the military command said four army officers were sentenced to 35 days in jail each for not being armed when three guerrillas commandeered their car before hijacking a bus monday
the officers were on their way to an army sporting event in track suits and fled when the guerrillas opened fire, the army said
three israeli hostages and the guerrillas were killed during the hijacking and later storming of the bus. the plo claimed responsibility.
more than 5,000 mourners attended the funerals of the slain israelis tuesday at beersheba in southern israel
in jericho, residents of the aqbat jaber refugee camp said palestinians killed an arab policeman suspected of collaborating, wrapped the body in a palestinian flag and dropped it at his mother's door
the army confirmed the body of nabil juma farah, 30, was found in the refugee camp monday night
it was the second killing of a suspected collaborator reported since violence began
police minister chaim bar-lev said he would encourage other arab policemen not to quit by raising their pay and trying to discover who killed farah
in mazraa sharqiya, 15 miles northeast of jerusalem, villagers said three israelis believed to be settlers stopped at a roadblock built of stones and trash bins and one shot hamideh, who owned a cafe and butcher shop
two of them got out and started to remove the stones. ... one of them got out and started to shoot,'' one witness said, speaking anonymously fear of reprisals
he said the settler fired at a home about 150 yards away then shot at hamideh's home next door, where the victim was standing
later tuesday, about 600 villagers chanting slogans and waving a plo flag carried hamideh's coffin through the village and buried him
associated press writer=
washington (ap) _ a week of talks between u.s. and japanese officials over participation by u.s. firms in billions of dollars worth of japanese building projects ended in failure tuesday
and, a u.s. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said president reagan under the law could retaliate against japan for what are considered unfair trade practices
that is one of the options,'' the official said, adding that the reagan administration will decide probably by the end of next week what its next step will be
the official said the u.s. side had exhausted its capacity to resolve the issues and was not ready to go on talking, given the differences between the two sides
he said the japanese, who had offered measures to allow u.s. construction firms to gain experience in japan on seven projects, wanted discussions to continue
the u.s. delegation was led by j. michael farren, deputy undersecretary of commerce for international trade. the japanese group was headed by peter sato, director general of economic affairs in the japanese foreign ministry
farren has criticized previous japanese proposals as offering american companies only limited experience, not enough to enable them to take part in normal japanese bidding on public projects
the u.s. official, as an example, cited the extension of the tokyo international airport at haneda, where he said the only opportunity offered to americans would be in ``compacting earth and laying concrete,'' and in building a monorail
the americans would not be competitive in the labor-intensive construction, he added. he said that under the japanese proposals they would not be allowed to participate in the design or engineering, nor in the building of a $900 million airport terminal
the official said the u.s. delegation also wanted the arrangements on participation by u.s. construction firms written into a formal agreement, while the japanese did not want to be bound and sought only a joint statement that unspecified arrangements were satisfactory
police used tear gas and water cannons on tuesday to scatter hundreds of demonstrators who turned an international women's day march into a protest against the military government
at dusk, police reported around 100 demonstrators detained, but reporters in santiago and other witnesses called that figure too low
demonstrators were also arrested in similar protests in valparaiso, 75 miles northwest of santiago on the pacific coast
the street protests were the first this year against the 14-year-old regime of gen. augusto pinochet
helmeted riot police in downtown santiago fought running battles for hours with protesters, most of them women
scattered repeatedly by police, the demonstrators would quickly regroup at a different intersection and renew their chanting of anti-government slogans
police used water cannons to put out flaming barricades erected by protesters
reporters saw a public bus set afire with gasoline bombs thrown by three people. the bus was destroyed, but all passengers fled without injury
the united nations declared march 8 as international women's day, but chile's government said leftist groups turned the day into a ``marxist event.''
tuesday's march was called by women's organizations and dissident groups
jesse jackson muscled out tennessee sen. albert gore jr. to win virginia's first presidential primary tuesday, while vice president george bush overwhelmed kansas sen. bob dole
in the democratic race, with 434 of 1,986 precincts or 22 percent reporting: jackson had 35,123 votes or 46 percent; gore had 18,797 votes or 25 percent; and massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 14,743 votes or 19 percent
missouri rep. richard gephardt had 2,981 votes or 4 percent; former colorado sen. gary hart had 1,412 votes or 2 percent, and illinois sen. paul simon had 1,121 votes or 1 percent
in the republican race, with 432 of 1,986 precincts or 22 percent reporting: bush had 26,737 votes or 52 percent; dole had 12,009 votes or 23 percent; and virginia native pat robertson had 8,908 votes or 17 percent, and new york rep. jack kemp had 1,978 votes or 4 percent
the democrats were awarding 75 of virginia's 84 national convention delegates. no republican delegates were at stake after the virginia gop's central committee decided against a binding vote
virginia's 50 republican national convention delegates will be chosen at district and state conventions based on the outcome of local gop mass meetings and caucuses being held over the next two months, and robertson's supporters are expected to dominate those events
two weeks ago, backers of the former television evangelist from virginia beach overthrew long-time party activists in newport news by taking delegate seats to the district convention
an austrian foreign ministry official said tuesday that president kurt waldheim has accepted an invitation to visit kuwait and that austria would not bow to ``zionist threats,'' a news agency reported
the official kuwait news agency quoted ministry general secretary thomas klestil as telling it that waldheim received the invitation from the emir, sheik jaber al-ahmed al-sabah, ``with all appreciation and welcome'' and would visit ``at the earliest convenient time.''
it would be waldheim's second visit to an arab country following the world furor raised over his service in the german army during world war ii
kuna quoted klestil as saying that austria ``will not succumb to zionist threats and pressures to remove president kurt waldheim from his office.''
klestil is on a tour of persian gulf arab nations following a visit by iran's foreign minister, ali akbar velayati, to vienna, austria's capital
kuwait and neighboring noncombatant states are pressing for international efforts to convince iran to end its war with iraq, now in its eighth year
waldheim has visited jordan, the vatican and pakistan since his election
a supreme court panel on tuesday rejected a challenge to censorship powers that allow a cabinet minister to close newspapers for publishing material he considered objectionable
earlier, police detained nine journalists during an anti-apartheid demonstration by about 100 black women outside the chamber of mines building
police arrived about 10 minutes after the peaceful protest began. the crowd dispersed and police began seizing journalists, including crew members of cbs and london-based world television news
world television soundman prince msuthu said police punched him
police spokesman col. frans malherbe said the nine were were taken to police headquarters but were released without charge
malherbe said emergency rules that have been in effect for nearly two years prohibit members of the media from being at the scene of unrest
the protesters, members of the federation of transvaal women, called on mining companies to oppose new government restrictions on anti-apartheid organizations. the women's federation is an affiliate of the united democratic front, one of 18 organizations covered by the ban issued feb. 24
apartheid establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national affairs and the 5 million whites control the economy and maintain separate services
the censorship ruling by the rand supreme court could lead to the closing of the weekly new nation, a newspaper published for black readers by the south african catholic bishops conference
during the hearing, home affairs minister stoffel botha said he had been ready to shut down the new nation in january. he said the paper published material that he felt promoted outlawed organizations, fanned revolt and incited hostility toward security forces
under a decree issued in august by president p.w. botha, the home affairs minister can install censors at newspapers or shut down the publications
in its challenge, the new nation said the decree was unenforceable because editors could not anticipate what the minister might consider objectionable
gabu tugwana, acting new nation editor, said in a telephone interview, ``the paper we are putting out for tomorrow could be the one before the last issue.'' he said the publishers intended to appeal the decision
new nation editor zwelakhe sisulu has been in detention without charge for more than a year
under the emergency decrees, the home minister is not required to give detailed reasons for his objections to published material
the head of the three-judge panel said in the ruling the president was ``legally correct'' to give the minister such power. this year</head>
the death of a 3-month-old boy in a home fire brought to seven the number of small children killed in residential fires this year, authorities said
n.e. wallace, an assistant city fire marshal, said the latest victim, christopher bolden, died monday in a fire apparently caused by an electrical short circuit
the boy's 6-month-old cousin, jessica baker, suffered smoke inhalation and was listed in critical condition tuesday in le bonheur children's medical center
wallace said three children from 1 to 3 years old died in residential fires in memphis last year. so far this year, seven youngsters age 6 or less have died
when the latest fire broke out, christopher was one of five children being cared for at a house by one of his aunts. the woman managed to escape from the house with three of the children, ages 21 months to 4 years, and firefighters saved jessica
the family was out front screaming that there were kids inside,'' said firefighter ron chastain. ``there was an awful lot of smoke, and as soon as we got the door open, a lot of fire shot out.'' community'</head>
pat robertson's poor showing in the super tuesday voting in the south shows that ``the traditional value community has been totally fractured,'' the chairman of christian voice said tuesday night
frankly, i'm surprised that he did not do better,'' said robert grant, who leads the largest conservative evangelical lobby in the country
in early returns, robertson did not come in better than third in any state, behind vice president george bush and sen. bob dole of kansas. he bested another conservative, rep. jack kemp of new york, however
grant said the opinion-makers on the far right of the republican party must now try to come to some consensus on who they will back
only as this community hangs together does it have any real impact,'' grant said. ``the traditional value community has been totally fractured with kemp taking a piece, robertson taking the charismatics to a degree and a large part going to dole and bush.''
he said the vice president's showing in the south ``is an indication that he may be a viable candidate for the bible belt-type vote, but he is going to have to work for it.''
however, said grant, ``the image or perception conveyed by the bush campaign has been to savage and to turn away conservative christian activities. this has not necessarily been the sentiment of the vice president but it has been the impression conveyed within his campaign and among many established republican types
if bush wishes to woo that vote, he has a good shot at it.''
a teen-ager who admitted plotting the fatal beating of a classmate in 1986 has not suffered from severe psychosis or hallucinations despite a history of behavioral problems, medical experts said tuesday
the norfolk superior court jury is expected to hear closing arguments then begin deliberations wednesday, the seventh day of the trial
rod matthews, 15, of canton is being tried as an adult for murder in the nov. 20, 1986, slaying of 14-year-old shaun ouillette, also of canton, who allegedly was lured to a wooded area by matthews and beaten with a baseball bat
matthews, who pleaded innocent by reason of insanity, said he had plotted the slaying for a month to experience what killing someone was like, according to testimony from two classmates to whom matthews showed the body
dr. michael annunziata, a court-appointed psychiatrist, told a norfolk superior court jury that matthews suffered from a ``conduct disorder'' but that he had not experienced classic symptoms of psychosis, such as hallucinations
matthews, said annunziata, had ``substantial capacity to conform his conduct to the requirement of law.''
annuziata on tuesday said the methodical planning of the killing did not indicate psychotic tendencies but suggested matthews was ``playing by different rules.''
earlier, dr. marcel kinsbourne, director of behavioral neurology at the eunice shriver center in waltham, testified that standard doses of ritalin, a drug matthews had been taking, should not trigger violent behavior
ritalin, a stimulant primarily used to control hyperactivity in children, has been a key aspect of the case
the defense had contended that matthews was a mentally ill youth from a troubled home and that his problems were exacerbated by the use of ritalin
dr. bernard yudowitz of belmont's mclean hospital said on monday that ritalin may have made it harder for matthews to control his behavior
vice president george bush cruised to an easy victory in tuesday's presidential primary, while favorite son albert gore jr. blasted past other democrats to win his home state
in the republican race, with 195 of 2,391 precincts or 8 percent reporting: bush had 10,747 votes or 61 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 3,600 votes or 20 percent; former tv evangelist pat robertson had 2,121 votes or 12 percent; and new york rep. jack kemp had 894 votes or 5 percent
in the democratic race, with 202 of 2,391 precincts or 8 percent reporting: gore had 34,449 votes or 76 percent; jesse jackson had 7,345 votes or 16 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 1,537 votes or 3 percent; and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 761 votes or 2 percent
gephardt was an early campaigner in tennessee, but since gore announced his candidacy in june, jackson has been the only other democrat to visit the state
gov. ned mcwherter, gore's southern campaign chairman, conceded that jackson was supported by most blacks, who constitute about 18 percent of the state's voters
dole and robertson targeted bush as the man to beat in tennessee. robertson was in the state three times since jan. 1 and has been represented by his wife twice. dole, who visited the state six times since last year, spoke in knoxville on march 1
robertson and bush visited upper east tennessee, republican territory, in the 10 days before the election. kemp was in knoxville on sunday, where he said he would reassess his future in the race after tuesday
gov. michael dukakis and vice president george bush romped to super tuesday victories in their home state of massachusetts, a delegate-rich field that was virtually abandoned as the candidates rushed south
in the democratic race, with 50 of 2,140 precincts or 2 percent reporting, dukakis had 6,594 votes or 60 percent; jesse jackson had 2,567 votes or 23 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 776 votes or 7 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 332 votes or 3 percent; illinois sen. paul simon had 277 votes or 3 percent
on the republican side, with 49 of 2,140 precincts or 2 percent reporting, bush had 1,690 votes or 57 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 789 votes or 27 percent; new york rep. jack kemp had 200 votes or 7 percent; and pat robertson had 148 votes or 5 percent
dukakis, the popular three-term governor of this liberal state, was a prohibitive favorite in the democratic primary, where 98 delegates were at stake, the party's third-biggest prize of the day
in the republican primary, 52 delegates were at stake, the fourth-biggest batch on super tuesday
bush carried massachusetts in the 1980 gop primary _ over ronald reagan _ and enjoys the support of many mainstream republicans. bush, who held a rally at historic faneuil hall last week, is the only republican candidate to visit the state since the new hampshire primary, although dole has sent his wife, elizabeth, for two campaign stops
in recent days, the bush and dole camps dueled with endorsements. bush was backed by former u.s. attorney general elliot richardson, dole by former sen. edward brooke
police swinging clubs dispersed hundreds of warsaw university students who marched for more academic freedom on tuesday, the anniversary of 1968 student protests
in the southern city of krakow earlier tuesday, riot police clashed repeatedly with student demonstrators and briefly detained 70-100 people, an opposition spokesman said
twenty years ago, march 8, 1968, police and communist party activists brutally attacked warsaw university students who were protesting censorship and political repression
this year's protests reflected a renewed campaign by student activists for legalization of the independent students union, or nzs. it was outlawed after the independent labor federation solidarity was suppressed with the declaratrion of martial law in december 1981
about 500 students chanting ``register nzs!'' and ``solidarity!'' and carrying banners began marching after an evening mass attended by about 2,000 people at st. anne's, a roman catholic church near warsaw university
riot police blocked the street 100 yards from the church, keeping demonstrators away from a monument to adam mickiewicz, the 19th century polish national poet
an nzs leader asked police to allow people to lay flowers at the monument. after demonstrators refused an offer to let a three-person delegation approach the monument, police charged the crowd, flailing with clubs. students fled
hundreds of people lining the sidewalk chanted ``gestapo! gestapo!'' police pushed several students and at least one middle-aged woman into vans, but how many people were detained could not be determined
at krakow's jagiellonian university, about 700 students tried to march to the main square in the city's old town and were blocked by riot police, said zygmunt lenyk, a krakow opposition activist
quoting accounts from witnesses, he said police attacked the crowd with clubs but about 50 demonstrators pushed through police lines to the square, where they were detained
lenyk said most of the students returned to campus and tried twice more to march to the square, about 500 yards away, but police attacked each time
students erected a street barricade with park benches and garbage cans but police vehicles drove through it, he reported
about 70 to 100 people were detained but police began releasing them by early afternoon, he said. lenyk reported at least three people severely beaten by police
in 1968, police and party activists went onto the warsaw university campus to beat and arrest protesters, many of whom were expelled, and a purge of reform-oriented intellectuals and jews followed. last week, the communist party said the purge was excessive
king hussein has invited yasser arafat, chairman of the palestine liberation organization, to amman to discuss the latest u.s. proposals on middle east peace, a government official said tuesday
the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the invitation ``comes within a framework of a united arab stand'' reached at the arab summit in amman last year
secretary of state george p. shultz explained the proposals on trips to the region before and after last week's nato summit in brussels
in tunis, the central committee of arafat's fatah guerrilla group said tuesday the shultz plan was ``nothing but a desperate attempt aimed at reviving the (1982) reagan initiative and imposing it on the region.''
cbs news, in a report from paris, said, ``cbs news has learned that the american ambassador to the united nations, vernon walters, met secretly with a top-ranking plo leader in tunisia last weekend. this according to senior plo officials who say the meeting took place at a private home at a seaside resort near tunis.''
plo sources say it probably had to do with how palestinians can participate in any future peace talks,'' the report said, and added walters denied he had met with the plo. ``in a statement read by a spokesman, walters said he had no authorization to meet with them and had not done so,'' cbs news said
in washington, state department spokesman charles redman said reports that walters met with plo representatives were ``absolutely untrue.''
the u.s proposals include limited self-rule for the 1.5 million palestinians living in the israeli-occupied west bank and gaza strip and an international peace conference that could include the five permanent members of the u.n. security council, israel, jordan, syria and palestinians, but not the plo
hussein and arafat decided in 1985 to take a joint approach to peace with israel, but hussein called it off in february 1986, accusing arafat of not keeping his promises
on monday, jordan's minister of information welcomed the u.s. peace effort and said the shultz proposals were being ``studied thouroughly with arab states.''
we welcome the american moves, and we believe that the american re-engagement in the peace process is positive,'' hani khasawneh told reporters
a class action suit filed on behalf of five illegal aliens tuesday challenges provisions of the government's amnesty program that would bar hundreds of aliens from obtaining legal residency
the suit, filed in u.s. district court, seeks to block u.s. immigration and naturalization service rules concerning aliens who do not meet some of the requirements for legalization but whose illegal status was ``known to the government.''
ins rules under the immigration reform and control act of 1986 provide amnesty to aliens who lived illegally in the united states before jan. 1, 1982 as well as to agricultural workers who can prove they lived in this country for at least 90 days in the year ended may 1, 1986
a problem has arisen over individuals who arrived legally _ with a visa _ but who remained in the country illegally after the jan. 1, 1982 cutoff date, according to debbi sanders of the washington lawyers committee for civil rights, one of the attorneys for the plantiffs
in cases like these, the statute grants amnesty to those whose illegal status was ``known to the government.''
volunteer agencies helping illegal aliens have sought to use social security and internal revenue service forms to prove that aliens in this category were known
the ins, however, maintained that ``known to the government'' meant known to the ins, sanders said, noting that this difference of interpretation disqualified hundreds of illegals
intrepretation of those four words is the basis for the suit filed by the lawyers' committee, the new york american civil liberties union, the hispanic national bar association and a washington law firm
it if filed on behalf of five unidentified aliens and four volunteer agencies: ayunda inc., the ethopian community center, the latin american youth center and the mexican american legal defense and educational fund
i think the government has taken too narrow of view of what the statute calls for,'' said doris meissener, acting immigration commissioner 1981-82. ``it is quite clear that the government is much more than ins.''
ins spokesman duke austin said, ``basically `known to the government,' means known to us ... and known that there was an illegal status.''
troops took over plants of the state petroleum company tuesday and arrested labor leaders in response to a strike that threatens to paralyze transportation and the industrial sector
the government began rationing gasoline and motorists waited hours in line. many buses and taxis in major cities stayed off the streets for lack of gasoline, tranport unions said
police in santa cruz and la paz rounded up leaders of the petroleum workers union. the government declared the strike illegal and said there would be more arrests if the walkout continues
the conservative government decided to take over petroleum plants and gasoline distributorships after the petroleum workers union rejected a 30 percent wage increase conditioned on their not striking for a year
the santa cruz refinery, 350 miles east of la paz, was surrounded by army units after workers turned off the plant's machinery following the breakdown of negotiations with the government
the plant produces 70 percent of the gasoline and natural gas used domestically. it also is responsible for much of the natural gas exported to argentina, the country's principal source of export earnings
saul soliz, leader of the petroleum workers union, said the government's linking of a wage increase to a promise of no strikes is ``a maneuver to divide the labor movement against the interests of workers.''
the union accused the government of planning to finance the 30 percent wage increase with the firing of 1,500 workers. minister of energy fernando illanes denied the charge. the government-owned petroleum company employs 7,000 workers
the ministry of information said the military intervened to prevent the destruction of equipment and guarantee a supply of fuel
many factories in la paz and other cities said they had enough fuel for only two more days and were cutting back on production
the government will not negotiate under pressure, more so since 11 out of 21 unions agreed to the wage increase,'' said illanes. seemed</note>
vice president george bush marched across the south on tuesday, overwhelming sen. bob dole as he headed for a near-sweep in super tuesday voting. dole braced to absorb the shock and the campaigns of the two remaining republican presidential contenders were dealt shattering blows
tuesday's voting seemed likely to bury the struggling campaigns of rep. jack kemp and pat robertson, who had claimed the south as his base of support
bush won decisive victories throughout the region, capturing more than 50 percent of the vote in many states, including delegate-rich florida
he also scored big wins in tennessee, kentucky, georgia, alabama, virginia, mississippi, north carolina and massachusetts
dole had pinned his southern hopes on north carolina, the home state of his wife, elizabeth.
abc and nbc also projected the vice president as winning texas and maryland
dole had hoped to pull out a win in north carolina, the home state of his wife, elizabeth
however, early returns showed the senate minority leader to be ahead in only one state _ missouri, which borders his home state of kansas
at stake tuesday were 712 delegates to the republican national convention. virginia was alone among the 17 gop contests holding a ``beauty contest'' that awards no delegates
bush's national campaign chairman, lee atwater, predicted that bush would pick up more than 600 of those delegates _ a gain that would give him a near-unassailable lead toward winning the gop presidential nomination
i would certainly hate to be in sen. dole's shoes after tonight and especially if he loses in illinois,'' atwater said. battered in tuesday's voting, dole turned his sights to next week's illinois primary in hopes of staging a comeback in midwestern and western states
dole said earlier in springfield, ill., ``if we take a little bath today, i am going to start my road to recovery in illinois just like i did 40 years ago.''
dole was referring to his recovery in an illinois hospital from wounds suffered during world war ii
kemp and robertson were far outdistanced by bush and dole. kemp trailed robertson in most southern states, and was expected to drop out by week's end. for robertson, the voting throughout the south was a replay of his third place finish in saturday's south carolina primary, when he could muster no more than about 20 percent of the vote
robertson seemed less likely to abandon his dogged pursuit of the presidency at this time. but the former television evangelist conceded in advance that ``it would take some miracle'' for him to beat bush
bush voted in houston, and then told reporters, ``if we exceed our expectations or live up to them, i think we'll be in good shape.''
top campaign aides had said earlier that they thought bush stood a good chance of winning at least 12 or 13 states
polls showed the vice president ahead in 16 of the 17 contests, including those in delegate-rich texas and florida. his chief rival, dole, was ahead only in missouri
it's going to be a little tougher as we go along, but i've been in tough fights before,'' dole acknowledged at a morning news conference in kansas city, mo
he then traveled to illinois and immediately challenged bush to a series of debates _ ``one-on-one, without moderator'' _ in that state, which holds its primary next tuesday
bush's chief spokesman, pete teeley, scoffed at the idea when asked about it in texas
if bob dole was so serious about debating, he would have shown up for the (feb. 19) dallas morning news debate,'' teeley said. ``we have a strategy which has been highly successful and we plan to pursue it, and that doesn't include having one-on-one debates with bob dole.''
dole campaign strategists had conceded in advance that super tuesday would likely belong to the vice president
in fact, the question appeared to be not whether bush would emerge the victor, but by what kind of margin _ and whether the drubbing would be fatal to dole, who finished first in the iowa caucuses but lost strength in the ensuing contests
the dole campaign had sought to keep bush from picking up more than 500 delegates tuesday
dole, though, was looking ahead to illinois, where he promised to ``issue a challenge or two'' to bush
the senate majority leader, a 1984 presidential contender and gop vice presidential candidate in 1976, was reportedly spending $500,000 on television advertising in the state
a defeat there could all but end dole's presidential efforts and a strong showing for the kanasan was by no means assured. bush is backed by illinois gov. james thompson and 93 of the state's 102 republican county chairmen
kemp, dead last in the south carolina primary last weekend, had not been expected to see that flagging effort revived in tuesday's voting. aides said the new york lawmaker and former pro-football star would reassess his race later in the week. he was expected to pull out
robertson's chances as a serious contender seemed likely to be all but ended if his losses in super tuesday states were as decisive as his third-place finish in south carolina, where he won only 19 percent of the vote
robertson's candidacy came to life with his strong second-place finish the iowa caucuses on feb. 8. but in the primaries that followed, his strength ebbed
even so, he told a north carolinia campaign audience as recently as monday: ``we will do very well in the south.'' race</head>
super tuesday belonged to george bush, an avalanche of southern votes propelling him into an all but insurmountable lead in the race for the republican presidential nomination
one month to the day that the vice president was humiliated in the iowa precinct caucuses, his candidacy devastated by a third-place finish behind bob dole and pat robertson, bush was in command of the gop race
his campaign manager, lee atwater, predicted bush would pick up about 600 of the 712 gop delegates at stake on super tuesday
what happened?
on feb. 9, few could resist writing bush political obituaries. dole flew to new hampshire with a claim to momentum that seemed likely to carry him to a second straight victory
i think the vice president's campaign is over,'' said pete du pont
the hemorrhaging of george bush has begun,'' said al haig
those assessments proved premature
it was du pont whose campaign was soon over; haig who didn't even make it to new hampshire primary day
attempts to explain how the race turned around so quickly are likely to center on whether bush recovered or dole blew it
for five days, dole looked like a winner in new hampshire. then came the ``straddle'' ads, bush campaign commercials that portrayed the kansas senator as waffling on taxes, the single most sensitive political issue in new hampshire
the ads ran all weekend before the primary and there was no response from the dole campaign
too late, dole realized what had happened. his surge in the polls leveled out. suddenly, as voters began making up their minds just before the primary, bush began to gain
when the returns came in the vice president had won by 9 points and an angry dole appeared on television and snapped that bush should ``stop lying about my record.''
but there was more to bush's comeback than effective commercials
the vice president also changed his campaign style. he eschewed the cautious speeches _ the attempts to be vice presidential _ that had marked his iowa campaign. he drove a fork-lift at a lumber yard and an 18-wheeler at a truck stop
this is the real me,'' he proclaimed to more than a few snickers
whoever it was, he went over better with new hampshire voters than he had with their iowa counterparts
but, possibly the most important factor in the bush comeback was ronald reagan, the man bush had served as a totally loyal vice president for seven years
in iowa, identification with reagan, the president blamed for a devastated farm economy, was not an asset. voters wanted to send a message to the white house and they chose dole as their messenger
but in new hampshire, with an economy that had boomed since reagan took office, the president was enormously popular. the same was true in the south
the calender had shifted to bush's advantage
might it now shift back to give dole a boost? the next big contest is the illinois primary, a midwest state, the region where the kansas senator has trounced bush in three contests _ iowa, south dakota and minnesota
while campaigning tuesday in springfield, ill., dole said, ``if we take a little bath today, i am going to start my road to recovery in illinois just like i did 40 years ago.'' it was a chicago physician who guided dole's recovery from world war ii wounds
editor's note: donald m. rothberg is the chief political writer of the associated press. neighboring pilot contradicts survivors on snow buildup. picks up 5th graf pvs, `robert benzon...'. subs 14th graf, `continental officials...', with 5 grafs to add survivor's explanation of loss of mechanic certification, and add detail on pilot's testimony. picks up 15th graf, `flight attendant...'.</note>
two survivors of the nov. 15 continental airlines crash at denver's airport told investigators tuesday that they thought they saw ice and snow on the wings as the dc-9 took off in a swirling snowstorm, but a pilot on another plane said the continental jet looked clear
moments after takeoff, the jet flipped over, hit the runway and broke into three pieces, killing 28 people and injuring the other 54 people aboard. some victims were trapped in the wreckage for more than six hours
wes zimmerman, a continental pilot on a neighboring plane that day, and crash survivors dr. fred helpenstell, 56, of nampa, idaho, and gregory wadsworth, 22, an airman stationed in idaho, were among 29 witnesses scheduled to testify at the national transportation safety board hearing, which opened tuesday
de-icing and the pilots' experience flying dc-9s were the chief issues raised during early testimony, although government officials have said their inquiry is not focusing on a single possible cause
zimmerman, whose continental 727-300 aircraft was on the 35-l runway at the same time as the continental jetliner, said he saw no ice or snow buildup on flight 1713
i felt good about how my de-icing was holding up,'' he said, explaining that he looked at nearby aircraft to gauge the condition of his own plane. but he acknowledged that his plane did not sit for as long between de-icing and takeoff as the ill-fated plane had sat
robert benzon, the ntsb investigator in charge of the inquiry, said during his opening statement that officials want to know why 24 minutes elapsed between the time flight 1713 was de-iced and the time it took off. other planes on the runway were taking off 15 minutes after being de-iced, he said
the reasons for flight 1713's 24-minute delay and the possible effects of snow or ice buildup on the wings and tail surfaces of the airplane during this delay are items of interest during this hearing,'' benzon said
in addition, the pairing of the two flight officers aboard flight 1713 would be discussed during the hearing, he said
capt. frank zvonek, 43, who had 198 hours on a dc-9 with only the previous 33 hours as captain; first officer lee bruecher, 26, had 36 hours piloting dc-9s and was flying the plane at the time of the crash. both men were killed
the pairing of two pilots with such experience in an aircraft type will be discussed during this hearing,'' benzon said
helpenstell, who suffered broken ribs and a broken finger in the crash, told the board that during takeoff from stapleton international airport he noticed that a wing looked wet
i wondered at one point, `is that ice?''' helpenstell recalled, ``but i decided it was just wet.''
wadsworth, who is stationed at mountain home air force base in idaho, said he had a clear view of the left wing
it had started to snow a lot harder, and it made me real nervous. it was like the snow was starting to pile up (on the wings),'' he said. ``i was very concerned, but i said it under my breath. i figured they do it (taking off in snowstorms) every day, and i was hopeful they would be able to do it this time. but unfortunately, that was not what happened. it was bad place.''
continental officials criticized wadsworth's testimony during the hearing, noting that he had lost a certification as an air force mechanic. wadsworth said he had been temporarily removed from mechanic duty because he had suffered flashbacks of the accident while he was on duty. he now works in a tool room
zimmerman, who had flown a dc-9 from june 1985 to february 1987, testified that before shortly before the stapleton crash, light to moderate snow was falling, not enough to affect safety
he said snow accumulation on his aircraft was ``very light. it was a cold snow, not a wet snow. it didn't build up on the flat surface of the wing.''
he testified that continental does not require pilots to have planes de-iced, but leaves it to the pilots' discretion. he estimated the time between the de-icing of his plane and takeoff at 17 to 18 minutes
under questioning by federal investigators, zimmerman said that if he had had to wait five minutes longer for takeoff, he would have re-evaluated whether his plane needed de-icing
flight attendant kelly englehart, 35, testified she was concerned when she learned that bruecher would be flying the plane. she and helpenstell also gave conflicting versions of the direction in which the aircraft rocked before it crashed
helpenstell said the plane rocked first to the right side on which he was seated and then came back suddenly to the left. englehart said the dc-9 rocked first to the left side and then sharply to the right
we felt the wing must have hit then. there were three large pops and a large explosion. i saw a large, orange fireball at the front of the cabin moving down. i shut my eyes and waited for it to be over. i waited for it to get me,'' she said. update with more rioting, two injured, bomb found in northern ireland. pick up 9th graf: prime minister...</note>
spanish police found an explosives-laden car tuesday that was believed rented by three ira members shot dead in gibraltar by british commandos, officials said
it was packed with powerful explosives made in czechoslovakia and rigged with a timing device set at 11:20 a.m., but the timer had not been connected, the spanish officials said. the white ford fiesta was in a parking lot at marbella, about 50 miles up the coast from this british colony
british officials in london said the irish republican army members, who were unarmed when commandos killed them sunday, had planned to detonate a car bomb tuesday during the 20-minute changing of the guard ceremony at the governor's residence. the ceremony began at 11 a.m
the royal anglian regiment now guards the convent, as the residence is called. the regiment was just transferred from northern ireland, where guerrillas of the mainly roman catholic ira have been fighting since 1969 to oust the british and unite the province with the predominantly catholic irish republic. protestants outnumber catholics about 3-2 in the province
soldiers patrolled convent square on tuesday and the ceremony went on as scheduled
all three of the ira members were from west belfast in northern ireland
in catholic west belfast, protesters outraged at the killings battled police and british troops throughout the day tuesday. at least two people were injured
police in northern ireland also reported a 1,600-pound explosive device was found in a hedge near the killeen customs post between newry and the town of dundalk in the irish republic and was defused
bands of youths in west belfast hurled gasoline bombs and rocks at security forces, hijacked vehicles and burned them, set fire to a lumber yard and erected barricades
they scattered as police and soldiers fired plastic bullets, but quicly reorganized
belfast police said a man's face was burned when his car was set afire and a woman was treated at a hospital for injuries suffered when her car was stoned
prime minister charles haughey of the irish republic held a special cabinet meeting. he told parliament later his government recognized britain's right to take reasonable measures against terrorism, but added:
we are greatly perturbed at the shooting dead of three unarmed irish people in circumstances where it appears from reports that they could have been arrested by the security forces. the law shouldn't operate like that.''
witnesses to the shootings said men in civilian clothes, believed to be members of the special air services anti-terrorist force, jumped from a car and opened fire on two men and a women walking down the avenue leading to the border between gibraltar and spain
two cars connected with the dead ira members were found in gibraltar. sir geoffrey howe, the british foreign secretary, said monday a third car was believed to be involved
he said it was not true, as earlier official reports had said, that a car the ira members parked near the governor's residence sunday was packed with explosives
howe said a ``dreadful terrorist act'' was averted when the commandos killed the ira members
agustin valladolid, spokesman for spanish state security in madrid, said the white ford was found in the sun parking lot in marbella at about 6:30 p.m. tuesday
he said it was left in the lot sunday, but there had been no danger of an explosion. valladolid said police had stepped up their search for a fourth member of the ira team
the ira identified the three people killed as mairead farrell, 31; daniel mccann, 30, and sean savage, 24. although unarmed, they were ``on active service,'' it said
backers of a constitutional amendment to make english the state's official language gathered about 260,000 new signatures tuesday, easily topping the number required to get on the november ballot, a spokeswoman said
we are feeling very good,'' said patricia fulton, spokeswoman for the florida english campaign
taking advantage of primary election day, volunteers stationed near polling places throughout the state collected about 60,000 signatures of registered voters, and workers from a california company collected nearly 200,000, ms. fulton said
the new signatures, added to the 236,000 already in hand, should put the movement at well beyond the 342,939 needed for a referendum. about 125,500 of the signatures already have been verified
the signatures were obtained despite the efforts of the league of united latin american citizens, which took out advertisements in hispanic newspapers around the state warning voters about the proposed amendment and urging them to register so that they could vote against it in the general election
we're accused of being racist or xenophobics, because people think we are anti-immigrants,'' said dr. mark laporta, chairman on the florida english campaign
nothing could be farther from the truth. my father was an immigrant,'' laporta said. he insisted the measure was designed to spur immigrants to learn the language and the ways of the united states
lulac and other hispanic groups oppose the florida and u.s. english campaigns because they believed they have racist elements
if enough signatures are verified, the proposed referendum would be submitted to the state supreme court for review of its wording
the referendum would ask voters to designate english as the official language, but would leave it up the state legislature to decide what, if any, government practices would be changed
proponent of the referendum, for example, would like to see the government increase funds for english-language education
a south african diplomat cited for simple assault after his car struck a protester and a police officer said tuesday that he was sorry about the incident
south african vice consul duke kent brown said during an interview with radio station wjoy-wqcr that he did not expect the group of anti-apartheid protesters to block his exit from a parking lot near the radio station monday
it's unfortunate that whole situation arose,'' he said
brown was charged with simple assault, released on his own recognizance and ordered to appear in court in april in connection with the incident
the state department said brown had consular, rather than diplomatic, immunity, meaning he was not automatically exempt from prosecution. but he can claim immunity in court as an ``affirmative defense'' on the grounds that the alleged acts were performed in the exercise of his consular function
about 30 members of the vermont committee on southern africa had gathered outside the station to protest brown's participation in a morning talk show, according to wjoy-wqcr news director jim condon
brown said he had expected the protest to continue, but that ``i would ignore them as i would leave.''
some of the protesters were on the hood of the car when it accelerated, condon said
brown said he did not see the police officer, todd shepard, who suffered bruises on his leg. ``i was very surprised to hear that a policeman had been injured and i did apologize to him when i saw him,'' brown said
brown said he was glad to hear that protester laurie larson of richmond was not badly injured. larson suffered minor bruises
a man who claims israeli agents threw his bride off a cruise ship to her death during their honeymoon in retaliation for a book he wrote critical of israel was charged tuesday with murder
scott robin roston, first told authorities his wife, karen waltz roston, was blown overboard by a gust of wind while jogging on feb. 13, and changed his story when authorities noted it wasn't windy that night
roston was indicted by a federal grand jury on a count of second-degree murder under a statute covering killings aboard ships. if convicted, he could be sentenced to life in prison
the bahamian government has sought to extradite roston, 36, because the death took place when the couple were on the cruise ship stardancer, which is registered in that country
under terms of its treaty with the united states, the bahamas cannot extradite roston if he is convicted or acquitted in this country, assistant u.s. attorney patricia collins said. he could still faces charges there, however, if the u.s. trial ends in a mistrial or hung jury, she said
defense attorney paul e. potter said he will seek bail during a hearing on friday. roston has been held without bail since his arrest feb. 15
roston, who lives in santa monica, is the author of ``nightmare in israel,'' published in 1987 by vantage press, a subsidy publisher whose authors usually help pay for the cost of their books
he feels that this murder is the result of a book he published last year in new york city in which he exposed the numerous human rights abuses which he perceived in israel,'' potter said after roston's arrest
potter said tuesday that the book is ``the key to the case.''
the body of mrs. roston, 26, was recovered by the coast guard and roston was arrested when the ship docked in los angeles. they had been married less than two weeks
potter said ``he feels that she was murdered by israeli secret agents.'' vote figures. no pickup.</note>
massachusetts gov. michael dukakis ran away with maryland's democratic presidential primary tuesday, while vice president george bush soundly defeated kansas sen. bob dole in the republican contest
democratic sen. paul sarbanes easily overcame two little-known primary opponents in his bid for a third term. he will face thomas blair, a millionaire newcomer to politics, who beat eight other candidates for the republican nomination
in the democratic presidential race, with 643 of 1,574 precincts or 41 percent reporting, dukakis had 65,527 votes or 45 percent to jesse jackson's 35,855 votes or 24 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. had 15,506 votes or 11 percent; and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 12,024 votes or 8 percent
former colorado sen. gary hart finished with 5,713 votes or 4 percent; and illinois sen. paul simon tallied 4,740 votes or 3 percent
in the republican primary, bush gathered 25,870 votes or 54 percent to dole's 14,643 votes or 31 percent, with 426 of 1,574 precincts or 27 percent reporting
new york rep. jack kemp and former tv evangelist pat robertson was next with 3,260 votes or 7 percent, followed by new york rep. jack kemp with 2,861 votes or 6 percent
bush won despite a late effort by dole that included a day of campaigning by the kansas senator in what his staff considered one of his better super tuesday states
at stake were 41 gop delegates and 67 democratic delegates
sarbanes' opponents in the democratic primary were a. robert kaufman, 56, a socialist who wants to use the campaign as a platform to express his concerns about the economy and social ills in the united states, and b. emerson sweatt, 44, who says he has masterminded federal drug control efforts since 1970, is owed $6 million by the federal government and claims to be the only man on earth with a ``valid legal right to subpoena the entire congress to testify in a civil suit against the government.''
blair, a montgomery county millionaire who had never run for office, was the pre-primary favorite
maryland got scant attention from the presidential contenders despite the switch to super tuesday from the traditional may primary, which democratic leaders hoped would help the state play a bigger role in the nominating process. reaction, comments from coleridge, other detail. no pickup</note>
the abu nidal palestinian terrorist group freed a british relief agency official and his syrian aide tuesday, five days after seizing them in this southern port city
peter coleridge, 44, middle east coordinator of the british relief agency oxfam, and omar traboulsi, 31, appeared physically fit when members of abu nidal's fatah-revolutionary council drove them to the sidon apartment of mustafa saad, a sunni moslem leader
we thank you for your hospitality,'' coleridge said in arabic when they reached the apartment on the second floor
abu nidal's guerrillas seized them thursday while coleridge was taking pictures of the ein el-hilweh palestinian refugee camp
coleridge told reporters tuesday: ``i am a guest in lebanon. i should have realized that shooting pictures at ein el-hilweh is a big mistake
i made a mistake by not asking for a permission from the authority in ein el-hilweh. i know and respect the people who took us. there has been no kidnapping ... they were only applying security procedures.''
we were well treated,'' he added
traboulsi sat next to coleridge and did not speak. coleridge said he ``will leave lebanon,'' but would not disclose his travel plans
coleridge told bbc radio's ``pm'' program he and traboulsi had been interrogated, blindfolded, handcuffed and put into the trunks of two cars
on tuesday, mustafa saad identified the men involved as being from abu nidal
coleridge said they were driven to an isolated place about half an hour from sidon and held there for the rest of their captivity
oxfam gave news of coleridge's release to his wife, angela, at their home in headington, england. the couple have three children _ jessie, 12, sara, 11, and edward, 5
mrs coleridge said she and the children were ``overwhelmed and absolutely delighted.'' she added, ``all i feel like doing now is sitting down and having a nice, quiet cup of tea.''
coleridge said he heard no news of any other hostages, including anglican envoy terry waite, during his captivity. waite disappeared in beirut in january 1987. no one has claimed responsibility
the release leaves leaves 22 foreigners still missing in lebanon, including nine americans. held longest is terry a. anderson, chief middle east correspondent of the associated press, who was kidnapped march 16, 1985
coleridge and traboulsi had gone to sidon last week to inspect relief groups supported by oxfam. it was the british official's first visit to lebanon in three years
coleridge said his camera and opel station wagon were returned, but a security source said the palestinians ``confiscated the film coleridge was shooting.''
abu nidal, whose real name is sabry al-banna, broke with yasser arafat's palestine liberation organization in the early 1970s and founded the fatah-revolutionary council
his followers have been blamed for scores of terrorist acts, including the december 1985 assaults at the rome and vienna airports in which 20 people died
coleridge and traboulsi were accompanied to saad's apartment by fatah-revolutionary council spokesman walid khaled
he said the men ``were held for questioning as a precautionary measure after shooting pictures in military zones.''
joe redington stole the lead of the 1,150-mile iditarod trail sled dog race on tuesday as he and herbie nayokpuk sailed past other mushers who had packed down a smooth, fast trail for them
redington, a wasilla resident who is a founder of the 16-year-old race, and nayokpuk, of shishmaref, took their mandatory 24-hour layovers on sunday. the race leaders passed them by, only to get bogged down in freshly fallen snow as they crossed the alaska range
the leading mushers then took their mandatory layovers at rohn, 271 miles from the race's start in anchorage. they watched helplessly as redington and nayokpuk _ and less than two hours later, joe garnie of teller _ powered past them
i kind of have this feeling in the back of my mind that we're going to see two eskimos _ garnie and nayokpuk _ blazing across this state,'' said jerry austin, one of the mushers taking a layover at rohn
joe runyan of nenana was the first musher to leave rohn, at 10:30 p.m. monday. but he has not declared his 24-hour layover, and so is behind redington, who left rohn at 7:20 a.m. tuesday. nayokpuk left rohn two minutes behind redington. garnie left at 9 a.m
still at rohn, in the order in which they arrived, were: jan masek of anchorage; lavon barve of wasilla; defending champion susan butcher of manley; jacques philip of thomery, france; austin, of st. michael; tim moerlein of kasilof; and, in 11th place, two-time iditarod champion rick swenson
from rohn, the teams descend from the heights of the alaska range into the timbered interior of the state for the longest stretch between checkpoints in the race. mushers must contend with a bleak and treacherous area known as farewell burn before reaching the next checkpoint, 93 miles away at nikolai
the race is inspired by a 1925 dog sled relay that rushed diphtheria serum to nome during an outbreak of the disease. the top 20 mushers will split a purse of $150,000. the winner will get $30,000. 03-08 0370</first> winner, results; picks up 4th graf, `eighty-two democratic ...'</note>
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. edged jesse jackson to win north carolina's democratic presidential primary tuesday, while vice president george bush held off a late surge by kansas sen. bob dole in the republican race
with 2,270 of 2,387 precincts or 95 percent reporting, gore had 224,514 votes or 35 percent; jackson had 212,833 votes or 33 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 130,870 votes or 20 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 37,978 votes or 6 percent; and former colorado sen. gary hart had 15,842 votes or 2 percent
in the republican race, with 2,279 precincts or 95 percent reporting: bush had 117,846 votes or 45 percent; dole had 104,093 votes or 40 percent; pat robertson had 25,356 votes or 10 percent; and new york rep. jack kemp had 10,931 votes or 4 percent
eighty-two democratic delegates and 54 gop delegates were up for grabs in the third-largest of 14 southern and border states holding primaries
dole strategists looked on north carolina as one of their best southern prospects _ largely because the candidate's wife, former transportation secretary elizabeth dole, is a native of salisbury, n.c
polls published over the weekend showed dole, who trailed by as much as 15 percentage points two weeks ago, had pulled even with bush. a survey by the charlotte observer showed both with 38 percent
kemp never developed a viable state campaign despite winning support of the leaders of the national congressional club, sen. jesse helms' organization
gore's appeal to southern pride drew endorsements from sen. terry sanford, former gov. jim hunt and dozens of state legislators and local officeholders. gore was in fourth place in a poll published two weeks ago but appeared to be surging last week
