massachusetts gov. michael dukakis and vice president george bush parlayed their neighborly ties into overwhelming victories in rhode island's presidential primaries on tuesday
in the democratic race, with 226 of 320 precincts or 71 percent reporting, dukakis crushed all challengers with 23,842 votes or 72 percent
next came jesse jackson with 4,572 votes or 14 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt with 1,389 votes or 4 percent; tennessee sen. albert gore jr. with 1,294 votes or 4 percent; illinois sen. paul simon with 837 votes or 2 percent; and former colorado sen. gary hart with 518 votes or 2 percent
in the republican contest, with 223 of 320 precincts or 70 percent reporting, bush tallied 6,449 votes or 65 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 2,222 votes or 22 percent; pat robertson finished with 590 votes or 6 percent; and new york rep. jack kemp was last with 476 votes or 5 percent
at issue were 22 democratic and 21 republican delegates
dukakis, the governor of a neighboring state, and bush, a new england native, had both worked the state long before their presidential campaigns officially began, and each picked up endorsements from his party's top local political figures
bush came to the state in 1986 to help two fellow republicans, gov. edward d. diprete and rep. claudine schneider, win re-election that year, and diprete and schneider repaid the favor with vocal support this year
gore got a burst of publicity and built a sizable organization as the result of a january visit to the state. jackson made headlines in november, when he took a scituate elementary school teacher with him on a trip to the persian gulf to deliver children's presents to u.s. servicemen there. victim</head> reference to marcel kinsbourne to `he' sted `she.'</note>
rod matthews killed, his attorney says, because a prescription drug he took for school stoked the fires of madness in his adolescent mind
in an ironic twist, matthews' victim, 14-year-old shaun ouillette, also took the drug, ritalin, for years, using it, his mother says, to cool the frantic behavior that plagued his childhood
it calmed him down enough so we could help him,'' said jeanne quinn, the victim's mother. ``i was so proud that he could learn to manage his life.''
matthews, 15, is being tried as an adult on murder charges in the nov. 20, 1986, slaying of ouillette. he has pleaded innocent by reason of insanity
the defense has not disputed testimony that matthews planned the killing for a month, lured his victim to a secluded woods, then stalked him from behind, hitting him repeatedly with a baseball bat
his friends have testified he told them of his plans, then showed them the body on two separate occasions. one quoted matthews as saying he killed ouillette because ``he wanted to know what it was like to kill somebody.''
police testified how matthews calmly lied to them about ouillette for the three weeks the boy's body lay in the snowy woods
the case is expected to go to the jury wednesday
in testimony last week, matthews' mother, janice, said her son's behavior had become a problem in the third grade and that he was placed on ritalin after a brief visit to his pediatrican
she cried as she told of the doctor's decision to prescribe the drug, a stimulant long used to calm hyperactive children and those with attention problems
the boy's doctor, theodore goodman, testified that he relied only on what mrs. matthews told him. there was no testing and no follow-up on the drug's effects
on monday, psychiatrist bernard yudowitz testified that if a child with mental illness is misdiagnosed and given ritalin, ``impulsivity and abnormal behavior increase and their ability to act appropriately in a given setting decreases.''
in my experience if the child has an underlying mental problem, ritalin may not help and it may hurt,'' he said
last week, norman bernstein, a harvard-based child psychologist, said matthews ``had within him a world of angry, fearful destructive thoughts.''
matthews attorney, john philip white, said ritalin contributed to the boy's homicidal intent
in this case is the insidious element of mental illness with the overlying thread of ritalin,'' white told the jury
but on tuesday, marcel kinsbourne, chief of behavioral neurology at the eunice shriver center in waltham, said the drug could not be considered a factor in the killing
norfolk county assistant district attorney peter casey asked kinsbourne if the drug would have an ``enhancing effect'' on matthews' planning, execution and coverup of the slaying
absolutely none whatever,'' he said
mrs. quinn, who listened from her front row seat, agreed
i don't believe it killed my son,'' she said. ``i suppose if i were his parent, i would be looking for any way to explain what happened, but ritalin doesn't answer it for me.''
mrs. quinn said her son took ritalin from age 7 through 11 to help calm his hyperactivity. the boy also received therapy, she said
in the end, she said, it worked. the boy was weaned from the drug and shaun even told his mother he wanted to become a youth counselor
a lot of the kids he saw in group therapy were messed up kids,'' she said. ``he wanted to help and now it's all gone. what a waste.''
gunmen in a car shot at a police station tuesday, killing one officer, and to cover their escape threw a grenade into a courtyard where children were playing, authorities reported
they said two suspects were arrested shortly after the attack, but the prisoners were not identified
no group asserted responsibility for the attack. it came less than a day after guerrillas of the corsican national liberation front vowed to intensify actions to win independence from france for the island in the mediterranean 125 miles off the french mainland
security minister robert pandraud, speaking at lunel in southern france, condemned the killing and said: ``we will fight against the murderers without pity.''
police said three or four people in a car fired pistols at the police station, fatally wounding an officer who was hit twice in the stomach
as they fled, the killers threw a hand grenade into a courtyard where several policemen's children were playing, and one of the children was treated for shock, according to authorities
police said the car used in the attack was found abandoned in a ditch near the police station
one of four masked members of the national liberation front, speaking to reporters monday near the town of bastiaa, said: ``there is no question of establishing a truce. we are going to pursue and even intensify our actions.'' the group has claimed responsibility for several assassinations, including the sept. 13, 1983, shooting of a top government official for northern corsica. updates results; picks up 4th graf, `the republicans ...'</note>
jesse jackson nudged tennessee sen. albert gore to win georgia's democratic presidential primary tuesday, while vice president george bush swamped his republican rivals
with 2,002 of 2,571 precincts or 78 percent reporting, jackson had 174,003 votes or 39 percent; gore had 149,180 votes or 34 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 62,987 votes or 14 percent; missouri rep. richard gephardt had 31,828 votes or 7 percent; and former colorado sen. gary hart had 13,116 votes or 3 percent
in the republican race, with 1,922 precincts or 75 percent reporting, bush had 135,769 votes or 54 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 57,628 votes or 23 percent; pat robertson had 43,668 votes or 17 percent; and new york rep. jack kemp had 13,213 votes or 5 percent
the republicans had 48 delegates up for grabs, with the democrats offering 77 delegates to their convention in atlanta in july
one of the state's best-known democrats, former president jimmy carter, withheld his endorsement. but another, sen. sam nunn, disclosed that he cast an absentee ballot for gore because his ``views come closest to my own views as to the steps our nation must take to meet our challenges at home and abroad.''
gop officials conceded bush's association with reagan and his organization gave him the edge, but robertson displayed organizational strength in some precinct meetings last month
jackson pulled off a surprise in 1984, winning southeastern georgia's 1st congressional district, which includes savannah. jackson's strong showing then was credited to a low democratic turnout combined with success in getting his supporters to the polls
dukakis made several other visits to the state, including stops in atlanta on the day he announced his candidacy and the day after his victory in the new hampshire primary
on sunday, dukakis stopped in for a half-hour visit with the former president, who has met with all the other candidates at various times
i think there's a great deal of compatibility between my basic attitude towards government and that of governor dukakis,'' carter said afterwards
to encourage participation in the primary, state officials included a referendum on broadening the eligibility for exemptions for the elderly from some property and school taxes
jesse jackson elbowed past tennessee sen. albert gore jr. to grab tuesday's presidential primary in mississippi, while vice president george bush left the rest of the republican field in the dust
democrats also waged a spirited primary battle for the senate seat john stennis is leaving after 41 years
in the democratic race, with 1,750 of 2,340 precincts or 75 percent reporting: jackson had 118,652 votes or 44 percent; gore had 91,337 votes or 34 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 22,661 votes or 8 percent; and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 14,996 votes or 6 percent. former colorado sen. gary hart had 9,900 votes or 4 percent
in the republican race, with 1,801 of 2,340 precincts or 77 percent reporting, bush had won with 78,424 votes or 67 percent; dole had 19,547 votes or 17 percent; former tv evangelist pat robertson had 15,115 votes or 13 percent; and new york rep. jack kemp had 4,289 votes or 4 percent
forty democratic delegates were at stake and 31 gop delegates
in the senate primary, rep. wayne dowdy battled secretary of state dick molpus for the chance to run against republican rep. trent lott in november for stennis' seat. with 1,456 of 2,340 precincts or 62 percent reporting, dowdy had 125,471 or 55 percent to molpus' 94,349 or 41 percent
gilbert founation, a biloxi pipefitter, had 8,012 or 4 percent
stennis, 86, announced last october that he would retire, making this only the second time in 41 years that the state has had an open u.s. senate race
dowdy, 44, who gained his congressional seat in a 1981 special election, stressed his experience in washington. molpus, 38, touted his record as director of federal-state programs under former gov. william winter and his work as secretary of state since 1984
in recent weeks, molpus made dowdy's attendance record _ ranked one of the five worst in the house according to molpus _ a campaign issue. dowdy has countered that his voting mark is almost the same as that of stennis'
the new democratic party government in manitoba, the only socialist administration in canada's 10 provinces, was defeated tuesday in a confidence vote
premier howard pawley's government had been clinging to power with a one-seat majority in the provincial legislature
but jim walding, a new democrat legislator, voted with the opposition conservative and liberal parties on a crucial budget measure and the result was considered a vote of no confidence
the vote was 28-27 against the government
opposition members pounded their desks victoriously after the vote
obviously we are in a very difficult situation,'' pawley said, and he indicated his party will meet wednesday to decide whether to call an early election
it is traditional in canada for a government defeated on a major measure considered to be a confidence vote to go to the polls
the crisis in manitoba has national ramifications since pawley is the most active provincial opponent of the free-trade agreement federal prime minister brian mulroney's conservative government negotiated last year with the united states, but which has yet to be ratified
pawley also opposes a constitutional accord mulroney secured with the province of quebec, recognizing the predominantly french-speaking province as a ``distinct society.''
vice president george bush jubilantly proclaimed himself the man to beat in the republican presidential sweepstakes, saying his super tuesday performance ``exceeded my fondest expectations.''
standing alongside his wife, barbara, in a packed hotel ballroom in his adopted home town, bush said, ``as i said ... whoever wins super tuesday convincingly is going to be the next president, and i'll repeat it: i'm going to be the next president of the united states.''
this exceeded my fondest expectations,'' the vice president said
you've given me and barbara a big lift,'' bush told supporters. he and his wife had begun the day by casting their ballots in the texas gop primary. bush then went into seclusion in the afternoon
bush basked in the glow of his election triumphs only briefly, giving a talk to supporters and greeting well-wishers in the ballroom, which was decorated with bush banners, the american flag and red, white and blue balloons. his aides had said earlier bush would not accede to sen. bob dole's demand that the vice president appear in one-on-one, lincoln-douglas-style debates in illinois
the vice president had awaited returns in a 21st floor penthouse suite in the westin oaks hotel, just a few blocks from the hotel houstonian, where he maintains a permanent residence. in washington, he lives in the official vice president's house
bush brought to houston two governors _ new hampshire's john sununu and south carolina's carroll campbell _ who had played pivotal roles in his earlier victories in their states
bush called his conquest of dole and rivals jack kemp and pat robertson ``a big, a major political victory. this is a national victiory.''
the vice president said he felt his performance tuesday was a reflection not of his campaign style but of his message ``to reduce the deficit without raising taxes, to make progress toward peace through strength, and making the united states strong ...''
reducing the threat of war is not a republican issue and not a democratic issue,'' he said. ``it's a national issue.''
bush had no public activities scheduled for wednesday and his campaign aides planned to hold strategy sessins here
the vice president planned to fly to chicago on thursday for the start of five days of intensive campaigning in the illinois primary
tennessee sen. albert gore jr. emerged king of the democratic hill in tuesday's presidential primary in arkansas, while vice president george bush brushed aside republican rivals
with 1,311 of 2,762 precincts or 47 percent reporting, gore had 79,145 votes or 37 percent; massachusetts gov. michael dukakis had 40,285 votes or 19 percent; jesse jackson had 37,772 votes or 17 percent; and missouri rep. richard gephardt had 26,538 votes or 12 percent
in the gop race, with 706 of 2,762 precincts or 26 percent reporting, bush had 14,527 votes or 48 percent; kansas sen. bob dole had 7,913 votes or 26 percent; and former tv evangelist pat robertson had 5,450 votes or 18 percent. new york rep. jack kemp had 1,387 votes or 5 percent
in the 1st congressional district, veteran democratic rep. bill alexander defeated political consultant darrell glascock, who went to court to get on the ballot. alexander had 41,552 votes, or 67 percent, to glascock's 20,034, or 33 percent. no republican sought the office
thirty-eight of arkansas' 44 democratic delegates and all 27 gop delegates were up for grabs
turnout was expected to be low with the top state offices not on the ballot because of a constitutional amendment that increased terms from two years to four years beginning with the 1986 elections. news digest: undated _ pm-super tuesday rdp, a0446; washington _ pm-super tuesday-analysis, a0443; san antonio, texas _ pm-jackson-south, a0442; undated _ pm-state primaries rdp, a0465; damascus, syria _ pm-syria-us, a0469; panama city, panama _ pm-panama, a0492; phoenix, ariz. _ pm-mecham impeachment, a0505; washington _ pm-arresting senators, a0499; chicago _ pm-soup kitchen smiles, a0448
