peter coleridge, 44, middle east coordinator of the british relief agency oxfam, and omar traboulsi, 31, appeared fit when members of abu nidal's fatah-revolutionary council drove them to the sidon apartment of mustafa saad, the sunni leader
we thank you for your hospitality,'' coleridge said in arabic when they reached the apartment on the second floor
commuter airlines that carried nearly 30 million people last year are being targeted for stepped-up inspections by the federal aviation administration after seven fatal accidents and 56 deaths since november
the agency announced the special inspections of the commuters, which normally fly aircraft of 30 or fewer seats, at a news conference tuesday. it said that about 20 percent of the 173 commuter carriers are expected to be singled out for particuarly close scrutiny
none of the airlines was identified and faa officials could not say immediately how the airlines would be selected to special attention
the world health organization's chief aids investigator called sex experts william masters and virginia johnson irresponsible for suggesting aids can be transmitted by casual social contact
dr. jonathan mann, the american director of who's global program on aids, challenged the noted sex researchers to produce scientific evidence or admit they were indulging in ``idle speculation.''
if it's just theorizing, then i think they have done us all a grave disservice,'' mann told reporters tuesday at the first international conference on the global impact of aids
a justice department official said tuesday he favors raising congressional pay to as much as $175,000 in exchange for ending a ``double standard'' exempting senators and representatives from federal ethics laws
assistant attorney general william weld said it is ``neither logical nor ... consonant with the notion of fair play'' to make it a crime for executive branch officials to accept fees or honoraria for job-related activities, while allowing members of congress to do so
in a national press club speech attacking public corruption, weld said he favors ``raising the salary of all members of congress to a level around somewhere between $150,000 and $175,000 a year. this would enable you to do some other things like prohibit honoraria.''
a prosecutor accused one of gov. evan mecham's lawyers tuesday of using innuendo to delve into the sex life of arizona's top lawman, a subject ruled off-limits at mecham's impeachment trial
attorney fred craft was trying to undermine the crediblity of department of public safety director ralph milstead as the key witness against mecham on an obstruction of justice charge
the 63-year-old governor, who has not attended any sessions of the impeachment trial since it began last week, is accused of ordering milstead not to help the attorney general investigate an alleged death threat to a grand jury witness by a mecham aide
bill britt, who repeatedly refused offers of food and a warm home, died two weeks before his children discovered his body, partially devoured by animals in the woods he called home since 1969
autopsy results tuesday showed that britt, 52, died of hypothermia and was dead two weeks before he was discovered monday by two of his three children in his makeshift wigwam in brookline, according to the suffolk county medical examiner's report
britt died in the woods near the chestnut hill reservoir, near the affluent community of the same name where he was born and grew up. he had lived in the woods since 1969, but did not attract much attention until 1985, when officials tried to move him into public or subsidized housing. britt's resistance to being moved brought him national attention; last may he appeared on ``late night with david letterman'' and at one point actor mickey rooney planned to buy the rights to his story
today is tuesday, march 15, the 75th day of 1988. there are 291 days left in the year. this is ``buzzard day'' in hinckley, ohio
today's highlight in history:
on the ides of march, 44 b.c., roman emperor julius caesar was assassinated by a group of nobles that included brutus and cassius
on this date:
in 1493, christopher columbus returned to spain following his first voyage to the new world
in 1767, the seventh president of the united states, andrew jackson, was born in waxhaw, south carolina
in 1820, maine became the 23rd state
in 1875, the roman catholic archbishop of new york, john mccloskey, was named the first american cardinal, by pope pius ix
in 1913, president woodrow wilson held the first open presidential news conference
in 1919, the american legion was founded, in paris
in 1944, during world war ii, the italian town of cassino was devastated by allied bombs
in 1956 the musical play ``my fair lady,'' starring rex harrison and julie andrews, opened on broadway
in 1964, elizabeth taylor married richard burton in montreal. it was her fifth marriage; his second
in 1965, before a joint session of congress, president lyndon b. johnson called for new legislation to guarantee every person's right to vote
in 1966, rioting broke out in the watts section of los angeles
in 1975, greek shipping magnate aristotle onassis died near paris at the age of 69
in 1977, the house of representatives began a 90-day test to determine the feasibility of showing its sessions on television
ten years ago: israel routed palestinian guerrillas from at least seven strongholds in southern lebanon. and israel said it would keep its troops in a ``security belt'' it seized along its northern border until an agreement was reached to ensure that the area could no longer be used for attacks against israel
five years ago: israeli foreign minister yitzhak shamir said he was leaving washington more optimistic about prospects of an agreement on withdrawing israeli troops from lebanon
one year ago: peggy say, the sister of kidnapped associated press correspondent terry anderson, said president reagan was being ``unjustly castigated'' for his arms-for-hostages deal
today's birthdays: actor macdonald carey is 75. former astronaut alan l. bean is 56. actor judd hirsch is 53. beach boy mike love is 47. rhythm 'n' blues star sylvester ``sly stone'' stewart is 44. rock guitarist ry cooder is 41
thought for today: ``no man has a right in america to treat any other man tolerantly, for tolerance is the assumption of superiority.'' _ wendell willkie, american politician (1892-1944)
the week before mikhail gorbachev arrived in the united states for the december arms summit, president reagan granted a rare interview to the four major networks' anchors
that's right, four: peter jennings of abc, dan rather of cbs, tom brokaw of nbc, and bernard shaw, washington anchor for cnn
although he had already interviewed reagan in october, shaw agreed that the prime-time news special in which he questioned reagan along with the three other anchors was a high-profile symbol of cnn's hard-earned respectability
that conversation the week before the summit was a turning point, i suppose you would have to say,'' said shaw in an interview at his anchor desk at the cnn bureau. ``i went back and asked (white house chief of staff) howard baker about that, and he said, `we regard you as the fourth network, and that's why we included you in the interview.'''
the reagan interview turned a lot of unsought attention on the low-key shaw, a former correspondent for abc, cbs and westinghouse broadcasting, who recalls idolizing edward r. murrow as a child in chicago and at 13 declaring, ``i want to be a cbs news correspondent.''
after stints with westinghouse and cbs, then covering latin america for abc, shaw joined cnn in 1980. he wanted to be an anchor, and ``there was no room at the inn at abc, a lot of other talented people standing in line.'' plus, he was encouraged to join the then-fledgling 24-hour news network by friends daniel schorr and george watson, the washington bureau chief
the next year, john hinckley shot president reagan outside a washington hotel where reagan had just delivered a speech
shaw had finished his news update summarizing the speech and switched back to cnn headquarters in atlanta when a staffer told him someone had fired shots at the president's motorcade
i screamed to the control room to tell atlanta to come back to us right away,'' shaw said. shaw filled viewers in with the sketchy information he had, then switched back to atlanta, but reese schoenfield, then president of cnn, ordered atlanta to go back to washington and stay there
and they did, and there we were,'' said shaw. he was on the air for 10 hours
i was pretty conscious that day of my demeanor, tone of voice and facial expressions,'' he said, ``because that camera magnifies everything, and i was determined to be as low-key as possible, as factual as possible and as dispassionate as possible. a story like that requires no heat.''
low-key is the operative word in describing shaw's style. he considers the celebrity aspects of his job ``corruptive'' and prefers to spend his free time with his wife, linda, and their two children. besides ``doing better'' in his job at cnn, shaw, 47, says his only ambition is to write books, fiction and non-fiction
he's a perfectionist who constantly worries about improving his performance and the network's. he said that when he left the air after the iowa and new hampshire primaries, he lay awake for hours ``replaying in my head what we did _ what we did right, what we did wrong, what i could have done better.''
he does his homework every time and worries over it like it's his first time, and calls afterwards to be critiqued on it,'' said cnn executive vice president ed turner. ``i don't know anybody as good as he is, in my 30 years in the business, at his specialty, which was a job once done brilliantly by (walter) cronkite, before him by (robert) trout, people who can sit with a breaking story for hours on end and never lose the various threads that you have to keep hold of.''
if it's grueling to be on the air for hours on end, it's also fulfilling
while his colleagues at the other networks struggle to get even an hour or two of prime-time coverage for the primaries, shaw, who anchors cnn's political coverage, gets the whole night
there was a magical moment, or hour, between 9 and 10 o'clock in manchester (n.h.),'' he recalled, ``and it seemed like every candidate was coming down to the ballroom to make statements. and it just looked like a visual ballet, where we went from kemp to gephardt to bush to dole, or what have you. and i looked up on the monitors, and we were the only ones on the air. and i felt good.''
elsewhere in television:
shooter _ david hume kennerly, who won a pulitzer prize for combat photo coverage in vietnam and served as official white house photographer in the administration of president ford, is co-writer and co-producer of ``shooter,'' an nbc movie now filming in thailand. it follows the exploits of an irreverent combat photographer, played by newcomer jeffrey nordling. steven ford, son of the former president, has a supporting role
super tuesday might have resolved a few political questions, but it has left the same old economic problems to be dealt with _ or dodged
biggest of these is the persistence of federal budget deficits in defiance of the candidates, who one and all declare it unconscionable that uncle sam should spend more than he receives
everyone knows what has to be done to balance the budget, but that's easy. the difficulty is in the accomplishment, and it is in that area, says the tax foundation, that the candidates have proved artful dodgers
declaring its astonishment at the wishful thinking that serves candidates in lieu of realistic tax and spending proposals, the foundation's ``shadow committee on the federal budget'' expresses despair
it suggests that the wishful, ``escapist'' thinking being expressed by the candidates might be setting the stage for even more deficits to come, perhaps even into the 21st century
to avoid the deficit issue, the group says, is to avoid not just the issue of the budget itself but of many challenges included in it, such as defense, space exploration, education, research, the role of government and dozens more
avoid the issue of the budget, and you avoid the issues that one would expect to be discussed in a presidential election year
what especially irritates the committee is that candidates have been churning out optimistic deficit projections that even a slight underperformance by the economy might subvert. in other words, committing the same old crime
with the structural deficit hovering around the $150 billion mark, it will not take much of a shortfall in economic performance to push the deficit to new record levels,'' it says
it is such evasion that created the deficits in the first place, and it was the continuation of such thinking, more so than poor economic performance, that perpetuated them
by avoiding the issues, americans became accustomed to the notion that, somehow, it was possible to have their cake and eat it, too. or, as president lyndon johnson put it, the nation could simultaneously have guns and butter
the latest evasion of the deficit issue was given almost official approval with the creation of an economic commission to recommend taxes and spending cuts designed to reduce the deficit. but its report won't come out until fall
once again, the harsh reality was pushed off into the future, allowing the candidates to discourse on more optimistic possibilities. but, says the foundation, that's dreaming
to begin with, the committee's march report states, there is little room for further cuts in defense spending, paring of grants to states and localities and reductions in the operating budgets of federal agencies
it points out that mandated payments for individuals, together with interest charges, now comprise more than 60 percent of total outlays, and those payments and interest charges are likely to increase in years ahead
these huge payments are also for existing needs, but there is a future to consider, too. and the future, always an unknown, is likely to present more possibilities for spending, and therefore more financial challenges
in the past, and it appears in the present, too, those challenges have not been met. and now they are being evaded by the very folks who want you to believe that it is they who should lead the nation into the future
poland has many crushing problems: burgeoning foreign debt, political dissension, inadequate social services. but the one that rankles poles the most is the telephone system
there aren't enough telephones to go around, but people who do have them find that if the phones themselves work, the system doesn't
one man said he dialed his office in warsaw three times in succession and each time reached a different number
at a community newspaper, a reporter picked up the office's only phone and got a dial tone
you are looking at a miracle,'' he said, holding up the receiver. ``it works.''
a westerner living in warsaw said her phone stopped working when workmen started digging in her neighborhood; she was told she would have to wait a month to have service restored
but the main thing is trying to get a telephone in the first place
more than 2 million applications for telephones are pending in poland and the list is growing faster than phones are being made and installed. the average waiting period is 13 years, but some have been waiting 20 years or more
like other areas of our economy, the situation is not satisfactory at the moment,'' said roman gebka, director of the telecommunications service for the state telephone and telegraph company
the basic problems now are a lack of equipment, a lack of cables ... and a lack of work force.''
poland has just 2.6 million telephone subscribers in its population of 37.5 million _ about 7 subscribers for each 100 people. subtract phones in offices and other public places, and that comes to just 1.8 million private phone customers
altogether poland has 11 actual telephone sets for every 100 people; the united states has 79, sweden 85, and great britain and west germany 51 each
in the countryside the problem is particularly acute. for 14.8 million poles in rural areas there are just 285,000 telephone subscriptions. and about 7,000 villages have no phones at all
but even people lucky enough to get phones have problems _ broken connections, buzzing or rattling noises on the line, mysterious misdirection of phone calls
not having a telephones is a fact of life in ursynow, a sprawling planned community of apartment blocks on the outskirts of warsaw. for its 135,000 people, it has 4,000 private telephones and 102 pay phones that often don't work. the commmunity eagerly awaits a central switching station that will allow 10,000 more phones
many poles do their telephoning while on the job, using the company phones. they also can try one of the nation's 85,000 pay phones, some of which work
hotel operators, restaurateurs and even private householders are usually willing to let others use their phones, for free or sometimes for a small fee
the cost of the lack of phones for poland's economy is very high and the prospects for any improvement soon are dim, gebka said in an interview in his office at the state telephone company in warsaw. he cited a soviet study that said one ruble invested in telephones led to three rubles in increased income
gebka said the ideal would be 20 million telephones in poland by the year 2000, or one for each of each of the 16 million to 17 million families expected by then, and the remainder for government and business
but he added that short of a miracle poland would not come near that goal. using all its currently available resources, poland can manage to install only about 150,000 phones a year
polish industry is as it is,'' he said. ``it produces as much as we are able to in this country. everything that the industry produces is being installed. there are no reserves.''
to step up production of telephone equipment and cable, he said, poland must build new factories
factories take five or six years to build and putting in additional telephone exchange stations takes about three more years, so it will take nearly a decade before poland can begin to speed up installations, gebka said
he also blamed part of the equipment shortage on the u.s.-led trade embargo that bans high-technology sales to the east bloc. poland's international calling capabilities are particularly hampered by the embargo, he said
the warsaw telephone exchange, which can handle up to 20,000 subscribers, is a long two-story building, about the size of an average elementary school in the united states. if poland had equipment using western microprocessors, the whole operation could fit into a single room, said janusz cienecki, the engineer in charge of the center
besides lacking the most sophisticated equipment, he said, the state-run telephone system has difficulty attracting qualified technicians because the starting pay is just 26,000 zlotys ($69) a month
a government report in february said more than 60 percent of the urban telephone systems are outdated and need modernization
communications minister antoni rajkiewicz has set a goal of adding 12 million new telephones in poland by 2010, but says it all hinges on increasing production capabilities of telephone equipment
in the meantime, most poles just wait
what shim min-sop is doing now conceivably could have landed him in jail not so long ago. he's drawing cartoons that poke gentle fun at south korean political leaders
and people are getting a laugh out of them, without worrying that something could happen to them as well
shim's cartoons seem tame by most standards. politicians and political parties are parodied as rival baseball teams and the jibes are never too strong. nevertheless, shim says, it is a remarkable change
in the past it was a taboo to caricature the big political names in this country,'' he said
ridiculing the president or making jokes about him, for example, were seen as anti-state acts
shim and other cartoonists have been able to take advantage of recent political liberalization in south korea to start injecting a little laughter and ridicule into politics
the cartoonists contend that political caricature is healthy and korean politics can benefit from it
cartoons and caricatures will bring the political leaders closer to the people,'' shim maintained
political cartoons have proliferated in newspapers and magazines and command large, enthusiastic audiences eager for a regular flow of material ranging from traditional editorial cartoons to long stories. literacy is very high in south korea but people prize cartoons for their humor
newspaper cartoons so far are low-key and ironic. some recent ones showed caricatures of the main political parties chasing each other in an unending circle, to symbolize ineffectiveness. another showed top leaders as squabbling babies
a favorite of cartoonists is to have bemused koreans staring at politicians battling for power and asking what is happening to the country
it is refreshing to see the taboos broken about the myths surrounding the political bigwigs,'' said han kye-su, a political analyst who has followed the growth of political cartooning
many cartoonists say they have always seen their work as a way of calling for reform and liberalization
korean cartoonists have been struggling for political change for a long time,'' shim said
cartoons are a valuable teaching tool that can vividly explain the meaning of an issue as well as amuse readers, shim added
the political cartoonist can present the issues in a more amusing, but understandable manner to the public.''
the newly installed president roh tae-woo, who pledged freedom of speech and expression after years of authoritarian rule, personally encouraged cartoonists to take up political subjects by saying he did not mind being caricatured
shim and other cartoonists say their work is still very gentle and restrained for fear of angering authorities and losing what freedom they have. but they say they expect to make their humor more biting as time goes on and liberalization expands
cartoonists are also restrained by fear of offending a politician's supporters, shim said. korea's factional politics stress loyalty and supporters tend to resent any joke at their leader's expense, he said
the reaction can be terrible from the supporters,'' shim said. ``people should learn to accept both positive and negative.''
anti-government students and dissident groups, which have long used cartoons in their political literature, also are making greater use of caricatures, but usually not in a humorous way
the cartoons distributed at anti-government rallies and meetings are biting and bitter. government and mainline opposition politicians are depicted as vicious tyrants suppressing the people with tear gas and clubs. some are more subtle, depicting the divided opposition leaders as crying infants quarreling over a toy
they are not jokes,'' said one dissident. ``they show the people the reality of the government and why there is no democracy in south korea.''
anti-government cartoons are distributed in pamphlets on college campuses or posted on trees and sidewalks at anti-government rallies
the united states, represented by a fiendish-looking uncle sam or a swaggering and bullying american soldier, is a fixture in the underground cartoons. dissidents claim the country's successive authoritarian governments have survived because of u.s. backing
one recent cartoon showed a tough-looking statue of liberty with a boxing glove on her upraised hand
shim and other cartoonists reject their underground competition and the radical politics behind it. they say change must be moderate
it's too early to expose politicians to a more revealing fashion,'' shim said
thirty-two years ago, roger vadim made the little-known brigitte bardot an international star with a movie called ``and god created woman.'' in 1988, the french director hopes to do the same with rebeccca demornay
not that the california-born, european-educated actress is unknown. she made a sensational film debut as the hooker who helped tom cruise conduct his ``risky business.'' roles in ``testament,'' ``runaway train,'' ``the trip to bountiful'' and other films have also been well reviewed
and god created woman'' provides her best role yet. and if you want to stay on her good side, don't suggest a comparison to how bardot played the role of a teen-age girl who was fatally attracted to men
there's really no relation between the two pictures,'' she insists. ``they have the same title and the same director. but really the title was used to get the film (financed) and really has no relation to the story or the characters.''
it's more a variation on the same theme than a remake,'' said vadim. ``what happened to a young girl at st. tropez in the south of france in 1956 can't really happen today in santa fe, n.m.''
vadim, who masterminded the careers of bardot, catherine deneuve and jane fonda and married bardot and fonda, was limited in his choice of a star for ``and god created woman'' because the producers, vestron, didn't want to go with an unknown
comparing her role to bardot's, was ``like comparing apples and oranges,'' demornay said. she outlined her own version of the character she played: ``robin is very mischievous, also naive and therefore funny a lot of the time. what attracted me to her was her strong streak of independent feminism. it might be disguised in her antics, but she really is a woman's woman.''
about vadim: ``he is great to work with, very perceptive, very sensitive to me as a woman. and as an actress and the protagonist in this film. it seemed very easy for him to identify with a woman, which is not easy for male directors. he's very laid-back and created an aura of relaxation on the set.''
the first ``and god created woman'' raised a furor among censors; the title was changed in italy, because the authorities ``didn't want god associated with such a film,'' vadim recalled
he still wonders what all the fuss was about: ``there was no nudity; bardot was naked only once and was covered by a sheet. i think the censors were infuriated because she played a woman who had no guilt about her sexuality.''
the 1988 version goes further with nudity and sex, though vadim insists he strove for a romantic feeling to the bedroom scenes. and eroticism presents no problem for demornay
i've done two women so far whose sexuality was part of the character,'' she said. ``robin in `and god created woman' was one of them (the other: `risky business'). it's delightful to me, if i can trust the sensibilities of the director, which i did, and if the scenes further the plot and illustrate facets of the character.''
are such scenes nervous-making on the set?
not to me,'' she said. ``it's as natural as anything else. i don't see this wall: `i'll do anything as an actress, but i won't express sexuality.' why not?''
the blond beauty was born in santa rosa, calif., 25 years ago but spent her childhood abroad. her parents divorced and her father is tv personality wally george
my stepfather died, and this made my mother restless,'' she said. ``she started to travel with both me and my brother. she was a very free-spirited, bohemian-type woman who thought a good education could be had by traveling and learning about new countries and cultures
so i lived in england for five years, in the austrian alps for seven years and in a lot of other countries in between for smaller amounts of time.''
returning to california in 1981, the actress enrolled at the lee strasberg theater institute, found an agent and won the ``risky business'' role over 800 applicants
surprisingly, the film didn't get her typed: ``i was lucky. most people seemed to view me as an actress playing the part of a call girl. i wasn't offered a lot of prostitute roles. i was able to play a young mother in `testament' with jane alexander. then `the trip to bountiful' with geraldine page. then a scruffy, tomboyish train mechanic in `runaway train.' so i've had good opportunities.''
what's next? she's brushing up on her shakespeare
a flutist with rubber lips, metal fingertips and not much else by way of physique is the latest graduate of the mcandroids laboratory in south london
being a robot and brand-new, it doesn't have a name yet, but its first public recitals will be given in september, when it goes on display at taiwan's new national museum of natural science
the flutist was born in the same cluttered workshop as tin twin, the guest keyboard player who thrilled teen-age fans of the thompson twins, a british pop group, on its 1986 world tour
like tin twin, the flutist is a robotized ``musician'' developed by mcandroids ltd., a special effects and 3-d animation team composed of two sculptors, a mechanical engineer and a computer artist
mcandroids' art and technology creations have been on display since 1984 in museums, traveling exhibitions and on tv shows across western europe
the flutist is going to t'aichung in taiwan along with a collection of musical instruments that visitors will be able to play without touching. set inside glass cases, the flute, organ, tubular bells, 16-string chinese zither and drum kit are activated by pressing buttons
it's very much a hands-on, discover for yourself exhibit,'' said sculptor richard glassborow. ``on one level it's entertainment; on another level it's seriously stimulating.''
the push buttons give spontaneous but precise control of the robotics that work the instruments. they can pluck out individual notes or create pulsating effects such as vibrato, tremolo or echo
musical phrases, such as a bass line, can be instantly recorded and the playback accompanied by improvisation. the instruments also can be commanded to play a simple preprogrammed tune
it was a choice to make it simple,'' said glassborow. ``if you make it very rich, they (the public) just stand and look at it. we wanted to make it very friendly.''
the flute's robotics are the most impressive, employing the head and pneumatically controlled fingers of a humanoid robot, or android. a valve controls the air that is pumped through the delicately positioned rubber mouthpiece into the lip plate
the instruments took three months to build and were sold to the designers of the museum's soundproof ``cacophony section'' for nearly $87,000
they demonstrate an individual's musical inventiveness and allow those without any musical skills to play music, according to glassborow
tin twin is a more readily recognizable android, with long arms that flit across the keyboard in simulating such smash hits of the thompson twins' as ``doctor doctor'' and ``sister of mercy.''
from a distance, the flashing lights in its eyes and outh give the impression that it is singing along in the chorus
mcandroids is made up of the 39-year-old glassborow; alan dun, a 37-year-old sculptor; engineer john barron, 34; and trevor piper, a 32-year-old artist. the company has found a niche in a fast-growing european market for special effects
in 1986, its three robotic ``french heads,'' composed of odd-shaped pieces of steel and glass fiber on top of tall poles, turned real heads at a robot sculpture display in the georges pompidou center in paris
vaguely resembling outer-space creatures, they turn to watch passers-by, stop and stare back, or babble among themselves in jolly jingles. a museum in glasgow, scotland, is negotiating for display rights
another favorite is a set of nine jack-in-the-box irish caricatures, including a priest, a bar wag and a politician, who pop up at the push of a button to give speeches on the environment. it was bought for an exhibition center in northern ireland's sperrin mountains
the company plans to build an android orchestra, a robotized skeleton riding a bicycle and a mechanical plant that will respond to temperature, light and human activity, such as people quarreling
anyone catching sight of the plant would say, `i know what it's thinking,''' said glassborow. ``this kind of work is a kind of mirror to human behavior.''
at the age of 19, reggae artist ziggy marley has seen enough of the world to know he wants to change it
i am not blind,'' marley says. ``even in jamaica, injustice happened. it happened all over the world. it means something all over the world.''
on the melody makers' new album, ``conscious party,'' marley sings of oppression, bigotry and hope for a better world
for anyone who follows reggae music, marley's political consciousness should come as no surprise. the late bob marley, ziggy's father, was reggae's most celebrated artist and famous for such protest songs as ``get up, stand up'' and ``i shot the sheriff.''
but while acknowledging the legacy of his father, ziggy marley is determined to establish his own identity. ``i want to be fulfilled myself rather than try to follow exactly in my father's footsteps.''
marley was born on october 17, 1968, in trenchtown, an impoverished section of kingston in jamaica. when he was 11, he formed the melody makers along with his brother, stevie, and sisters, cedella and sharon
the melody makers' first song, ``children playing in the streets,'' was written by their father. in 1985, they released their first album, ``play the game right,'' which received a grammy nomination for best reggae record. in 1986, they released the album ``hey world.''
we're brothers and sisters,'' marley said. ``doing music was part of being a family.''
hey world'' contained such overtly political songs as the anti-apartheid ``666,'' and on the new album, he continues to confront injustice with songs such as ``tomorrow people,'' the first single to be released
tomorrow people, think of your past,'' he sings, attacking those who think only of the future and their indifference to humanity
the original idea was from robots, like the movie `robocop' _ people becoming androids,'' marley said. ``scientists are making dangerous things.''
although ``conscious party'' is only marley's third album, he is already attracting the attention of some of the music industry's most highly acclaimed artists. talking heads members chris frantz and tina weymouth produced the record and rolling stones guitarist keith richards plays on the song ``lee and molly.''
lee and molly'' is a story about racial bigotry. lee is a white man who dates molly, a black woman, and is beaten up by his father because of the relationship. the song is based on an actual couple who went to high school in kingston with cedella marley. ``he (lee's father) thought going out with molly set a bad example,'' cedella recalled
ziggy marley identifies strongly with the people of africa. on ``tumbling down,'' he uses the symbols of the eagle, the bear and the lion to warn against the consequences of superpower oppression of the third world
the eagle is the united states and their allies. the bear is the soviet union because of what they've done in ethiopia and afghanistan,'' marley said. ``the lion is africa. bad things are done against my people. consequences will come down on you.''
marley also sings about africa on the ballad ``dream of home.''
home is africa,'' marley said. ``we know that's where we originated from. we have to get rid of (south african president p.w.) botha. through ourselves, our music, we fight apartheid
new love'' is the album's only love song, although it's more about the spiritual quality of love rather than a particular person
my love is always new; it shouldn't get boring,'' marley said. ``love can hurt you, like lee and molly. but new love is like the sun rising. like the morning dew.''
marley is a rastafarian and religion plays an important role in his life and music. on ``a who a sey,'' he attacks those who do not share his belief in a higher being
my religion is a way of life. if i please jah (god), i will please many more people,'' he said
the melody makers started touring in 1975 and have appeared at shows with stevie wonder, the clash, the late peter tosh and jimmy cliff. they performed at reggae sunsplash last august in jamaica. with a worldwide tour scheduled to begin in april, marley is anxious to play his new songs in front of a live audience
it's like relating to people. like me talking to you,'' marley said. ``that is where the people feel the music and feel with you. i'm dealing with people.''
marley hopes his music will help bring about his vision for a better world
we have the obvious,'' he said. ``no war. no pollution. a better life for human beings. no prejudice. everybody has an opportunity. everybody has the basic things
people say they live and then die. i don't believe in death. we believe in live and live. we believe in life. we are the people.''
probably the best development affecting the nation's beleaguered public schools is also among the least noticed: the growing alliance between educators and the business world
at a time when schools have been barraged by critics in the reagan administration and elsewhere, along comes burger king, honeywell, metropolitan life and others in the corporate community who not only are arguing public education's case, but are putting considerable money where their mouths are
a new book, ``american business and the public school: case studies of corporate involvement in public education'' (teachers college press, $24.95), offers a valuable, scholarly dissection of this budding relationship between these formerly estranged bedfellows, and it explodes several myths in the process
the 278-page book was edited by marsha levine, an official of the american federation of teachers, and roberta trachtman, affiliated with the city university of new york. their book argues that self-interest is too simple an explanation for the recent upsurge in corporate interest in better schools
business doesn't get involved in education just because it needs skilled workers,'' argues owen b. ``brad'' butler, retired chairman of procter &amp; gamble who wrote a foreward to the book
most big companies are multinational,'' butler said during a recent visit to new york. ``they can find the workers they need somewhere. the primary interest they have in better schools is that the united states is their home base, and business can't remain healthy unless the united states remains peaceful, prosperous and democratic.''
the book completes a trilogy of studies commissioned by the committee for economic development, a research organization dominated by top business executives which butler chairs. the two earlier reports, ``investing in our children,'' published in 1985, and ``children in need,'' published last september, were each front-page blockbusters
those previous reports, which called for such innovations as massive new governmental investments in programs to help the neediest students, forced all who had typecast business executives as socially callous arch-conservatives to reconsider
the latest book, while not as headline-making, will likely be the most enduring of the three. and like its predecessors, this report challenges some widely held notions about the nature of business-corporate partnerships
it offers, for the first time, useful detailed case histories of business-school partnerships that work, written by insiders. a key ingredient seems to be a new willingness on the part of business to enter such relationships as partners, rather than superiors
metropolitan life's chairman, john creedon, is presented as having ``profound respect for education and educators.'' the company's involvement in school reform has become renowned through, among other things, an annual survey of teacher attitudes it has conducted for the past several years
what's in it for met life? three things, according to the book: its view that it has obligations to the nation as a corporate citizen; its desire to ensure future employees have needed job skills; and a belief that well-informed citizens are better insurance risks
honeywell, the minneapolis-based computer firm, first became interested in education in the 1970s and decided that it had to help local school districts develop better curricula
in seattle, for example, honeywell employees invited citizens in snohomish county, wash., to figure out ways to ``prepare students for a high technology future in a low technology environment.'' the result is a school-business partnership dubbed link
burger king, meanwhile, has developed an awesome array of educational programs since 1983, from fast-food management courses, to scholarship programs and even a curriculum on crime prevention. the company also honors 100 principals and teachers each year. the budget for such programs has grown from $1.5 million in 1983 to $3.9 million in 1986. some 3,000 workers in 900 restaurants have benefitted from the programs
the long-term benefit we are seeking is a consistent, unified public perception of burger king as a good corporate citizen,'' writes burger king's barbara gothard. ``people come to burger king because of quality, service and value. but they are also influenced by their perception of how good is the company backing the product.''
seven or eight years ago, it was difficult to imagine that this would occur, that business and education would become so interested in each other,'' said c. michael timpane, president of columbia teachers college. ``now business isn't just looking at narrow job skills. they realize two things: that people change jobs, and jobs themselves change
when educators looked at that, they thought that this was very congenial. business was asking us to do what we wanted to do all along _ only better.'' for anyone interested in understanding one of the most heartening developments of the 1980s, this book is an excellent place to start
lee mitgang has covered education for the ap since 1981
jim horn has played on records by george harrison, frank sinatra and the beach boys. he's played in movies with elvis presley and spencer tracy
and he's played the theme songs for such tv shows as ``the odd couple'' and ``the courtship of eddie's father.''
harrison, the ex-beatle, recruited him for the historic 1971 concert and movie, ``concert for bangla desh.'' he was part of the famous ``mad dogs and englishmen'' concert tour in 1970 that propelled joe cocker to star status
the public may not have heard of jim horn, but in recording circles in the united states and europe he's a versatile instrumentalist
i've been around awhile and i've been able to do some things,'' he says modestly about his 25-year music career and a resume bulging with achievements
his specialty is the saxophone, but he also plays the flute, piccolo and recorder. over the years, he's played a multitude of other instruments while being associated with many of the top names in show business
he can be heard playing his horn on harrison's latest hit lp, ``cloud nine.''
his (harrison's) singing sounded better than ever,'' horn said in an interview before a recording session with country star hank williams jr. ``and when he plays, you know it's him _ that slide guitar.''
horn worked with another former beatle, paul mccartney, a year ago when mccartney helped produce an album by guitar legend duane eddy
he (mccartney) worked with the musicians well,'' he recalled. ``everyone knew what to do. he was real jovial and funny, cracking jokes. he was fun to work with.''
presley, too, was a free spirit when horn played in the movies ``girls, girls, girls'' and ``roustabout.''
he liked to sit around and play,'' horn said. ``he'd `jam.' he was into karate and he'd break wood when the producer and director weren't around. they didn't like him doing that.''
sinatra, for whom horn played flute on the hit ``strangers in the night,'' was businesslike and a quick worker
he'd rehearse once and then do one take,'' horn recalled. ``he made it relaxed. he was a real pro.''
it was horn's piccolo playing on the beach boys' hit ``good vibrations.''
people like their hawaiian shirts and visualize themselves on the sand with a beer in their hand,'' he said. ``the beach boys make fun music and they didn't let it die.''
horn, who lists his age as ``as old as the beatles,'' was born in compton, calif., and spent most of his life in los angeles. while living there, he played music in the movies ``guess who's coming to dinner'' starring tracy, katharine hepburn and sidney poitier, ``grease,'' ``footloose,'' ``shaft,'' ``stayin' alive'' and many others
he moved to nashville four years ago and is now working on his own album of sax instrumentals, ``neon nights.''
he learned how to play the piano at age 7, the trumpet at age 9 and the sax at age 12
the sax was a real popular instrument when i learned,'' he said. ``there was a sax solo on every record. i wanted my own band and wanted to be able to do solos. i thought they were a whole lot of fun.''
he said he correctly developed his talent and always worked to get better
i practiced a lot as a kid. i learned the proper way to play, then listened to albums, especially the sax solos, and played along with them. it gave me insight. i concentrated on my `ear.'''
even today, he's constantly updating his style and listening to music for trends
i hear songs on the radio and then i may change my style a little,'' horn said. ``but i have the same conviction. some musicians are lazy. they won't buy new equipment. you have to change with the times. it's easier to relate to music that way. i listen to pop and rock on the radio a lot and switch back and forth.''
he owns seven saxes, four flutes and five recorders. his most expensive instrument is a $4,000 baritone sax
despite his success, some instruments have given him trouble. he played the oboe and english horn for records by the carpenters, but later gave them up
they were too demanding,'' he said. ``you had to make your own double reeds. it was too time consuming.''
and he can't master the harmonica, which even school kids can play with little training
i'm trying,'' he admitted. ``i can't get the hang of it. i'm used to blowing out.''

born to be bad'' (rounder) _ george thorogood and the destroyers

albums are really superfluous for george thorogood and the destroyers. this is a bar band, and a very good one, whose music is best heard in a sweaty bar instead of a living room
but commerce calls. thorogood must fulfill a record contract, and ``born to be bad'' is the latest product
if ``born to be bad'' sounds a little familiar, it should. it comes six years after ``bad to the bone.'' what's next _ ``born to be bone?'' or ``born in the badlands?'' how about just plain ``bad?'' maybe that's too familiar
there aren't many things that distinguish ``born to be bad'' from any other george thorogood album since his 1977 debut. the band's sound has become fuller over the years with the addition of a saxophone player and a rhythm guitarist, but the content is largely the same
born to be bad'' has the obligatory chuck berry tune (``you can't catch me''), the traditional sinister guy song (title track), the dance floor stomper (``shake your money maker''), paens to the fairer sex (``i really like girls'') and some blues to highlight thorogood's mean guitar
familiarity doesn't have to breed contempt. the production is crisp and the playing inspired, so most of side 1 genuinely cooks. side 2 flags considerably because of the repetition and one slow blues song too many
do yourself a favor. save the money you may be inclined to spend on ``born to be bad'' until the destroyers happen to come to town. you shouldn't have to wait too long, although they may not duplicate their 1981 feat of playing in 50 states in 50 days. buy a ticket to the concert, grab a dance partner, and have fun
_ by david bauder, associated press writer


if my heart had windows'' (mca) _ patty loveless

patty loveless' new album consists of 10 songs, and the writing credit is different on each. but loveless' singing and the production of emory gordy jr. and tony brown make the album into a cohesive set that's as country as grits
if my heart had windows'' includes a honky-tonk waltz (the title cut, by dallas frazier); country swing (hank williams' ``i can't get you off of my mind''); and plenty of ballads
loveless' full-throated alto really hits its stride on side 2, climaxing on john and johanna hall's ``fly away,'' which lives up to its name with a soaring chorus reminiscent of the halls' defunct pop group, orleans
the arrangements, built around the solid rhythm section of leland sklar and eddie bayers, include such nice touches as a steel and fiddle playing in unison on the break of ``i can't get you off of my mind.'' the material occasionally sags, but most of the album contains strong and honest performances
_ by steven wine, associated press writer
stand and deliver'' is a kind of thinking man's ``rocky'': melodramatic, full of street-level emotion, with a knockout of an ending that may even convince you that good can occasionally triumph against implausible odds
but what's so special about this movie is that the knockout is scored not with fists, but with the power of young minds
it is an inner city classroom drama based on true events at garfield high school in the east los angeles barrio, a failing school so tough it faced losing its accreditation in 1982
into this mess strides jaime escalante (edward james olmos), a computer specialist who has dropped out of the business world to be a teacher. his first surprise is that the school has no computers. he is assigned to a math class
olmos, whose previous credits include ``zoot suit,'' and an emmy award-winning role as lt. castillo on the tv series ``miami vice,'' is quietly charismatic as a teacher capable of sparring with and inspiring a class of tough hispanic youngsters _ the sort of kids current fashion holds should be ranted at with bullhorns, or expelled
lou diamond phillips, appealing though a bit goody-goody as the late rock sensation richie valens in ``la bamba,'' gives a more complex performance this time around as a wonderfully understated angel, a street gang member finally won over by his dedicated teacher
thanks largely to the crisp direction of ramon menendez, who also co-wrote the screenplay with producer tom musca, it is refreshing to see streetwise, underprivileged children presented as something other than one-dimensional, unreachable monsters
escalante wins over angel and the others with tough humor and personal contact. when they taunt him, he aims his retorts back with devastating accuracy
tough guys don't do math, they fry chicken for a living,'' he tells one macho student
and he relates lessons to his students' ethnic heritage: ``it was your ancestors, the mayans, who first contemplated the concept `zero.' you have math in your blood.''
then he gets a crazy idea: he's going to teach these kids calculus. if they can pass the advanced placement calculus test that would be an almost guaranteed ticket to college and scholarships
what follows is an all-too-authentic portrayal of how a single dedicated teacher is alone in believing that his students can make it. he must face down skeptical parents, fellow teachers _ even investigators from the educational testing service in princeton, n.j
in the end, the students do succeed, but only after a bitter and racist battle with test officials who simply can't accept that barrio kids could perform so well. the school rises from disgrace to national prominence
the ``dedicated-teacher-conquers-tough-kids'' plot is not new to hollywood. glenn ford faced down student sidney poitier in ``the blackboard jungle'' in 1955, and poitier reversed roles as the dedicated teacher in ``to sir with love'' in 1967
stand and deliver'' far exceeds those films in authenticity and dramatic punch. ``stand and deliver'' delivers
the warner bros. release is rated pg
motion picture association of america rating definitions:
g _ general audiences. all ages admitted
pg _ parental guidance suggested. some material may not be suitable for children
pg-13 _ special parental guidance strongly suggested for children under 13. some material may be inappropriate for young children
r _ restricted. under 17 requires accompanying parent or adult guardian
x _ no one under 17 admitted. some states may have higher age restrictions
lee mitgang has covered education for the ap since 1981
consumers have regained virtually all the confidence they lost as a result of the october stock market crash, according to a new survey
the conference board said monday its consumer confidence index was 113.9 points in february, up from january's 109.9 points. the index, which uses a 1985 base of 100, stood at 115.1 in october, before the oct. 19 stock collapse
in a separate report, the business research concern's help wanted index painted a somewhat less optimistic picture. the index, which reflects the amount of help wanted ads in 51 major newspapers across the nation, declined to 153 in january from 155 in december
a significant number of american companies will bolster hiring this spring, according to a leading temporary job service
manpower inc. said monday its employment outlook survey indicated 29 percent of respondents plan to raise employment rolls in the april-june quarter, while 6 percent expect declines. sixty-two percent plan no change and 3 percent don't know, the survey stated
americans took out $5.42 billion more in installment debt than they paid off in january, the biggest monthly increase in four months and the second strong month in a row, the government says
the federal reserve said monday that consumer credit grew at a seasonally adjusted rate of 10.6 percent in january, following an increase of $3.98 billion in december, which translated to an annual rate of 7.9 percent
growth in both months was greater than the 5.9 percent rate for all of 1987, which represents a considerable slowdown compared with recent years. the rate was 10.5 percent in 1986
takeover specialist carl c. icahn, texaco inc.'s largest shareholder, has thrown his support behind the company's plan to emerge from bankruptcy court protection
icahn also promised monday to drop his effort get himself and four allies elected to texaco's board of directors if its management would agree to put the nation's third-largest oil company up for sale for a minimum of $55 per share
icahn is believed to have bought his 14.8 percent stake in texaco at prices averaging in the mid- to high-$30s per share
mobil corp. plans to sell its montgomery ward division for $3.8 billion to an investor group led by the man credited with restoring the 115-year-old department store chain to profitability
a group headed by montgomery ward president bernard brennan will acquire the nation's eighth-largest retailer in a leveraged buyout, it was announced monday
the proposal calls for brennan's group to pay more than $1.5 billion in cash for the chicago-based retailer and assume $2.3 billion of its debt
italian tire manufacturer pirelli has launched a $1.86 billion offer for firestone tire &amp; rubber co., urging firestone to scrap a plan to sell 75 percent of its tire-making business to bridgestone of japan
pirelli said monday that its offer of $58 a share in cash for firestone's 32 million common shares outstanding was contingent on firestone's dropping the tentative agreement reached with bridgestone just three weeks ago
chicago-based firestone, which ranks third among u.s. tiremakers, declined comment on the offer
general electric co. is attempting to buy roper corp., which only last month signed a merger agreement with whirlpool corp
the ge offer, disclosed monday, is $45 a share, or $423 million, for roper's 9.4 million common shares outstanding. whirlpool had bid $37.50 a share, or $352.5 million
the offer marks the first time ge, a major manufacturer with interests in finance and broadcasting, has made an unsolicited offer for a company
american standard inc. says its board of directors will consider the latest hostile buyout offer from black &amp; decker corp. and indicated it might sweeten its own alternative plan a second time
american standard, a plumbing and air conditioning maker, made the announcement monday after sweetening its defensive recapitalization plan to $2.3 billion last week
black &amp; decker is offering $73 a share for american standard's 31 million common shares outstanding, or a total of about $2.26 billion
lorimar-telepictures corp., a television program supplier that has been losing money, says it is discussing the possibility of being acquired by warner communications inc
lorimar, the product of a merger two years ago, said monday it was approached by new york-based warner and preliminary talks were under way ``to explore the desirability of a business combination.''
lorimar said its board has made no decision as to whether such a deal would be in the best interests of shareholders
the supreme court has handed investors a victory, placing a heavy burden of proof on companies sued for denying they are holding merger negotiations after informal talks have begun
by a 4-2 vote, the supreme court said monday if companies withhold important information affecting stock prices, it must be presumed that investors who bought and sold the securities were relying on that information
separately, the high court agreed to hear a reagan administration appeal aimed at allowing the government to take a bigger tax bite out of some corporate mergers
a federal judge has cleared the way for the regional bell telephone companies to offer certain new computerized information services, including voice storage and electronic mail
but u.s. district judge harold greene, in a 66-page decision, refused monday to retreat from an earlier decision in which he said phone companies could transmit information but could not generate or manipulate the content of the information
the stock market drifted aimlessly monday in a quiet session that saw the dow jones average of 30 industrials slip 1.49 to 2,056.37
bond prices moved modestly lower while interest rates were little changed
the dollar drifted lower against most major currencies
livestock and meat futures prices rose sharply, energy futures fell, grains and soybeans were mostly higher and precious metals retreated. conflict</head>
new reports indicate consumers have increased their borrowing pace and have regained nearly all the confidence they lost as a result of the october stock market crash
two other reports on the employment outlook came to seemingly conflicting conclusions, with the conference board reporting indications of lessening demand for workers and manpower inc. _ a temporary employment concern _ projecting strong hiring this spring
in the consumer credit report, the federal reserve said americans took out $5.42 billion more in installment debt than they paid off in january, the biggest monthly increase in four months and the second strong month in a row
the fed said consumer credit grew at a seasonally adjusted rate of 10.6 percent in january compared to a 7.9 percent annual rate in december and a 5.9 percent rate for all of 1987
consumer credit is regarded as a reflection of trends in consumer spending, which accounts for about two-thirds of u.s. economic growth
consumers apparently are willing to borrow because unemployment was down _ it hit a nine-year low of 5.7 percent in february _ and consumer confidence is rebounding, according to david cross, an economist with the futures group, a washington consulting firm
the conference board, in issuing its monthly consumer confidence index, said consumers have been heartened by continuing strength in the economy
but the private business research organization said consumers also may be feeling more optimistic because their paychecks are larger because of tax cuts that took effect jan. 1
the consumer confidence index was 113.9 points in february, up from january's 109.9 points and 100.8 in november, after the crash
the index, which uses a 1985 base of 100, stood at 115.1 in october, before the oct. 19 stock collapse
the conference board's help wanted index painted a somewhat pessimistic picture of the employment outlook. the index, which reflects the amount of help wanted ads in 51 major newspapers across the nation, declined to 153 in january from 155 in december
the index, which uses a 1967 base of 100, reflects changes in demand for labor and general business conditions
kenneth goldstein, a conference board economist, said the drop in the index signaled a slowdown in hiring plans by employers
in contrast, manpower said a significant number of american companies will bolster hiring this spring
manpower said its employment outlook survey indicated 29 percent of respondents plan to raise employment rolls in the april-june quarter, while 6 percent expect declines. sixty-two percent plan no change and 3 percent don't know, the survey stated
mitchell s. fromstein, manpower's president, said it was the company's strongest spring hiring forecast in four years and suggested manufacturers in all regions of the country are unusually buoyant about the economy
crude oil futures have retreated in response to renewed fears of opec price discounting
on the new york mercantile exchange, contracts for april delivery of west texas intermediate crude oil settled at $15.37 per 42-gallon barrel on monday, down 22 cents from friday's close of $15.59
among refined products, the april contract for wholesale no. 2 heating oil slid 0.13 cent to 43.41 cents. wholesale unleaded gasoline fell 0.57 cent to 43.94 cents a gallon
i think the catalyst behind today's decline is additional rumors about opec individual nations offering discounts to customers,'' said william byers, an oil analyst with bear, stearns &amp; co
byers said the rumors of price discounting by members of the organization of petroleum exporting countries partly grew out of reports that a delegation from the united arab emirates was visiting tokyo this week
the rumors are really all over the map,'' he said
reports that opec might push for more production controls helped boost prices on friday. shareholder suits</head>
a new supreme court ruling regarding when companies must disclose merger discussions could lead to fewer mergers and hinder corporate competitiveness, according to some legal experts
in the same ruling handed down monday, the court affirmed for the first time a key legal theory strengthening shareholder ability to sue a company for fraud. approval of the so-called fraud-on-the-market theory could spawn a wave of new lawsuits by disgruntled shareholders, lawyers speculated
the ruling stemmed from a case that attracted enormous attention because it raised questions about a company's legal responsibilities regarding disclosure of information that could affect its stock price, including preliminary merger negotiations with another company
the case was considered especially significant because of the wave of mergers that have reshaped corporate america over the past several years. the ability of a company's management to negotiate quickly and discreetly before disclosing a merger proposal has played a key role in that trend
from a company's point of view, the supreme court's ruling certainly is going to make life more difficult,'' said john f. olson, a prominent washington securities lawyer at the firm of gibson, dunn &amp; crutcher. ``it will make companies a lot more cautious about what they say publicly. you're going to see a lot more `no comments.'''
advocates of disclosing merger talks, including the securities and exchange commission, argue that such information is vital to the efficiency and integrity of the financial markets, as reflected by a company's stock price
opponents, including many corporate executives, argue that premature disclosure of merger talks can artificially inflate stock prices, cause a deal to collapse and alert potentially hostile acquirers to a hitherto unknown buyout opportunity
the supreme court's ruling concerned basic inc., a cleveland-based concern that merged with another company in 1978 after its executives denied for months that merger talks were under way
some shareholders who had sold their stock prior to the merger sued the company for fraud, contending its denials of talks had deflated the price. if they had known about the talks, the shareholders argued, they wouldn't have sold
basic executives contended they weren't obligated to disclose the merger talks until they had reached a fundamental agreement
the supreme court rejected both sides' arguments and ordered a separate test for when a company must disclose merger talks. that test measures the probability of whether a merger will occur and must be considered on a case-by-case basis, the court said
attorneys said it was difficult to predict the ultimate consequences of the court's ruling but agreed it could pose serious new problems, particularly in defining the probability of a merger
it's vague in the sense it makes life very difficult,'' said william golub, an attorney for the new york firm of rosenman &amp; colin, which represented basic
at what point does someone decide a merger is probable? the consequence is you either have to say everything, or else you can say `no comment,''' he said
if the chief executives of two companies talk about a merger on the golf course, that doesn't necessarily mean it's probable. but if the issue has to be resolved 10 years later by a jury, it may decide yes, that golf-course meeting was the point of probability,'' golub said
carl liggio, a new york securities lawyer who filed a legal brief on behalf of the defendants, said the high court's ruling could hurt companies and their shareholders
the problem is that when you put businesses in a fishbowl, as you do with hindsight standards of materiality and disclosure, it makes them less competitive,'' liggio said. ``it's more difficult for them to conduct business.''
of possibly more significance, some attorneys said, was the court's endorsement of the fraud-on-the-market theory, which holds that stockholders rely on the the presumed honesty of the market to set a fair price
under this theory, stockholders can sue a company for damages by proving they bought or sold during a time in which the company gave false information or withheld news from the market that would have affected its stock price
although lower courts generally have accepted the theory since its inception in the mid-1970s, this was the first time the high court sanctioned its validity
this is more significant in terms of exposure to litigation,'' golub said. ``it just means this type of lawsuit will continue to grow.''
takeover strategist carl c. icahn says he will keep pressuring texaco inc. to put itself up for sale, but also will support the company's plan for emerging from bankruptcy reorganization
icahn, texaco's largest shareholder, said monday he would drop his attempt to win five seats on texaco's board of directors if the oil giant voluntarily puts itself up for sale at $55 a share
i'm not looking to run texaco. i am looking to enhance all shareholders' value,'' said icahn, who owns 14.8 percent of texaco's stock
icahn is believed to have purchased his stake at prices averaging in the mid- to high- $30 per share range. the stock closed monday at $44.37{, unchanged from friday
icahn met with reporters monday after appearing before a closed meeting of the council of institutional investors, which includes representatives of more than 50 pension funds
among others appearing before the group was texaco's president, james w. kinnear, who said takeover talk stirred by the activities of icahn and others was hampering the company's efforts to restructure itself and prepare for its emergence from chapter 11 bankruptcy protection
kinnear said texaco is continuing its efforts to sell unprofitable assets and negotiate partnership agreements on other properties. in addition, the company is seeking short-term loans to help pay creditors when it emerges from bankruptcy protection, which it expects to do in april
we have found that as we go to these negotiations and go to get bank loans, the very presence of corporate raiders makes it very difficult to get the job done,'' kinnear said. ``the banks are terrified. the co-venture partners are concerned.''
icahn said the ``real problem'' was that texaco's management was not sufficiently accountable to its shareholders
he said he would vote for the reorganization plan ``because that's what the shareholders want.'' but he reiterated his dissatisfaction with what he called texaco's ``take-it-or-leave-it plan _ which shareholders must accept or see the company blown up.''
the white plains, n.y.-based company filed for bankruptcy court protection last april to avoid having to post a potentially ruinous bond while appealing a $10.3 billion judgment held against it by pennzoil co
a houston jury awarded the judgment to pennzoil in 1985 after finding texaco interfered with pennzoil's 1984 attempt to acquire part of getty oil co., which texaco later acquired itself
texaco's shareholders have until march 21 to vote on a reorganization plan that would bring the company out of bankruptcy protection and pay a $3 billion out-of-court settlement with pennzoil
earlier this year, icahn failed to win permission from bankruptcy court judge howard schwartzberg on a separate plan that was basically the same but would have stripped away texaco's takeover defenses
icahn later said he would run a slate of five candidates _ including himself _ when the seats come up for a vote at the next texaco annual meeting, expected to take place in may
he has gained the support of another noted takeover strategist, t. boone pickens, also has accumulated texaco shares
icahn said monday he wanted the board seats so he could push his efforts to persuade other board members sell the company voluntarily
if you want to see friendly bids, you'll see plenty. if hostile, i have no idea. (but) if bids start at $55 and if they couldn't get that _ if it couldn't be done in a friendly basis _ i'll agree i was wrong and i'll withdraw my slate,'' he said
wilbur ross, an adviser to texaco's shareholders bankruptcy committee, who also appeared at the meeting, predicted the reorganization plan would be approved overwhelmingly
the mail we've gotten (from small investors) has been running nine or 10 to one in favor,'' he said. ``i don't know of any institutions not in favor _ and the institutions own 40-to-50 percent of the stock.''
potential buyers from italy, canada and the united states are setting their sights on several corporate targets, apparently undaunted by merger agreements that the managements of those targets have reached with other suitors
the moves by general electric co., italy's pirelli societe generale sa and canada's campeau corp. are somewhat reminiscent of texaco inc.'s ill-fated purchase of getty oil co. in 1984
texaco has been in federal bankruptcy court since last april, where it sought refuge rather than post a potentially ruinous bond of more than $10 billion to appeal a texas court's ruling that it illegally had interfered in an agreement by pennzoil co. to buy part of getty
in the past, you fought tooth and nail up to when the company accepted a bid, and once a company accepted a bid it was on to the next game,'' said daniel schwartz, managing director of ulmer brothers inc., a merchant banking firm that specializes in mergers and acquisitions
but clearly that doesn't seem to be the rule anymore,'' he said
ge and pirelli announced their offers monday, while campeau took action last week
the new bidders feel they are on solid legal ground. they all are appealing directly to shareholders of the target companies instead of asking the companies' directors to back out of any agreements
texaco got in trouble because getty was privately-owned, so for texaco to take it over it had to get the getty directors to back out of their deal with pennzoil. texaco argues that getty's deal with pennzoil was not legally binding, but has reached a tentative $3 billion out-of-court settlement of the dispute
the new offers include these deals:
_pirelli offered $1.86 billion for firestone tire &amp; rubber co. on monday even though firestone agreed last month to combine its core tire-making operations with those of japan's bridgestone corp. in a joint venture. pirelli said its offer was contingent on firestone calling off its deal with bridgestone
_general electric, making what it called its first unsolicited takeover bid, offered $423 million monday for roper corp., even though the augusta, ga.-based appliance maker has agreed to be acquired by whirlpool corp. for $352.5 million
_campeau corp., the canadian retailing giant, is pressing its months-long pursuit of cincinnati-based federated department stores inc., despite federated's definitive agreement last week to be acquired by r.h. macy &amp; co. for $6.1 billion. campeau has an outstanding $6.18 billion offer
because of texaco's experience, ``lawyers and their clients are much more careful to not put themselves in a position where someone could claim interference with someone else's agreement,'' said klaus eppler, a partner in the law firm of proskauer rose goetz &amp; mendelsohn
by going straight to the shareholders, the bidders cannot be accused of asking the directors to renege on previous agreements, eppler said
the three offers signify that deals actually are not complete until a buyer's tender offer expires and the acquiring company can actually buy the shares
i'm somewhat at a loss as to why all of a sudden this type of behavior is now acceptable,'' schwartz said
it used to be when you had a done deal, you didn't have people coming in with tender offers. but you've got three of them right here,'' he said
but although the flurry of such deals may be unusual, buyers and sellers typically make arrangements for such eventualities. for example, macy's agreement to buy federated requires federated to pay up $45 million in so-called ``breakup fees'' to macy in the event their deal falls through under certain circumstances
such provisions typically are aimed at discouraging other bidders from making a play for a company that has agreed to be bought out by someone else
a planned management-led buyout of montgomery ward &amp; co. will close mobil corp.'s ill-fated venture into retailing, while giving the venerable retailer a chance to reap all the benefits of its recent successes
montgomery ward said monday that an investor group led by president and chief executive bernard brennan would acquire the company from mobil in a $3.8 billion leveraged buyout
the group, which also includes general electric capital corp., will pay more than $1.5 billion in cash for the 115-year-old, chicago-based company and assume $2.3 billion of its debt
this is a historic day for montgomery ward,'' brennan told a news conference. ``we've gone through an awful lot over the years. ``in 1987, we earned $130 million after taxes. in 1980, we had $162 million loss after taxes.''
faced with a financial drain from the retailer during the early 1980s, mobil _ which acquired montgomery ward in 1976 for about $1 billion _ has wanted to sell the chain for some time. brennan, credited with turning the retailer around in recent years, had been negotiating for months to acquire the company
it's a business that we don't know too well,'' said mobil chairman allen e. murray. he also said new york-based mobil, the nation's second-largest oil company, believed it would be best to concentrate on its core businesses
murray said in a telephone interview monday that mobil began receiving inquiries about montgomery ward last summer, but declined to identify the other parties interested in buying the retailer
mobil stock rose $1.12{ to $44.75 in new york stock exchange trading on monday
brennan said ge capital, a unit of general electric co., will take over ward's credit-card operation
in a leveraged buyout, investors borrow heavily to buy out a company and then pay off the debt with the target company's cash flow or the sale of its assets
but brennan said the company has no plans to sell other assets or to lay off any employees under the buyout plan, which takes effect in 60 days
we see no need at this time to reduce employment. for example, in chicago, we've added 300 jobs in the last six months,'' brennan said
this is not a leveraged buyout that says, `let's shrink the company.'''
during its comeback effort, montgomery ward laid off 17,000 employees, closed its jefferson ward discount stores and other unprofitable branches, and shut down the catalog division that dated back to the company's early days
it moved into specialty retailing, opening appliance and electronics stores, and is converting its department stores to emphasize specialty formats including electronics, home furnishings and recreational items
last month, montgomery ward announced it was realigning its field-office management to create new specialty retailing positions
our customers are middle america. we don't want to be too avant garde, and we don't want to be downscale.'' said brennan, a former executive of chicago-based sears, roebuck and co
consumers have the advantage that we have people running the business that owns the business,'' brennan said. ``independence gives us much more flexibility.''
mobil has not indicated what it would do with the money from the sale. energy analyst bruce lazier, of the investment firm prescott, ball &amp; turben, said he believed corporate capital investment will receive the largest share
my guess is that, that will reduce their short-term debt and that gives them an extra $2 billion of funds available number one for reinvestment in capital expenditures if the opportunities arise and, number two, gives them flexibility to increase dividends and share repurchase plans,'' lazier said in a telephone interview
martin l. longstreth jr., who worked his way up from clerk to chairman of the philadelphia stock exchange, has died of cancer. he was 42
longstreth died in his home sunday, just 2{ months after he was diagnosed as having cancer, his family said
the stock exchange board will name a successor within several months, president nick giordano said monday
after graduating from villanova university in 1967 with a bachelor of science degree, longstreth spent two years in an executive training program with a philadelphia bank before entering the securities business
he spent a year in the retail end of the business before becoming a clerk on the floor of the philadelphia exchange
longstreth worked as an options special and floor broker from 1972 to 1980. he served as senior vice president of the philadelphia stock exchange from 1974-75, in charge of floor surveillance for equities and options. he was named chairman of the exchange in march 1984
he is survived by his wife, francis, and nine children
gillette co. is urging its shareholders to reject an attempt by a new york-based investment partnership to oust four company directors at next month's annual meeting
colman mockler jr., gillette's chairman and chief operating officer, said in a statement mailed monday to shareholders that coniston partners intended to sell or dismantle gillette if the hostile takeover succeeds
the principals of coniston group have no experience in directing or running a worldwide manufacturing or consumer goods company as an ongoing enterprise,'' stated mockler. ``the board of directors believes that the objective of coniston group is to force the immediate sale or dismemberment of gillette.''
coniston controls 6.76 million gillette shares, or about 5.8 percent of the company's shares outstanding, and has indicated it wanted the company to boost its stock price either by restructuring or negotiating a merger with another party
mockler contended the company's major restructuring in 1986, the result of repeated takeover attempts by revlon group inc., had helped enhance shareholder values. mockler said gillette's earnings per share rose a record 41 percent in 1987
coniston, through two subsidiaries, is seeking to solicit a majority of shareholders to elect four nominees to the gillette board at the april 21 meeting in boston. one of the seats up for election is mockler's
gillette shares rose 12{ cents to close at $40.75 monday on new york stock exchange trading
gus oliver, a principal of coniston partners, said letters explaining the group's proposal should be mailed to shareholders later this week
monday was the final day for shareholders to qualify to vote at the annual meeting
gillette underwent a major restructuring after rebuffing a third hostile takeover bid by revlon, which agreed not to seek to gain control of gillette under a 10-year pact signed in november 1986
following the accord, gillette laid off about 2,400 workers and sold off a several sudsidiaries and discontinued unprofitable divisions, including a line of high-quality writing instruments and 28 percent interest in eye world stores
gillette spokesman david fausch said further cutbacks in some international operations, such as cosmetics and beauty aids, are planned as part of the restructuring
coniston last year was instrumental in forcing a major restructuring of allegis corp., the parent of united airlines
separately on monday, gillette said it had received notification that new york real estate developer donald trump had received federal trade commission clearance to increase his holdings of the company's stock
trump now may purchase up to 24.9 percent of gillette's stock. trump owns about 400,000 shares, which was less than three-tenths of 1 percent of gillette's 115 million common shares outstanding
a gillette statement monday said the company has not received any communications from trump
a financial restructuring of shoney's inc. means $730 million for stockholders who will receive one-time dividends of $20 in cash and stock for each of their shoney's shares, officials said
this is not giving up, this is a fresh start,'' according to mitchell boyd, vice chairman and chief executive officer of the nashville-based restaurant chain
financing of the recapitalization will be through cash and about $600 million in bank borrowings through a syndicate headed by the canadian imperial bank of commerce, boyd said sunday
shareholders will receive $16 per share in cash and a subordinated debenture with a face value of $4 for each share of shoney's stock they own, and will retain ownership of the stock
shareholders will not receive dividends but will receive interest of 48 cents on each note, compared to the 18 cents per share dividends received last year
company chairman ray danner, who started the 1,400-restaurant chain in 1959, stands to receive about $110 million in cash for his 6.9 million shares. retired senior chairman alex schoenbaum, founder of the concept, owns about 3.2 million shares and would receive about $51 million
the two own 28 percent of the outstanding stock of shoney's, which had revenue last year of $694 million
shareholder approval is not required for the plan, but the board of directors decided sunday to submit the proposal to shareholders because of its massive scope
the recapitalization plan is designed to shift the company's emphasis from growth through physical expansion to growth through improved profit margins at existing locations, boyd said
the plan will also allow the founders to cash out, while leaving them as major owners of the stock for the next few years, and provide incentives to the second generation of top management, boyd said
the plan permits executives to immediately cash in all outstanding stock options and would set aside an additional 1 million shares for management stock options over the next several years, allowing management to own up to 17 percent of the company
president miguel de la madrid urged producers and businesses to hold down prices this month, saying it ``will be decisive for the success'' of his anti-inflation program
our goal is not only to reduce inflation in march, but to continue dominating this harmful phenomenon the rest of the year,'' the president said monday in a speech broadcast nationwide over radio and television
de la madrid said his program, called the economic solidarity pact, had brought down inflation, allowed for a budget surplus and reduced government use of public credit, bringing down interest rates
inflation for february is expected to be about 8 percent, or about half the 15.5 percent registered in january, he said. consumer prices rose 8.7 percent in the first half of february and inflation was a record 159.2 percent in 1987
today i can affirm with satisfaction that the basic commitments of the pact are being fulfilled by ... workers, businessmen and the government,'' he said
he said the government had increased its income while cutting spending through reinforced austerity measures
the budget surplus, not counting debt service payments, meant the government used less public credit and lightened pressure on interest rates, he said
the minimal variation in the value of the peso currency against the dollar from december 15 to february 21 also helped reduce inflation, he said
the peso stood monday at 2,330 to the dollar on the free market, compared with 2,286 a month ago. the rate is used for tourism and most border transactions. a second rate, the controlled rate, used for 75 percent of all transactions, closed at 2,241 to the dollar, compared with 2,205 a month ago
with the start of the second phase of the plan march 1, treasury secretary gustavo petricioli announced that both rates, which had been sliding against the dollar, would remain unchanged this month
prices of government price-controlled items, which include gasoline, electricity and basic foods, were frozen for the month and a wage increase for the month held to 3 percent, below what had been expected
the minimum wage rose march 1 to 8,000 pesos a day or about $3.50
budget secretary pedro aspe told a meeting of state financial officials on sunday that the stabilization of the economy now was ``within reach.''
letting up on the inflation fight, he said, would mean a reversal of the gains achieved so far
aspe told the state financial officials that the government's program did not constitute a ``shock'' plan, the name given to drastic measures taken by brazil and argentina to rid their economies of hyper-inflation
mexico's plan, he said, does not include a ``generalized control of prices and salaries'' such as other countries have imposed
a federal judge will decide after reviewing a psychiatrist's report whether an arbitrageur accused of plotting to kill convicted stock speculator ivan f. boesky should be turned over to a psychiatric facility in new jersey
u.s. district judge whitman knapp extended an order monday placing john a. mulheren in manhattan's metropolitan correctional center, a federal detention facility, until wednesday, when knapp is to examine the report of the psychiatrist, dr. naomi goldstein
detention hearings were being held to determine if mulheren should be released on bail, held by federal authorities or turned over to a psychiatric facility recommended by his attorneys
late saturday, u.s. district judge pierre leval ordered mulheren to remain at the mcc after federal magistrate kathleen a. roberts ordered earlier in the day that mulheren be released to the carrier foundation in new jersey
the government had argued that the new jersey facility was not secure enough to hold mulheren, senior partner at jamie securities co
mulheren, 38, of rumson, n.j., was detained feb. 18 on a federal criminal complaint that he threatened to kill boesky, a central figure in the government's investigation of insider trading on wall street, and michael davidoff, boesky's former head trader
according to police reports, mulheren was carrying weapons and ammunition while making threats against the men, who might be witnesses against mulheren
we feel he has to be in a secure facility. there's a real possibility mr. mulheren will get out and do it again,'' the assistant u.s. attorney handling the case, robert gage, told the court
mulheren's lawyers argue that he is a manic-depressive who had failed on the day of his arrest to take lithium, a drug prescribed to control extreme mood swings and impulses
at the hearing, they presented testimony from the arresting police officers who had grown up with mulheren and other testimony that indicated mulheren was a model citizen and not a threat to society
defense attorneys also said they were concerned about mulheren's health and wanted him where he could receive better care
knapp initially appeared to be against having mulheren examined by a psychiatrist. but he later changed his mind and ruled that mulheren should be examined by goldstein, a manhattan psychiatrist with whom knapp is familiar and whom the government had suggested
goldstein will be allowed to review mulheren's records and interview his attorneys and wife. however, knapp stipulated that information from the psychiatrist would not be used in a court unless the trial judge so ordered. information from the wife was not to be used in court at all
at the 2 p.m. hearing wednesday, knapp will review the initial impressions of goldstein about mulheren's behavior potential and decide whether to send the case back to roberts or send the defendant to the new jersey facility
a federal judge says he'll order new delegate elections at 68 united auto workers local unions in the southwest following reports of irregulatites in the campaign and election
u.s. district judge richard suhrheinrich said monday new elections will be ordered in the contested 1986 race between incumbent uaw region 5 director kenneth worley and his top assistant, jerry tucker
tucker was fired after he announced in may 1986 that he was entering the race against worley. tucker lost by two-tenths of a vote, but nearly 27 votes in the contest were challenged
the u.s. department of labor investigated the election and filed three lawsuits against the uaw, charging that some illegal delegates voted in the august election, that tucker was fired illegally and that worley illegally used union money for an individual campaign
worley spent $13,000 in union money to buy jackets for delegates to the uaw's constitutional convention in august 1986, where they voted for regional directors and other union officers. the jackets bore the region's number and worley's name
members in other regions bought their own jackets, as did tucker's region 5 supporters, said tucker's attorney, joseph yablonski
the labor department investigation also found that worley sent out campaign fliers typed on a uaw typewriter on uaw stationary in a uaw office, which also is illegal for an individual's campaign, said labor department attorney janet graney
the uaw declined comment until it receives the order
the order, requiring new delegate elections in the eight-state region, would end at least part of a 21-month legal battle by tucker and the labor department
region 5 includes uaw locals in missouri, kansas, oklahoma, arkansas, texas, louisiana, colorado and new mexico. after new delegates are elected for each local, they will vote at a mini-convention for a regional director
frank perdue, the 67-year-old head of perdue farms inc., is stepping down from his post, but says he will remain directly involved in managing the large poultry company
donald w. mabe, a 30-year veteran of the company who most recently served as vice chairman and president, has replaced perdue as president and chief executive officer, according to a company statement
the change will relieve perdue, associated by many television commercial watchers with his motto, ``it takes a tough man to make a tender chicken,'' from many day-to-day executive duties, the firm said late last week. but he plans to work directly with mabe
in other appointments, perdue's son, james a. perdue, vice president of the company's quality improvement division, was named to the chairman's committee, the top policy-making body, and pelham b. lawrence, vice president and chief financial officer, was elected to the board of directors
mabe, who joined perdue in 1957 as a broiler service supervisor, has been broiler marketing specialist, director of broiler sales and service, director of the hatching-egg program and production manager of the firm. in 1967 he was named vice president and general manager of processing and in 1972 he was appointed executive vice president of the company. elected to the board of directors in 1963, he was named president in 1979 and vice chairman in 1984
james perdue joined the family business in 1983 as a management trainee. he has served as a foreman, quality control coordinator and plant manager in salisbury, as well as quality control manager for the company's delmarva operations. he was named vice president of quality improvement in 1987 and has been on the board of directors since 1979. president</head>
philadelphia electric co. chairman james l. everett iii is retiring and will be replaced by joseph f. paquette jr., a former philadelphia electric executive who is currently president of a michigan utility
the changes, announced by philadelphia electric on monday, came as the utility struggles to restart its peach bottom nuclear plant that was shut down by the federal government last year
everett, 61, said monday he would retire at philadelphia electric's april 13 board meeting, when paquette is to be elected his successor. paquette will serve as philadelphia electric's president until everett's retirement
everett will remain on the utility's board as chairman of the executive committee
paquette, 53 is president and chief operating officer of cms energy corp., the jackson, mich.-based parent of consumers power in jackson, mich. he previously spent 30 years at philadelphia electric and held a number of management positions
everett's job had been in jeopardy since the nuclear regulatory commission decided last march 31 to close the peach bottom plant after control room operators were found sleeping and playing video games on the job
his pending retirement follows the departure last month of philadelphia electric president john h. austin
william shane, chairman of the pennsylvania public utility commission, had called for everett's resignation. he said monday he was delighted with the latest changes
the utility also announced monday that corbin a. mcneill jr. will become its executive vice president for nuclear operations next week. mcneill, 48, will be responsible for directing the company's nuclear operations, including the nuclear department's reorganization and efforts to get nrc approval to restart the york county power plant
philadelphia electric must assure the nrc that it can operate the plant safely before the agency will allow peach bottom's two reactors to restart
philadelphia electric submitted part of a new restart plan on nov. 25, outlining management changes at peach bottom and at the limerick nuclear plant in montgomery county. on feb. 12, philadelphia electric submitted the second half
in the plan, the company promised to provide more and better-trained plant operators, a new management team at the plant and a better employee value system
the nrc has found a list of deficiencies in the plant's operations, including the release of mildly radioactive water into the susquehanna river, misclassification of radioactive waste shipment and poor implementation of fire requirements
the shutdown is costing philadelphia electric and its three partners in the plant about $14 million a month to buy replacement power
peach bottom was opened in 1974 and is owned by philadelphia electric, public servcie electric &amp; gas co., of newark, n.j.; atlantic electric co., of atlantic city, n.j.; and delmarva power &amp; light co., of wilmington, del
stocks rose this morning after relatively quiet trading in the previous session
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 7.12 points to 2,063.49 by 10 a.m. est
among broader market barometers, the new york stock exchange's composite index measuring all listed issues rose 0.55 to 151.08. the american stock exchange's market value index rose .74 to 294.88
gaining issues outnumbered losers by more than 2-to-1 on the nyse, with 625 up, 257 down and 475 unchanged. volume on the big board totaled 51.37 million shares after the first 30 minutes of trading
on monday the dow jones industrial average slipped 1.49 to 2,056.37
advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 6 to 5 on the nyse, with 845 up, 710 down and 416 unchanged. big board volume totaled 152.58 million shares, down from 201.41 million in the previous session.  with 4 grafs to update with comment from roper, whirlpool; picks up 14th graf pvs, russ leavitt .... ^by linda stowell</note>
general electric co.'s unsolicited bid to acquire appliance-maker roper corp. _ which already has agreed to a merger with rival whirlpool corp. _ is seen as a competitive move in a consolidating industry
ge on monday offered to pay $45 a share, or $423 million, for roper's 9.4 million common shares outstanding
the unsolicited offer _ the first ever by ge _ topped the whirlpool offer of $37.50 a share, or $352.5 million, agreed to last month by roper
analysts applauded the move by ge, the well-known appliance maker which also has major interests in finance, broadcasting and other manufacturing, which was seen as a thrust against a competitor in the major appliance field
it makes sense and the numbers look real good,'' said nicholas heymann, a vice president of drexel burnham lambert inc. in new york. ``in terms of what they're getting, they're trying to make a statement with the price.''
roper's stock soared $11 to $48.37{ a share in composite new york stock exchange trading monday, indicating that speculators expected a higher offer to emerge. ge fell 75 cents a share to $43.37{ and whirlpool dropped 62{ cents a share to $28.75
roper, which is based in augusta, ga., makes gas and electric ranges, including some of the ranges marketed by ge
heymann said ge had carved out a niche in the gas range market within the past three years, and was no. 3 in that business with 15 percent of the market
this year they are revamping the range line and i think they would like to be vertically integrated in the gas line,'' heymann said. ``if they expand, they could vertically integrate and could move up to 20 or 25 percent of the market.''
it appears the ball is back in whirlpool's court,'' heymann said
roper, based in augusta, ga., said today it would meet with ge representatives and give the company information it had requested. roper said it would inform its shareholders of the board's position on the ge offer on or before march 18
whirlpool expects to received the detailed ge offer today, said donna mclean, a spokeswoman for benton harbor, mich.-based whirlpool
right now, we're right where we were. we have not said we're going to up the ante at all,'' mclean said
in a statement monday, david whitwam, whirlpool's chairman, president and chief executive officer, said the company was still committed to acquiring roper as a major step in its growth strategy
russ leavitt, a senior analyst for salomon brothers inc. in new york, said the merger attempt gives ge a ``potentially strengthened position in the cooking business.''
it also gives them an entree to sears, which is a major appliance retailer where ge has not been involved,'' leavitt said, referring to sears, roebuck &amp; co. ``roper is a sears supplier of cooking products and in the past ge has sold very little to sears. it could help them get into that market.''
ge said it made the offer after learning from a securities and exchange commission filing that roper agreed to the whirlpool merger under threat of a ``unilateral takeover.''
ge said that in discussions with roper management last year, roper officials said they wanted the company to remain independent
we concluded that because we approached roper on a friendly basis and because roper had been forced into play by the whirlpool offer, we should make an offer,'' said jack batty, a spokesman for ge. ``we would describe our offer as competitive.''
batty also noted the industry consolidation stemming from stepped up competition. other major appliance mergers in recent years included maytag corp.'s acquisition of magic chef co. and the acquisition of white consolidated industries by sweden's electrolux ab
we feel that it would significantly strengthen ge's appliance business in an increasingly competitive global market,'' batty said. ``we became impressed with the quality of their products. ...we think it would enhance our competitive position.''
ge's tender offer expires april 1. whirlpool's offer expires march 25
in its fiscal year ended last july 31, roper had net income of $24 million on $703 million in sales. gas and electric ranges account for about 40 percent of sales
ge had 1987 revenue of $40.5 billion and net income of $2.9 billion. ge's major appliance business last year had a pretax operating profit of $490 million on $4.72 billion in revenue
frank perdue, the 67-year-old head of perdue farms inc., is stepping down from his post, but says he will remain directly involved in managing the large poultry company
donald w. mabe, a 30-year veteran of the company who most recently served as vice chairman and president, has replaced perdue as president and chief executive officer, according to a company statement
the change will relieve perdue, associated by many television commercial watchers with his motto, ``it takes a tough man to make a tender chicken,'' from many day-to-day executive duties, the firm said late last week. but he plans to work directly with mabe
in other appointments, perdue's son, james a. perdue, vice president of the company's quality improvement division, was named to the chairman's committee, the top policy-making body, and pelham b. lawrence, vice president and chief financial officer, was elected to the board of directors
mabe, who joined perdue in 1957 as a broiler service supervisor, has been broiler marketing specialist, director of broiler sales and service, director of the hatching-egg program and production manager of the firm. in 1967 he was named vice president and general manager of processing and in 1972 he was appointed executive vice president of the company. elected to the board of directors in 1963, he was named president in 1979 and vice chairman in 1984
james perdue joined the family business in 1983 as a management trainee. he has served as a foreman, quality control coordinator and plant manager in salisbury, as well as quality control manager for the company's delmarva operations. he was named vice president of quality improvement in 1987 and has been on the board of directors since 1979
stocks rose today in active trading, influenced by dividend-related buying and selling strategies
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 13.09 points to 2,069.46 by 11 a.m. est
among broader market barometers, the new york stock exchange's composite index measuring all listed issues rose 0.76 to 151.29. the american stock exchange's market value index rose 1.07 to 295.21
wall street analysts said the market's strength was a good sign that reflected a desire by institutional investment managers to put unused money to work before the end of the first quarter march 31
the one thing insitutions want to avoid is lack of performance at end of a quarter,'' said philip c. puccio, manager of institutional trading at dillon read &amp; co. in new york
gaining issues outnumbered losers by nearly 3-to-1 on the nyse, with 922 up, 384 down and 471 unchanged. volume on the big board totaled 86.55 million shares after the first 90 minutes of trading
nearly a third of that volume came from trading in stocks that carry dividend yields of at least 9 percent: chemical new york, detroit editson, pacific gas &amp; electric and mcdermott international
investors who buy detroit edison's stock before thursday will capture the right to receive the next quarterly dividend payment. the deadline to capture the dividend in the other three issues expires today
on monday the dow jones industrial average slipped 1.49 to 2,056.37
advancing issues outnumbered declines by about 6 to 5 on the nyse, with 845 up, 710 down and 416 unchanged. big board volume totaled 152.58 million shares, down from 201.41 million in the previous session
a subsidiary of r.h. macy &amp; co. inc. launched a cash tender offer today to buy 80 percent of federated department stores inc., which remains the target of a competing buyout offer from campeau corp
a wholly-owned macy subsidiary, fds acquisition corp., commenced the cash tender offer at a price of $74.50 per share for up to 70.43 million shares, or approximately 80 percent, of federated common stock. macy plans to swap shares in the merged company macy's-federated inc. for the remaining 20 percent of federated stock
analysts have estimated the total value of the macy offer at $6.1 billion
the tender offer is proceeding under a definitive agreement signed by federated and macy last week
toronto-based campeau is offering $75 per share for 80 percent of federated's stock and $44 per share for the remaining stock. the campeau offer, which has a blended value of $68 per share, totals $6.18 billion
campeau's offer expires at midnight march 15, while the macy offer expires april 4
federated stock was unchanged at $66.62{ at midday today on the new york stock exchange. brilliant'' with ``most intense''; picks up 6th graf, industry has ....</note>
hundreds of scientists plan to gather wednesday to help design a $456 million machine that will generate the most intense x-ray beams in the world, the laboratory's director says
the scientists, who are coming from some of the nation's major industries and universities, will gather at argonne national laboratory near suburban lemont
alan schriesheim, argonne's director, said president reagan allotted $12.6 million in his proposed fiscal 1989 budget to the research, development and construction at argonne of the machine _ called a synchroton
congress has not yet passed the funding for the project. but schriesheim said he is optimistic lawmakers will approve the funding because of the synchroton's ``extraordinary variety'' of applications in pure science and industry
the machine would produce the most intense and powerful x-ray beams ever generated and will be used to help scientists explain the interior of matter, schriesheim said in a telephone interview monday night
industry has taken a keen interest in the development of the machine, named the 7gev advanced photon source
the machine has already attracted more industrial participation in the planning and design stages than any basic research machine ever built in the country,'' said david baurac, an argonne spokesman
some of the 7gev advanced photon source's applications would be in the petroleum, bio-medical, semiconductor, computer and airplane industries, schriesheim said
future applications might include the creation of a plastic stronger than steel, faster computer chips and improved diagnosis of heart disease, he said
international business machines corp of armonk, n.y, american telephone &amp; telegraph co. of new york, boeing co. of seattle, and exxon corp. of new york are among the businesses expected to attend the two-day meeting to help design the machine to meet their needs, schriesheim said
three hundred scientists are expected to attend the meeting, baurac said
argonne hopes to begin constructing the machine in late 1988 or early 1989. the machine will take about seven years to build, and its construction would generate 1,500 jobs, baurac said
once built, 300 scientists and technical staff members would run the machine, and about 1,000 scientists from industry, universities and other laboratories would use it each year, baurac said
the synchroton works by taking positrons and accelerating them almost to the speed of light. the synchroton then uses sophisticated arrays of magnets to wiggle the beam violently to generate ``the brightest beams of x-rays in the world'', baurac said
positrons are ``like electrons with positive charges,'' baurac said
grain and soybean futures prices opened mostly higher today on the chicago board of trade
soybean futures showed the greatest strength, gaining from follow-through buying from monday and from a lack of farmer selling overnight, analysts said
soybeans got an additional boost from the agriculture department's announcement that last week's u.s. soybean exports totaled nearly 22 million bushels, more than the market had expected, said jerry gidel, an analyst for g.h. miller &amp; co. in chicago
corn futures advanced on news that the soviet union had purchased 300,000 metric tons of u.s. corn for delivery in the current marketing year, which began sept. 1
wheat prices rose slightly in reaction to a mixed bag of news surrounding the usda's auction of government-owned wheat, gidel said
the positive news was that the agency had sold just 1.6 million bushels of wheat in friday's auction. but the usda also said it would continue its schedule of thrice-weekly auctions, each with a target of 10 million bushels, through march 25
in early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 1{ cents higher with the contract for delivery in march at $3.05{ a bushel; corn was \ cent to 1 cent higher with march at $2.01} a bushel; oats were } cent to 1 cent higher with march at $1.91{ a bushel; soybeans were 1\ cents to 2{ cents higher with march at $6.15 a bushel
