firestone tire &amp; rubber co. management's rejection of a merger with pirelli in favor of a venture with bridgestone corp. set the stage for the italian tiremaker's $1.86 billion tender offer for firestone, pirelli's chief says
pirelli societe generale sa, the world's fifth-largest tire maker, began negotiating at firestone's request over a merger of their tire operations in october 1986, pirelli chief executive gianbattista digiorgia said monday
the talks broke up with no agreement last march but resumed early last month, digiorgia said in a telephone interview from new york
we had a talk with them in the beginning of february, making a proposal that seemed to us to have been accepted,'' digiorgia said. ``a couple days later they announced the preliminary agreement with bridgestone.''
pirelli said its offer monday of $58 cash a share for firestone's 32 million common shares outstanding was contingent on firestone's dropping the tentative agreement reached with bridgestone on feb. 16
that agreement, calling for the japanese tire manufacturer to buy 75 percent of firestone's tire-making business for $1.5 billion, left pirelli ``no choice'' but to make an offer directly to firestone's shareholders, the italian company said in a statement
pirelli's offer also was conditioned on pirelli's acquiring at least two-thirds of firestone's shares in the tender offer and on the removal of firestone's anti-takeover defenses, pirelli said
if pirelli acquires control of firestone, it will sell certain segments of the company to french tire manufacturer michelin
john j. nevin, chairman of chicago-based firestone, stated late monday that the company's board was reviewing the offer and asking shareholders to await its recommendation before deciding whether to tender their stock to pirelli
the board will complete its review by march 18, nevin said
firestone stock shot up $13.50 a share to $63.12{ in composite new york stock exchange trading monday, topping pirelli's $58-a-share offer in reflection of speculation that a higher offer might emerge
pirelli had been regarded as a possible suitor for firestone, and just before firestone announced its bridgestone agreement speculation was rampant that a bid was about to be made
lawyers for pirelli on monday went to u.s. district court in cleveland to try to stop firestone from enforcing the ohio takeover act and from using its ``poison pill'' anti-takeover measures. a poison pill is a move by a takeover target company to make its stock less attractive to a potential acquirer
judge alice batchelder denied pirelli's request for a temporary restraining order and set a hearing for next monday to review the constitutionality of the ohio takeover laws
acquisition of firestone, the world's fourth-largest tiremaker, substantially would increase pirelli's current 1.5 percent share of the u.s. tire market, the world's largest. it also would give the italian company its first u.s. manufacturing facilities
it is known in our strategy that we need production facilities in the states,'' digiorgia said
we are present in eight countries so far,'' he said. ``it can be good for us to have a major presence in the states in order to improve our overall presence in the marketplace.''
analysts said acquiring firestone's u.s. tire business would be the easiest way for a foreign manufacturer to establish a solid foothold in the u.s. market and remain a contender in the fiercely competitive global industry
firestone is the only game in town for a tire company located outside the united states that wants to get in in a big way,'' said donald descenza of nomura securities international inc. in new york
firestone's got the plants, the distribution system and the relationships with general motors, ford and chrysler,'' he said
firestone has about 21 percent of the lucrative u.s. original-equipment market for passenger cars, said ed noga, editor of rubber &amp; plastics news, an akron, ohio-based trade journal
goodyear holds 34 percent of that market, uniroyal 20 percent, general 13 percent, and michelin 11 percent, noga said
firestone ranked fourth among tiremakers worldwide in 1986 sales of tires alone, behind goodyear, michelin and bridgestone, noga said
pirelli, based in milan, was fifth with 1987 sales of $3.65 billion
under the plan to spin off parts of firestone to michelin, the french group would pay about $650 million for firestone's brazilian holdings and its master care inc. auto service business, pirelli stated
michelin also would have an option to buy 50 percent of firestone's synthetic rubber and diversified product holdings in the united states for about $150 million
on feb. 16, bridgestone and firestone said they intended to form a new akron-based business called firestone tire co. that would own firestone's worldwide tire-making operation
bridgestone would own 75 percent of the joint venture
non-opec oil-producing countries are scheduled to meet in london on wednesday to consider ways of stabilizing world oil prices, egypt's top petroleum official said
in a statement distributed tuesday by the state-run middle east news agency, oil minister abdel-hady kandil said egypt called the conference to discuss ``deteriorating conditions in the world oil market.''
he said conferees planned to discuss ``means of halting the decline in prices and the best way to help producing countries, both inside and outside opec, maintain a steady income.''
kandil said it was not known how long the meeting would last. he also said it was not directed against the 13-member organization of petroleum exporting countries
besides egypt, participants will include the soviet union, china, norway, angola, malaysia, brunei, oman and mexico, kandil said
in stockholm, however, a norwegian oil ministry spokesman was quoted as saying that norway had declined an invitation to attend the meeting
the spokesman said norway remained resolute in its commitment to support opec in seeking stable oil prices, despite the recent downturn on world markets
tandon corp. said tuesday it has sold off the disk-drive business on which the company was founded to western digital corp. for $49 million in cash and other considerations
western digital, of irvine, a leading maker of computer storage, communications, video controller and logic-processing units, also will assume about $28 million in tandon liabilities, the companies said
the deal, which was agreed to in december and completed tuesday, involves tandon's winchester disk drive engineering and manufacturing facilities in santa clara and san jose, calif., and singapore, as well as plated media operations in santa clara
tandon, based in chatsworth, will be left with its fledgling business of manufacturing its own line of personal computers
as part of the deal, tandon agreed to buy western digital products to meet its production needs for at least two years
the acquisition of tandon's disk-drive operations gives western digital a business whose revenues grew to $280 million in 1987 from $78 million in 1985
class action suits have been filed against de laurentiis entertainment group inc. and its founder, italian film producer dino de laurentiis, charging the defendants with securities laws violations
the suits claim the defendants sold millions of dollars worth of securities to the public, while misrepresenting or failing to disclose information that would have been important to the investors who bought them
the plaintiffs charged that the company's directors and others ``participated in the wrongdoing in order to continue and prolong the illusions of the company's success as a financier, producer, distributor and exploiter of theatrical motion pictures.''
they also contend that de laurentiis' management wasted corporate assets in lavish spending and knowingly raised ``public funds for such purposes.''
they claim the film company failed to inform investors that de laurentiis, the former chairman of the entertainment group, received more than $300,000 for use of a beverly hills mansion and a rolls royce, the suit said
it is unfortunate that investors have seen more than $89 million of their money being lost,'' said richard d. greenfield, a haverford, pa., attorney representing the plaintiffs. the suits were filed monday in superior court
the suits were filed on behalf of those who purchased de laurentiis securities between may 30, 1986 and june 22, 1987. the securities included $65 million worth of notes and more than 2 million shares of common stock
de laurentiis group attorney robert goldsmith declined comment, saying he was unaware of the court action
the 68-year-old de laurentiis stepped down from his post as chairman and chief executive of the entertainment group last month so that the company, which has been hit by a string of box-office flops, could proceed with restructuring
the company posted losses of $36.2 million for the nine months ended nov. 30. it's failing films included ``near dark,'' ``weeds,'' ``hiding out,'' and ``date with an angel.''
the suits, which seeks unspecified damages, also name painewebber inc., the company's underwriter, and an active promoter of its securities
stocks rose broadly today in heavy trading, strengthened by dividend-related buying strategies, takeover speculation and a desire by institutional money managers to improve first-quarter portfolio performances
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 16.74 points to 2,073.11 by 2 p.m. est
among broader market barometers, the new york stock exchange's composite index measuring all listed issues rose 1.07 to 151.41. the american stock exchange's market value index rose 1.56 to 295.70
wall street analysts said the market's strength was a good sign that partly reflected a move by investment managers to put unused money to work before the end of the first quarter march 31
the one thing institutions want to avoid is lack of performance at end of a quarter,'' said philip c. puccio, manager of institutional trading at dillon read &amp; co. in new york
others said speculators who had sold stock on the hunch the market would decline were aggressively buying, a phenomenon known as short-covering which can boost prices dramatically
activity in stocks subject to takeover speculation also helped strengthen prices. still, there was an underlying feeling that wall street remains deeply affected by the uncertain aftermath of the october crash
we're still in that bear market mentality,'' said hank streifler, senior vice president on the trading floor at shearson lehman hutton inc. ``we haven't moved over that hump.''
gaining issues outnumbered losers by more than 2-to-1 on the nyse, with 1,031 up, 489 down and 431 unchanged. volume on the big board totaled 182.6 million shares with two hours of trading left
more than one-third of the volume today came from trading in stocks that carry dividend yields of at least 9 percent: chemical new york, detroit edison, pacific gas &amp; electric and mcdermott international
investors who buy detroit edison's stock before thursday will capture the right to receive the next quarterly dividend payment. the deadline to capture the dividend in the other three issues expires today
