gulf &amp; western inc., the entertainment, publishing and financial services giant, said its first-quarter profit slipped 8.9 percent compared with strong results a year earlier
martin s. davis, chairman and chief executive, said tuesday the results were in line with the company's expectations and that he expected improvement for all of fiscal 1988
the company said its profit fell to $63.1 million, or $1.05 a share, in its first fiscal quarter ended jan. 31 compared with earnings of $69.3 million, or $1.11 a share, a year earlier
revenue for the first quarter rose 8.3 percent, to $1.18 billion from $1.09 billion a year earlier
operating income from motion pictures for the quarter was down from record results for the christmas holiday quarter a year earlier, when the company had the movies ``star trek iv: the voyage home,'' ``the golden child'' and ``crocodile dundee'' in u.s. theaters and ``top gun'' in foreign release
this year, the company had the movies ``eddie murphy raw'' and ``fatal attraction'' in u.s. theaters and ``beverly hills cop ii'' and ``the untouchables'' in international release
television operations reported higher operating income. gulf &amp; western produces television programs such as ``cheers,'' operates the madison square garden cable tv network and owns 50 percent of the usa cable network
consumer publishing results were strong, but the costs of product development depressed results from educational publishing and professional information services
consumer and commercial finance operations improved, as a result of increased finance charge revenue and gains from insurance operations as well as gains in credit card receivables and real estate lending
davis said one reason for his optimism about prospects for earnings growth later this fiscal year is the planned release of the films ``crocodile dundee ii'' and ``coming to america'' with eddie murphy and revenue from syndication of the television shows ``cheers,'' ``webster'' and ``family ties.''
the company also announced it had boosted its quarterly dividend to 35 cents a share from 30 cents a share, payable april 1 to shareholders of record march 18. in addition, gulf &amp; western declared a two-for-one stock split in the form of a 100 percent stock dividend, payable may 2 to shareholders of record april 8
bankers trust new york corp., the nation's eighth-largest bank holding company, said monday it will establish a major operation in edinburgh, scotland, to provide global custody facilities for british and european owners and managers of large investment funds
scottish office industry minister and member of parliament ian lang, said through the scottish development agency here that the move is an important boost for the expanding financial services industry in scotland
bankers trust already has 400 employees in scotland through its acquisition last august of edinburgh-based world markets company, which provides global financial information services. the new operation will add another 150 jobs
a spokesman for the scottish development agency's north american offices, said that more than $158 billion in funds is managed in scotland, making it the second-largest financial services sector behind london in the european economic community
stocks rose broadly today in heavy trading, strengthened by dividend-related buying strategies, takeover speculation and a desire by institutional money managers to improve first-quarter portfolio performances
the dow jones average of 30 industrial stocks rose 20.72 points to 2,077.09 by 3 p.m. est
among broader market barometers, the new york stock exchange's composite index measuring alllisted issues rose 1.22 to 151.75. the american stock exchange's market value index rose 1.91 to 296.05
wall street analysts said the market's strength was a good sign that partly reflected a move by investment managers to put unused money to work before the end of the first quarter march 31
the one thing institutions want to avoid is lack of performance at end of a quarter,'' said philip c. puccio, manager of institutional trading at dillon read &amp; co. in new york
others said speculators who had sold stock on the hunch the market would decline were aggressively buying, a phenomenon known as short-covering which can boost prices dramatically
activity in stocks subject to takeover speculation also helped strengthen prices. still, there was an underlying feeling that wall street remains deeply affected by the uncertain aftermath of the october crash
we're still in that bear market mentality,'' said hank streifler, senior vice president on the trading floor at shearson lehman hutton inc. ``we haven't moved over that hump.''
gaining issues outnumbered losers by more than 2-to-1 on the nyse, with 1,111 up, 447 down and 409 unchanged. volume on the big board totaled 207.81 million shares with an hour of trading left
about one-fourth of the volume today came from trading in stocks that carry dividend yields of at least 9 percent: chemical new york, detroit edison, pacific gas &amp; electric and mcdermott international
investors who buy detroit edison's stock before thursday will capture the right to receive the next quarterly dividend payment. the deadline to capture the dividend in the other three issues expires today
