corning glass works said tuesday that it has agreed to acquire international clinical laboratories in a cash deal valued at around $260 million
chairman james houghton said he hoped the merger would broaden corning's laboratory services. the company said it planned to combine nashville-based international clinical with its laboratory subsidiary, mepath inc
corning said it offered $26 a share for 3 million unissued shares of international clinical stock and has an option to buy all of the shares owned by certain directors and officers of the company
the deal, which is set to expire by march 28, is subject to federal approval and to corning acquiring a majority of international clinical's shares
international clinical operates 13 major laboratories, mainly in the south and west, and had sales of $205 million last fiscal year and net income of $4.8 million
besides laboratory services, corning makes consumer housewares, optical fibers and other telecommunications equipment, and specialty glass and ceramics
its metpath subisidiary, which is based in teterboro, n.j., has about a dozen testing labs nationwide
grain and soybean futures prices closed mixed tuesday on the chicago board of trade, with wheat and corn futures ending lower while soybeans advanced
the substantial losses in wheat futures were due to heavy speculative selling stemming from a lack of major new export business, analysts said
an agriculture department report showing the u.s. winter wheat crop in good to fair condition was also seen as bearish for wheat prices
and the usda announced late monday it would continue through march 25 its thrice-weekly auctions of government-held wheat, another negative factor for wheat prices
soybean futures advanced on indications of rising world demand for vegetable oils, analysts said
most corn futures contracts finished fractionally lower in quiet trading
i guess corn was kind of trapped between beans being up and wheat being down,'' said jerry gidel, an analyst for g.h. miller &amp; co. in chicago
at the close, wheat was 4 cents to 6 cents lower with the contract for delivery in march at $3 a bushel; corn was 1\ cent lower to } cent higher with march at $2.01{ a bushel; oats were { cent lower to 1\ cents higher with march at $1.92 a bushel; soybeans were 1{ cents to 4} cents higher with march at $6.17 a bushel
stocks strengthened broadly today in heavy trading, helped by dividend-related buying strategies, takeover speculation and a desire by institutional money managers to improve first-quarter portfolio performances
the market for the last couple of weeks has been extremely constructive,'' said philip c. puccio, manager of institutional trading at dillon read &amp; co. in new york. ``the institutions have been more willing to invest money sitting on the sidelines.''
trading designed to capture high-yielding dividends of utility stocks accounted for much of the volume. a surge in speculative trading in stocks of companies possibly targeted for takeovers also contributed to the busy pace
share prices on the london stock exchange closed lower tuesday but above their worst levels after prime minister margaret thatcher ruled out an early cut in bank base lending rates
the market's attention once again was dominated by the strength of the british pound on foreign-exchange markets. trading volume was light in most shares
at the close, the financial times-stock exchange 100-share index was down 3.2 points at 1815.0. the index fell as much as 9.4 points in response to mrs. thatcher's statements, but then recovered somewhat on the strength of early gains on wall street
volume was 420.9 million shares, up slightly from 404.8 million on monday
the pound's strength sparked concern about the competitiveness of british exports
but mrs. thatcher told the house of commons the government didn't intend to lower interest rates to curb the pound's strength, for fear of spurring inflation
the dow jones average of 30 industrials rose 24.70 points to 2,081.07, the highest level since the october stock market crash
gainers outpaced losers by 2-to-1 on the new york stock exchange, with 1,067 up, 532 down and 396 unchanged
big board volume totaled 237.68 million vs. 152.98 million the previous session
the nyse's composite index rose 1.09 to 151.62
at the american stock exchange, the market value index rose 1.90 to 296.04
prices for future delivery of cocoa rose tuesday as a new price-support scheme emerged from an international meeting in london, but analysts said the plan was unlikely to halt the slide in prices
on other markets, cattle futures advanced sharply while the pork complex was mixed; grains and soybeans were mixed; precious metals retreated; energy futures were mostly higher; and stock-index futures advanced
the international cocoa organization's failure to reach agreement on a new price-support plan after five days of meetings triggered the automatic implementation of a scheme allowing the icco to withhold up to 120,000 metric tons from the market
but the organization lacks sufficient funding to finance the plan and its members, representing consumer and producer nations, were sharply divided on what intervention price should trigger the withholding mechanism, analysts said
it's very questionable whether the withholding program will have any impact on the market,'' said kim badenhop, an analyst with merrill lynch capital markets inc
the spot price for cocoa has fallen more than $400 a metric ton since july due primarily to abundant supplies and rising production
the icco intervened with a buffer-stock buying program that began in january, but the organization exhausted the program's 250,000-metric-ton allocation within two months
the first news of the new price-support plan sparked a rally on new york's coffee sugar &amp; cocoa exchange, where the contract for march delivery settled $17 higher at $1,600 a metric ton
but badenhop said trading enthusiasm flagged on later reports explaining the problems with the plan
cattle futures posted impressive gains for the second consecutive session on the chicago mercantile exchange in reaction to higher cash prices for cattle, carcasses and boxed beef, analysts said
the cattle market had been depressed due to a lenten-season drop in consumer demand for meat. but a wave of packing plant closings last week has reduced beef supplies to the point where wholesale prices have begun to rise, said william j. arndt, an analyst in chicago for dean witter reynolds inc
some concern remains that the drop in slaughters will lead to a backlog of slaughter-ready animals but ``right now we're trading the cash and the cash is strong,'' arndt said
hog futures followed cattle higher while frozen pork belly futures retreated on an exchange report showing an unexpectedly steep increase in supplies, he said
live cattle settled .20 cent to 1.37 cents higher with april at 72.92 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .55 cent to .85 cent higher with march at 81 cents a pound; hogs were .08 cent to .42 cent higher with april at 43.72 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .75 cent lower to .25 cent higher with march at 53.95 cents a pound
