most energy futures prices rose slightly on the new york mercantile exchange in response to calls for meetings among oil-producing nations, analysts said
west texas intermediate crude oil settled 6 cents to 15 cents higher with april at $15.45 a barrel; heating oil was .07 cent to .19 cent higher with april at 43.49 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .23 cent lower to .41 cent higher with april at 43.71 cents a gallon
stock-index futures advanced slightly on the chicago mercantile exchange, where the contract for march delivery of the standard &amp; poor's 500 index settled .80 point higher at 269.10. the underlying spot index closed 2.05 points higher at 269.43
stocks rose strongly tuesday in a rally powered by takeover speculation, dividend-related buying and increased interest in blue chips, sending the dow jones average to its highest finish since the october crash
the closely watched average of 30 industrial stocks, which had been lagging behind the broader market recently, finished at 2,081.07, up 24.70, the best post-crash close since 2,071.62 on feb. 29. other market indices also advanced
wall street analysts said the rally partly reflected a desire by managers of institutional investment funds to put unused money to work, especially because the first quarter is drawing to a close in three weeks and the best-possible portfolios must be presented to clients
we're coming into show-and-tell time, the window-dressing period,'' said lawrence wachtel, an analyst at prudential bache securities inc. ``these guys can't sit there with piles of cash in a boiling market and not get called down by the people who pay them to manage money.''
others said the increased interest in stocks reflected true buying interest and waning anxiety by investors over the impact of the oct. 19 collapse, along with indications that the economy is thriving
as we move further away from the october break, more people have thrown away their bear market caps and put bull market caps on,'' said joseph barthel, technical trading strategist at the butcher &amp; singer inc. investment firm
others agreed that the potential for a stronger rally exists and some predicted the dow jones industrials would soon surpass the 2,100 barrier, but many professional strategists were reluctant to declare that the underlying post-crash nervousness has evaporated
we're still in that bear market mentality,'' said hank striefler, senior vice president on the trading floor at shearson lehman hutton inc. ``we haven't moved over that hump.''
in composite new york stock exchange trading, gaining issues outnumbered losers by 2-to-1, with 1,072 up, 535 down and 404 unchanged. volume on the nation's largest stock market totaled 237.68 million shares, vs. 152.98 million in the previous session
buying interest in selected stocks to capture high-yielding dividends accounted for about 25 percent of the volume, which was the highest since jan. 25, when 275.25 million shares were traded
among notably higher blue chip stocks, procter &amp; gamble rose 1{ to 82\, du pont rose 2} to 87{, and general electric rose 1{ to 44~
oil stocks were boosted by takeover speculation in that industry. unocal rose 1~ to 37~, kerr-mcgee rose | to 36{ and phillips petroleum rose { to 15]
digital equipment fell 4 to 120] after the company unveiled a line of powerful computers to challenge ibm. analysts lowered their earnings estimates for the company because it didn't introduce new software for the computers
metals stocks rose broadly, reflecting increased prices in the metals markets. reynolds rose 2 to 45], asarco rose | to 24| and alcoa rose 1{ to 47}
nationwide turnover in nyse-listed issues, including trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter market, totaled 267.02 million shares
the new york stock exchange composite index of all listed issues rose 1.09 to 151.62
standard &amp; poor's index of 400 industrials rose 2.90 to 312.42, and s&amp;p's 500-stock composite index rose 2.05 to 269.43
the wilshire associates 5,000 equity index, which measures the market value of all u.s. stocks, rose $19.12 billion
at the american stock exchange, the market value index rose 1.90 to 296.04
the nasdaq composite index for the over-the-counter market closed at 376.93, up 2.39. from homer, ark., to homer, alaska, and date to nov. 23; also moved on general newswires</note>
the commuter accidents cited by the faa as the reason for the special inspection program were crashes of a ryan air beech-19 nov. 23 near homer, alaska, 18 fatalites; a regional express cessna 404c dec. 22 near chadron, neb., two fatalities; a south central air piper pa-31 dec. 23 near kenai, alaska, six fatalities; a panorama air piper pa-31 dec. 23 near maunaloa, hawaii, eight fatalities; a promptair cessna t-210c jan. 4 near bedford park ill., one fatality; a trans colorado fairchild swearingen jan. 19 near durango, colo., nine fatalities; and an avair fairchild swearingen feb. 19 near morrisville, n.c., 12 fatalities
mark peabody didn't crack a smile as the vice chairman of ford motor co., surrounded by cameras and microphones, leaned across the assembly line to hand him a check in an envelope
i was kind of nervous _ all those tv cameras,'' he said after harold poling chatted with him and gave him the check, peabody's share of ford's industry-record $4.6 billion in 1987 profits
on tuesday, ford distributed $653 million in profit-sharing checks averaging more than $3,700 to 156,479 hourly and salaried workers _ a record in profit-sharing for any u.s. corporation
most checks were distributed earlier in the day, but peabody and his pals on the main transmission assembly line at ford's livonia transmission plant agreed to wait until poling could distribute their checks in a ceremony recorded for posterity
it's not only the politicians who can call this super tuesday,'' poling told a crowd of cheering workers, adding that the plant's 4,500 employees received $17.6 million, or an average of $4,450 each
the livonia transmission workers' checks were higher than the company average because the workers have high seniority and the work force at the plant has remained stable for the past few years, said peter pestillo, vice president for employee and external affairs
workers on peabody's line assemble transmissions for front-wheel-drive cars such as the popular taurus-sable and the new lincoln continental. most of them, peabody included, said they are lucky to be there at all
most were on layoff from other plants and had enough seniority to be called to work at livonia when ford added the line three years ago
more than 160,250 ford workers in the united states received previous record profit-sharing checks averaging $2,100 for 1986, when ford earned $3.29 billion
ford workers took home an average $2,100 in profit-sharing for 1985, $2,000 for 1984 and $400 for 1983, when the company distributed the first checks
in the past five years, ford said it has given out more than $1.6 billion to its workers
general motors corp. workers received no share of gm's $3.56 billion in 1987 profits at the same time that the corporation said it would distribute $184.6 million in stock bonuses to executives
gm workers also received no 1986 profit-sharing, although executives received millions of dollars in cash and stock bonuses, angering gm workers heading into national contract negotiations
gm, the nation's largest automaker, switched to the ford profit-sharing formula for 1988, but the company said that formula still would have generated no profit-sharing had it been used for 1987
marks and spencer plc, britain's most profitable retailer, said tuesday it signed an agreement to purchase the swank u.s. clothing chain brooks brothers from canada's campeau corp. for $770 million
but it reiterated that the brooks brothers purchase is conditional on the success of campeau's $6.18 billion cash bid for federated department stores inc., which is being contested by r.h. macy &amp; co
marks and spencer agreed to pay $720 million for brooks brothers itself and for preferential rights to lease space in the enlarged 800-strong campeau stores empire
the purchase price also included $50 million in exchange for campeau's pledge not to set up a speciality menswear chain in the next five years that would compete with brooks brothers in japan or the united states. marks.</note>
the dollar continued to slide tuesday as the british pound again soared and other major currencies took their cue from sterling
gold prices were mixed. republic national bank of new york quoted a bid price of $435.70 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. est, down from $436.80 late monday
analysts said the british currency was buoyed by high interest rates and the strength of the country's economy
prime minister margaret thatcher ruled out an early cut in interest rates, giving the pound a further boost tuesday. she told parliament a drop in rates ``would not be in the interest of inflation at the present time.''
robert ryan, a senior currency trader at irving trust co., said ``interest rates across the board seem to be ruling the markets right now,'' with the currencies of countries with higher yields _ such as the pound _ turning in the best performances
sterling rose to $1.8415 from $1.8135 late monday in london. in later new york trading, the pound rose to $1.8425 from $1.8180 late monday. the pound has gained nearly 7 cents against the dollar in two days
the dollar also continued under pressure because of signals that the u.s. economy is strong, analysts said
last friday's labor department report that the unemployment rate fell to 5.7 percent in january convinced traders that the economy is healthier than had been expected
the market believed the economy ``could maintain demand for stronger imports and keep the u.s. trade deficit wide,'' said gary dorsch, a market analyst with lns financial group in chicago
dorsch predicted the dollar could fall toward 165 west german marks before there is central bank intervention to support the u.s. currency
the dollar traded at 1.6668 marks in europe, down from 1.6765 late monday. in new york, the dollar was quoted at 1.6673 marks, down from 1.6771 late monday
in tokyo, the dollar fell to a closing 127.80 japanese yen from 128.87 yen. later, in london, the dollar edged back up to 128.10 yen, and in new york, it rose to 127.93 from 127.835 yen
dorsch said the yen was down largely because of technical factors
other late dollar rates in new york, compared with late monday's rates, included: 1.3770 swiss francs, down from 1.3833; 5.64825 french francs, down from 5.7085; 1,231.00 italian lire, down from 1,238.00; and 1.25375 canadian dollars, down from 1.25415
other late dollar rates in europe, compared with late monday's rates, included: 1.6668 west german marks, down from 1.6765; 1.3790 swiss francs, down from 1.3870; 5.6625 french francs, down from 5.6880; 1.8780 dutch guilders, down from 1.8840; 1,234.00 italian lire, down from 1,239.75; and 1.2524 canadian dollars, down from 1.2562
gold fell on new york's commodity exchange, where it closed at $435.30 a troy ounce, down from $437.30 late monday
but gold rose in europe in response to the dollar's weakness, bullion dealers said
in london, gold increased to a late bid price of $438.10 a troy ounce, up from $437.20 late monday. gold rose in zurich, switzerland, to $436.50 an ounce from $436
earlier, in hong kong, gold dropped to a closing bid of $438.00 an ounce from $438.75
silver prices fell in new york and london. on the commodity exchange, silver slipped to $6.310 a troy ounce from $6.395 late monday. in london, silver fell to $6.36 a troy ounce from $6.42 late monday
pontiac is offering $500 cash rebates on its $6,399, korean-built pontiac lemans and, for those buying their first new car, an additional $600 discount, the general motors corp. division said tuesday
pontiac said it will offer the $500 rebate on all lemans delivered through april 30
pontiac also added lemans to the first-time buyer program announced friday. the program also offers $600 discounts to first-time buyers of the sunbird, grand am, fiero and some firebird models and expires sept. 30
with both discounts, the suggested base price of the lemans for a new buyer falls to $5,299
also on tuesday, ford motor co. announced it was extending its incentive campaign until may 11. the program offers rebates of up to $1,000 on nine car models and up to $500 on seven trucks
even though our combined car and truck sales during january and february increased 26 percent over the year-ago period, the incentive program is being extended to keep our dealers in a competitive position,'' said robert rewey, ford vice president for sales
the campaign includes $500 rebates on ford escort, manual-transmission tempo, mustang (except 2.3-liter engine model), bronco ii, aerostar, and f-150, f-250 and f-350 pickup trucks and mercury lynx, tracer and manual-transmission topaz
it also offers rebates of $600 on most ford thunderbird and mercury cougar models and $750 on the 2.3-liter engine mustang, on all mustang models in california and hawaii, and on ford taurus and mercury sable
a $1,000 rebate is available on the ford thunderbird turbo coupe and mercury cougar xr7
american standard inc. said tuesday it plans enter negotiations with hostile suitor black &amp; decker and other potential purchasers, but will continue developing its defensive recapitalization plan
in a release issued late tuesday, american standard said it would pursue alternatives that include a sale of the company
american standard expects to provide confidential information to, and to engage in, discussions and negotiations with black &amp; decker and other potential purchasers of the company,'' american standard stated in the release
american standard had been vehemently resisting black &amp; decker's overtures since the towson, md.-based company made its initial buyout offer in late january
on monday, new york-based american standard had indicated it would consider black &amp; decker's latest offer of $73 a share for american standard's 31 million common shares outstanding, a total of about $2.26 billion
american standard, a plumbing and air conditioning manufacturer, also said it was considering sweetening its own recapitalization plan for a second time
the $2.3 billion recapitalization would pay shareholders $64 in cash, $5 in securities and one share of stock in the recapitalized company for each old share. the plan was revised last friday from an earlier proposal that had a cash portion of $59 a share
american standard shares fell 25 cents to $73 a share tuesday in new york stock exchange trading. black &amp; decker fell 25 cents to $17.75 a share
analysts had said monday they expected american standard to come up with another sweetened proposal before the march 19 deadline for the black &amp; decker tender offer
john h. hanemann was elected tuesday to a two-year term as chairman of commodity exchange inc., the world's most active metals market
hanemann, a senior partner of prestige metal trading co., was elected to a two-year term at the annual meeting of comex members, the futures exchange reported
it was the first direct election of the chairman by the full membership in the exchange's 55-year history
hanemann succeeds alan j. brody, who will remain comex president and chief executive
re-elected to the board were john d. coffin, martin presler, salvatore demicoli and robert hussa. elected to the board for the first time were jack gandolfo, robert b. harmon jr., steven karvellas, mel schnell, leo walsh and salvatore azzara
futures traded on the comex include gold, silver, copper and aluminum
the u.s. dollar rose marginally against the japanese yen wednesday morning in tokyo, while stock prices gained following an overnight advance on wall street
the dollar traded at about 127.95 yen at late morning in tokyo, up from its opening of 127.80 yen. the dollar had dropped 1.07 yen to 127.80 yen on tuesday
trading was quiet in foreign exchange, where dealers awaited the outcome of u.s. presidential primary elections. the ``super tuesday'' election results were expected wednesday afternoon in japan
on the tokyo stock exchange, the 225-share nikkei stock average, down 150.85 points on tuesday, rose 103.62 points, or 0.41 percent, to close the morning session at 25,465.73. volume was a light 5.5 million shares
michio katsumata of nomura securities, japan's largest brokerage house, said tokyo stock prices were supported by tuesday's rally on the new york stock exchange and by stabilization of the foreign exchange market
investors also appeared to be buying shares deemed to be at bargain prices after the tokyo market's decline on tuesday, dealers said. not work on academy awards show, meeting with mediator breaks off until wednesday. picks up 7th graf pvs, `there were...'.</note>
officials of the writers guild of america's western unit voted unanimously tuesday not to allow guild members to write for the academy awards show scheduled for next month
the producers of the academy awards had asked that the guild allow the writers to continue working on the show
the board of directors of the writers guild of america west voted unanimously this evening to deny the request for waiver from the academy of motion picture arts and science for the academy awards ceremonies,'' said guild spokeswoman cheryl rhoden
what that means is that writers guild writers will not be writing the academy awards ceremonies,'' ms. rhoden added
the strike by 9,000 members of the writers guild of america against the alliance of motion picture and television producers began monday, a week after their contract expired
bob werden, spokesman for the academy of motion picture arts and sciences, had said earlier tuesday that the academy had asked for the waiver. in past strikes, entertainment unions have usually granted waivers for the oscars
without the waiver, ``we'll struggle on somehow,'' he had said
scriptwriter mel shavelson, former wga president, and another union member, jack rose, were hired by the academy to write the program, which is scheduled to be televised worldwide by abc-tv on april 11
if there is no waiver, i won't do the show,'' shavelson said tuesday, adding the writing was far from complete. ``most of the work is done when the cast shows up at rehearsal. it's rewriting, really
if there is no waiver, you will find out how good actors are at ad-libbing,'' he said. in general, writers provide most material for the hosts and presenters at the ceremony; the winners' thanks are their own
meanwhile, a federal mediator brought together negotiators for 9,000 striking scriptwriters and entertainment producers tuesday to outline differences in a walkout the union says could cripple hollywood
bargainers for the writers and the producers began meeting at midday with commissioner leonard farrell of the federal mediation and conciliation service
in the early evening the meeting was recessed until 11 a.m. thursday
both sides outlined differences and issues, but no bargaining was conducted, said alliance spokesman herb steinberg. sticking points were writers' demands for increased fees and creative rights
the final offer by producers was rejected by the guild sunday and talks broke off. no new bargaining sessions were scheduled
about 2,000 pickets gathered monday outside 20th century fox studios. meanwhile, producers urged writers to defy the picket lines and said temporary replacements may be hired
there were no large picket line demonstrations tuesday
as the writers marched, alliance president and chief negotiator nick counter said producers may begin hiring temporary replacements for striking writers until a settlement was reached
our companies are encouraging whoever wants to come forward to write these scripts,'' he said, urging union and non-union writers to cross picket lines
counter said non-guild writers were being sought to keep soap operas afloat and to keep the wheels turning on hollywood's game show circuit
while the writer's guild said talk shows and soap operas would be the first to feel the effects of the strike, probably turning to reruns, the producers said other shows had stockpiled scripts
the wga strike is the fourth since a 17-week walkout in 1973. the longest, in 1981, lasted three months
it's the same kind of feeling as we had in 1981,'' counter said, predicting the strike may be an extended one. ``this could go on even longer than that.''
speaking for the producers, steinberg said: ``we feel all the issues were dealt with fairly. they went on strike on issues we felt were resolved.'' he added that producers were ``ready to write a check for $550 million'' for a new three-year contract. the alliance represents about 200 producers and studios.   
